<html><head><title>That astonishing microchip</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<h1><center>That astonishing microchip</center></h1>

IT MAY be hard to believe, but it is less than 20 years since this newspaper was introducing readers to the existence of the integrated circuit, then still exotic, and predicting that it would change the world. It did, and in pretty short order. The world's appetite for chips has so far been almost as abundant as the silicon from which they are made.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Throughout this period, chip technology has evolved rapidly, more or less in conformity with the exponential growth in power predicted by Gordon Moore, a founder of Intel, America's leading chip maker. Every time engineers seem close to bumping against the technology's limits, they find some new way to make circuits smaller, faster and cheaper. As a result, the chips that were exotic yesterday are now the commonplace components not just of the computer but also of the car, the camera and the cash card. By common consent it has been the most productivity-enhancing, life-changing technological revolution since the harnessing of steam power in the 18th century or, in the 19th, of electricity itself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Also by common consent, this revolution also has much further to go. But if the revolution in microelectronics is not yet faltering, there are signs of two big changes.
</p><p><b>Hogs</b>
<br>One is taking place inside the semiconductor business itself. For much of the industry's short life, making chips has been a licence to print money. The first half of the 1990s was especially lucrative; sales last year topped $150 billion. Since Christmas, however, demand has fallen below expectations. Bad news in any industry, this is catastrophic in one where a single factory can cost more than $1 billion to build. The world's most advanced manufacturers are, it seems, no less vulnerable than farmers to the " hog cycle"; extrapolating from the present, they get the future wrong.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although chip makers have got supply and demand out of kilter before, there are grounds for expecting a much bigger impact this time around on the shape of the industry (see <a href="sf1.html">page</a>). And as the industry changes, so the way people think about chips should change, too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For too long, governments have invested the industry with a special mystique. A decade ago, the United States got into a panic when Japanese chip makers seemed to be getting the better of American ones. The chip, it was argued, was at the heart of the digital age, and America had therefore to make its own. Likewise, some Asian tigers still see in chip making not just a way to make money, but also a short-cut to a higher-technology economy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But this view is, at best, out of date. Like steel, chips have become just any other commodity. From the point of view of national economies, it matters little where they are made, provided that they are available to be cheaply bought. What matters more is how they are subsequently used.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Which is, of course, the second big change. For the first 20 years or so of microelectronics, the applications for the new technology seemed obvious. Computers shrank, then moved from the basement to the desktop to the wristwatch, which will soon doubtless be able to phone the nearest restaurant as well as announce that it is time for lunch. Intelligence, of a sort, became distributed: a car's brakes may now "think" quite hard about how to avert a skid. It was microchips that made Ronald Reagan's "star wars" dream almost feasible; maybe you really could track and destroy hundreds of thousands of fast-moving objects in space. The potential applications seemed as boundless as the human imagination.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is that the imagination does have bounds. Arguably, part of the industry's present plight is the result of computational power having briefly outstripped useful applications for it. A case in point is the reluctance of people to buy Microsoft's new operating system, Windows 95. Though it simplifies and prettifies what appears on the computer's monitor, this program requires more memory than most home computers currently possess. The chip industry hoped that this would propel demand for its own products, but a lot of consumers seem to have decided, for now at least, to forgo the marginal improvement the software provides.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Taken alone, the fate of this product is nothing more than a straw in the wind, a function of one firm's decisions about timing and pricing. But a lot of other straws are bending the same way. Having initially been transformed by microelectronics, the consumer-electronics industry must now struggle to dream up new "killer applications" as lucrative as personal stereos and video recorders. There are branches of science in which it is not too fanciful to wonder whether researchers have run out of sound ways to use all the computation at their fingertips. With "genetic algorithms", computers are more or less asked to crunch numbers aimlessly in the hope of something interesting popping up. It is telling that economists have so far found the precise productivity benefits of information technology difficult to pin down and measure.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Can people ever run out of new uses for computers? For a while, perhaps, but not for long. If anything, the computer is right now in the early throes of a new phase of its revolution, as it becomes more an instrument of communication, less one of computation. It is, after all, only in the past few years that microelectronics has invented what amounts to a whole new dimension of commerce and discourse. You do not have to be a nerd or a mystic to see that historians will look back upon the emergence of "cyberspace" as a turning point no less decisive than the advent of the computer itself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A machine that transforms communication impinges far more radically on people's lives than one that transforms computation. Why mass media, when information can be consumed in individualised packets? Must workplaces be "places" at all? The next limiting factor is not going to be the ability to imagine the future, or to invent it; many people think they can imagine it all too well. It is their willingness to embrace it that will matter most.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?827532000,iss">Search</a>
