<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>An edgy peace</h2>
After four years of strife, <b>Sarajevo</b> <b>was reunited</b> in accordance with the Dayton peace plan. But when Bosnia's Muslim-Croat federation took over the last of the city's Serb suburbs, most residents fled--under pressure from Serb nationalists hostile to the notion of a multi-ethnic Bosnia. Meanwhile, transatlantic tension is again rising, as the Europeans refuse to back American plans for arming Bosnia's Muslims, and the Americans have yet to provide any money for economic reconstruction.<p>Britain blocked the latest European plans to develop an embryonic cross-border European police force, <b>Europol</b>, arguing that the European Court of Justice should not be allowed to settle disputes involving the new force.<p>The British government's scientific advisers admitted for the first time that <font size=-1>BSE</font>--better known as <b>"mad cow disease"</b>--may be transmitted to humans through infected beef. The government promised stricter controls on the beef industry and more money for scientific research.<p>Germany's main opposition party, the Social Democrats, demanded that unlimited immigration of <b>ethnic Germans</b> from the former Soviet Union, where up to 2m may still live, should be stopped.<p>The Duma, the lower house of the Russian parliament, voted to reassert "the legitimacy" of <b>the Soviet Union </b>and to denounce the 1991 treaty that set up the Commonwealth of Independent States. The votes, which have no direct constitutional force, were condemned by President Boris Yeltsin.<p>The Swedish parliament approved <b>Goran Persson</b>, a former finance minister, as the country's prime minister to replace Ingvar Carlsson, who has retired.<p>
<h2>For sure</h2>
Senator Bob Dole clinched the Republican nomination for the <b>presidency </b>with a convincing sweep of mid-western state primaries. The press worried intensely about his age and state of health. His only remaining rival, Pat Buchanan, promised to continue to fight for "the rights of the unborn" and for American workers.<p>General <b>Colin Powell </b>ruled out running for "any elective office", thereby squashing speculation that he would be Mr Dole's running-mate.<p><b>Ross Perot </b>announced that he would run for the presidency if supporters of his Reform Party asked him to. He would, however, prefer to see his party led by "George Washington II", assuming he could find him.<p>Trade ministers from all western-hemisphere countries but Cuba met in Cartagena, Colombia, to discuss pan-American <b>free trade</b>. At the World Trade Organisation in Geneva, the <font size=-1>EU</font>, backed by Mexico and Canada, denounced the United States' new law on investment in Cuba; a formal dispute may follow. In Florence, Central American foreign ministers met <font size=-1>EU</font> ones, to upgrade links; the region gets more aid from <font size=-1>EU</font> countries than from the United States, but two-way trade is only $5 billion a year.</p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><p>Three <b>Colombian</b> <b>ministers </b>were named for investigation in the drug-money scandal relating to last year's presidential election. One of them, the country's foreign minister, Rodrigo Pardo, resigned "temporarily".<p><b>Guatemala's</b> <font size=-1>URNG </font> rebels and army began a truce, after 35 years of fighting.<p>

<h2>Bar the shouting</h2>
A war of words broke out between America and China over <b>Taiwan</b>. After a Chinese demand that American warships stay clear of the Taiwan Strait, the defence secretary, William Perry, said that America "has the best damned navy in the world, and no one should ever forget that." Taiwan asked America to sell it weapons to break any possible blockade by the Chinese.<p>The Bangladeshi prime minister, Khaleda Zia, agreed to an opposition demand for a <b>neutral government </b>to oversee a future general election, but she refused to step down immediately.<p>The Indian government, burdened by a corruption scandal, will hold a <b>general election </b>in late April and May.<p>China's parliament, the National People's Congress, passed a law stating that <b>defendants are innocent </b>until proven guilty.<p>Australia's <b>Labor Party</b> elected Kim Beazley as its new leader, to replace Paul Keating, who led his party to defeat in the recent general election.<p>
<h2>Underwhelmed</h2>
<b>Zimbabwe's </b>President Robert Mugabe, 72, was re-elected for another six years. He took 93% of the votes, but in a turnout of only 32%.<p><b>Sierra Leone</b> got a civilian president, Ahmad Tejan Kabbah, after four years of army rule. Declared winner, he said the soldiers would hand over by end-March.<p>Mathieu K&eacuter&eacutekou, <b>Benin</b>'s old dictator, thrown out through the ballot box in 1991, appeared to have been brought back by voters disillusioned with President Nic&eacutephore Soglo. But the result remains unclear.<p><b>Sudan</b>, which may soon face <font size=-1>UN</font> sanctions for harbouring men suspected of trying to assassinate Egypt's president last year, also held a general election at which the president and most of his cabinet were re-elected.<p>South Africa's president, <b>Nelson Mandela</b>, was granted a divorce from <b>Winnie</b> after 38 years of marriage.<p>The cycle of violence in <b>Bahrain</b> continued with a hotel bombed and large-scale arrests. The government's new security measures are expected to include a special court to try protesters.<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
