<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Fighting the flab</h2>
<P>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>Europe's largest car maker seems to have recovered from a bad spell of several years. Though still some way off its best year, <b>Volkswagen</b> more than doubled its net profits in 1995 to DM336m ($234m) on worldwide sales up 10%, and said it would sharply raise its dividend. But its French counterpart, <b>Renault</b>, saw net profits sag by 41% to FFr2.14 billion ($429m). Commercial-vehicle sales jumped but its car-making unit sunk from a profit of FFr289m to an operating loss of FFr1.7 billion, putting the French government's hopes of privatising Renault in jeopardy.<p>America's <b>Rockwell </b>is seeking a buyer for its aerospace and defence businesses, valued at some $3.5 billion, as the country's defence industry continues to consolidate rapidly; both Boeing and McDonnell Douglas are said to be interested in buying.<p>The German government said <b>Airbus Industrie </b>would have to turn itself from a loose consortium into an efficient, commercial company before it would consider subsidies to develop new planes. A&eacuterospatiale, the consortium's French member, appeared to welcome the idea even though it could suffer most.<p>Workers and managers were close to settling the strike at two of <b>General Motors</b>' parts factories in Dayton, Ohio. The strike, which began on March 5th over job security and the outside supply of some parts, had affected nearly all <font size=-1>GM</font>'s 29 American factories and some 175,000 workers. It was the firm's most damaging in 25 years.<p>Swedish-Swiss <b>ABB</b>, one of Europe's most admired companies, is suspected by European Union investigators of participating in an alleged price-rigging cartel in the European market for district heating.<p>Sweden's Wallenberg industrial empire expects to raise between SKr15.5 billion ($2.3 billion) and SKr18.5 billion with the sale of a 50% stake in <b>Scania</b>, the world's most profitable lorry maker, in a stockmarket flotation.<p><b>The Russians and Americans may produce a joint </b><b>supersonic passenger jet</b>, based in part on the Tupolev-144, freshly out of mothballs, whose maiden flight was in 1968 and which resembles a larger version of the Franco-British Concorde.<p>
<h2>Trades and swaps</h2>
<p>Shaking off the previous week's upsets not only in America's markets but worldwide, the <b>Dow Jones </b>soared to a new record before dropping back after Digital Equipment warned of a poor outlook for computer sales.</p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>The <b>London Stock Exchange</b> is moving after all to a system of electronic order-driven trading, in place of its present market-making system. This was the change advocated by Michael Lawrence, its former chief executive, whose dismissal in January was blamed by many on the power of the exchange's market-making members.<p>World <b>financial regulators </b>met in Florida and agreed to share information on unusual trades, in an effort to prevent another shock like the collapse of Britain's Barings bank last year.<p>Nine former executives at <b>Barings </b>have been barred from working in the City for up to three years by the Securities and Futures Authority. But Peter Baring, chairman of the group, and Andrew Tuckey, chairman of the investment-banking unit, were cleared by the authority.<p>
<h2>Muscle flexing</h2>
Managers of Calpers, the California Public Employees' Retirement System, asked the pension fund's board to approve an international <b>corporate governance</b> programme. The $97 billion fund would pressure the foreign firms in which it invests to be more responsive to shareholders.<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>The Japanese economy </b>grew at its fastest rate in five years, an expansion boosted by stronger than expected consumer spending. In the last quarter of 1995, <font size=-1>GDP</font> grew by 0.9%, giving an annualised rate of 3.6% that more than doubles many estimates of growth, despite a shrinking trade surplus.<p>There were fresh rumours in <b>Argentina </b>that Domingo Cavallo would resign. Wrong again. But he did cut taxes to boost the economy, still saying that <font size=-1>GDP</font> would grow by about 5% this year.<p>Brazil's government announced an 8 billion <i>real </i>($8.1 billion) bail-out of <b>Banco do Brasil</b>, the country's largest bank.<p>
<h2>Kids' stuff</h2>
<p><b>Michael Jackson</b> and <b>Prince Alwaleed bin Talal bin Abdulaziz Saud</b>, a Saudi businessman whose interests include large stakes in Citicorp, Euro Disney and Canary Wharf, are forming a global entertainment company, Kingdom Entertainment, that will focus on " family values".<p>Britain's General Electric has found a successor to<b> Lord Weinstock</b>, who has now been managing director for 33 years and is to retire later this year. He is George Simpson, chief executive of Lucas Industries, a British engineering group which recorded a 38% jump in first-half profits to &#163;61.6m ($95.9m).<p>In a bid to placate unions opposed to privatisation, the French government said it would retain control of <b>France T&eacutel&eacutecom</b> while hoping to convert the state utility into a corporation with its own capital. But as Europe's telecoms giants come closer to liberalisation, even that step upsets the unions. They threatened to strike.<p><p></p>
</td></tr></table></center>
