<html><head><title>When the chips are down</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif" alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>When the chips are down</h1>
<p><b>The semiconductor business, one of the world's largest industries, is about to go through a period of wrenching change</b></p>

<p>FOR most of the 1990s, the chip industry has seemed like one of the most extraordinary money-making machines ever devised. Demand soared; the power of the chips themselves soared; and prices rose or stayed stable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The result was a bonanza for chip makers which outweighed the experience of the mid-1980s, when price wars split the business in two, driving many American firms out of the mass-production end of the industry making memory chips and forcing them to concentrate on higher value-added chips such as micro-processors. It also outweighed the late 1980s, when Japanese firms (which concentrate on memory chips) lost billions during a trade war with America. The past few years have been richer than all those tough years combined.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bankers Trust calculates that profit margins for Taiwan's chip makers, for example, rose from 16% in 1990 to nearly 60% in 1995. Last year, the number of memory chips sold rose 40% and the memory-chip business probably made profits of nearly $30 billion on revenues of $55 billion. Some fabrication plants have been making nearly $1 billion in net profits each year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What was just as extraordinary was that this period seemed to overturn a basic rule of the chip business which says that the power of a chip doubles every 18 months and, as a corollary, prices halve (originally, it was every year: the rule was expounded as long ago as 1965 by Gordon Moore, a co-founder of Intel, an American chip maker). More power for less money was the combination that made semiconductors the business that transformed business. Yet in the early 1990s, with personal-computer (<font size=-1>PC</font>) demand skyrocketing and memory chips in short supply, the price of these basic chips climbed to three times their cost of production and stayed there, defying every established pattern.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Then, last December, it all started to go wrong. First, prices started to tumble. The market price of the most common kind of memory chip, which had been as high as $13 in November 1995, began dropping by more than $1 a month as <font size=-1>PC </font>makers dumped excess stocks after disappointing sales during the Christmas season. By March the price was down to around $9 (see <a href="sf1.gif">chart</a>; for comparison, a state-of-the-art micro-processor can cost $1,000).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In January, things got worse. The Semiconductor Industry Association reported that its so-called " book-to-bill" ratio had dropped to 0.92, its lowest point since 1985. That meant that for every $100-worth of chips the industry was making, it was only taking orders for $92-worth of new ones. It was the first time since 1989 that the indicator had gone below 1.0. At first, the industry shrugged off that figure as an anomaly. Then came February's number: 0.90. For businessmen accustomed to soaring sales, this sort of slump is enough to send them to the window ledge.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Suddenly, manufacturers are scrambling to postpone planned expansion. Micron, America's largest memory-chip producer, says it will delay completion of a $2.5 billion fabrication plant in Utah. Fujitsu of Japan has announced it will delay the start of a similar plant in Britain. A consortium of American and Asian firms has scrapped plans to build another plant in Taiwan.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The cutbacks are needed. Profits for the five big Japanese chip makers had been expected to grow 55% this year; instead, analysts reckon, they will grow 15%. In the past six months, the Philadelphia semiconductor index, a measure of the share prices of American chip makers, has dropped 45%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For users of chips--which now means everyone from purchasers of <font size=-1>PC</font>s to manufacturers of cars and pop-up toasters--the fall in chip prices must be welcome. Chips are now everywhere--there are some 200 billion in use, installed in everything from computers and telecommunications to greetings cards. The average American house has 50 chips in consumer goods from the microwave oven to the door chime; a new <font size=-1>BMW </font>may have more than 50. Automotive semiconductors alone are a $5 billion market. All these businesses will benefit--albeit, in many cases, marginally--as their components become cheaper.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So will other firms. Firms such as South Korea's Samsung and Japan's <font size=-1>NEC</font> have used their semiconductor factories as cash cows to bankroll expansion into everything from <font size=-1>PC</font>s and cars to aerospace. If memory-chip prices continue to fall, the cash cows will run dry, exposing the real costs of money-losing or inefficient parts of the conglomerates, which could force the parent firms to pull back from some markets altogether. This is bad news for them, of course, but good for competitors, who no longer have cross-subsidisation from semiconductors to worry about. And consumers everywhere should benefit in the long run because production and investment will no longer be skewed by profits from chips.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But to leave the argument there, and to say that no one need worry about falling semiconductor prices, is to under-estimate how much a shake-out in the chip industry would matter in its own right. The reason has to do with the sheer size of the business. Worldwide semiconductor sales passed $150 billion last year, three times what they were a decade ago. Chips in all their varieties now make up some 15% of the world equipment market, up from 7% in the mid-1980s. By mid-1997, if the growth rates of 1995 were to continue, America's chip manufacturers (which are, remember, mainly in the luxury end of the business) would be bigger than its steel industry; by 2000, they would be as big as aerospace. Mr Moore has facetiously remarked that, on these trends, the world's semiconductor market would be bigger than the world's <font size=-1>GDP</font> by 2040. Upheavals in such an industry matter.
</p><p><b>Wheel of misfortune</b><br>(see <a href="sf2.gif">table</a>)<br>So why have prices suddenly plunged? And might they go on falling?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All industries have downturns. But semiconductor firms have good reason to fear theirs more than most. The chip market tends to be highly unstable, partly because there are few industries that involve such massive fixed costs and partly because demand for chips can change rapidly, while a new fabrication plant can take a year or more to build.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The long lead times needed to build a plant mean that the supply of chips tends to be sticky: that is, it does not adjust smoothly to price changes or to changes in demand. Normally, manufacturers tend to reduce the output of goods for which demand and price are falling. But last year's investment in chips will produce a big extra supply just as prices are slumping. This will push prices even lower.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The volatility of the chip market is compounded by manufacturers' high fixed costs. New fabrication plants ("fabs") can cost well over $1 billion, and the biggest will cost more than $2 billion within a year or two. State-of-the-tech fabs become obsolete in three to five years; staying ahead in such a business requires a large chip maker to spend vast sums simply to keep up with technology. Last year semiconductor firms spent $30 billion on new fabrication capacity. Intel, America's largest chip manufacturer, spent $3 billion alone.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To recoup its investment, a semiconductor firm will want to run the plant as near to full capacity as possible. This means it might not cut production even when demand drops, producing a glut and even lower prices. Conversely, when demand rises, there may be no spare capacity in existing plants, leading to a shortage and soaring prices.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Curiously, such market instability is a characteristic that the high-tech chip business shares with that most basic of industries, agriculture. Farming is also a commodity business in which supplies adjust stickily to demand because of long lead times (the months it takes to grow a crop or fatten an animal for market). Farmers must fix next year's output on this year's prices, leading to unstable price swings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Volatile prices have long been used to justify government intervention in agriculture (to smooth out price fluctuations). Such intervention has occurred in the chip market, too--and made matters worse.
</p><p><b>Sinking the chip</b>
<br>In the 1980s, when <font size=-1>IBM</font> launched the <font size=-1>PC</font> revolution, Japanese firms had both the technical skills to design new chips and the money to build new plants. They started selling chips cheaply into America, causing American firms to cry foul and to accuse the Japanese of "dumping" chips at below the cost of production. The American government took up their cause, imposing steep import tariffs on Japanese chips and some consumer-electronic hardware.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The strategy backfired. By 1987 all but two big American firms had left the memory-chips business for higher-value microprocessing. Meanwhile, the tariffs had helped drive up the cost of memory chips by nearly 300%, harming chip purchasers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With America mostly out of the memory market, and Japan reining in output to avoid worsening the trade row (and because its economy was beginning to slow anyway), the result was another overshoot, this time the other way. Demand outstripped supply and prices soared. Hence the artificially inflated chip prices of the early 1990s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Markets, like nature, abhor a vacuum. South Korean firms such as Samsung and the <font size=-1>LG </font>Group (then Lucky Goldstar) looked at high memory-chip prices and saw a chance to make a killing. Designing chips is a research-intensive job. But making them is largely a matter of buying the equipment and building a "clean room" in which to put it. The Koreans started building their own fabs, financed by the deep pockets of the <i>chaebol--</i>the family-owned conglomerates of which they are part. Last year, South Korea overtook Japan as the largest producer of memory chips, just as Japan had overtaken America ten years earlier.
</p><p><b>The chip cyclist returns</b>
<br>Given the experience of the Japanese, it might seem foolhardy for the South Koreans to bet so much of their expansion on memory chips. But they, and others like them, may have thought the industry had changed and its cycles had been tamed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Chip makers are now in closer contact with their customers than they once were. With a direct link to a <font size=-1>PC </font>makers' inventory system, a chip maker can use "just-in-time" manufacturing techniques to keep supplies tied more closely to demand. Electronics firms have cut their average chip inventory from 11 weeks in 1985 to just three, which should, in theory, restrain massive over-supply. The industry is geographically dispersed. In the 1980s, almost all of it took place in America or Japan, making chips sensitive to the yen/dollar exchange rate. Today, new entrants are flooding in from Asia (notably South Korea, Taiwan, Singapore and Hong Kong). And chips are now being used in more industries than before, making suppliers--apparently--less sensitive to any one business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, as the current downturn shows, these changes have not proved enough to flatten out the chip cycle. Surges of investment continue, regardless of what is happening to inventory-control systems. Though new producers are starting up, America and Japan still have nearly 80% of the world market between them. Above all, the spread of chips into new markets is not what it seems. True, chips are found in thousands of different devices these days. But chip manufacturers still make most of their money from just one industry: computers. Dan Hutcheson, president of <font size=-1>VLSI</font> Research, a California-based consultancy firm, reckons that computers account for some 60% of semiconductor revenues. Mobile telephones account for perhaps another 10%. Nothing else comes close.
</p><p><b>Fear Windows</b>
<br>So, ubiquitous or not, chips remain vulnerable to the fortunes of the computer business. Both the recent slump in memory-chip prices and the plunge in the book-to-bill ratio have their roots in changes affecting the <font size=-1>PC</font> industry. Those changes stem primarily from the rise of Microsoft, a software company.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In their 15 years of existence, <font size=-1>PC</font>s have evolved in fits and starts. Bursts of activity followed the invention of processor chips, made by Intel. Intel started with the 8086 chip, then the 80286, then the 80386, each separated by about three years. Each was faster than the previous generation, and sold a lot of new <font size=-1>PC</font>s. But the number and value of chips in those machines stayed about the same. Then came Microsoft's Windows operating system, introduced in the late 1980s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Windows required 4m bytes of memory to run well, twice as much as most <font size=-1>PC</font>s then had. As the system took off, new <font size=-1>PC</font>s were made with at least that much memory, doubling the growth in demand for memory chips. Last year, Microsoft released Windows 95, which needed twice as much memory again. As <font size=-1>PC</font> users groaned under the hype surrounding the new program, chip makers were slavering at the thought of the extra demand it required.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But nothing happened--or not much. Companies have been slow to buy Windows 95, partly because of associated hardware costs, partly because it is not clear to them how to use the extra software power, and partly because Microsoft has another, more powerful, operating system, called Windows <font size=-1>NT</font>, in the wings. The result is that many firms have decided to wait and see whether to upgrade--and are buying nothing in the meantime. This has not only hurt memory chips, but has also slowed demand at the higher-value-added end of the business, micro-processing. Intel's latest processor, the Pentium Pro, runs efficiently only under one of the two new versions of Windows. In this respect, though the chip business may no longer be monolithic, different parts of it are affected similarly by changes in computing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Chip makers hope that their computer-driven woes are temporary. If <font size=-1>PC</font> sales begin to pick up soon, the "book to bill" ratio might rise above 1.0 and the free fall in prices might slow (though, with new capacity coming on stream, prices are likely to keep going down).
</p><p><b>Chip shape?</b></b>
<br>But even if this happens, the big problem--the heart-stopping price of a new fabrication plant--remains. Chip makers are running up against the physical limits of the technology itself: transistors on a state-of-the-art chip are now packed so closely together that they are near the point beyond which electrons tunnel through insulating walls and individual atoms become obstacles. Engineers may be able to get around this hurdle but the cost is likely to be astronomical. Meanwhile, the law of diminishing returns seems to be setting in. Between 1984 and 1990, the cost of a fabrication plant doubled but chip makers were able to triple the performance of a chip (measured by the number of components packed on to a sliver of silicon). They are unlikely to do as well next time. The next generation of fabs will see costs double again by 1998, but this is likely to produce only a 50% improvement in performance. What, then, can firms do?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The answer is three things:
<li> Team up. Writing recently in <i>Scientific American</i>, a monthly journal, the founders of <font size=-1>VLSI </font>Research calculate that rising costs will soon make chip manufacturing unaffordable for single firms. Increasingly, chip makers are sharing the costs of a new fab with customers, competitors, even countries. <font size=-1>IBM </font>and Toshiba are building a fab together, as are Motorola and Siemens; all four are working together on design. Texas Instruments started with a deal with the Italian government for a new fab, then tied up with Taiwan's Acer, Japan's Kobe Steel and a Singaporean consortium. The alliances have saved it more than $1 billion in capital costs over the past few years.
<li> Subcontract manufacturing. Other firms are dealing with the problem of expensive fabs by not having one at all. These so-called "fabless" firms design the chips, then contract the manufactuer of them out to a "foundry" (a factory without its own design operation). The advantage for the fabless firms is that they can get into the chip business without having to spend billions on manufacture. The foundries still face the problems of the investment cycle, of course, but at least they can mix and match customers to help spread the risk of any one customer going sour. Fabless chip firms make up just 1% of the market today, but are expected to have 5% by 2000. In the meantime, foundries such as Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing and Singapore's Chartered Semiconductor Manufacturing are booming.
<li> Specialise. One of the advantages of separating design from production is that it lets companies exploit technology niches while leaving the cost of manufacturing to a contractor. As Intel has faced more competition in the micro-processor business, it has diversified, producing some 30 different kinds of 486 chips, compared with just two versions of its first processor. Toshiba is doing the same with memory chips.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Firms that survive to produce chips in five or ten years' time are likely to have adopted one or all of these strategies. But chip makers' immediate concern is simply to survive the next year or two as new entrants flood into the market. Mr Hutcheson reckons that Taiwan's chip makers, for instance, may soon discover that the profits that lured them in are no longer there. Likewise for some of the South Korean firms, such as Samsung, that have expanded most aggressively. The memory-chip market, he says "has never been for the weak of heart" . A lesson to remember in the good times: the bad times invariably return.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?827532000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
