<html><head><title>Too little change</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>GP fundholding</b></p>
<h1>Too little change</h1>
<p><b>According to the Audit Commission, one of the key elements of the government's health reforms is not yet working</b></p>

<p>"FUNDHOLDING"--the freedom of <font size=-1>NHS</font>-employed family doctors to manage their own budgets--is "one of the great successes" of the government's controversial <font size=-1>NHS</font> reforms, according to Stephen Dorrell, the health secretary. At the beginning of 1996, there were 2,200 fundholding general practicescontrolling &#163;3 billion of health-care spending. By next month, 15,000 practices (one in two) will be managing their own fixed budgets to pay for primary care, drug costs and non-urgent hospital treatment. <font size=-1>GP</font> fundholders boast that they have improved patient care, introduced new methods of treatment, and shortened hospital waiting times.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But how far are these claims justified? A two-year inquiry to be published shortly by the Audit Commission, a government agency which reviews public spending, provides scant comfort to the scheme's champions, which include this newspaper. Some details of the report, the most extensive examination so far of the fundholding experiment, were first leaked earlier this month to the <i>Health Service Journal</i>, a medical weekly. Since then <i>The Economist</i> has seen a draft of the entire report.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It concludes that most fundholding doctors have secured "few measurable benefits to patients". Instead, fundholders themselves have garnered a fair part of such benefits as have been achieved. On average 60% of the scheme's savings have been used to improve surgery premises. Though patients benefit from this, some doctors have done even better, pocketing higher prices for their practices when they sell them to other doctors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These findings will embarrass ministers who claim that the government's <font size=-1>NHS</font> reforms--designed to create an "internal market" by splitting "purchasers" and "providers" of health care--have revolutionised the delivery of services to patients. But the Audit Commission's findings will delight Labour and the Liberal Democrats, who have argued that the administrative costs of fundholding outweigh whatever benefits it has produced. Labour is committed to ending fundholding.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most common complaint against fundholding is that it is creating a two-tier health service. If only that were so. In fact, the Audit Commission's report finds that average hospital waiting times for patients of fundholders were not significantly shorter than those for non-fundholding practices. The commission acknowledges the scheme's considerable potential to improve delivery of primary health services, but says that most doctors are failing to exploit its possibilities. Instead they continue to purchase the same products and services in the same quantities from the same hospitals and drug companies as in the past. In short, little has changed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Few fundholders, the report says, possess the information needed to improve the lot of their patients. Most do not know the average waiting time to see a hospital specialist or the length of the queue for particular specialities. The commission also found no evidence that fundholders prescribe drugs more economically--by using, for example, generic instead of branded versions--than other doctors. Most fundholders also failed to save money by greater use of day surgery for minor operations instead of hospital treatment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Audit Commission is particularly critical of health authorities, which employ <font size=-1>GP</font>s, for failing to monitor the performance of fundholders. Some 15% of <font size=-1>NHS</font> spending is already controlled by fundholders but financial oversight of this spending is patchy, according to the report.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More than one in five fundholders overspent their budgets in 1993-94. But, whereas fundholding practices are allowed to keep surpluses from their budget, and use the extra money in subsequent years, there is no mechanism for health authorities to claw back deficits. This lack of financial discipline is highlighted by the commission's report. Only 13% of the 1,308 fundholders surveyed had received any response to the financial reports they filed monthly with the health authority. Half of the fundholders interviewed by the commission had not been visited by their health authority during the previous year. The report condemns this as inadequate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps the most damning aspect of the report is the spotlight it puts on the costs of fundholding. Staff, equipment and computing costs swallowed &#163;232m in the first five years of the scheme, the equivalent of two additional hospitals. But this is only part of the additional cost.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Local health authorities estimate that it costs them &#163;5,900 a year to deal witheach fundholder. The Audit Commission quotes the estimate of one hospitaltrust that it costs four times as much to negotiate contracts with 13 fundholding practices, accounting for 4% of the trust's income, as it does with the local health authority, accounting for 91% of its income. The <font size=-1>NHS</font> reforms were bound to raise administrative costs--if only because there was little administration, and thus financial transparency, before them. But these numbers look excessive set against the lack of measurable benefits for patients which the commission has found.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Amid so much bad news, it is easy to overlook the good. The report accepts that fundholding has led to improved communication between <font size=-1>GP</font>s, hospitals and hospital doctors. This must be of benefit to patients. It also notes that some innovative fundholders have introduced real improvements for their patients, such as local physiotherapy services. One fundholder switched orthopaedic operations to a different hospital, thereby saving his practice &#163;40,000 a year. But, says the commission, there are simply too few such examples.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The message that comes loud and clear from the Audit Commission is that the additional costs of fundholding can be justified only if real benefits to patients can be secured. The commission believes this is possible. The scheme has considerable potential, it says, arguing that the principle of devolving control over purchasing decisions to <font size=-1>GP</font>s should, eventually, produce a more efficient and responsive <font size=-1>NHS</font>. But the potential of fundholding, the commission says, has yet to be realised.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The commission makes no specific recommendations about how to do this. But it is clearly wrong that there are few sanctions against those practices which either overspend or underspend by large amounts. Deficits should not automatically be made good; nor should decisions over profit levels be left to the sole discretion of fundholders. Health authorities, which are responsible for most purchasing decisions, cannot entirely abdicate their responsibility for primary health care. They need closely to monitor both the clinical and financial performance of all fundholding practices, encouraging the spread of the best techniques. As the Audit Commission points out, the <font size=-1>NHS</font> has barely begun the first steps on a huge programme of change. The right incentives are not yet in place.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?827532000,iss">Search</a>
