<html><head><title>Tears at bedtime</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Divorce law</b></p>
<h1>Tears at bedtime</h1>


<p>(See <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>)<br>LIKE the impulse to probe a painful tooth, divorce law appears to be irresistible to legislators. Rich countries all over the world have been tinkering with ways to make divorce better, or at least less awful. In Britain, a divorce bill proposed by Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, receives its second reading in the House of Commons on March 25th, after a rough passage through the House of Lords. If it passes, it will be the fourth change to the divorce laws since 1969. And it will not be the last. On March 21st, the cabinet met to discuss the Lords' last-minute amendment, requiring equal pension rights. The government would prefer not to deal with the complexities of pension-splitting in this bill, but knows it cannot wish it away. The issue is particularly sensitive in Britain, because job-based pensions predominate; in Europe, where state pensions are more important, it has been fairly simple--though expensive--to extend equal pension rights to all adults.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britain differs from other developed countries in two other important respects. Three-quarters of British divorces are fault-based: one partner accuses the other of adultery, cruelty or unreasonable behaviour. In many of these, one partner agrees to carry the blame in order to get a quick divorce (a two-year wait is required for a no-fault divorce). With a good lawyer and an uncrowded court schedule, a determined couple can get a divorce in three months.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Continental Europe and all other English-speaking countries have already moved towards a norm of no-fault divorce; in those countries where fault is retained, such as France, it is used sparingly. Defenders of fault say that it acts as a deterrent to frivolous divorce; sceptics wonder why, then, so many British couples seem eager to assign fault--and why Britain has the highest divorce rate in Europe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britain is also unusual in that divorce is possible--and not uncommon--before arrangements about finances, custody and child support have been agreed to. This, too, would change under the bill: no deal, no divorce. In some ways, then, Britain is swimming with the tide. But in others, Lord Mackay's controversial reforms set Britain somewhat apart. The first is that, under his bill, there would be no distinction between contested and uncontested divorces, as there is now. France, Belgium, Germany, Italy, Portugal and most other European countries (except some in Scandinavia) maintain some kind of distinction between divorces in which both spouses want to end a marriage, and those in which only one does. Typically, where there is an unwilling spouse, he or she can delay a divorce, but not deny it indefinitely. Critics of Lord Mackay's bill argue that removing this distinction undermines the principle that marriage is binding: it makes matrimony the only form of contract that one party can breach without penalty.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second provision that would make Britain different from many of its European neighbours concerns mediation. The legislation recommends using counsellors, rather than lawyers, to reach a settlement, in order to make divorce less nasty. Just as getting rid of fault eliminates the need to tell, or make up, outrageous stories about the "guilty" spouse, getting rid of the lawyers (some of the time, anyway) is supposed to minimise conflict.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although mediation is presented as voluntary, in practice it may often be mandatory. About three-quarters of divorces are sought by women; three-quarters of these use legal aid. To the extent that legal-aid money is instead used for mediation, the effect could be to limit legal assistance. Feminists fear that more women than men would be hurt by this. Perhaps, but feminist-friendly Australia and Canada have long emphasised mediation, and are happy with it. New Zealand has gone furthest of all. Its state mediation service is free to all couples; the government claims a high rate of reconciliation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Curiously, mediation seems an English-language phenomenon, perhaps a response to the ferociously confrontational nature of Anglo-Saxon legal systems. Nowhere in continental Europe (except a few Swiss cantons) has come out as strongly as Britain in favour of mediation. Although Germany encourages the practice, Belgium actually removed a requirement to mediate in 1994. Scandinavian countries and the Netherlands work on the principle that, if a couple wants to split, the partners should work out the details by themselves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The third point of difference between Britain and the rest is that Lord Mackay is using divorce reform explicitly to assert the value of marriage. Reducing the trauma of divorce presents opportunities to save salvageable marriages, which he argues is the state's duty and in its interest. And yet by treating all divorce alike and putting a larger burden on the couple to come to terms, Britain would be moving in a distinctly Scandinavian direction. The Scandinavians, though, do not share Lord Mackay's view of marriage. They see it as a voluntary arrangement between two individuals, and divorce as an individual right that should be easy to exercise.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One issue no country has come to grips with is that a large minority of divorced fathers lose interest in their children. In Britain, two years after divorce about 40% of fathers have stopped visiting regularly; and Sweden is not alone in reporting that the proportion of men paying child support is slipping. Such paternal aloofness can damage children in ways that show up in their behaviour, schooling and health. Through the much-hated Child Support Agency, Britain seeks to enforce the collection of child support, but the divorce bill goes no further in defining parental obligations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other countries are experimenting with ways to instil the idea that post-divorce fatherhood means more than sending a cheque. Germany's proposed family law stresses that the non-custodial parent (almost always the father) retains legal responsibility; it also appeals to parents to respect their child's desire to see the absent parent. Australia's new family law encourages couples to draw up detailed "parenting plans". A number of countries, including Portugal, the Netherlands, Sweden and Denmark, promote "joint responsibility" arrangements that assert both parents' legal responsibility for their children. It is too early to say whether such legal remedies have had any effect. In practice, mothers are still likely to do most of the work, with occasional assistance from dad.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?827532000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br3.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
