<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>High and dry</b> &nbsp;
At a public inquiry into the water shortages in Yorkshire last summer, Yorkshire Water denied claims that it had proposed evacuating a million people from their homes if reservoirs ran out. Trevor Newton, its managing director, resigned, saying it had nothing to do with the inquiry.</p>
<p><b>Talk is cheap</b> &nbsp;
Oftel, the telecoms regulator, said that from next year <font size=-1>BT</font> would have to cut its prices by up to 9% a year in real terms, because its profits were " supernormal" compared with other telecoms operators worldwide.</p>
<p><b>KO'd</b> &nbsp;
In Britain's first trial of pay-per-view television, an estimated 600,000 households paid to see Britain's Frank Bruno beaten in the third round by America's Mike Tyson for the <font size=-1>WBC</font> world heavyweight boxing title.</p>
<p><b>No appeal</b> &nbsp;
Rosemary West was denied leave to appeal against her convictions for murdering ten young women and girls.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><p><b>Society wedding ring</b> &nbsp;

Introducing a new law to give building societies broader powers, the government unexpectedly proposed that societies planning to merge would be "ring-fenced" from takeover bids for up to a year.</p>
<p><b>Money-making route</b> &nbsp;
John Watts, a transport minister, said the maintenance of England's motorways and trunk roads would be taken out of local councils' control and opened up to competition from private firms.</p>
<p><b>Inflating</b> &nbsp;
A surprise rise in underlying inflation in February, by 0.6% month-on-month to an annual rate of 2.9%, hit hopes of further interest-rate cuts, and led to some calls for a rate rise.</p>
<p><b>Addicted</b> &nbsp;
Heroin seems to be back in fashion, customs officers said. They seized a record 1,117kg last year.</p>
<p><b>Eyes down</b> &nbsp;
Staff at a bingo club in Coventry became the first to pass a new National Vocational Qualification in gaming. As well as demonstrating their knowledge of the rules, they were tested on their communication skills and understanding of health and safety laws.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
