<html><head><title>Stay back, China</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p><h1><center>Stay back, China</center></h1>THEY may be only war games this time, but the roar of China's guns and missiles in the seas close to Taiwan brings Asia to a dangerous turning-point. China's blatant attempt to intimidate Taiwan before its first democratic presidential election, on March 23rd, suddenly has East Asia's most populous power eyeball-to-eyeball with its fourth-largest economic power, with all the damage that an accidental clash or a military miscalculation could do to stability in the region. But China's challenge goes beyond that. It cannot safely be left unanswered.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By using force to press its claim to Taiwan--as, last year, to vast tracts of the South China Sea--China has once again served notice on its neighbours and on the United States, the country with the greatest influence in the region, that it now feels strong enough to play Asia's power game by its own rules and win. If China is allowed to get away with bullying Taiwan, the security of one of the world's most dynamic, and potentially richest, regions will be in jeopardy. Yet standing up more stoutly to an increasingly pushy China will take the sort of clear thinking and plain talking that China's neighbours prefer to avoid.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not just that the East Asians are wary of attracting mighty China's wrath--though they are. They had hoped, as western governments had, that reforms at home, combined with fast-growing trade with the outside world, would give China a big enough economic stake in the region in general and in Taiwan in particular to want to avoid a bust-up. Renegade province though it supposedly is, Taiwan is, after all, one of the biggest investors in the mainland. But money-making has not proved enough of a distraction for the newly assertive China. Meanwhile, other pressures have been at work that now make the China-Taiwan tiff too dangerous to shrug off, as East Asia's governments are still trying to do, as an " internal" Chinese affair (see <a href="as1.html">pages</a>).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As China has grown in weight and confidence, so has Taiwan. Its huge overseas trade (12th in the world) and vast foreign-exchange reserves (second only to Japan's) make it an economic power in its own right. More important, it will soon have a properly elected president with a legitimate claim to speak for Taiwan's 21m people. That government would be foolish to provoke China unnecessarily by declaring independence, but it cannot simply ignore popular will. To judge by opinion polls, there is as yet no majority in Taiwan for declaring independence (if only because that would certainly provoke a direct Chinese military attack), but there is even less support for unification with the mainland. Contrary to China's expectations, and no doubt to its even greater annoyance, this week's gunfire diplomacy will probably diminish one-China enthusiasm still further.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By contrast, China's leaders, locked in an unnerving--and seemingly never-ending--struggle to succeed Deng Xiaoping, have only China's visceral nationalism to fall back on as their justification for holding on to power. As China's economy has grown, so its armed forces have added new muscle. Although the end of the cold war brought a hope of greater peace in Asia than most countries, including China, have known for a couple of centuries, China has deliberately taken it as an opportunity to press its territorial claims by force.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The opportunity has no doubt looked all the more promising because America, preoccupied with domestic politics, has begun to scale down its military role in Asia. China's row with the Philippines last year over reefs in the South China Sea produced only a belated and barely audible squeak of protest from Washington. So when Taiwan started to push harder and more successfully for a higher profile around the world, China saw no reason not to shove forcefully back.</p><p><b>Drawing dragon claws</b><br>This time, to its credit, America has responded swiftly and prudently. By moving two aircraft carriers close to Taiwan, it has sent an unmistakable signal that it will not allow Taiwan to be toyed with at China's whim. If China steps up the harassment, America could do a lot more, from patrolling the Taiwan Strait to helping Taiwan get hold of more of the equipment, including missile defences, that it needs to protect itself. And if China is bent on war, America could muster enough firepower to disrupt any attempt either to blockade Taiwan or to invade it.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet China may already feel it has achieved a lot. By firing even unarmed missiles close to Taiwan's main ports and forcing ships and aircraft to be rerouted, it has demonstrated the island's vulnerability. Judging by the pusillanimous response from most governments in the region, China may also have concluded that, come the next crisis, America would find even less support for a tough response.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet there is plenty, well short of military action, that others could do to avert such a crisis. China's leaders may be in a mood to set territorial claims above economic needs in part because they calculate that using force against Taiwan would do China no lasting damage. The message therefore needs to be conveyed--and not just by America, but by East Asians and Europeans too--that a lunge for Taiwan or an attempt to strangle its economy would make China an economic as well as political outcast: such loutishness should immediately lose China the trading benefits it now enjoys and bar it from the world's economic and financial clubs.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;East Asia's governments squirm when faced with such plain speaking. Yet helping America to hold China to the rules of peaceable behaviour is the only way to preserve the stability on which the region's continued prosperity depends. In the end, the best solution to the Taiwan problem for all concerned would be a political deal, negotiated between the two governments. But Taiwan points out, reasonably, that it will not negotiate under duress. And China will see the point of talking only if it is convinced that it stands to lose less by talking than by gunfire. By contrast, appeasing China over Taiwan will only feed China's appetite for trouble.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="as1.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
