<html><head><title>Is Taiwan really part of China?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" alt="Asia">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Is Taiwan really part of China?</h1>

<p>ONE sure way to baffle and shock any Chinese citizen is to quote what Mao Zedong had to say about Taiwan in 1936. "The immediate task of China", he said, was "to regain all its lost territories." But he added that that did not include Japanese-occupied Korea, which instead was promised "enthusiastic help in its struggle for independence." He went on: "the same thing applies to Taiwan."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To many Chinese today, it is unbelievable that such an arch-nationalist should have spoken so cavalierly of independence for what is now an "inalienable part of China's sovereign territory". They have been brought up to regard the "division" of China as an historical accident: the arbitrary ceasefire line in an unfinished civil war, like the demilitarised zone across the Korean peninsula. This illusion is fostered by Taiwan's anomalous control of small islands just off the mainland coast, which prompted two crises in the 1950s, and may yet spark another.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But when Mao spoke, his attitude was consistent with the way China had always dealt with Taiwan: as an afterthought. When, in 1623, China faced a Dutch demand for a trading post to match Portugal's at Macau, the Chinese official who ceded one by pointing at Taiwan thought he had pulled off a crafty ruse. He was fobbing the barbarians off with a disease-ridden haunt of pirates, home to some Chinese settlers, but outside any formal Chinese jurisdiction.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Dutch lost control of Taiwan in 1662, when Koxinga, a half-Japanese general, fled there from China with the military remnants of the Ming dynasty, as it crumbled in the face of the Manchu armies. The government of mainland China gained control of the island only in 1683, when it defeated Koxinga's son.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even after this victory, Taiwan was run more like a colony than a fully integrated part of China. The imperial powers had two main interests on the island: keeping down insurrection and importing its rice and sugar. For military and economic reasons, the authorities in Beijing began paying more attention to Taiwan in the second half of the 19th century, but it was only in 1887 that its status was upgraded to that of a full province. Eight years later, however, it became Japan's first colony. By the time Mao was speaking, Taiwan had been a Japanese colony longer than Korea had.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Chinese sovereignty over Taiwan dates from the 1943 Cairo Declaration, in which the allies decided what to do with Japan's empire after the war. Many Taiwanese, wistful for independence, regarded the nationalists as another occupying army, which was largely consistent with the army's behaviour after the Japanese surrender in 1945. To this day, one of the most significant divisons in Taiwan is between mainlanders who arrived with Chiang and "Taiwanese", most of whose forebears arrived centuries before.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At Cairo, the Americans had assumed that post-war China would be under Chiang Kai-shek's nationalists. When Chiang lost the civil war and was driven into Taiwan in 1949, he, like the Communists, was committed to the ideal of "Chinese reunification". As a result, the nationalists engaged in a war of diplomatic attrition with the Communists for recognition as the government of "China". They gradually lost the support of all their important allies and, in 1971, their seat at the United Nations. As countries switched diplomatic recognition to the mainland, the protocols they signed recognised Taiwan as "part of China".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Chinese conviction that "Taiwan is part of China" may be relatively recent, but is nonetheless visceral. It seems to be based on geographic proximity, which is hardly an argument, ethnic kinship, which is not much stronger (is New Zealand, for example, an "inalienable" part of Britain?), and "international law", which seems to mean other countries' acquiescence in the formulation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Throughout Taiwan's history, its fate has been decided elsewhere. It was handed to the Dutch in talks in Fujian, to Japan after a war in Manchuria, and to China in Cairo. The effrontery of Taiwan's people in recent years has been to suggest they might have a say themselves.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="as3.html">Next article</a>
</p>
