<html><head><title>Knocking knees</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" alt="Asia">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>


<h1>Knocking knees</h1>

<p><font size=1>BANGKOK</font></p>
<p>IF AMERICA was hoping that its firmness over Taiwan would embolden China's Asian neighbours, it will have been disappointed. The response of most of South-East Asia would make an ostrich seem bold. Only Singapore's elder statesman, Lee Kuan Yew, has discussed the crisis with any frankness, acknowledging its seriousness and suggesting that it might be defused if the Taiwanese drop their bid to join the <font size=-1>UN</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No country has criticised China and most of South-East Asia has striven to sound neutral. Thailand's foreign minister, Kasem Kasemsri, went further. "When a country conducts military exercises on its own territory to deter its province from breaking away," he asked, "would you oppose it?" Since its prime minister is making a visit to China later this month, Thailand is particularly keen to preserve good relations. It even took the unusual step on March 13th of trying to block a press conference in Bangkok to launch a report by Amnesty International on human-rights abuses in China.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Indonesia, which like China may fear for its territorial integrity, there has even been some criticism of American actions<i>. Kompas</i>, one of Indonesia's largest newspapers, speculated that the United States might be more inclined to confront China because of disputes over human rights and intellectual property. If so, the paper concluded, "then the <font size=-1>US</font> action is deplorable." 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But even countries like Vietnam and the Philippines, which have territorial disputes with China in the South China Sea and have attracted pots of investment from Taiwan, refrained from outright condemnation of the exercises. They must hope that, if China ever rounds on them, the rest of Asia will react a little more boldly.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
