<html><head><title>Don't help us</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Small businesses</b></p>
<h1>Don't help us</h1>

<p>IT WAS a bit of an anticlimax. A leaked letter between ministers had suggested that the government was about to abolish the employment rights of the millions of people who work for small firms. When John Major spoke to a gathering of business leaders on March 11th, he announced only a timid set of measures to aid small firms, including a promise that the government will pay its bills more promptly. The prime minister is still said to be wondering whether curbing workers' rights would result in more jobs in small firms (and more votes for the Tory party). If he decides to do more, he faces some difficulties.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The European Court reminded him of one of these on March 12th: the government's power to liberalise Britain's labour laws is checked by its treaty obligations in the European Union. The court overruled Britain's attempt to avoid an <font size=-1>EU</font>-wide rule setting a maximum working week of 48 hours. A more surprising problem is that, whatever the economic merits of labour-law reform, many of its intended beneficiaries seem far from excited at the prospect.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At his meeting with business leaders, Mr Major was given a report on what 800 small firms wanted from the government. They did grumble about employment rights, industrial tribunals and so on. But they did not call for them to be abolished. The government may be mistaking the weight that small firms attach to the issue. Of the 100 or so recommendations in the report, only 16 were calls for deregulation--and there were nine calls for more regulation, such as stricter laws on the disqualification of company directors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Similarly, Labour's proposed minimum wage is not as unpopular among employers as ministers hoped. Their attempts to stir a fuss over the issue at the Confederation of British Industry's conference last November fell flat. Some security and cleaning firms, for example, want a minimum wage, to stop them being undercut by rivals who pay their workers less. In a study of 174 small firms, carried out last year by Kingston University, 56% said a minimum wage of &#163;4 an hour (probably more than Labour would impose) would not harm them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;David Storey of Warwick University questions claims that cutting workers' rights and other "red tape" would create many new jobs. Mr Storey divides small firms into three categories. First are the "short life" firms--weak businesses, virtually doomed to fail whatever happens. Second are the "trundlers", firms whose owners are happy as things are and have no desire to expand. Finally, there are the "flyers" , the 4% or so of small firms that are both able and willing to grow quickly. This small proportion, says Mr Storey, creates about half of all new jobs. His research finds that these firms rarely complain that labour laws are holding them back.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for getting the owners of small firms to vote Conservative, the Kingston study brings more gloomy news for Mr Major. Only 14% of owners of small firms thought a Labour government would be bad for their business; 29% said it would help.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
