<html><head><title>A mess on the Mersey</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Local government</b></p>
<h1>A mess on the Mersey</h1>

<p><font size=1>LIVERPOOL</font></p>
<p>IN THE old days of the hard left, Liverpool appeared to suffer from too many Labour councillors. Now its problem seems to be too few. Labour's slim grip on power in the city is one of the reasons why, on March 10th, the council voted to increase its council-tax bills by 4.5%, making the &#163;1,006 bill for properties worth &#163;68,000-88,000 the highest in the country for the third year running.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Liverpool's councillors say that their tax rate for this property price-range is bound to be higher than other cities because they have fewer high-value, higher tax-paying properties. Some 68% of the city's houses are valued at less than &#163;40,000. But that cannot be the whole story: 64% of neighbouring Knowsley's properties are valued at under &#163;40,000, and although its economy is in as bad a shape as Liverpool's, and its council was in as much of a mess until recently, it set a proud &#163;774 tax rate for the band that gets hit for a grand in Liverpool.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The main difference between Knowsley and Liverpool is that in 1988, Knowsley council's ruling Labour group, after purging the hard left from its ranks, decided that the council needed a new broom. The council appointed a chief executive, David Henshaw, who not only improved services but also persuaded councillors to cut the workforce by a third even though Knowsley's 15% unemployment rate is more than twice the national average.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The ruling Labour group in Liverpool has cut around 20% of the council's workers since 1988, but, because of its own weakness, has found it hard to push the efficiency drive as far as Knowsley's. Whereas Labour holds 63 out of 66 seats in Knowsley, in Liverpool it has only 50 out of 99 seats, to the Lib Dems' 42. With Liverpool's jobless rate at 17%, councillors are understandably reluctant to increase it in case their own jobs are axed by vengeful voters. Even after the high tax rate was announced, crowds were outside city hall protesting at service cuts threatened in some areas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Divisions in the Labour group make it even harder for the council to take tough decisions. Its leader, Harry Rimmer, survived a recent deselection attempt only after regional party officials intervened.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Councillors would find it easier to streamline local government if the private sector were to create lots of jobs. But the problem is circular. At Knowsley, where Mr Henshaw has reformed the planning department, the council took just three weeks in December last year to give a television-shopping company, <font size=-1>QVC</font>, permission to build a warehouse and telephone-service centre expected to employ 1,100 people. Liverpool's failure to pull in such prizes perpetuates its problems.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
