<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>Stud down</b> &nbsp;
Will Carling said he would resign after eight years as England's rugby-union captain, denying that it had anything to do with allegations about his relationship with the Princess of Wales.</p>
<p><b>Outed</b> &nbsp;
David Ashby, a Tory <font size=-1>MP</font> who lost a libel case against the <i>Sunday Times</i>, which said he was homosexual, was dropped as parliamentary candidate by his Leicestershire North West constituency party.</p>
<p><b>Prudence pays</b> &nbsp;
The Prudential, Britain's largest life insurer, revealed plans to share between its policyholders and shareholders a surplus in its investment funds said to be worth up to &#163;5 billion.</p>
<p><b>Gushing</b> &nbsp;
A study sponsored by Britain's offshore oil and gas industry said that reserves are still rising, production has still not reached a peak, and there will be enough to satisfy national demand for at least the next 15 years.</p>
<p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><b>Split</b> &nbsp;
The government successfully fought off an attempt in the House of Lords to extend the minimum period between the requesting and granting of a divorce from 12 to 18 months in cases where children were involved or the split was contested.</p>

<p><b>Emergency</b> &nbsp;
The Audit Commission called for an urgent review of hospitals' accident and emergency units. It suggested that around 30 are too small to be viable, and should close.</p>
<p><b>Unthinking</b> &nbsp;
Ignoring protests from Jewish groups and academics, Oxford University's Balliol College accepted a &#163;350,000 donation from Gert-Rudolph Flick, grandson of a convicted Nazi war criminal, to found a professorship in the history of European thought.</p>
<p><b>Phantom scribbler</b> &nbsp;
Simon Sunderland, a graffiti artist, was jailed for five years by a court in Sheffield, after defacing buildings and bridges for more than a decade.</p>
<p><b>Little monsters</b> &nbsp;
A Cardiff pet shop is to charge a &#163;1 admission fee to deter children because, the owner says, they cause stress to his reptiles.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
