<html><head><title>Israel's abyss</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<h1><center>Israel's abyss</center></h1>

IS THE Middle East peace process slipping into history? It could be. The bomb that tore bodies apart in the heart of Tel Aviv on March 4th, after similar atrocities in Jerusalem, may have tipped the balance. Any scramble back to sanity will be extraordinarily difficult, even if the outrages stop. Israelis, traumatised by the slaughter of some 60 people, believe they have been cheated in their land-for-peace deal with the Palestinians. But the alternative is bleak: three years of courageous risk-taking undone, a cruel war of attrition, an end to Israel's hopes of normal relations with the Muslim world. The evil men behind the suicide-bombers can congratulate themselves. Seldom, it seems, has terrorism been more effective at achieving its ends.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Palestinian-Israeli negotiation had reached a turning-point, the first interim stage all but completed, the search for a permanent solution about to begin. Most Israelis and most West Bankers and Gazans liked what was happening. Despite the acknowledged obstacles ahead--the status of Jerusalem, for instance--both sides believed that they would probably get there in the end. But now the process, always fragile, is cracking as Israeli public opinion, always volatile, starts to swing vehemently against it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first bus-bombing in Jerusalem on February 25th eliminated Shimon Peres's comfortable lead in the approach to Israel's election on May 29th. The Tel Aviv bomb cast doubt on his ability even to remain prime minister for the next three months (see <a href="ir1.html">page</a>). Another bomb would almost certainly do for him. And Labour's loss of power, whether it comes now or after the election, could spell the end of a peace process that has been identified with Mr Peres and his men since secret talks began in Oslo three years ago. Though Binyamin Netanyahu, the leader of the Likud opposition, now says that he would not reverse what has so far happened, his intention to leave things stuck as they are, allowing Palestinians municipal autonomy within self-contained cantons, makes barely better, or safer, sense.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Striving to protect his people and to save himself politically, Mr Peres is faced with the problem of not knowing where to strike or at whom--an impotence that adds to the national anger. Emergency measures to make Israel's cities more secure are the first, obvious necessity. This means not only more soldiers in the streets but the end, at least for the time being, of Mr Peres's hopes of Israelis and Palestinians living peaceably together: separation is now the ugly rule. Beyond this, Israeli soldiers are swarming into West Bank villages, punishing the families and neighbours of suicide-bombers and suspected terrorists. This has the vengeful smell of collective punishment, but its main purpose is to deter other would-be " martyrs" by showing that while they skip off to paradise their mothers will be homeless.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though Mr Peres, in a vote-tugging flourish, has given the army freedom to go where it will, it has so far restrained itself from plunging back into the Palestinian cities it withdrew from so recently. It should stick to this self-restraint if it can. Even if the soldiers were to track down their quarry, which they admit is difficult, their return would dilute Palestinian opposition to terrorism--and signal that the clock had been truly turned back from peace to no-peace.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But if Israeli troops hold back, Yasser Arafat's men must do the job for them. Mr Arafat, who no less than Mr Peres stands or falls by the peace process, has outlawed all militia groups, made wide arrests and promised to co-operate fully with Israel "to wipe out terrorism". Yet he is not doing enough to satisfy the Israelis. Is this because he will not, or because he cannot? The statements made in the name of Hamas's military arm, Izzadin al-Qassam, offering conditional ceasefires just before a new bombing, were despicable, not worth a straw. But they do suggest that the movement is split, making its more lethal branches, perhaps protected by outsiders, even harder to get at.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Where Mr Arafat does break ranks with the Israelis is in hesitating to take on Hamas's religious and political structure--though, in answer to Israeli pressure, his police have begun raiding schools and mosques. He would be wise to be careful, even though money for Hamas charities does indeed make its way to the militia, and to the sheikhs who preach martyrdom. It remains vital, in the interests of peace, for Mr Arafat to keep his lines open to Hamas's political leaders.
</p><p><b>No prospect pleases</b>
<br>The Arab-Israeli prospect, which had been smiling, is suddenly grim. But more and more Israelis, earlier opinions turned on their head by the terrorist mayhem, are arguing that "peace" with the Palestinians is the grimmest prospect of all, costing them more lives than the Palestinian uprising ever did. Israelis are giving up land but are not being allowed to live in peace. Moreover, whatever land-for-peace deal is finally struck, most of the world's Palestinians will remain dissatisfied, their eyes fixed on the bits of Israel-proper where their families once lived.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this is true. Yet the alternative is worse. A frozen peace process will not freeze violence: on the contrary, the collapse of Palestinian hope would cut such restraints as there are. Nor would Israel be able to isolate itself from an area that it would, in effect, be reoccupying: the suicide-bombers who this week crossed into Israel and found their way into the centre of its cities showed the permeability of even sealed frontiers. And though the <i>intifada</i>, the three-year mass uprising in which youngsters armed with stones challenged the military occupiers, will not resume, a new version of Palestinian revolt, and Israeli reprisal, could be much nastier: grown-up men with grown-up arms, killing indiscriminately.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After a horrible two weeks, such a scene is no longer wholly remote. It can be avoided, but only if Israelis and Palestinians reflect clear-eyed on the choices before them. For this they need a period of calm. Let us hope they get one.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826322400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ir1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
