<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<h2>Peace on the rack</h2><p>Islamist suicide-bombers struck again, killing 19 people in Jerusalem and 13 in Tel Aviv, and imperilling the entire <b>Middle East peace process</b>. Fighting for political survival, Shimon Peres responded to widespread anger by sending Israel's army into the West Bank to punish the bombers' relatives, close Islamic institutions and catch as many militants as it could. Yasser Arafat's security forces made widespread arrests in the areas they control.
<p><b>Iranians </b>were due to go to the polls on March 8th to elect a new Majlis (parliament). No genuine challenge to the Islamic republic was allowed but reformists and conservatives, operating within the system, fought each other in an intense week-long campaign.</p>
<p>Muhammad Massari, a leading <b>Saudi dissident </b>living in London, half-won his appeal against the British government's trade-related attempt to deport him to Dominica. The government was ordered to think again.</p>
<p><b>Nelson Mandela</b> was pronounced "in excellent health" by doctors after undergoing medical tests at a clinic. Rumours about the health of the 77-year-old South African president had caused the currency to fall sharply.</p>
<p><b>Benin's</b> election went to a second round after President Nic&eacutephore Soglo almost tied with the former Marxist dictator, Mathieu K&eacuter&eacutekou.</p>
<h2>Spain's right wins</h2>
<p>Jose Maria Aznar, leader of the conservative People's Party, won <b>Spain's</b> <b>general election</b> on March 3rd, ending 13 years of Socialist rule under Felipe Gonzalez. The margin was narrower than expected and 20 seats short of a majority. Mr Aznar is trying to strike a deal with moderate Catalan nationalists to form a government.</p>
<p>Turkey's two main centre-right parties, Mesut Yilmaz's Motherland and Tansu Ciller's True Path, at last agreed to form a <b>coalition government</b>, excluding the Islamic-minded Welfare party, which won the most seats in December's general election. Under the agreement Mr Yilmaz and Mrs Ciller take it in turns to be prime minister.</p>
<p>Heavy fighting was reported around <b>Grozny, </b>the Chechen capital, after rebels launched a new offensive and retook parts of the city.</p>
<p>(<a href="wtw1.gif">See chart</a>)<br>The size of <b>Europe's population </b>is likely to stay the same over the next three decades, but the proportion of people over 60 will go up by a half, according to a study by the European Commission. Europe's median age, 36 today, is likely to hit 45 in 2025.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Austria's</b> two main parties, to the left and right of centre, agreed to renew a coalition government under the present chancellor, Franz Vranitzky.</p>
<p>An opinion poll suggested that the French remain <b>split down the middle</b> over the future of Europe. A single European currency by 2000 is favoured by 49%, with 42% against. Asked if the date set for <font size=-1>EMU</font>--1999--should be postponed, 42% said yes, whereas 43% said "everything should be done" for the single currency to be brought in on time.
<h2>Here comes Bob</h2>
</p>
<p>Senator Bob Dole swept the board in the Republican <b>presidential primaries</b> in South Carolina, Georgia, Massachusetts, Colorado and several smaller states. His total of delegates looked unbeatable, and he was endorsed by the speaker of the House, Newt Gingrich. Lamar Alexander abandoned the race and endorsed Mr Dole but Steve Forbes battled on. So too did Pat Buchanan, determined to keep his populist voice in the campaign, although he called Mr Dole's nomination "inevitable" .</p>
<p>Colombia was listed by the American government as a country not co-operating enough in the fight against <b>drugs</b>. It will forfeit American aid, as will Afghanistan, Myanmar, Iran, Nigeria and Syria. Peru and Bolivia, named last year, were removed from the list.</p>
<p>The American Congress approved a bill tightening sanctions against <b>Cuba</b> by hitting foreign companies doing business there. Canada, the EU and Caribbean countries have protested against the measure.</p>
<h2>Oz turns right</h2>
<p>Australia's Labor Party was crushingly beaten by John Howard's Liberal-National coalition, giving the country its first <b>conservative government </b>for 13 years.</p>
<p>Holders of <b>Hong Kong passports </b>will be able to visit Britain without visas after the British colony is taken over by China next year, said Britain's prime minister, John Major, during a visit to Hong Kong this week.</p>
<p>Singapore has ordered organisations which provide links to the <b>internet</b> to block access to sexually orientated and politically sensitive material.</p>
<p>In a renewed campaign against <b>Taiwan</b>,China proposed to fire missiles in international waters close to the island's main ports. Taiwan appealed for help.</p>
<p>At least 13 people died and hundreds were hurt as voting took place for 92 seats in the <b>Bangladeshi</b> parliament.</p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
