</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Green shoots</h2><p>(<a href="wtw2.gif">See chart</a>)<br><b>American factory orders</b> rose 0.5% in January, faster than analysts had expected, after climbing 1.7% in December, an apparent sign that the economy may be returning to quicker growth.
<p><b>Growth in Japan</b> is likely to pick up this year, but only slowly, according to the Tankan survey of business sentiment conducted by the Bank of Japan.</p>
<p>German<b> unemployment </b>rose by 107,000 in February to a new post-war seasonally-adjusted high of 3.97m. The unemployment rate, based on unadjusted figures, climbed from 10.8% to 11.1%.
<h2>Clinched</h2>
Two of Switzerland's leading pharmaceutical firms, Ciba-Geigy and Sandoz, are to merge to create a new company called <b>Novartis</b>. The new giant, the world's second-biggest drugs enterprise, will have a market capitalisation of SFr75 billion ($63 billion). In 1995 the combined sales of the partners amounted to SFr36 billion.</p>
<p>The profits of <b>Glaxo Wellcome</b>, the product of another big drugs merger last year, rose 30% before tax in 1995, to &#163;2.5 billion ($3.8 billion). But sales of its best-selling drug, Zantac, are falling, and its patent protection in America may lapse next year.</p>
<p>Kvaerner, a Norwegian ship builder, agreed to pay &#163;904m ($1.38 billion) for <b>Trafalgar House</b>, a loss-making British construction-to-shipping conglomerate, valuing Trafalgar at a 30% premium to its market value before the takeover.</p>
<p>Gordon and Anita Roddick, founders of <b>Body Shop International</b>, a British cosmetics group, abandoned plans to convert back into a private company, 12 years after they went public. The Roddicks, who disliked the City's " short-termist" attitudes, said that bank borrowings for a share buyback would have hit future growth.</p>
<p>America's Compaq said it was cutting prices on business desktop computers by as much as 20%, prompting Hewlett-Packard and Digital, two other computer manufacturers, to <b>cut prices</b> too. Before these discounts, price competition had largely been limited to the retail sector of the computer market.</p>
<p>Australia's richest man, <b>Kerry Packer</b>, passed the control of Publishing &amp; Broadcasting, his media company, to his 28-year-old son, James. Mr Packer will, however, remain chairman of Consolidated Press, a private company that controls about 45% of Publishing &amp; Broadcasting. In December <b>Rupert Murdoch</b>, boss of News Corp, another media group, appointed his 24-year-old son Lachlan deputy chief executive of the company's Australian operations.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>In Germany, <b>Escom</b>, one of Europe's largest computer companies, admitted it was asking shareholders and creditors to stump up DM100m ($68m), after losing DM125m in 1995, nearly three times the company's initial estimate. Escom blamed a sharp fall in prices for computer components such as microprocessors and memory chips, which made its stocks less valuable. Escom's share price fell 17% on the news.</p>
<p>Imperial Chemical Industries, the British chemicals, paint and explosives group, signalled the start of a<b> buying spree</b> by purchasing Bunge Paints, South America's biggest paint company, for $390m.</p>
<p><b>BT</b>, Britain's biggest telecoms company, complained to the Spanish competition authorities about the behaviour of <b>Telefonica</b>, Spain's state operator. <font size=-1>BT</font> accused Telefonica of using confidential information to lure its Spanish customers away with offers of lower prices.
<h2>Gold bears</h2><p>(<a href="wtw3.gif">See chart</a>)<br>After climbing to a six-year high of $415 per ounce in February, the price of <b>gold</b> fell to $393, as speculators abandoned the market to buy shares instead.</p>
<p>The Commodity Futures Trading Commission said it would investigate the activities of <b>broker-group associations</b> in the trading pits of America's futures and commodity exchanges. The associations will be scrutinised for anti-competitive behaviour.
<h2>Networking</h2>
America's United Airlines may merge its computer-reservations system with Worldspan Travel Information Services, a rival system owned by Delta Air Lines, Trans World Airlines and Northwest Airlines. This would create the biggest <b>airline-reservations network</b> in America.</p>
<p>International Lease, an American <b>jet-leasing</b> company, is expected to announce $6 billion in orders for new planes from Airbus and Boeing, two big manufacturers, underlining the recent strength of the world commercial plane market.</p>
<p><b>Russia </b>said that it was planning to raise its import tariffs by an average of 20%. But it has shelved plans to block imports of American poultry, following strong American protests.</p>
<p>An appeals court in America threw out a ruling blocking <i>Business Week </i>magazine from publishing details of <b>sealed court documents</b> relating to a suit between Procter &amp; Gamble, a consumer-products giant, and Bankers Trust, an investment bank that had sold the company loss-making derivatives contracts.</p>
<p></p>
</td></tr></table></center>
