<html><head><title>Emergency</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>National Health Service</b></p>
<h1>Emergency</h1>


<p>ANY number of complaints from doctors about the problems of the National Health Service can easily be ignored. A dead child cannot. On March 6th, an inquiry into the death of a ten-year-old boy with a brain haemorrhage who had been shuttled between hospitals blamed health-service management; the same day Stephen Dorrell, the health secretary, announced new guidelines to ensure better use of intensive-care beds. The health service's problems will be underlined on March 13th, when the Audit Commission produces what is expected to be a highly critical report on accident and emergency facilities at hospitals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Public horror at the boy's death reflects a widespread belief that the health service's priority should be to look after people in an emergency. A series of similar failures suggests that this is what the health service is least good at these days.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Part of the problem is that the demand for emergency services has risen unexpectedly. Emergency admissions rose by 13% in 1989-94. The pattern of demand, however, seems uneven. Some hospitals report much sharper rises. Kingston Hospital, for instance, says that if present trends continue, by the end of this year its emergency work will have increased by 50% since 1994.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Doctors have many theories to explain the increase in accident and emergency work. Some blame better drugs and equipment for generating demand: these days, for instance, anybody suspected of a heart tremor will be rushed into hospital for sensitive new tests and treatment. Patients are getting increasingly litigious, too, which may encourage <font size=-1>GP</font>s to get people off their hands by sending them to hospital.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While demand for emergency services is going up, supply is being squeezed because of several developments in the health service. One is the general--and generally benevolent--pressure to use resources more efficiently.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Accident and emergency patients go into either intensive care or emergency beds. There are only 2,600 intensive-care beds in Britain. They are expensive, because they involve round-the-clock specialist care, so there is pressure on cost-conscious hospitals to keep their number down. A survey last year found that such beds were running at high occupancy levels--about 90%. This leaves little slack to cope with unexpected rises in demand.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most emergency patients are put in what are classified as acute beds. Since 1991, 9,000 of these beds have been cut--7% of the total. The fall is partly an effect of trying to keep costs down, but mostly it is the result of medical advances, such as less invasive surgery, which reduce the need for long stays in hospital. Again, though, one side-effect is that there are higher occupancy rates and less slack.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Normally, if acute beds are full and there is a rush of emergency admissions, beds which would otherwise be used for "elective" surgery, such as varicose veins or hip replacements, get used instead. But this means cancelling elective operations. The sticks and carrots of the internal market include financial rewards for hospitals if they hit certain targets for elective work--meeting the Patients' Charter target of making nobody wait for more than 18 months for surgery, or carrying out certain volumes of work. If they do extra emergency work, then, they may lose those bonuses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And extra emergency work does not pay for itself. Hospitals are paid for such work either through a block contract--a lump sum based on a fixed number of admissions--or through a contract that covers the full cost of admissions for a certain number, but pays less than the full cost of each extra patient above that. Either way, hospitals make a loss on extra emergency work.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A further problem is the burden placed on the health service by the government's failure to make proper provision for old people under the community-care programme. A survey of geriatricians carried out by the British Medical Association last year found that 77% of doctors reported difficulties in finding nursing-home places for their hospital patients. In January, Aintree Hospital in Merseyside was unable to discharge 56 patients because local authorities had run out of money to fund community care. Since it costs around &#163;135 a night for an acute bed in a hospital, and &#163;40 for a local nursing-home bed, this does not make a lot of sense.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No doubt hospitals could manage their resources better. But it would also help if the government ensured that its policies sent them the right signals.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826322400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
