<html><head><title>Cuts both ways</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Scottish local government</b></p>
<h1>Cuts both ways</h1><p><font size=1>EDINBURGH</font></p><p>THE government is usually on bad terms with councils, and with Scotland as well, so it is not surprising that the issue of Scottish local-government finance is a wee bit tricky. This year is especially tough, though, because the government has reorganised Scottish councils. So troublesome has the issue become that, on March 7th, Michael Forsyth, the Scottish Secretary, announced an inquiry into the cost of local government in Scotland.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In April, 29 new unitary councils will take over from the 62 two-tier regional and district councils. Although the government gave the new councils 2.9% more than the old councils to spend in this year, the reorganisation, which was supposed to cut costs, threw up some unexpected problems.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Glasgow's new council, for example, found it was getting &#163;750m to cover spending programmes costing &#163;800m because the outgoing Strathclyde Regional Council had favoured Glasgow. A scheme to deal with this by diverting money from councils in the rest of the region to Glasgow reduced the gap from &#163;50m to &#163;20m. But still the Glaswegians complained.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a former Thatcherite hatchet-man, Mr Forsyth is surprisingly flexible; and he is unwilling to erode his party's modest support in Scotland. So on March 4th he dug out an extra &#163;38m from his budget to subsidise bills and raised council-spending ceilings by &#163;58m. Even so, Glasgow's councillors decided the next day, when they could make themselves heard above bawling protestors, to increase the council tax by 19% and cut 2,000 jobs. Other Scottish councils took similar decisions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour smirked at the government's embarrassment. But the Tories' current problems with Scottish councils will pale into insignificance beside those Labour will face if it wins the next general election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Scottish parliament that Labour plans to set up will have to find any extra money for local government (which Labour says was &#163;395m short this year) from the share of public spending (which Labour says will be tightly controlled) that it gets from the Treasury. That implies eating into other parts of the Scottish Office budget, or raising income tax in Scotland.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The parliament, meanwhile, will get no help from Labour local authorities. This year's crisis is happening partly because councils ran down their reserves, built up debts and failed to make staff cuts to finance pay rises. They have passed these problems on to their successors, even though the leaders of the old and new councils are often the same people.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On March 8th the Scottish Labour Party's conference in Edinburgh will revel in Mr Forsyth's discomfort. But some hard thinking will be needed if it is not to be a future target for the same demonstrators who have been barracking the Tories.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826322400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br3.html">Next article</a>
</p>
