<html><head><title>Expensive ride</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>The channel tunnel link</b></p>
<h1>Expensive ride</h1>


<p>IN JUNE 1990 Margaret (now Lady) Thatcher declared that not a penny of public money would go into a 70-mile high-speed rail line linking London with the channel tunnel. On February 29th John Major's government brushed that promise aside and announced that it would provide &#163;1.4 billion towards its &#163;3 billion cost.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And that is only part of the story. The total amount of public subsidy is still unknown because the government has refused, so far, to make available the cost-benefit analysis on which its decision was based. In any case, spectacular <font size=-1>U</font>-turns do not come cheap. London &amp; Continental Railways, the consortium that won the contract to build the line, has also been given the company which runs Eurostar trains between London and Paris and Brussels, as well as a valuable package of railway stations and land in London.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Labour Party estimates that these sweeteners, together with the direct subsidy, are worth &#163;5.7 billion. But this is almost certainly an exaggeration. The assets handed over to the consortium, such as Waterloo International and St Pancras stations, are worth a fraction of the amounts Labour attributes to them. The best proof of this is that the contract to build the line, which included the transfer of assets, was vigorously contested by four big groups of firms. The winning bid was the one which asked for the lowest level of subsidy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, the total subsidy is clearly a lot more than the government cares to admit. Whatever it is, the government justifies heavy subsidies by arguing that the high-speed link will bring &#163;6 billion worth of benefits to the public. But this also looks like an exaggeration. Most of the benefit is said to take the form of quicker journey times, reduced overcrowding and improved reliability of rail travel to the continent. The rest comes from the expected regeneration of decrepit parts of London and benefits to passenger services in the south-east of England.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, the Department of Transport admits that the passenger benefits are based on forecast figures provided by London &amp; Continental. Forecasts have a nasty habit of going wrong. In Eurostar's first year of operation, it carried only 3.5m passengers, barely a third of what it had forecast. And the high-speed link will shave only 30 minutes off the three-hour journey between London and Paris, which is difficult to translate into billions for consumers on even the most generous reckoning.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;David Starkie, a transport economist and adviser to the House of Commons Transport Committee, says that state aid to build the high-speed link raises serious competition issues. How can ministers justify subsidising international rail travel, he asks, when they object to Spain bailing out Iberia, its international airline? Robert Ayling, British Airways' boss, says that his firm will look closely at the rail deal to see whether the subsidies infringe <font size=-1>EU</font> or domestic laws. With so many unhappy voices, the government may be wondering what it is getting for its billions.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826322400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
