<html><head><title>After the bombs</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" alt="Section heading">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>After the bombs</h1>
<p><b>The revival of Islamist terrorism leaves Israel buffeted and Palestinians trapped. Our correspondents report; first, from Jerusalem </b></p>

<p>AS VICTIMS of Sunday's suicide-bomb attack in Jerusalem were being buried the next day, the wailing of sirens drowned the eulogies. A Palestinian driver, had deliberately run his car into a crowd of hitch-hikers in the north of the city and had been shot dead by passers-by. Or had it all been an accident? Police evidence, backed by a less-than-reliable statement from Hamas's military wing, strongly suggests that he had indeed meant to do what he did. But the confusion seemed to symbolise Israel's distraught condition as Islamist terrorism returned after a six-month respite. Twenty-four people had been killed by the bus-bomber in Jerusalem; one by another suicide-bomber in Ashkelon the same day.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;During the 1994-95 bombings, the question after each incident was whether negotiations with the Palestinians could go on. This time, the negotiations, having produced an interim result, are on hold anyway, pending Israel's election on May 29th. The question now is the electoral impact of renewed terrorism. The prospects for the peace process depend on this. The right-wing Likud, while grudgingly accepting the present arrangements, remains implacably opposed to eventual Palestinian independence. The governing Labour Party is moving steadily towards a " two-state solution".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In an opinion poll conducted within hours of the two bombings, the lead of Labour's Shimon Peres over the Likud's Binyamin Netanyahu swung from a previous nine points to just two. Maybe the pendulum will swing back, if there are no further attacks. But how far? One pollster, Mina Tsemach, points to a key block of what she calls "emotional voters" who had switched from Likud to Labour after the murder of Yitzhak Rabin last November. Now they seem to have switched back.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet one group, she notes, appears to be more constant than others: first-time voters, who have been politically galvanised by Rabin's assassination. "For them, peace is more important than anything," says Ms Tsemach. "Terrorism will not shift them."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In another way Israeli reaction is different from that provoked by earlier bombings. Then, thousands of people were ready to gather at the site, cursing the prime minister and his peace policy. Opposition politicians made a point of being photographed among the angry crowds. This time the demonstrators were few in number, and the politicians stayed away. "Now is a time for unity in mourning and unity in strength," said a newly statesmanlike Mr Netanyahu. Raucous recrimination no longer fits the national mood.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The superficial moderation of the public debate should not, however, give Mr Peres and his party cause for confidence. The fear and the fury engendered by earlier mass-killings are present again, albeit in more silent, sullen form. Instant polls cannot take the full measure of the emotional storm buffeting the soul of the nation. It is almost as if the shooting of Yitzhak Rabin and this week's bus-bombings were vying with each other for Israeli hearts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new terrorism has freed some right-leaning voters from the inhibitions that evolved after Rabin's murder by a far-right religious fanatic. It has also brought a dramatic closing of ranks. David Levy, a former foreign minister who left the Likud last year to form his own party, is now negotiating his way back. This deal, concluded in principle though still to be signed, comes after a similar pact between the Likud and Tsomet, another right-wing party, led by a former army commander, Rafael Eitan.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Netanyahu is having to pay a heavy price in terms of safe slots on Likud's list of Knesset candidates. His reward is that Mr Eitan, and now Mr Levy, will not stand for the prime ministership, leaving him and Mr Peres to slug it out alone. There will be no later run-off, as there would have been in a multiple-horse race. Mr Netanyahu regards this as critical to his chances. The group that so often holds the key to Israeli elections, the ultra-orthodox, will turn out on May 29th to vote for their own Knesset candidates, and some will take the opportunity to vote for Mr Netanyahu at the same time. But would they bother to turn out a second time? Probably not.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Mr Peres, the bombings and their political fall-out have been a nightmare come true. His opinion-poll ratings had slipped slightly in recent weeks, but the gap opened up by the Rabin murder had been so wide that he remained confident of victory. His strategy had been to follow as centrist and uncontroversial a course as possible. Now he has to demonstrate toughness, partly in order to convince middle-of-the-road Israelis that Yasser Arafat is a dependable partner in peace. In pursuit of this, he sent the army chief of staff, Lieut-General Amnon Shahak, to demand that the Palestinian Authority arrest a string of known Islamic activists in the Gaza Strip.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The two suicide-bombers themselves, young Hamas supporters, came from the Hebron region, which is still under Israeli military rule--awkward for those who want to blame all outrages on Mr Arafat's incompetence or bad faith. But Israel insists, credibly enough, that the explosives, the orders and the religious inspiration all came from inside Gaza. So Mr Peres threatens to postpone the handover of most of Hebron to Palestinian rule, due at the end of March, unless Mr Arafat co-operates. Meanwhile, he has reimposed an indefinite closure of the border between Israel and the West Bank and Gaza. He will be under strong pressure from his election managers to keep it closed until polling day.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825717600,iss">Search</a>
