<html><head><title>Welshing on devolution</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>


<h1>Welshing on devolution</h1>

<p>IT WOULD be nice to think that the new powers for local government in Wales announced by William Hague, the Welsh secretary, in a Commons debate on February 29th, represented a belated Tory conversion to the merits of local democracy. It would be nice but it would be wrong. Mr Hague's proposals are really aimed at embarrassing Labour over its plans for a new Welsh assembly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In his speech, Mr Hague proposed to transfer &#163;35m of funds for miscellaneous economic and social-development projects from his Welsh Office to local government. Local councils will also get control of &#163;364m of <font size=-1>EU</font> structural funds going to Wales. In future this will be handled by an independent executive controlled by the local authorities, rather than the Welsh Office.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These measures follow his announcement in November of a bigger role for the Welsh grand committee of <font size=-1>MP</font>s. It will be able to question ministers and will hold half its meetings in Wales.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both measures are designed to take the steam out of Labour's commitment to Welsh devolution. In Scotland, where most attention on Labour's devolution plans has been focused, most Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s are strongly for an assembly. But Labour's 27 Welsh <font size=-1>MP</font>s range between enthusiasts for a powerful Welsh assembly and those who would rather not have one at all.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Recently Labour has built a fragile unity around a plan devised by Ron Davies, the shadow Welsh secretary. He proposes an assembly that would not have legislative or tax-raising powers, but to which the Welsh Office and Welsh quangos would be accountable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In opposing those plans, Mr Hague hopes to make an ally of Welsh local councils. The most powerful of these, including Cardiff, are Labour-controlled. Local councillors are nervous that a new Welsh assembly would erode their responsibilities. By giving councils more power, Mr Hague hopes to convince them to criticise Labour's plans, rekindling the dissent in Labour's ranks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Tory share of the Welsh vote has halved since the 1992 general election, according to recent public-opinion surveys by <font size=-1>MORI</font>, a polling firm. All six Tory seats in the province are at risk. As Welsh opinion is divided about devolution, opposing it may be a clever political move.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, with only one in seven Welsh voters now saying they will vote Tory--even fewer than in Scotland--the Tories face a difficulty. How much longer can they project themselves as the party of the union, when they have almost disappeared as a political force in three of the United Kingdom's four countries?

</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825717600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
