<html><head><title>Downbeat</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Policing</b></p>
<h1>Downbeat</h1>


<p>SICK leave is a reasonable indicator of unhappiness with a job. So it is fair to conclude that, with sick leave among police forces ranging up to 20 days per officer per year, and patrol officers the sickest of the lot, that the bobby on the beat is none too happy these days.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is one of the central problems of modern policing. Patrol policing is what the public wants; it satisfies some of the fastest-growing demands on police forces; it fits in with modern trends in crime-prevention. But policemen do not like it. A report published by the Audit Commission on February 29th, and one by the Police Federation a week earlier, both address the problem, but offer different solutions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Around 60% of police officers are patrol constables. The gloom that pervades their ranks was illustrated by a survey in 1995. Nearly two-thirds described their morale as "not very" or "not at all" high; only a third wanted to go on being a patrol officer. Part of the problem is that the work is out of doors, around the clock and physically risky. But it is also one of those ancient institutional facts that other policemen look down on patrol officers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The public, by contrast, cannot get enough of them. On balance, people are satisfied with almost everything the police do, according to polls: from responding to emergencies (68% net satisfaction; that is, satisfied minus dissatisfied) to preventing crime (18% net satisfaction). But they are not at all satisfied with the number of patrol officers (net satisfaction: minus 20%).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Police forces have justified failing to satisfy this demand for more bobbies on the beat by arguing that patrols contribute little to the police's main job, which is catching criminals. But both strands of this argument are questionable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Catching criminals is nowadays a smaller part of what people ask the police to do. Increasingly, the police are summoned to deal with neighbourhood disputes of the sort that tighter communities once settled for themselves. Patrol officers who know their areas are better-equipped to do this than are emergency response teams. Also, police forces are nowadays trying new ways to tackle crime--and officers on patrol may make these methods work better. In London, for instance, the Metropolitan Police's successful Operation Bumblebee (against burglars) and Eagle Eye (against muggers) relied on intelligence. Patrol officers who know their beats are good intelligence-collectors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, as the Audit Commission points out, patrolling is held in such low esteem that forces fail to make the best of it. Officers are shifted around so quickly that they never become familiar with their beat. Too often, they are not provided with the information they need to deal with recurring problems. Giving patrol officers the support they need and time to get to know an area, argues the commission, will help the police in their ambition to prevent crime rather than just react to it. And what does the Police Federation recommend? You guessed it: more policemen.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825717600,iss">Search</a>
