<html><head><title>Voice of America?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<h1><center>Voice of America?</center></h1>

THE peasants are coming with pitchforks!" cried Pat Buchanan on the eve of the New Hampshire vote. Peasants? Pitchforks? Why not? Mr Buchanan's America is a medieval land where honest workers toil for pitiful wages, where castles of virtue are besieged by the forces of Tinseltown, where borders must be defended with armed guards, and where foreigners poison the wells. And this Republican candidate has won the New Hampshire primary with 28% of the vote.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is still highly unlikely that he will be the party's nominee. Political parties wish to preserve themselves. The Republicans have only to whisper the name " Goldwater"--just as the Democrats have only to whisper the name "McGovern"--to remember that nominees from the wild fringes of the party spell death at the general election. Failing a late eruption by a party idol, it is likely to be either Bob Dole (second, with 27%) or Lamar Alexander (third, with 23%) who will lead the Republicans against Bill Clinton in November.
</p><p><b>Tapping insecurity</b>
<br><ro>On the other hand, nothing is certain. The race is now wide open. And if the organisation is on Mr Dole's side, and a bit of momentum on Mr Alexander's, all the passion is on Pat's. He is a natural orator. His supporters adore him. He runs a clever grass-roots campaign based on small contributors and free radio time. He taps deep into some dismayingly widespread and long-lived American opinions--isolationism, protectionism, thinly-veiled racism; and into some more reasonable, and more widespread, anxieties. That is what makes him dangerous. In Mr Buchanan's topsy-turvy world, the right is so far right that it becomes the left: government once again becomes the arbiter of both morals and markets. But that philosophy has its attractions in eras of unsettling change. He plays them for all they are worth.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In doing so, Mr Buchanan has opened with axe-blows the cracks which the Republican party, for eight years, has been delicately papering over. Is the party the voice of the religious right, stoutly opposed to abortion, homosexuality and all that could be called "liberal"? Or can it speak for the confused but tolerant majority? Is it the party of free-trade, or tariffs? Internationalist, or vowing to keep American boys and American aid safely at home? And, most important of all, is it a forward-looking party of reform, limited government and faith in the market, or one that, in the name of conservatism, demands a stronger and more intrusive state?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Buchanan's share of the vote was not large. More than 70% of New Hampshire's registered Republicans, who are a particularly rebellious and conservative lot, preferred somebody else. But it was a victory, all the same, and not simply the by-product of Mr Dole's failings. Mr Buchanan's appeal runs deep and the Buchananite side of the party should not be underrated. It includes, potentially, everyone who feels battered by the new economy, baffled by the Internet, nostalgic for Main Street, resentful of foreigners. According to opinion polls, fully one-third of American workers are worried that someone in their family will be laid off next year, and half are worried that their income will not meet expenses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The economic indicators, to be sure, should put these worries in perspective. America created nearly 8m jobs last year, and the "misery index"--inflation (2.5%) plus unemployment (5.8%)--is at its lowest for almost three decades. But ordinary workers seem more impressed by the fact that the actual purchasing power of wages has stayed flat for 10-15 years; and that flagship corporations such as <font size=-1>AT&T</font> have recently laid off workers in the tens of thousands.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some of these people voted for Ross Perot four years ago, although Mr Perot's eccentric authoritarianism took the form of a war on lobbyists and big government. Some of them voted for Bill Clinton, who always understood economic insecurity better than George Bush did. The Republicans need all these voters back in order to win in November. Here lies Mr Buchanan's threat: he can get their attention better than anyone else can. And, in the process, he can tug the whole campaign in his direction. It has happened already. The debate over tax reform, a good thing in itself, was quickly turned into a competition among the candidates to offer the largest tax cut, in airy disregard for the effect this would have on the deficit. And the debate over economic policy soon foundered in a morass of populist rhetoric against big corporations, with even Mr Dole declaring at last that the Republicans would henceforth be "the party of Main Street, not Wall Street"--whatever that meant.
</p><p><b>Fear of change</b>
<br><ro>This does not sound like the brave new Republican Party that was meant to have swept the country in November 1994, bringing with it irresistible notions of leaner government, citizen empowerment and a new high-tech American century. And it is not. That election was a revolution in the minds of a few, who erroneously read a mandate in it for full-scale reform of government. The mass of voters meant merely to send an anti-establishment, anti-Washington message. That message can also be heard in Mr Buchanan's speeches, half-buried in passionate cant.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Newt Gingrich and his followers have yet to persuade the mass of Republican voters that economic change, and the freer operation of the market, can be exciting rather than frightening. And although the desirability of smaller, more efficient government is generally accepted, the loss of a particular federal pay-cheque or safety net is not. The Gingrich wing of the party, in fact, may be even less representative of the mass of Republican voters than the Buchanan wing. No candidate this year has even mentioned the "Contract with America" , or indeed made the case for a balanced budget. The candidates sense that this year Republican voters want no one so much as Ronald Reagan: charm, effortless leadership, low taxes, a full complement of federal services, and a budget deficit into the trillions of dollars.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Who will be brave enough to puncture the Reaganite dream, while blocking the Buchanan nightmare? Mr Dole has the courage, and the battlefield experience in Congress; but he has no new ideas, and none of that essential confidence in the future that used to typify his party. Mr Alexander is light on both experience and personality, but, alone among the candidates, he has kept some of the flame of 1994 alive; he believes in the devolution of power from Washington to the states, the downsizing of government and the central importance of education in getting and keeping jobs. All this has been fuzzily expressed so far. Sharpened up, it could be an antidote to Mr Buchanan. The Republicans certainly need to find one, and fast.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825112800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
