<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="wtw1.gif" alt="Politics"></p>

<center><p align=center><hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<ro>
<h2>Impasse</h2>
<p>The <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s <b>bombing campaign </b>continued with an explosion that destroyed a double-decker bus in central London, killing the bomber and injuring eight other people. The British and Irish governments failed to agree on a formula for starting all-party political talks over Northern Ireland's future.<p>About a million people in Madrid, together with the prime minister, Felipe Gonzalez, and other politicians, demonstrated against violence by terrorists of the <b>Basque nationalist group</b>, <font size=-1>ETA</font>, who have carried out several murders in the run-up to a general election being held on March 3rd.<p>President Jacques Chirac proposed a drastic shake-up of France's mainly <b>conscript armed forces</b>, which may become all-voluntary by 2001.<p><b>Bosnia's Serbs </b>agreedafter talks in Rome to restore relations with <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s peace implementation force, Ifor. Days later, progress was slow, and the Bosnian city of Mostar stayed divided between Croats and Muslims, despite an agreement in Rome that the division would end.<p>The <font size=-1>IMF</font> gave a vote of confidence in <b>Russia's reforms</b> by agreeing to a $10 billion loan. It will be disbursed over three years; $4 billion could be paid this year alone. But the Fund's conditions are tough: monthly inflation below 1% by the end of 1996, and a budget deficit no<p>bigger than 4% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>.<p>A coalition <b>government in Turkey</b> seemed increasingly likely as leaders of the pro-Islamic Welfare Party and the secular, right-wing Motherland Party sorted out who would be prime minister first. Haggling continued over how the other ministries should be shared out.<p>After six days stranded off the west coast of Wales, the <i>Sea Empress</i> was at last towed off the rocks. But the <b>oil tanker </b>had already leaked half its 135,000-tonne load of crude oil, one of the half-dozen worst spillages ever.<p><ro>
<h2>Feeling high</h2>
<p><b>Pat Buchanan</b>, fire-breathing populist, won the New Hampshire Republicans' primary; ex-top-dog Bob Dole came second; Lamar Alexander, would-be new top dog, third. Mr Alexander said Mr Dole should quit the race because he was out of ideas; Mr Dole said Mr Alexander should quit because he was out of money. Bill Clinton easily won the Democrats' vote. Now on to Arizona and the South.<p>A survey of <b>illicit</b> <b>drugs</b> showed that their use among American teenagers is rising; that only 36% of teenagers admit to being frightened of drugs (47% last year); and that an increasing number say " being high feels good".<p>In <b>Cuba</b>, the government banned a planned meeting of the pro-democracy Concilio Cubano and arrested many activists.<p><ro>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Back to the fold</h2>
<b>Saddam Hussein's</b> two sons-in-law returned with their wives to Iraq from their brief self-exile in Jordan. Iraq's opposition-in-exile had decided the men had too much blood on their hands to be acceptable; and Mr Hussein had offered pardon.<p>Iraqi and <font size=-1>UN</font> envoys finished their first technical negotiation on an <b>oil-for-food deal</b>.Mr Hussein now has to decide whether to press on.<p>Israel's Labour Party narrowly defeated a Likud proposal that would have made a change to <b>Jerusalem's</b> current status virtually impossible. This did not mean, insisted Labour, that it would actually allow any change.<p><b>Qatar</b> said it had foiled an armed bid to reinstate its ex-ruler, ousted by his son, the present ruler, while he was on a visit to Switzerland last June.<p>Saudi Arabia's <b>King Fahd</b> took back the powers he had passed to Prince Abdullah.<p><b>Zaire's</b> government said it would take fresh steps to get rid of Rwandan refugees, accusing Rwanda's government of reluctance to help.<p>The <font size=-1>UN</font> tribunal on genocide has indicted two <b>Rwandan Hutus</b>. The two, a former militia leader and a mayor, have been held in Zambian jails since their arrest last year at the request of the tribunal.<p>The <font size=-1>UN</font> expressed alarm at goings-on in <b>Somalia</b>. New food shortages look likely and politics remains chaotic.<p><ro>
<h2>More ministers go</h2>
As <b>India's bribery scandal </b>continued to widen, four more government ministers resigned; three others had quit earlier. They are among more than 100 government and opposition politicians and civil servants whose names appear in the diary of a currency dealer charged with money-laundering.<p>The Philippine government claimed that <b>Chinese navy maps </b>were found in a pirate ship after a gun battle. Piracy in the South China Sea has been blamed on "rogue units" of the Chinese navy.<p>The ruling <b>Bangladesh </b>Nationalist Party won most parliamentary seats in a general election. But, deterred by an opposition boycott and a general strike, only about 15% of the electorate voted.<p>America is offering to move part of its air base in <b>Okinawa </b>to another site in Japan. Okinawa's local government had asked the Americans to leave, following the rape of a Japanese girl by American soldiers.<p><ro>
<h2>Happy holidays</h2>
<p>A coincidence of Chinese new year (it's the year of the rat), Carnival, and the end of Ramadan probably meant that a record number of people were on <b>holiday </b>at some point this week. A rough <i>Economist </i>estimate puts the figure at at least 3 billion.<p><p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></p></center>
