<center><p align=center><hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p><p><ro>
<h2>Togetherness</h2>
<p>(<a href="wtwimg1.gif">See chart</a>)<br>The French government has asked <b>Dassault Aviation</b>, which makes defence aircraft, and <b>A&eacuterospatiale</b>, a partner in Airbus Industrie, to create a single aerospace group within two years. The government also said it would privatise <b>Thomson</b>, a consumer and defence-electronics group; Marcel Roulet, ex-head of France T&eacutel&eacutecom, is to replace Alain Gomez as Thomson's chairman.<p>Britain's <b>Thorn EMI</b> announced that it would split its music and rental operations into two quoted companies. It said that in the nine months to December pre-tax profits, minus exceptionals, rose 29% to &#163;429m ($680m). The music side, largely <font size=-1>EMI</font>, a big record company, is valued after the demerger at &#163;5.8 billion; Thorn, which includes America's Rent-a-Center network and Britain's Radio Rentals, at &#163;1.8 billion.<p><b>CompuServe</b>'s parent is to spin off the successful on-line computer service mainly to shareholders, with less than 20% being offered to the public. Some of <font size=-1>H&R</font> Block's shareholders reckon the value of CompuServe--4.3m subscribers and growing--is not showing up in its parent's share price.<p><b>CUC International</b>, a big American consumer marketing group, is broadening its range in the electronic marketplace, where last year it launched Shoppers Advantage on the Internet, to include education and games. Now it is spending $2.2 billion to buy Davidson &amp; Associates, a maker of educational and entertainment software, and Sierra On-Line, a computer-games software firm.<p>Britain's <b>Grand Metropolitan </b>is bringing in an American to take charge of its poorly performing drinks division. John Keenan, who is retiring from the food division of Philip Morris, is the first outsider to be brought in at board level for 20 years.<p><p><b>BET</b>, a business-services firm, rejected a &#163;1.8 billion ($2.8 billion) hostile bid from <b>Rentokil</b>, a rival pest-control and office-services group, saying that Rentokil's plans were muddled. Most analysts nevertheless expect the bid to succeed, though Rentokil may have to raise its offer.<p><b>WPP Group</b> became the first company in the marketing-services industry to declare what looks likely to be a series of record profits for 1995. Exceeding the market's expectations, pre-tax profits rose by a third to &#163;113.7m ($179.5m), with revenues up 9% to &#163;1.6 billion.<p>America lodged an appeal against a ruling from the <b>World Trade Organisation</b> that had accused it of unfair discrimination against petrol imports from Brazil and Venezuela.<p>Russia dismissed its top <b>diamond-trade</b> official, Yevgeny Bychkov, just as he was reopening talks with De Beers Consolidated Mines of South Africa about the terms on which Russia supplies the De Beers cartel that dominates the world diamond market.<p><ro>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>State aids</h2>
<p>Germany's largest shipbuilder, <b>Bremer Vulkan</b>, which is likely to declare a loss of DM1 billion ($700m) for 1995, sought protection from creditors in order to avoid bankruptcy. Its woes mounted when the European Commission found that DM600m meant for improving Bremer Vulkan's east German yards had been used elsewhere in the group, and demanded that the money be returned to its original purpose. Around 23,000 jobs are at risk.<p>In a shake-up at a leading Swedish bank controlled by the powerful Wallenberg family, Peter Wallenberg and two other directors are to step down from <b>Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken</b> in April. The bank is still recovering from massive losses run up in the 1980s.<p>There were ructions at <b>Fiat</b> on the eve of the expected departure of its chairman, Gianni Agnelli. The chief operating officer of the Italian car maker, Giorgio Garuzzo, was removed, apparently after falling out with Cesare Romiti, the firm's chief executive.<p><ro>
<h2>Fragile rand</h2>
Despite central-bank intervention, the <b>South African rand </b>plunged to a record low of 4.03 to the dollar before pulling back slightly. Panic began after unfounded rumours circulated about Nelson Mandela's health and about an easing of foreign-exchange controls.<p>Britain's <b>National Westminster Bank</b> is to pay the financially embarrassed Indosuez of France &#163;472m ($729m) for its 75% stake in <b>Gartmore</b>, a leading British fund manager with &#163;25 billion under its control. The combined firm would be Britain's fourth-largest fund manager, with some &#163;83 billion under management.<p>NatWest also declared pre-tax profits for 1995 up 10% to &#163;1.75 billion ($2.76 billion). But with <b>Eurotunnel </b>poised to renegotiate its vast burden of debt, the bank, which has some &#163;250m in outstanding loans to the Channel tunnel operator, took a &#163;101m bad-debt provision, widely assumed to relate to loans to Eurotunnel.<p><p>(<a href="wtwimg2.gif">See chart</a>)<br>Two French mammoths returned to profit. <b>Groupe Bull</b>, a computer maker, made money for the first time in years, recording a net profit of FFr306m ($61.4m) in 1995 after a 1994 loss of FFr1.96 billion. And <b>Elf Aquitaine</b> swung to a profit of FFr5 billion in 1995, a year after losing FFr5.4 billion.<p><p></p>
</td></tr></table></p></center>
