<html><head><title>The man who keeps on going</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="am.gif">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>LEXINGTON</b></p><table border=6><tr><td>


<h2>The man who keeps on going</h2>

<p>IN THE summer of 1994 Lamar Alexander explained over a quiet dinner in Portland, Maine, how he was putting together the basis for a presidential bid. It was a methodical approach. The former education secretary and two-term Tennessee governor was driving across America to take the national pulse. Once a month he was hosting a televised " Republican Neighbourhood Meeting", narrowcast to party activists nationwide, to build a network of supporters and test his ideas. He sensed that, come 1996, Republicans would be looking for someone of Bill Clinton's generation who was not a Washington insider.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He spent the next 18 months doggedly following his plan--raising money, building an organisation, shaking hands in Iowa and New Hampshire--even though most of the time he was little more than a blip in the polls. Better-known candidates fell by the wayside, but Mr Alexander kept going, like the indefatigable bunny in battery advertisements. Then, this month, the long-promised surge started to happen.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Having scrambled into the front-running threesome in the Iowa caucuses, this week he found himself surrounded by cameras in New Hampshire, talking to overflowing audiences and emerging with 23% of the votes, only four points behind Bob Dole. Suddenly, the plaid persona who was in danger of becoming a joke is a canny candidate with a plausible chance of becoming president. How has he done it?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It has been a triumph of Lamarketing. Mr Alexander identified his niche and packaged himself to perfection. If Lamar were a product on a supermarket shelf, with "NEW!" stamped all over its folksy red-and-black wrapping, it would be the safe-looking brand you turn to after rejecting the stale or risky alternatives. He advertises himself as "a little bit different", an outsider from the "real world", fit (unlike old Bob Dole) to be "the first president of the next century" and capable (unlike any other Republican) of besting slick Bill Clinton in debate. Remember your ABC, he tells voters in his soothing voice and with his telegenic ease: Alexander Beats Clinton.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He has a good story to tell of his record as Tennessee's governor; his success in attracting Japanese investment offers a cheerful antidote to Buchananite protectionism. Mr Alexander lacks the spark to fire his audiences, but he warms them with talk of a "rising, shining America", with country music and with his renditions at the piano of "Alexander's Ragtime Band" and "The Tennessee Waltz". As he talks to voters--right hand reaching out, left hand casually in pocket, microphone clipped to his tie, head tilted to express concern and ever ready to smile--he has one underlying message: "Meet Mr Feelgood."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Look inside the packaging, however, and you discover a Lamar who is not quite as advertised. His outsider image, to start with, is phoney. A lawyer, Mr Alexander went to Washington as legislative assistant to Senator Howard Baker, graduated to the Nixon White House and later worked in the Bush cabinet. Now he blasts Washington and calls for the abolition of the Education Department; he was strangely silent on such themes when he was in Washington and running the department he now wants to kill.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His connections helped Mr Alexander to raise his family's net worth from $151,000 in 1978 to perhaps $3m now. With his surge to serious status has come a surge of reporters' interest in his family finances. His wife, Honey, seems to share with Hillary Clinton a talent for turning small investments into large profits--a $320,000 profit, for example, on the $10,000 paid for shares in Whittle Communications. "If anything distinguishes Lamar Alexander's career as a public official," writes Charles Lewis in his gloriously detailed account of the 1996 candidates' finances and friendships, "The Buying of the President" (Avon), "it is how much that career has benefited Lamar Alexander."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Alexander prides himself on running a positive campaign even while he politely trashes Mr Dole. He beams that he is the candidate with new ideas without offering any beyond a broad appeal for a return to civic virtue ("we should demand less from Washington, more from ourselves" ) and a handful of specific proposals that can generously be described as half-baked. He would substitute charitable giving for state welfare, set up a special branch of the armed services to patrol America's borders, agree with America's allies on burden-sharing around the world. But he offers few details. His crispest idea is the one that has the least chance of being approved by any Congress: returning to a citizen-legislature by cutting lawmakers' pay and sending them home to cool their heels for six months of the year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this explains why nice Mr Alexander has his enemies. Journalists now subject him to the scrutiny he avoided in his stealthy rise. The Christian right thinks him a liberal. The libertarian right thinks the revolution is not safe in his slippery hands. Many Republicans want to see Ronald Reagan in their presidential nominee, but in Mr Alexander they see George Bush. Indeed, the Bush network is looming large in the race for the nomination. Texas, where George W. Bush is governor, is up for grabs now that Phil Gramm is out, and brother Jeb runs the party in Florida.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Like him or not, Mr Alexander is no longer underestimated. His formidable drive and strategic canniness have already taken him further than most people thought he would go. But, to go even further, he needs to raise big money, fast, and he must start winning primaries rather than coming in a feisty third. In the words of a song performed by a Nashville artist at Mr Alexander's rally in Derry last Sunday:<ul><font size=-1>It's a long, long way from the tips of my fingers
To the love hidden deep in your heart.</font></ul>
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825112800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
