HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 04:27:21 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:00 GMT
Content-length: 3869
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>January sales</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>The economy</b></p>
<h2>January sales</h2>


TIPPED to be the "year of the consumer", 1996 is off to a slow start. January's inflation figures revealed the biggest monthly falls in the prices of clothes and shoes (5.6%) since 1921, and in household goods (3%) since records began in 1956. This provoked much talk of frantic price-cutting. The impression of empty shops and stationary merchandise seemed confirmed on February 21st when new figures showed that seasonally-adjusted retail sales were 0.6% lower in volume terms in January than in December.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Retailers need not despair. January's fall in sales followed a strong fourth quarter of 1995, when sales surged at an annual rate of 3.4%. Compared with January 1995, this January's retail sales were 2.3% higher. And, says David Mackie, an economist at J.P. Morgan, retail sales in January were hit by the two "roll-over" weeks on the National Lottery--the extra money gambled may have shaved as much as four-tenths of a percentage point off retail sales during the month, as consumers switched cash from small purchases. Very cold weather was a problem too: strikingly, sales did rise in "non-store retailing and repair", much of which is mail order.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The impression of widespread price-cutting is also wrong. Despite the falls in the prices of clothing and household goods, inflation excluding mortgage interest and indirect taxes was unchanged in January. The prices of personal goods, leisure services and motoring all rose.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is also less to the much-hyped supermarket wars than meets the eye. J. Sainsbury, for instance, launched its "January savers" with much fanfare: a mixture of discounts of up to 50% and buy-two-and-get-one-free deals on 100 basic items. However, according to Mike Conolly, Sainsbury's director of operational marketing, the cost was small because it merely concentrated the firm's usual discounts on fewer items.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Talk of fierce price competition due to the launch of various loyalty cards, such as the "Clubcard" introduced by Tesco last year, is also mistaken. These do reward the customer, perhaps by as much as 1% a year for a regular shopper. But many customers will receive less. And retailers reckon to regain much of the lost revenue by using the information generated by the card to aim special offers at likely takers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is no sign of a fall in retail profit margins: gross margins have risen from 14% to 18% over the past ten years. Such healthy margins may be the result of a lack of competition. A paper to be published on February 28th by London Economics, a consultancy (whose research has been sponsored by Tesco), disputes this, arguing that high margins reflect the need to pay for heavy capital investment which has raised the quality of service. Possibly. But if spending does accelerate this year, retailers may be able to push prices up, and the margins will be healthier still.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825112800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br3.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
