<html><head><title>Sinking feelings</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Tanker disaster</b></p>
<h2>Sinking feelings</h2>

<p>BRITAIN may no longer rule the waves, but it leads the world in oil-tanker disasters. This week it increased its lead when the Liberian-registered <i>Sea Empress</i> spilled 65,000 tonnes of crude into the sea as it lay on the rocks off Milford Haven in Dyfed, Wales. Three of the world's six biggest tanker-spills have now occurred around the rocky coasts of Britain: France, America and Tobago have had one each. This has nothing to do with being a big oil producer in the North Sea; the wrecks were all delivering or passing through. Bad luck and geography matter more. The real debate is now over how Britain handles such spills.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britain was introduced to this modern form of environmental disaster in 1967 when the <i>Torrey Canyon</i> ran aground off Land's End. Three years ago, off the Shetlands, the <i>Braer</i> broke up, spilling 85,000 tonnes of oil. On February 15th, the <i>Sea Empress</i> hit the rocks. Six days later, after repeated attempts to dislodge her in winds of up to 40 knots, she was refloated--but not before leaking twice as much oil as the <i>Exxon Valdez</i> did in 1989, causing $15 billion worth of damage to the Alaskan coast.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The fact that another tanker recently ran aground close to where the <i>Sea Empress </i>hit the rocks has added to the usual row that blows up after each wreck. The first tanker was one of the new double-hulled vessels, whereas the <i>Sea Empress</i> is one of the last single-hulled vessels to be built. The <i>Sea Empress</i> appears to have taken a wrong turn, but the real controversy is about what happened, or failed to happen, next.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government is being criticised for not implementing the findings of the inquiry which followed the <i>Braer</i> disaster. It recommended that more big tugs should be laid on, to stop every tanker crisis turning into a disaster. The government did follow this recommendation to the extent of laying on one such tug in Shetland, and another in the south-west, close to the sites of previous disasters.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Critics say that this has been inadequate, and that tugs did not get to the stricken <i>Sea Empress</i> quickly enough. The longer a holed tanker sits on the bottom, the more difficult it becomes to dislodge it. Seawater fills the gap left by spilt oil, making it harder to get the vessel off the rocks. The government denies any lack of tugs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Milford Haven is in a sheltered area, and is a refuge for rare birds and dolphins. Yet the <i>Braer</i> spill was less disastrous than first predicted. Strong winds dispersed its cargo of light oil, with little damage to wildlife. The <i>Sea Empress</i> was also carrying a light grade of oil. With luck, nature will quickly clean up humanity's mess.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825112800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
