<html><head><title>Learning to pay</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Higher-education inquiry</b></p>
<h2>Learning to pay</h2>

<p>AN INDEPENDENT inquiry into the future of the universities, announced in the House of Commons on February 19th, gets both the government and the Labour Party off a nasty hook. Neither of them wants to be first to admit that the only sensible way to meet the increasing cost of higher education is for students to stump up something themselves. The Liberal Democrats did just that, in a policy paper published the next day. But the two larger parties prefer to let the inquiry reach this conclusion for them, safely after the next election. The inquiry will look into all aspects of higher education. Yet its most pressing task is to find the fairest way to make students pay. Progress has already been made towards finding an answer.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most promising proposal is to let students borrow to cover their living expenses and tuition from a " learning bank". On graduation, they would repay the loans through extra national-insurance contributions of perhaps 3-5% of their earnings. Interest would be charged on the loans at, say, a few percentage points above inflation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ideally, private investors would finance the loans, minimising the burden on public-sector borrowing. The banks refused to take part in the current, smaller-scale scheme for student loans, fearing the costs and the bad publicity incurred in chasing thousands of graduates for fairly small amounts of money. Using the national-insurance system would overcome this problem. Employers are obliged to deduct contributions from their workers' pay. Even self-employed people think twice about evading national-insurance payments because doing so also deprives them of their entitlement to some benefits.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Iain Crawford and Nicholas Barr of the London School of Economics, who are preparing detailed proposals for a graduate-repayment scheme, say it is not the banks but the life-assurance and pension funds who are the most suitable investors to finance student loans. These funds are designed to make long-term investments, and they are accustomed to making complex calculations such as the likely earnings, credit risks and life expectancies of graduates. There is already a market for securitised credit-card debts; student loans, in which the repayments are taken directly from pay packets, would be much less risky.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Messrs Crawford and Barr suggest that the learning bank could invite investors to make competitive bids for packages of, say, &#163;10m of student loans. Since a few graduates would never earn enough to repay their loans, or would try to dodge paying them, the investors would bid at a discount. The government would make up the shortfall, but would then face no further liability. The investors would get the rights to repayments on the whole &#163;10m in return for taking on the risks of non-payment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a market in student loans to succeed, says David Sutherland of Scottish Amicable Investment Managers, the repayments would have to be spread typically over 15 years. This would make the securitised loans similar to the long-dated gilts which funds like his are already used to buying in large quantities.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825112800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br5.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
