<html><head><title>Still hope for Ulster's peace</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<h2 align=center>Still hope for Ulster's peace</h2>

BOMBS bring a dreadful sort of clarity. The message behind the Irish Republican Army's bombing of London was unmistakable. When it unilaterally called an open-ended ceasefire 17 months ago, the <font size=-1>IRA</font> assumed that in return Sinn Fein, its political wing, would obtain a seat in all-party negotiations on Northern Ireland's future. Persuaded by a year of stalemate that the British did not intend to let Sinn Fein into all-party talks, the <font size=-1>IRA</font> set off a bomb in London on February 9th and then, six days later, it planted more bombs, paralysing much of central London. We are still here, the <font size=-1>IRA</font> was saying; and we can still be violent.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed; the surprise is that anyone had ever doubted it. Yet they had; and that, in the end, could be the point that the bombs highlight most clearly. At the heart of the British government's policy since the 1994 ceasefire has lain the idea that terrorism in Northern Ireland had lost its energy, and with it the will to fight. The advantage thus gained could be pressed home by British and unionist demands that the terrorists must begin to hand over their weapons before Sinn Fein could be admitted to all-party talks. Although they did not share those demands, the Irish and American governments did share the basic assumption behind them. But that assumption was wrong. One way or another, terrorism will lurk in Ulster's shadows even if a political settlement is eventually reached. The task is to deprive it of popular support and thus to isolate it. And the resumption of the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s bombing campaign may have made that task easier.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most of all, the bombs have damaged Sinn Fein. Nationalists in Ireland, north and south of the border, share Sinn Fein's frustration with the intransigence of Ulster's unionists, and the British government's reluctance to over-ride them. But those same Irish nationalists are horrified at the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s bombing of London. " I was willing to believe that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> had ended the killing for good," John Bruton, Ireland's prime minister, told his parliament. "That act of faith has now been thrown back in my face." Ireland and Britain promptly cut off ministerial contacts with Sinn Fein, and demanded a restoration of the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s ceasefire.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No one knows what the <font size=-1>IRA</font> intends. The London bombs could easily lead to a full-scale resumption of Ulster's 25-year-long conflict. But even if that is not the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s intention, its resort to violence is short-sighted. It demonstrates that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> is still willing to disregard the will of the vast majority of people in Northern Ireland, nationalist and unionist alike, who want the violence to end. The bombs also seem to confirm unionist accusations that, if Sinn Fein does not get its way at the negotiating table, the <font size=-1>IRA</font> will use bombs and bullets.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And unionists are not the only ones who will now wonder whether dealing with Sinn Fein makes sense. Democratic politics is always complicated, and often slow. Mr Major may well have been delaying all-party talks, as Sinn Fein charges, in exchange for unionist support in the House of Commons, where the Conservative Party's slim majority has got even slimmer in recent months. But that does not justify the resumption of a war that Sinn Fein's own leaders have admitted that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> cannot win. In that war, Irish republicans have always taken the longest of views. The fact that their patience ran out after only 17 months of diplomacy contradicts their professed commitment to democratic change. True democrats, despairing of Mr Major, would have chosen simply to wait a further 15 months (at most) for a British general election. Nor are republican fears realistic. Britain does not want, nor would Ireland or the United States tolerate, the reimposition of a Protestant unionist hegemony in Ulster.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, it would be a mistake to shut the door entirely on Sinn Fein, as the British, Irish and American governments all recognised after the first bomb. Those governments will maintain contact with the party through officials. The biggest reason to do this is that, as even some unionists admit, most Irish republicans in Ulster want a permanent end to the conflict. Belfast's Falls Road greeted the news of the first London bomb with gloom and dread, not celebration. Revealingly, loyalist terrorists did not retaliate and called for Sinn Fein to be given time to restore the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s ceasefire.</p><p><b>Breaking the stalemate</b><br><ro>The peace process can still be salvaged. But to do that, all sides to the conflict will have to re-examine their attitudes. The political settlements now in place in South Africa, the Middle East and even Bosnia, make it all the more incredible that a settlement in Ulster is so elusive.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nationalists of all stripes need to understand Britain's concerns. Although Mr Major's efforts to keep his own government in office may not be an edifying sight, they are understandable in a democracy. Nevertheless, Mr Major also has a responsibility to try harder to get all-party talks going, and to draw people from both sides who have supported terrorism into the democratic mainstream. To talk secretly to Sinn Fein before the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s ceasefire, as Mr Major's government did, and then to deny the party a place at the negotiating table for 17 months after the ceasefire, has been perverse. To give the impression that he was brushing aside the views of the Irish government was a grievous blunder.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among democratic politicians, it is the unionists who most need to learn the art of compromise. Happy with the status quo, they have seen no need to negotiate. But nationalists, even the peaceful variety, will never settle for the status quo. Northern Ireland will never enjoy stability unless unionists compromise. Unionist fears of being pushed into a united Ireland are as unrealistic as those of Irish republicans. The best guarantor of Ulster's link with Britain is not London, but Dublin, where there is no support for ending the partition of Ireland as long as Ulster's majority remains opposed to it. Despite the London bombs, the unionist refusal to talk to Sinn Fein has also been misplaced. Britain and Ireland have proved for the past 25 years that they are not going to let the <font size=-1>IRA</font>, through Sinn Fein, dictate the terms of a final settlement.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The British and Irish governments have spent the week following the first London bomb searching for a formula to get talks going. But they cannot concoct one on their own. With realism and a spirit of compromise from the parties in Ulster, any formula could work. Without them, none will.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="contents.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
