<html><head><title>Why peace broke down </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<h1 align=center><img src="northernireland.gif"></h1>

<h1>Why peace broke down </h1>

<p><b>The Irish Republican Army's bomb in London's Docklands on February 9th brought a shattering end to the 17-month-long ceasefire in Northern Ireland. On February 15th, the police defused a bomb in the British capital's West End. Why has the IRA returned to violence? And is this the end of the peace process?</b></p>

<p>IN RETROSPECT, there were plenty of warning signs that Northern Ireland's peace process was in jeopardy. Exasperated by the failure to start all-party talks, leaders of Sinn Fein, the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s political wing, had been saying since last summer that the peace process was under threat. In this, they were reflecting grass-roots opinion: for the past few months, republican supporters in the province had grown ever more despondent and angry at the lack of political progress to the decades-old dispute.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet when the <font size=-1>IRA</font> called off its ceasefire late on the afternoon of February 9th, it still came as a shock. The <font size=-1>IRA</font> sent a coded message to <font size=-1>RTE</font>, Ireland's state-owned broadcaster: it was greeted with disbelief. The <font size=-1>IRA</font> had to make a second call to ask why the news had not been broadcast. Earlier that same week, British security sources had said they did not expect an early resumption of <font size=-1>IRA</font> violence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Peace had transformed everyday life in Northern Ireland. It had been embraced with enthusiasm across the province's deep political divide. Most republican and loyalist activists, who had supported the gunmen on both sides, had said that the war was over, and that securing a political settlement through dialogue had become their goal. Perhaps the most visible sign of this commitment to peace was the euphoric reaction to President Clinton's visit to the province on November 30th: crowds of nationalists and unionists welcomed the president with joyous rallies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Then, at 7:01 pm on February 9th, a 1,000-pound bomb ripped through London's Docklands, east of the City, smashing windows in office blocks, injuring 43 people and killing two. Abruptly, the mood in Ulster shifted from optimism to despair. The mood darkened further with the discovery of a bomb in London's West End. At best, the <font size=-1>IRA</font> was signalling its frustration in failing get Sinn Fein into talks. At worst, it was resuming full-bloodied " armed struggle" against British rule in Northern Ireland. What was beyond doubt was that the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s ceasefire had ended.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What went wrong? A whirl of meetings between politicians of every stripe, trumpeted "breakthroughs", Anglo-Irish summits, visits to the White House by party leaders, and endless television interviews all gave the impression of political progress. But this was misleading. After 17 months of politicking, Ulster was not much closer to a political settlement before the bomb--or even to negotiations leading to such a settlement--than it had been when the <font size=-1>IRA</font> announced its ceasefire.
</p><p><b>The unspeakable and the intractable</b>
<br><ro>To understand why the peace process has proved so hard to maintain, it is necessary to recall the history of the conflict in Northern Ireland, one of the longest and most intractable in Western Europe. Irish nationalists, who account for 40% of Northern Ireland's population and are mainly Catholic, have always thought that the province was an artificial creation, gerrymandered in 1920 to give mainly-Protestant unionists a permanent majority. Nearly 50 years of discrimination under the unionist-dominated parliament at Stormont Castle, a palace near Belfast, persuaded most nationalists that an "internal settlement" (ie, one that excludes Ireland) would be unacceptable because it would leave them permanently under the unionist thumb.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the other side, unionists have always said there is no reason why Ireland should be a political unit just because it is a geographic one. They argue that those who wish to remain part of the United Kingdom should have the right to do so. Today, most unionists admit that a return to rule by a local assembly in Stormont is neither possible nor desirable. But they adamantly refuse to consider joining a united Ireland, in which they would be a permanent minority, and see any moves to forge links with the Irish government as the beginning of a slide towards unification.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such conflicting aspirations and fears have nurtured nationalist virulence alien to the rest of Britain and Ireland (<a href="sfchart1.gif">see chart</a>). When Catholic civil-rights protesters marched under the Stormont regime at the end of the 1960s, Protestant police and counter-protesters responded by attacking them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Out of the civil strife which followed, the <font size=-1>IRA</font>, whose roots lay in the revolution that had established the Irish Free State 50 years earlier, was reborn--and so was a "republican", anti-British ideology. This viewed Britain's presence anywhere in Ireland as colonial and Ulster unionists as British stooges. On the unionist side, loyalist terrorists, who viewed all Catholics as subversives, sprang back into action.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These attitudes, legacies of 25 years of conflict, have dogged the current peace process from the start. But they are not the only ones in the province. After 25 years of stalemate, most people want peace. This was why hopes rose so high when the latest peace efforts began.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among the nationalists, the main figure arguing for accommodation is John Hume, the leader of the Social Democratic and Labour Party (<font size=-1>SDLP</font>), which is the largest nationalist party in the province. After years of discussion with Gerry Adams, Sinn Fein's president, Mr Hume seemed to have persuaded him of the view held by most people in the Irish Republic: that <font size=-1>IRA</font> violence, not the British government, had become the biggest obstacle to a settlement, and that the unionists would never be persuaded to compromise, let alone join a united Ireland, by bombs or bullets. Sinn Fein moderated its rhetoric, and established secret contacts with the British and Irish governments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the Downing Street Declaration of 1993 both governments tried to reassure everyone in Ulster that their concerns would be taken into account and no settlement imposed. When the <font size=-1>IRA</font> announced an open-ended ceasefire at the end of August 1994 (followed by a loyalist ceasefire six weeks later), Northern Ireland seemed at least on the brink of a durable peace.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Almost immediately old suspicions resurfaced. Sinn Fein's leaders were all too aware that their party's share of the vote, about 10% in Northern Ireland and a mere 2% in the south, would not give it much clout on its own. So they persuaded the <font size=-1>IRA</font> to stop its violent campaign only after winning promises from Mr Hume and Albert Reynolds, Ireland's then prime minister, that the <font size=-1>SDLP</font> and the Irish government would help ease Sinn Fein's way to the negotiating table. Together, the party's leaders told their supporters, nationalists across Ireland could get Britain and the unionists to accept a change. The help of Mr Clinton's White House would also be relied upon to press for an equitable settlement.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unionist leaders saw this "pan-nationalist" front as a conspiracy to bully the British into accepting a slow-motion unification of Ireland. They bitterly resented the meddling of the Americans. Why, they asked, should we believe that the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s ceasefire is anything but tactical? Why should we talk to Sinn Fein while the <font size=-1>IRA</font> retains its weapons? Sinn Fein, claimed unionist leaders, had to establish its democratic credentials before unionists would negotiate with it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The British government tried to assuage unionist concerns. First it refused to meet Sinn Fein for three months, to ensure that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> ceasefire was genuine. Then it demanded that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> declare its ceasefire "permanent". And then it demanded that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> make a gesture to bolster the confidence of unionists by decommissioning some of its weapons before Sinn Fein could meet British ministers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble was that neither side sees the British as honest brokers. Nationalists, even the majority who oppose the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s campaign, have long believed that when push comes to shove, the British will invariably side with the unionists. Ironically, the unionists do not trust the British any more than the nationalists. With some justification, unionists suspect that most people on mainland Britain would be happy to settle for any resolution of the conflict, even a united Ireland. British efforts over the past 20 years to meet nationalist demands by involving the Irish government in a settlement have fuelled unionist fears that Britain wants to wash its hands of Ulster.
</p><p><b>Towards the bomb</b>
<br><ro>Britain's attempts to steer through this sea of suspicion were unsuccessful. Eventually, the government abandoned its demands that Sinn Fein declare the ceasefire permanent; nor did the <font size=-1>IRA</font> hand in any weapons. But British ministers met Sinn Fein leaders. In February 1995, the British even went so far as to publish, together with the Irish government, a "framework" document sketching an outline political settlement. This involved a power-sharing assembly in Northern Ireland, which would remain part of the United Kingdom but would be linked through cross-border government bodies with the Irish Republic. Such a formula (similar to an attempt, called the Sunningdale agreement of 1973, to end an earlier round of fighting) may well be the only way to reconcile the demands of both nationalists and unionists.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Sunningdale foundered on the rock of unionist opposition--and so did John Major's negotiations. Unionists were enraged, arguing that the British prime minister had misled them, and that he was trying to impose a settlement against the wishes of Ulster's majority. Meanwhile Sinn Fein's leaders seemed at first confused, then angered by the British.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For years they had been told by the British that the alternative to <font size=-1>IRA</font> terrorism was dialogue. They believed this meant that, once the <font size=-1>IRA</font> had abandoned its violent campaign, Sinn Fein would be allowed a place at the negotiating table where a political settlement would be hammered out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sinn Fein's supporters felt that unionist leaders and the British government were out to humiliate them, that their demands for weapons handovers and delays would only increase, and that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> was no longer being asked simply to stop waging war, but to surrender. This, they believed, was the prelude to the internal settlement they dreaded. Despite its connections with, and support for, the <font size=-1>IRA</font>, Sinn Fein also has scores of elected local councillors. Its leaders demanded that its electoral mandate be recognised, and that talks without "pre-conditions" begin.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the British insisted on the idea of some form of weapons disposal before any all-party talks, the Irish government and the <font size=-1>SDLP</font> were dismayed. Like Sinn Fein, they had assumed that the terrorist ceasefires would allow all sides to come to the negotiating table. As months of stalemate dragged on, spirits sagged.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nationalists in Ireland, and not just republicans, came to believe that unionist leaders would negotiate only if the British called all-party talks over their objections, but that the British had no intention of doing this. Mr Major's dwindling majority in the House of Commons made it likely that he would need to rely on the support of the nine <font size=-1>MP</font>s of the Ulster Unionist Party to stay in office. Nationalists noted this, but gave Mr Major little credit for trying to pursue peace negotiations anyway. Instead, they accused the British government of trimming its support for the peace process because of parliamentary arithmetic and argued that Northern Ireland should take precedence over "party politics" at Westminster.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For their part, British ministers argued that without the unionists at the table, talks were pointless. They insisted that unionist demands for an <font size=-1>IRA</font> gesture on weapons as a "confidence building" measure were reasonable given the ferocity and length of the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s campaign. This was not a demand for surrender. If the <font size=-1>IRA</font> truly wanted peace, asked the British, why could it not make this simple gesture?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After an ominous summer of sectarian marches and rioting, the deadlock became unmistakable when, by late autumn, the British and Irish governments had failed to agree on a way forward. Then, on the eve of Mr Clinton's visit to the British Isles in November, the two governments hastily announced a compromise--a "twin track" approach. Along one track would proceed discussions leading to all-party talks by the end of February. Along another, a three-man international commission examined ways to break the impasse over arms. The commission was headed by George Mitchell, a former American senator.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the commission reported on January 24th, it recommended another compromise: instead of talks before disarmament, or disarmament before talks, both should proceed at the same time. Barely consulting the Irish government, Mr Major immediately rejected this proposal, and repeated his demand that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> disarm before talks. If Sinn Fein would not accept this, he said, he proposed instead an alternative of his own: special elections to choose delegates to all-party talks before disarmament. Make a gesture over weapons, he told Sinn Fein, or win a democratic mandate to talks--take your pick.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unionists were delighted. The idea had been theirs. It also sounded reasonable to British officials--how can democrats oppose elections? But it confirmed many of the worst fears of nationalists. After months of stalling, Britain seemed to be brushing aside the Irish government and the Anglo-Irish partnership that had formed the bedrock of the peace process. It had hastily rejected an international effort to offer a way forward. It had adopted the unionists' agenda, conjuring fears of a purely internal settlement. It had erected another hurdle in the way of Sinn Fein's entrance into talks. Sixteen days later, the bomb went off in Docklands. Mr Major's response to the Mitchell commission, Mr Adams speculated, had been the "last straw".
</p><p><b>Examining the wreckage</b>
<br><ro>The bomb has left all sides pessimistic, but it has set back, rather than stopped, the search for a settlement. Unionist leaders predictably claimed that the bomb confirmed the suspicions they had held of Sinn Fein and the <font size=-1>IRA</font> all along. But few others tried to make political capital out of the attack and neither the British nor Irish government, despite the bloodshed, seems ready to slam the door on Sinn Fein.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;True, the bombing provoked a bout of finger-pointing between London and Dublin about who was to blame for the political stalemate. A few days later, however, both adopted a more conciliatory tone and scrambled to work out a new route to all-party talks. Both governments broke off ministerial, though not official, contacts with Sinn Fein. Both also demanded an immediate restoration of the <font size=-1>IRA</font> ceasefire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Major still called for elections. But, in a subdued House of Commons, also said he was open to other ideas. The <font size=-1>SDLP</font>'s Mr Hume proposed referendums in both parts of Ireland to ask people to repudiate violence and to back all-party talks. Mr Major was unenthusiastic about this but refrained from ruling it out. Ireland's prime minister, John Bruton, said he was willing to discuss elections, but only if "proximity" talks (like those held in Dayton, Ohio, to reach an accord in Bosnia) were also considered. The Irish had proposed such talks before the bombing. Both governments seem to realise that, whatever the <font size=-1>IRA</font> now does, the only way to salvage the peace process is to restore their partnership. A meeting between the two prime ministers is expected next week.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The bomb has left the strategies of both the <font size=-1>IRA</font> and Sinn Fein unclear. Sinn Fein's top leaders denied prior knowledge of the bomb. They expressed sympathy for its victims, but refused to condemn it. Instead, they explained it as the inevitable response to British and unionist intransigence, and the delay in starting all-party talks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The bombing seemed to cause as much gloom among Sinn Fein's supporters in Northern Ireland as among anyone else. Yet, mindful of bloody divisions that have riven their movement in the past, republicans were determined not to split. Mr Adams and other top Sinn Fein leaders may not have been told the precise timing of the bomb, but they surely must have known that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> was about to call off its ceasefire. The most likely explanation is that they lost an internal argument over whether to return to violence and, to avoid a split, went along with the decision.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for the <font size=-1>IRA</font> itself, its return to violence was the more surprising because few could see any persuasive political logic to its decision. Even if the upshot is that all sides think again and act more flexibly, the <font size=-1>IRA</font> will pay a high price for the bombing. It will now be more difficult, not easier, for the two governments to get unionists to the same table as Sinn Fein. The bombing has also increased doubts about whether the republicans are genuinely committed to democracy, and whether they have the patience for the slow pace and compromises that the democratic process entails.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Gloom and fear have returned to Ulster. Yet a political settlement, even peace, should still be possible. Ordinary people's attitudes really do seem to have changed. After the bombing, demonstrators poured on to the streets of Belfast and Londonderry to show their support for peace.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An unexpected bright spot was the behaviour of the fringe parties representing loyalist terrorist groups, the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s bitterest foes. They called for restraint, ruling out a renewal of hostilities unless the <font size=-1>IRA</font> launched an all-out campaign in the north. One loyalist leader argued that Mr Adams had to be given time to restore the <font size=-1>IRA</font> ceasefire. Loyalist prisoners even issued a statement accusing mainstream unionist leaders of "gloating" at the bloody end of the <font size=-1>IRA</font> ceasefire. Such a response would have been unimaginable 17 months ago.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is clear that the people of Northern Ireland want a peaceful resolution of their conflict. But what compromises they are willing to make to obtain it, and how their politicians can lead them to that goal, remain obscure. Ulster, like so many other troubled places on earth, now needs statesmen, not mere politicians.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="contents.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
