<html><head><title>Golden goals</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">


<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="br.gif"><p><font size=-1>These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=center valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<table border=6><tr><td>
<h2>Golden goals</h2>
<p>FAUSTINO ASPRILLA is reputed to earn &#163;30,000 a week. This juicy salary has not prevented the Colombian soccer star from becoming the latest hero of Newcastle United fans. His match-winning debut on February 10th maintained the team's lead in the English premier league. Were Mr Asprilla instead earning a similar salary as managing director of a British widget manufacturer, those same fans would regard him as an over-paid fat-cat. Is there a rational explanation for such an apparently contradictory attitude to top pay?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Stefan Szymanski, an economist at Imperial College Management School in London, reckons so. People are happy to accept rates of pay that are fairly set. The procedure for determining the rate for a job should be just; pay needs to be seen to reward effort and skill; and the rate should reflect a worker's perceived worth. Footballers pass all these tests, he claims, better than senior executives.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Executives' pay is seen to be set by their peers, rather than in a market. Footballers' salaries are determined by a fiercely competitive transfer market. Club managers and players--the buyers and sellers--have opposing interests, the manager to keep pay low, the player to push it up, so wages are set by the normal market forces of supply and demand. In contrast, company directors, many of whom are buyers (as well as sellers) by dint of sitting on remuneration committees at other firms, have an incentive to bid up the going rate for the job.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for testing whether pay accurately reflects effort and skill, that is much easier in the case of players than company bosses. If two directors are watching a football match, it is impossible to tell whether they are cementing a deal or having a nice time. But, says Mr Szymanski, not only is the performance of each footballer easily observed; 70% of the explanation for the position of a club in Britain's Premier League arises from the relative size of its pay bill. A company's profits may soar because of a growing economy, or its share price rise simply because the stockmarket has risen, rather than because its managers are doing a good job.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But here's the rub. The pay of Britain's top footballers rose by around 60% between 1991-92 and 1994-95--far more than the pay of Britain's company directors. Yet in that period, Britain's economy has grown faster than that of any other big European country, and its exports have risen to record levels. Not since 1984 has a British club won Europe's top honour, the Champions' Cup.

</td></tr></table>

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="contents.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br3.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
