<html><head><title>In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="brbrief.gif"><p><font size=-1>These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=center valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<center><p align=center><hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<table width=65%><tr><td valign=top width=30%>
<b>Just the job</b><br>
The official unemployment count fell by an unexpectedly sharp 29,300 to 2.2m in January. But construction firms said they expected to cut 45,000 jobs in 1996, despite figures showing that their new orders in December were the highest for two years.<p>
<b>Rentamum</b><br>
A London hospital said it was arranging the first surrogate birth on the National Health Service. An unnamed woman will get expenses of up to &#163;10,000 for having a baby on behalf of another who has lost her womb.
<p><b>King's shilling</b><br>
Faced with a shortage of 2,500 troops, the army offered serving soldiers a &#163;250 bonus for persuading their friends to join up.
<p><b>Wages of sin</b><br>
More prisoners will be allowed to do paid work while serving their sentences, the government said. But they will have to contribute towards their keep and give money to crime-prevention and victim-support schemes.


</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>

<b>A fine decision</b><br>
Michael Howard, the home secretary, announced that people will no longer be jailed for failing to pay fines. In 1994 22,500 fine-defaulters were jailed.

<p><b>God not Tory--official</b><br>
The Church of England is no longer a male-dominated " Conservative Party at prayer"; it is increasingly left-wing and women are winning more influence, a survey of 500 General Synod members found.

<p><b>Oliver Twist 1996</b><br>
An outcry forced Liverpool council to drop proposals to give poor children, who get their school meals free, smaller portions than those who could afford to pay.
<p><b>That's that</b><br>
The Samaritans and Childline said their telephone counsellors were on standby for a wave of calls from distraught teenagers after pop heart-throbs Take That said they were splitting up.
<p><b>Pink pound</b><br>
A Manchester entrepreneur launched plans for what he claims will be the world's first gay shopping centre, including a dry cleaners which will launder frocks for transvestites.</td></tr></table></p></center>


