<html><head><title>Death by the invisible hand</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="story.gif" width="285" height="28" alt=""> <td align=rightvalign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist"border=0></td></tr></table><img src="deathby.gif"><br> <h3>Ending written by <i>Peter Andreae</i></h3> <p> <!--Body text below this line--> <B><I>NextTuesday at Lunch</I></B><br> Asquith looked up from his second pint. Precious lack of progress had brought on a new lunch-time habitfor him. "We've talked to the lot on all 14 floors, but nothing pans out to murder. What I can't figure out is if Rathbone was foundlying on his back, he was facing 'Market Forces'. Why didn't he atleast get out of the way when it fell? We really don't know whodunnit,howdunnit or even whydunnit. It's not for lack of leads, because no one is holding back. "There's an information glut. Ask a simple questionand you get a editorial on some advanced topic. "Who ever murdered Rathbone is one cool customer with not a hint of guilt. <I>TheEconomist</I> just continues on in chaos as usual." </P><P> "Don't talk to me about chaos." Greg looked gaunt and pale. He had quit drinking at lunch and ate very little. "I asked Dr. Hamiltonhow she found anything in those heaps of papers around her office. She went on for half an hour about how she uses 'Chaos Theory' toorganize her files. But could she find a copy of the Magna Carta? You know, she retrieved it in less than 15 seconds. I haven't aclue what she was talking about." </P><P> After a week of working with <I>The Economist</I> staff, two detectives had a closer kinship. </P><P> Greg brightened up. "You would think these brains with their degrees in economics would be filthy rich. But no! I found from thepost-room fellows that Rathbone supplemented his income by writing under a pseudonym for the tabloids." </P><P> "That's better than writing under no name for <I>The Economist</I>." </P><P> "But that's not all. Strachey was in on it, too. In fact probably the whole staff were supplementing their income to some degree.Rathbone was the main one, because he had the contacts. These workaholics were not only putting out <I>The Economist</I> every week,they were writing a good percentage of Britain's finest rags! But the best irony of all was that Julia Barrington was their editor. Shewould cut and mark their copy mercilessly and have them rewrite it over and over. She would browbeat them until their column had the"right" degree of low brow to meet the market. She read widely in her niche and had a deep understanding of that genre." Greg had pickedup some nasty big words lately. </P><P> "Do you think there was blackmail?", Asquith was trying to work out the implications. "No, I don't see how. You know, all we'vedone is write huge reports and get nowhere. The chief wants someone behind bars and quickly." </P><P> "The only one who wasn't moonlighting was Hodgskin. "Greg got back onto his subject. "Thirty years ago he had a brilliant careerahead of him. Politically and economically he fitted right in with <I>The Economist</I> and its readers. At that time you could have onephilosophy for life. Now it's all constant change, no structure to hang data on, to plan a direction for the future. Hodgskin's just afrustrated burnt out old crisp but still a man of absolute principle. I rather relate to that." </P><P> "I went to check out the artist who made the 'Market Forces' sculpture." Asquith changed topics. "He is the oddest one yet, morelike New Age technical borfin than an artist. Talked about electrical auras, force fields, machine-human telepathy and machine-humanempathy, what ever that is. Builds all his own electronics, you know. The sculpture is just the cover for his gadgets. The only thing Iunderstood was that his gizmos need lots of power and the batteries are really heavy. To save power it turns on and off, intermittently.He stuffed all the equipment into the top of the pyramid. That's why it took so much effort to correct 'Market Forces' yet one personcould bring it crashing down. Moreover, I think <I>The Economist</I> crew like this sculpture because they are taken in with all thearty-technical jargon. He says they like his sculpture because it talks to them literally." </P><P> "Yes, more interesting information, but how does it help solve the case?" asked Greg. </P><P> "You are right. No use at all." Asquith was going to order another pint. </P><P> "Back to work." said Greg. </P><B><I>Later that Same Day </I></B> <br> Asquith was leaving <I>The Economist</I> after a discouraging afternoon; not that it was anydifferent from any other afternoon on this case. His head ached. The mystery was in a fog. Couldn't the case just go away. Couldn't hejust go back to dealing with simple thugs and punks. Wouldn't it be nice to have some extra cash to spend on his upcoming vacation.Wouldn't it be great.... </P><P> Crossing the plaza he became aware of a pleasant feeling of wellbeing. There was a quiet humming in the air, though he couldn'timmediately locate the source. He was now quite sure it was trying to communicate something to him. Had one of the sculpturesturned itself on? Maybe the statues of Walter Bagehot or Sir James Wilson had been upgraded. No, they didn't do anything for him. Look!There, above 'Market Forces', a faint glow. It's getting clearer. An apparition? A wad of cash? A big wad of cash! </P><P> He found purchase for his feet on the bottom ridge of the pyramid, and a spot for his left hand about the apex. He reached for thecash, but it exceeded his grasp. As he stretched, the invisible hand of gravity brought down 'Market Forces'. </P><!--Body text above this line--> <p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> HomePage</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?851130000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; -&nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> </p> <p align=center><font size=-1> </p> </td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
