<DOCNO>WT09-B18-72</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA096-001037-B001-329</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/18-01-97/thriller2.html 199.173.162.110 19970215045426 text/html 7080
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 04:50:22 GMT
Last-modified: Wednesday, 15-Jan-97 17:14:54 GMT
Content-length: 6892
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Death by the invisible hand</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="story.gif" width="285" height="28" alt="">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<img src="deathby.gif"><br>
<h3>Ending written by <i>Shaiontoni Bose</i></h3>
<p>
<!--Body text below this line-->

<I><B>Friday evening</B></I>

<BR>
"Until these questions are satisfactorily answered I don't see how we can wrap up the case."

<P>
"Well," mused Asquith, " Julia may not be as dim as all that. After all she had access to her own
e-mail . She could have found out he was cheating on her and been conducting some assignation on the
side. The fur coat could have been a gift from some well-heeled old pussy who liked Rathbone's long
nose and copiously gelled wavy locks."
</P>

<P>
Greg whistled, "what a lot of big words you do know, lad! Ever thought of writing for them?"
</P>

<P>
Asqiuth, who had, blushed prettily but forbore to comment.
</P>

<P>
Greg, having caught him on the wrong foot, pursued his advantage. "I notice you too are moving along
the lines of <I>Cherchez la Femme</I>."
</P>

<P>
"We have to explore all possibilities, sir", Asquith replied . "I still think we should look at it
from an intellectual angle. These people don't quite think like - well- like, er,normal people do."
</P>

<P>
"Well said," said Greg. 'In fact, I wonder if there are any normal people left in this world. I'm
getting frazzled myself. By the time I've finished here I'll be ready for the ruddy loony bin. Never
seen so many suspicious characters lurking around altogether. Why don't they ever sign any of their
articles in their mag ?"
</P>

<P>
Asquith ventured, "They call it bylines, sir, not signatures. It's a paper, not a magazine."
</P>

<P>
Greg snorted. 'Why do they want to be anonymous? That Editor chappie - he doesn't even have a mug
shot in that history book about the paper. One gent has a magazine hiding his face. What's he in a
photograph for then? Have you seen the size of that tome?
</P>


<P>
"In Pursuit of Reason" by R.U. Nutty. It's a wonder that isn't the murder weapon instead."
</P>

<P>
"What was that last thing you said, sir?"
</P>

<P>
"About the book?"
</P>

<P>
"Yes sir, being the murder weapon."
</P>

<P>
"And the sculpture could have been used to cover up evidence. Rathbone wouldn't have to be standing
around waiting to be mashed. He could be brained, if you'll pardon the expression, elsewhere and then
dragged to the present scene of the crime."
</P>

<P>
"Let's see what Forensic says".
</P>

<P>
"If we do consider the book as a possible murder weapon how do we prove it ? Everybody will possess a
copy .
</P>

<P>
"Everybody should .We could check the ones who don't and find out why while we wait for Forensic".
</P>

<P>
Almost every one who had been given their copy of "In Pursuit of Reason" still possessed it .
</P>

<P>
Three people couldn't account for its absence. One was Thomas St. Loe Rathbone for obvious reasons.
One was Geoffrey Hodgskin whose nervousness increased under stringent questioning.. One was the
author of the book, a regular visitor to the paper and its library. She sounded like she wished
sometimes (only sometimes) that she had never written the book.
</P>

<P>
"That Rathbone was always snooping.He wanted to know what dirt I'd dug up on the paper. Snide remarks
were a habit with him. If I were to do him an injury I'd have done it during the writing of the book!"
declared Ms. Nutty. 'Why don't I have even one copy? I can't stand the sight of it ! Do you realize
the kind of paperwork and organisation it required? Anyway, believe me I only write about murders to
get them out of my system. I wasn't on the premises within the last few days. I can prove it." And she
did.
</P>

<P>
"This one-upwomanship can get a little trying ," said Greg as he checked the list of names. "Perhaps
we should look for the book and the lever in the same place. If the book has anything to do with all
this, that is. Is there a paper shredder in this place?." He grinned with pleasure, " They'll get their
knickers in a twist over this in Production but you had better check if they do possess anything so
organised.Are the shreds thrown away everyday or disposed of on a weekly basis. Call Geoffrey Hodgskin
for his daily dose."
</P>


<P>
Rathbone nosed around a lot, didn't he?" said Asquith,thoughtfully but he couldn't con-tinue.
Hodgskin burst in and collapsed limply onto a chair.
</P>

<P>
"You threw the book at him, didn't you-" said Greg.
</P>

<P>
"Yes, but I didn't kill him.I swear it. I didn't even knock him out. He made me furious. He came and
sneered at me in the Archives room. He was angry because I wouldn't tell him what I was looking for.
He has --- had --- a habit of snitching scoops off other people. He wrote brilliantly but he didn't
play fair . Someone heard us arguing and looked in just as I threw the book.He can confirm it."
</P>

<P>
"Why didn't you tell us?" said Greg, exasperated.
</P>

<P>
"I thought <I>I</I> was the prime suspect," said Hodgskin, simply.
</P>

<P>
"Where's the book?" Asquith leaned forward.
</P>

<P>
"I don't know." Hodgskin shivered. "I hope I'm not next on the list..." He stared into space,
tonelessly murmuring, 'I'm investigating a scam on the stockmarket. The archives are helpful in
tracking down names and information, even possible sources for scoops. Rathbone knew something too. He
kept insinuating that I give the beat to him because he said he'd do a better job of reporting it
...that he knew more about it than I did. That he even had a list of names of those who benefitted
most. He hinted that some unscrupulous bloke in this office had sabotaged the computers to destroy
data that had been collected.That he would expose him when the time came"..........
</P>

<P>
Geoffrey Hodgskin suddenly stopped short and looked at Greg and Asquith as they shouted, "Who was it
who opened the door?"
</P>

<P>
"Donald Barrington", Hodgskin whispered, "wanted to meet me at The Royal Arms tonight.
</P>

<P>
"Why did you jeopardise a perfectly good career?" asked Greg.
</P>

<P>
"Because I was bored", said Barrington simply.
</P>

Asquith raised an eyebrow.

<!--Body text above this line-->
