<html><head><title>Death by the invisible hand</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="story.gif" width="285" height="28" alt="">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78"
height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<img src="deathby.gif"><br> 
<h3>Ending written by <i>Sanjay Perera</i></h3> <p> 
<!--Body text below this line--> 
<B><I>Saturday morning</I></B>
<BR>
Greg sounded forlorn as he spoke to Asquith in their car: "Well, looks like we are stuck. No bloody
light at the end of the blasted tunnel."
<P>
"I think, sir," said Asquith, "we may have to take a different approach, look at things from a more
creative point of view."
</P>

<P>
Greg sighed, "And what would that be young squire?"
</P>

<P>
"Remember those Agatha Christie mysteries with their surprise twist endings? Sometimes you had a
situation where everyone, all the principal characters were the culprits...the murderers."
</P>

<P>
There was a pause in his breathing as Greg considered this, "You think the entire ruddy staff of <I>The
Economist</I> conspired to kill Rathbone?"
</P>

<P>
"You see, sir, it's like in 'Murder on the Orient Express', they all did it ... Sean Connery was in it,
and so was Vanessa Redgrave."
</P>

<P>
"What! Why on earth would film stars want Rathbone dead?"
</P>

<P>
"No, no, they were in the film version of the..."
</P>

<P>
"I see, no need too be condescending now," said Greg gruffly, "but how likely is it that the whole
damn lot of 'em would have killed Rathbone?"
</P>

<P>
"Why not, sir?" John Major thinks he's going to win the next General Election, how likely is that,
sir?"
</P>

<P>
"Good point."
</P>

<BR>
<P>
Both Greg and Asquith were querying Julia Barrington again when she said with tears in her eyes, "You
know, Zoe thinks there is only one way to find out who killed poor Tom."
</P>

<P>
The sleuths leaned forward in earnest ready to receive the information.
</P>

<P>
"She has decided to see Madam Madonna, the renowned medium, the one at Kensington. She will summon Tom
to point out the killer. She apparently holds regular conversations with John Wilkes Booth..."
</P>

<P>
"Aha, I know who that is, that's the fellow who shot Kennedy!" said Greg triumphantly.
</P>

<P>
"Er, no sir, that was Lee Harvey Oswald."
</P>

<P>
"Right now, you were saying..." Greg turned hurriedly to Julia.
</P>

<P>
"Sir, I've got it!"
</P>

<P>
"Well now, not the clap again?" asked Greg maliciously. Julia took several steps away from Asquith.
</P>

<P>
Asquith blushed, "I meant, sir, why don't we get Madam Madonna down this evening and assemble all the
usual suspects on the staff and let her point out the villains."
</P>

<P>
"Excellent -- the benefits of a university education," said Greg reluctantly.
</P>




<B><I>
Saturday afternoon</I></B>
<BR>

"You want me to get all the people on your list here, into the board room for a briefing this evening?
We almost missed sending out our edition because of all that's happening around the world and the
interruption caused by your investigations," said a harried Edward Strachey.

<P>
"Sorry about that, but this is a murder investigation and we believe we may be able to solve the
mystery this evening..." said Greg.
</P>

<P>
At that moment Strachey's phone rings and he picks it up. He listens intently for over a minute then
shouts, "Oh no! Bollocks and hell!" Then slams the phone down.
</P>

<P>
"What is it?" enquired Asquith.
</P>

<P>
"Lathbury just found out that Andrew Neil's book 'Full Disclosure' was ghost written by Rupert Murdoch
and Pamella Bordes..."
</P>

<P>
"What, the chap who bought over Indonesia?" asked a shocked Greg.
</P>

<P>
"The same," grunted Strachey, "and that's not all of it, Kenneth Clarke has crossed over to Labour and
the Tories have announced that they are launching their secret weapon to lead them into the next
election..."
</P>

<P>
"Portillo?" asked Asquith.
</P>

<P>
"No, Dennis Thatcher."
</P>

<I><B>Saturday evening</B></I>
<BR>

The two detectives looked at the faces of all the people in the boardroom. Madam Madonna was now
seated at the head of the table and asked everyone to hold hands above it, including Greg and Asquith.


<P>
When she had entered the room, there had been a gasp of surprise from everyone as she was dressed like
the Madonna in a bright silver bikini and a sharply protruding conical bra. "Call me Evita," she had
said, "one must move with the times."
</P>

<P>
Madonna/Evita's eyes rolled upwards and her eyelids shivered before closing. Then there was a sharp
cough as she said, "Tom, Tom Rathbone we need to talk to you, we need to ask you who committed that
murder so foul...who killed you Tom, tell us...so that justice will be served..."
</P>

<P>
"This is creepy," whispered Julia to Sophie Hamilton next to her.
</P>

<P>
"Well, it's more fun then writing next week's leader on why Netanyahu will be a one-term prime
minister."
</P>

<P>
"Tom, Tom Rathbone come to me..." she coughed again, and then she sat upright and there was a
decidedly snooty look on her face as a distinctly Oxonian accent came from her mouth.
</P>




<P>
"Yes, yes, I'm here, what the devil do you want? I was just having this wonderful chat with Matahari
when you summoned me. By the way, hope Jeffers is there because I've also met Adam Smith who said his
book was actually a subtext on the ills of a free-market economy, choke on it you old sod!" There was
a nasty chuckle from Madonna/Evita's mouth.
</P>

<P>
Hodgskin turned red and shouted" "You lying bastard!"
</P>

<P>
"Well, I'll tell you what you want, all of you...I was returning home about midnight that fateful day
when I had stopped for a quick smoke near Market Forces."
</P>

<P>
"Didn't know he smoked," said Donald Barrington casually.
</P>

<P>
"I had first walked over to Wilson and told him that he looked so bloody awful as a statue, then
strolled over to Market Forces when I saw....him, but it was too late, he tipped his hand and sent
that cursed monument crashing on me, before I finished my smoke."
</P>

<P>
There was a tense silence as the medium shuddered and coughed violently. Then a serious demeanour took
over her features and a five o'clock shadow appeared on her face.
</P>

<P>
"Yes, it was I who pushed that ugly monument over that scarilegious rascal, it was I...Walter
Bagehot," the words emerged calmly from Madonna/Evita's mouth.
</P>

<P>
There was a gasp of shock around the room. Hodgskin moaned: "Oh, a miracle, the patron saint is upon
us, praise be...there is a God!"
</P>

<P>
"Do shut up Hodgskin, you're interrupting me. I killed Rathbone because he had no respect for patron
saints. Yes, I want a free exchange of ideas but when I heard him say those words that Monday morning,
"Bugger Bagehot", I knew he had to be taken to task. An example had to be set."
</P>

<P>
"Lord almighty, the ghosts of <I>The Economist</I> past and present...is this happening? What a story this
will make," said Strachey in awe.
</P>

<P>
"Since I am here, I think I ought to warn you about the future. You are in great danger of electing a
new government soon, but your new prime minister will prove to be a neo-Trotskyite."
</P>

<P>
"I knew it, we could never trust Blair!" screamed Hodgskin.
</P>

<P>
"You fool, I meant Peter Mandelson. If you were to ever have another staff member as rude as Rathbone
again, punish him severely and appropriately, if you don't want my invisible hand tipping statues."
</P>

<P>
"What should we do, O Great One?" asked Hodgskin reverentially.
</P>

<P>
"Make them listen for a full hour to a speech by a Singapore cabinet minister, or..."
</P>

<P>
"How cruel, what sadism," said Julia.
</P>

<P>
"Spend a night locked in a seedy hotel room with Australia's Pauline Hansen."
</P>

<P>
"Rather vicious ideas from a patron saint, don't you think?" Lathbury asked his editor quietly.
</P>

<P>
With that Bagehot left the medium as her head flopped onto the table from exhaustion.
</P>

<P>
"What do we do now?" asked Asquith turning to Greg.
</P>

<P>
"We'll have to file a report, but leave it at misadventure? I also think we had better haul Madam
Madonna here to the station for some questions."
</P>

<P>
Madonna/Evita sits up and seems normal again. She yawns and rubs her bristled chin, "There must be an
easier way to make money."
</P>


<!--Body text above this line--> <p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The
