<html><head><title>Death by the invisible hand</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="story.gif" width="285" height="28" alt="">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78"
height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<img src="deathby.gif"><br> <h3>Ending written by <i>Daniela Pinez-Jovanovic</i></h3> <p> 
<!--Body
text below this line--> 

<B><I>Saturday Lunch
</I></B>
<BR>
"Indulging in chocolates while on duty, aren't you, Asquith?" Greg waved the report that described a
puddle next to the statue. 
<p>Asquith had the good grace to blush. "Mrs. Barrington offered me some
chocolates. I though she would be more likely to confide in me after we had shared a few
strawberry-liqueur-filled bonbons."
<p>"She did not tell you a thing, my lad, did she?" Greg patted his paunch and smiled indulgently.
<p>"The lab report says that the pebble I found was too small to unbalance
Market Forces." Greg said pointedly. "But I learnt from Zoe that Mrs. Barrington had broken the heel
of her shoe on Wednesday." He cleared his throat. "She does wear extremely high heels." 
<P>
Greg nodded appreciatively. "Get to the point, my boy!" 
<P>
"Any solid enough small object at least three inches high,
placed at a proper point, could have been used to destabilize Market Forces. Furthermore, Mrs.
Barrington is unable to account for the present location of the heel of her shoe."
<P> "The Cinderella touch." Greg said fondly. 
<P>Asquith said nervously, "I thought that perhaps you could talk to her. She
has an alibi for that evening and she could not have put that heel there earlier without being seen."
<P>"You could not break her down!" Greg rubbed his hands cheerfillly.
<P>




<B><I>Saturday Afternoon</I></B>

<BR>
Greg was sitting with his head between his hands. The two hours he had spent with Julia Barrington had
confirmed his feeling that with <I>les femmes</I>, as with economists, the curves did not restrict themselves
to their figures. 
<P>"A member of the graphics department had borrowed the heel Wednesday at eight to
hold his drawing board level. He says it's been there since." Asquith proffered the heel at his
understandingly frustrated superior.

<br>
<P>
Mr. Lung, dressed in a three piece suit, stood in front of Greg. "You work for Thomas St. Loe
Rathbone, at his place of residence in Belgravia, in the capacity of butler? 
<P>"Yes, Sir." Mr. Lung did
not volunteer an explanation. 
<P>"With what money did Rathbone hire a Chinese butler?" Greg said
offensively. "
<P>The money from the semi-conductors factories, Sir." 
<P>At that point Greg screamed,
"Asquith!" 
<P>"Sir!" Asquith ran into the room ready to protect his superior officer. 
<P>"Has Rathbone
factories?" Greg asked sharply. 
<P>"We are just running the facts on his laptop. Starting at the tender
age of 11, Rathbone played the stock market and built an empire, not of paper only. His last venture
was in-" 
<P>"-Semi-conductors." Greg finished for him. "What was this mogul doing scraping a living at <I>The
Economist</I>? And why has nobody told me about this before?" 
<P>"It was a secret." Mr. Lung offered kindly.
<P>"Mr. Rathbone felt that if his colleagues at the magazine" "Newspaper," Greg and Asquith said in
unison. "He thought that he would not have been hired if his non-academic proclivity had been known.
That's why he enjoyed writing articles against capitalism." Mr. Lung beamed at the policemen. 
<P>At that
point Greg left the room, presumably to buy a hat.
</P>


<B><I>Saturday night</I></B>
<BR>
"I did not know about it because I just returned from my fact-finding holiday in Polish coal-mines."
The Science editor squirmed. "It was sent to us by the maker of the alloy for our survey of the metal
industry." "When did you put it under the statue?" Asquith asked. 
<P>"I put it there a week ago. It is a
memory alloy and I was testing whether it would work after a week of compression under a heavy object.
The one-inch long spring could not have opened to its full three inch unless it was stimulated by some
electrical current." 
<P>"What enticed Rathbone to remain in that spot long enough to be crushed?" Greg
prodded. "How about a picture of Rathbone in fluorescent disappearing ink, set at a height just above
Rathbone's? Fascinated by his own reflection, and looking upward it would have been unlikely for him
to realize that the sculpture was falling on him until it was too late." The Science editor exulted.
<P>
"Can you prove you were in Poland, young lady?" Greg asked suspiciously.

<P>
"Hodgskin wanted to make a fool of Rathbone, but why kill him? Once dead Rathbone was an uninteresting
opponent who couldn't be made to listen to arguments!" The editor insisted. The dark circles under his
eyes had reached the dimensions of flying saucers. 
<P>"Wasn't the liquid that activated the alloy the
work of Hodgskin's landlady's large, shaggy dog? Didn't we find the spring, still extended to its full
length, holding sprigs of parsley in his landlady's kitchen brought back by the dog? And couldn't he
have trained the dog to push vigorously at an object?" 
<P>Asquith coughed. "Sir? The spot had been
slightly corroded by a regular application of dog urine. It seems that the dog is jealous of the
landlady's paramours and is usually left outside at particular times, and-" 
<P>"And this breed of dogs
tend to develop an inflammation of certain glands that result in a tendency to kick when lifting the
hind legs." Greg said wearily. 
<P>"Have you already seen the report, Sir?" Asquith asked. "You cannot
prove that Geoffrey did it." The editor insisted loyally. 
<P>"Once the lab finds the disappearing ink,
we'll tie the case against him!" Greg said with satisfaction.
</P>

<P>
At 2.00am, Greg and Asquith walked out of the building. Refusing to look at the still-prone statue,
Greg gazed instead on the spotlights aimed at the art exhibit. "Asquith!" He cried. "That spotlight,
there!"
<P>"The one that's aiming into space?" Despite the cmcking of his knees Asquith bent dutifully to
examine the spotlight. "There is a sheet of plastic at the front, with words etched on it." 
<P>Greg
turned suddenly to the student intern who had been looming pathetically close. "What do you know about
this, young man?" 
<P>"It was only a joke! The projection of the quote on the statue was a joke about
Market Forces! I did not know the thing would fall! It's the sculptor's fault!" 
<P>"What does it say,
Asquith?" Greg asked. 
<P>Asquith giggled nervously. "It says, 'In the long run, we are all dead. Signed,
Maynard Keynes.'"
</P>


<!--Body text above this line--> <p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The
Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a
href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?851130000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a
href="index.html">Contents</a> </p> <p align=center><font size=-1> </p>
