<html><head><title>Death by the invisible hand</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="story.gif" width="285" height="28" alt="">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<img src="deathby.gif"><br>
<h3>Ending written by <i>Phil Sheehan</i></h3>
<p>
<!--Body text below this line-->
<B><I>Saturday morning</I></B>
<BR>Inspector Greg, looking well-rested and cheerful, was at his desk. "Answered those questions for me, lad?" 
<P>   "Four of the five, sir." Asquith sounded satisfied without sounding pleased. 
<P>   "Expect I'll need only two." 
<P>   "Which two would that be?" 
<P>   Greg furled his brow, as if considering what to ask. "First one, how could Rathbone afford cashmere?" 
<P>   Asquith furled his brow, as if considering whether to answer. "Rathbone couldn't. The coat was a gift from the Britain editor." 
<P>   "Two for one," said Greg, his face spreading in a congratulatory grin. "The second question was, why did the Britain editor keep him on? Seems to answer itself." 
<P>   Asquith wasn't sure whether it was Greg or himself being congratulated. "She kept him on, because they were getting it on," he said. 
<P>   Another congratulatory grin from Greg, this one unambiguous. "As I was saying to Mrs. Greg, that Hamilton's a right little raver when she's off duty." 
<P>   "Had a similar conversation with my wife," said Asquith, a trifle disingenuously. 
<P>   "So. Now the e-mail makes sense." 
<P>   Asquith nodded in agreement. "The bogus message to Barrington." 
<P>   "Nothing bogus about it." 
<P>   "Beg pardon, sir?" Asquith's brow furled again, this time of its own accord. 
<P>   "Rathbone dumped the dim Julia Barrington for the brilliant Sophie Hamilton." 
<P>   Having accepted the notion of sex at <I>The Economist</I>, Asquith hesitated to confine it to orthodox pairings. "Barrington said it was a ruse. None of Rathbone's quotations." 
<P>   "Anyone clever enough to intercept messages would spot quotations. If it had been a ruse, it would have included a quotation, so's to sound authentic." 
<P>   "Why did Rathbone?" 
<P>   "He wasn't breaking a date, he was ending an affair. Best to be brief and direct." 
<P>   "Then Rathbone wasn't waiting by the statue for Barrington."
<P>   "Excellent, lad, you're catching on." Greg leaned back in his chair. 
<P>   Asquith continued, "He was waiting for Hamilton." 
<P>   "Sorry, no points. Lost a few, in fact." Greg shook his head and sat back upright. 
<P>   "Who was he waiting for?" 
<P>   "He wasn't waiting. But no matter. What about the crowbar?" 
<P>   "Nothing. We've ransacked litter bins throughout the area." 
<P>   "Rubbish." 
<P>   Asquith tried not to sound condescending. "Which is what we expected, sir."
<P>   "I mean, wrong place to look." Greg had forgotten who ordered the litter-bin search. 
<P>   This time Asquith did try to sound condescending.  "Where ought we then to look, sir." 
<P>   Greg wasn't having it. "Where you ought then to look, Constable Asquith, is in that jumble of trash in the courtyard." 
<P>   "Jumble of trash?" 
<P>   "The statuary thing, the one Hodgskin ran into, think it's called Fiscal Rectitude." 
<P>   "Not any more." Asquith tried to regain his dignity. "The artist came round to fix it Thursday, said he liked the new configuration, left it as was and retitled it Gross Domestic Product." 
<P>   "Honest label, that one. Scrabble about in Gross Domestic Product Asquith, and you'll find your missing crowbar. Tell the lab to check for fibers." 

<P><B><I>Saturday afternoon</I></B> 

<BR>Asquith sat down resignedly next to Greg, who was half-way through his shepherd's pie and more than half-way through his pint. "The crowbar was in Gross Domestic Product." 
<P>   "Fibers?" 
<P>   "Lab found bits of leather on it, not sure yet where they're from." 
<P>   "Not sure?" Greg tried not to sound condescending. "They're from Rathbone's gloves." 
<P>   "Rathbone?" 
<P>   "Think, man. The Barrington thing was over and Hamilton was in a meeting. He'd nothing to do for an hour. So he pinched the crowbar to upend that bloody statue." 
<P>   "Rathbone toppled Market Forces?" 
<P>   Greg took a deep breath and stifled a belch. "Where're the notes on the group that found Rathbone's body?" 
<P>   Asquith fished about in an inner pocket. "Right here, sir." 
<P>   "Who actually spotted it?" 
<P>   "It was, here we are, it was the deputy editor." 
<P>   "What did he say?" 
<P>   "His words, they all agreed, were 'Market forces seems to have come a cropper.'" 
<P>   "Aye, and what did he say next?" 
<P>   "He said, a moment sir, the notes are jumbled, he said, 'No doubt Geoffrey will blame Tom.'" 
<P>   "Why would he say a thing like that." 
<P>   "Got me there, sir." 
<P>   Greg banged his fist on the table, jarring but not upsetting the remaining quarter-pint. "Because it's exactly the sort of thing Tom Rathbone would do." 
<P>   "True enough, sir, but your point?" 
<P>   Greg's eyes rolled up, as if to heaven, but did not roll back in dismay. "My point is, that's what happened. Rathbone upset Market Forces to upset the others, particularly Hodgskin. He'd levered it up to the tipping point when his foot slipped on that pebble you found."  
<P>   "He wasn't using it to prop the statue?" 
<P>   "Hulking gob of junk like that, prop it with a pebble? Rubbish. His foot slipped on the pebble, he lost his balance, and Market Forces fell on him. He flailed about trying to escape, and inadvertently pitched the crowbar into Fiscal Rectitude." 
<P>   "So Rathbone's death was accidental." Asquith's voice betrayed a touch of disappointment. 
<P>   "Not to say self-inflicted," Greg added. He shoveled in a mouthful of shepherd's pie and washed it down with the last of his bitter, while Asquith tucked his notebook and his pride into an inner pocket. "By the by, which other questions have you answered?"
<P>   "The editor had a dim secretary because <I>The Economist</I> needed her husband's technical expertise," said Asquith. "To keep him they had to give her a job. Management figured she'd do the least harm to the operation as the editor's secretary." 
<P>   "Didn't the editor take that as a personal insult?" 
<P>   "Journalists take everything personally. It's in their nature." 
<P>   "Which appears to answer my question about Hodgskin." Greg glanced at the remainder of the shepherd's pie, then pushed the plate away.  
<P>   "Hodgskin took everything personally," said Asquith, "same as the rest. Only thing different about him was, he was honest about it." 
<P>   "Which, I gather, is not in the nature of journalists?" 
<P>   "Not so far as we can determine, sir." 
<P>   "Thank you, Asquith. Oh, one last item." 
<P>   "You wondered why people as intelligent as these like such idiotic modern art." 
<P>   "And the answer?"
<P>   "Haven't the faintest, sir." 
<P>

<!--Body text above this line-->
<p align=center>
