<html><head><title>Death by the invisible hand</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="story.gif" width="285" height="28" alt="">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<img src="deathby.gif"><br>
<h3>Ending written by <i>Lucy Shigemitsu</i></h3>
<p>
<!--Body text below this line-->

<P>    "Well, the last is not much of a mystery, sir. Nobody really
likes the art," Asquith pointed out. "Everybody seems to agree that the works
are ridiculous but they are part of the exhibition. The competition to show
the essence of the Economist," he reminded him.
</P>
<P>
    Julia Barrington sashayed by just then, distracting a good number of
the men in the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
    "It still doesn't make sense. Strachey has the authority to get rid of
this pretentious nonsense," Greg countered.
</P>
<P>
    "Sir," Asquith hastily interjected, before Greg could start
meandering. "A few more inquiries might unearth the answers. If I
could look into the histories of..."
</P>
<P>
    "Eager aren't we?" the inspector rejoined sarcastically, cocking a
curious eyebrow. "Very well. Do what you will. Within reason, of
course. The competition is still on. Let's see who resolves the
questions first."
</P>
<P>
While he was waiting for Ms. Hamilton to return from a meeting
occasioned by yet another political crisis, Detective-Inspector Greg
discreetly searched the contents of her desk.
</P>
<P>
    "Well, what do we have here?" he murmured. In the upper right hand
drawer, hidden beneath piles of bills and a daily planner, was a
photograph of Ms. Hamilton and the deceased in what could only be termed
a very heated embrace.
</P>
<P>
    He quickly shut the drawer and moved to a place by the window scarcely
a second before the Britain editor entered the room. She studied him
with a wary eye, clearly displeased that he had been let into her office
during her absence.
</P>
<P>
    "Ahh, Ms. Hamilton. I won't take up too much of your time. I just
have a few more questions."
</P>
<P>
    She frowned but politely invited the inspector to have a seat.
    "Let us begin with this art competition. Who first had the bright
idea..."
</P>
<P>
From the atrium, Detective-Constable Asquith watched as Ms. Barrington
took a sip of water from the glass cup. Only then did he approach her
desk outside Strachey's office.
</P>
<P>
    "Ms. Barrington, Inspector Greg must take a statement from you," he
said.
</P>
<P>
    From her seat behind the desk, she looked up with an alarmed
expression.
</P>
<P>
    "It is only routine," he quickly assured her. "He is in the board
room."
</P>
<P>
    The moment she left, he carefully emptied the contents of her glass
into the nearest potted ficus tree. He gave the cup to a man from
forensics. They conferred briefly before the man left for the lab. A
table by the water cooler had been stocked with identical glass cups for
visitors. Asquith filled one of these with water and placed it on her
desk.
</P>
<P>
    "That was strange," said Ms. Barrington, as she returned from the
lift. "I couldn't find Inspector Greg anywhere."
</P>
<P>
    He smiled in an abashed manner which was really quite charming. "I'm
sorry. He must have gone to lunch," he explained apologetically.
</P>
<P>
    "That's all right," she said good-naturedly. "It has been very hectic
around here."
</P>
<P>
    "He'll probably want to talk to you later in the afternoon, then," he
said, before heading off for Mr. Hodgskin's spacious office. Hodgskin
had already left for the day. Between the pages of a large atlas on the
topmost bookshelf in the office, he found a letter addressed to Hodgskin
from a Mr. Cornelius Wilde in America.
</P>
<P>
On his way to Strachey's office from the personnel office, where he had
gone after his interview with the Britain editor, Greg passed the
receptionist's station.
</P>
<P>
    "There is a call for you, Inspector," Zoe informed him, holding out the
phone's receiver.
</P>
<P>
Just as he closed the door to Hodgskin's office, Asquith heard the
turbo-speed clicking of computer keys. He peered briefly through the
open doorway of the small adjacent room which was cluttered with cables,
whirring terminals, and blinking modems. Henry Lathbury sat before a
large computer screen covered with closely set lines of unintelligible
alphanumeric symbols. He was typing away furiously, completely
oblivious to the detective-constable's presence.
</P>
<P>
    Asquith ruefully shook his head, feeling terribly antiquated, before he
continued down the long hallway toward Rathbone's office.
</P>
<P>
<B><I>Friday evening</I></B>
<BR>    "Kipling was right, Asquith!"
<P>
    "Sir?"
</P>
<P>
    "Rathbone was having an affair with Ms. Hamilton, too," Inspector Greg
revealed triumphantly over dinner. "That explains why she tolerated him
when the other editors had already chucked him out as unendurable. It
also means that, like Barrington, she had motive. Jealousy. But she
seems to lack the means, the technical wherewithal, so to speak. Unless
they conspired..."
</P>
<P>
    "Sir," Asquith interjected. "Barrington was not jealous of his wife's
relationship with Rathbone, for it was not a dalliance. Rathbone and
Julia Barrington were brother and sister."
</P>
<P>
    The look of astonishment which crossed the Inspector's face at this bit
of news was more gratifying than Asquith could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
    "I was struck by a certain similarity between their features," he
continued. "I began to suspect they were related but, if so, why were
they hiding it. I ran a check on her prints. It turns out Ms.
Barrington ne Rathbone and Mr. Barrington have been convicted five
times in the past seven years for fraud and industrial espionage."
</P>
<P>
    "What a piece of work," Greg mused, almost appreciatively. "Never said
she was his lover. Just let us reach our own conclusions."
</P>
<P>
    "There was nothing on Rathbone, though," Asquith added. "Stuck-up Mr.
Superior' Rathbone probably didn't want anyone to know that his sister
was a jailbird."
</P>
<P>
    "That's why Strachey was forced to hire her, despite her lack of
secretarial skills." At Asquith's puzzled look, Greg proceeded to
explain. "I asked Ms. Hamilton about the art competition. Strachey had
originally suggested the silly idea. Apparently, he had championed the
concept for monetary gain. Strachey received a hefty commission from
three of the four schools. Yet, he was having problems making his car
payments. His funds were rapidly being depleted while Rathbone was
somehow making enough to afford cashmere. After several minutes,
Strachey finally broke down. He admitted that Rathbone had been
blackmailing him. He had discovered that Strachey's master's degree
from Harvard was not actually Harvard University in Massachusetts but an
undistinguished school which goes by the same name. Strachey feared
that if his superiors got wind of this, they would reconsider his
editorship. In return for Rathbone's silence, Strachey paid him 650 a
month. Strachey didn't know why Rathbone had insisted he take on Ms.
Barrington as his secretary, though."
</P>
<P>
    "So, Rathbone used his leverage over Strachey to find a good paying
position for his sister. I suppose Donald Barrington got his job by
more conventional means?"
</P>
<P>
    "Without a doubt. He knows a great deal about computers and such. 
When one of the staff of the technical department moved to Australia,
Barrington was the best qualified applicant. But damn! There goes our
prime suspect," Greg exclaimed irritably. He brooded quietly for a few
moments. "Asquith, were you able to find out anything more about
Hodgskin? By all accounts, he loathed Rathbone."
</P>
<P>
    "In his office, I came across a letter from an eccentric American
billionaire, a Mr. Wilde, who is sponsoring some sort of economics
contest. The first person to correctly solve all the riddles wins
$1,000,000. I think Hodgskin was convinced that the answers could be
found in the 1840s Economists. That's why he is perusing them with such
fervour. The deadline is only a fortnight away."
</P>
<P>
    "Makes sense. Rathbone had insinuated to Hodgskin, more than once,
that he was old and obsolete and would soon be on his way out. 
Hodgskin's not stupid. He saw that Hamilton and Strachey sided with
Rathbone on every major issue. That's why he was taking everything so
personally. He also missed his last doctor's appointment, so he had
stopped taking his Prozac. With the pressure of losing his job, he was
probably desperate to win the competition. $1,000,000 takes the sting
out of being sacked. A pity Hodgskin has an airtight alibi." Greg
downed the last of his beer and frowned. "That brings us back to Ms.
Hamilton."
</P>
<P>
    It suddenly came to Asquith in a flash. "Lathbury, sir!"
</P>
<P>
    "What about him?"
</P>
<P>
    "Lathbury is a very smart fellow. Double first, after all. And quite
ambitious, too, from what I gather."
</P>
<P>
    "Being intelligent is not a crime, Asquith," Greg retorted testily. 
"Even for a snotty-nosed, little jerk like Lathbury."
</P>
<P>
    "He is a computer wiz, sir. When technical support is busy, everyone
on the 13th floor turns to him."
</P>
<P>
    "His r&eacutesum&eacute in the personnel office did list several computer science
courses," Greg admitted.
</P>
<P>
    "His office is a veritable hacker's paradise. He could have gained
access to the e-mail accounts, read about the midnight meeting, and sent
that fake e-mail to Ms. Barrington."
</P>
<P>
    "And why would he have wanted to kill Rathbone?"
</P>
<P>
    "Professional jealousy. Rathbone was a cocky, disagreeable sort. My
guess is that Rathbone intimated that the next available editorship
would be his. Lathbury believed him, just as Hodgskin did. Lathbury
felt that this was grossly unjust, since he was smarter and had been at
<I>The Economist</I> for two more years. With Rathbone out of the way,
however, Lathbury would be next in line to succeed one of the current
editors. I don't think he worried much about Hodgskin. Probably
thought he was too batty to be seriously in the running."
</P>
<P>    They interviewed Lathbury in his office later that night. At first, he
adamantly denied everything. When, in a fit of pique, he contemptuously
derided them as "feckless gumshoes who conjure up slanderous fairy tales
out of thin air predicated on scuttlebutt, cashmere coats, and pebbles,"
they knew they had him. Only the killer would have known about the
pebble and its central role in Rathbone's death by the invisible hand.
<P>
<!--Body text above this line-->
