<html><head><title>Death by the invisible hand</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="story.gif" width="285" height="28" alt="">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<img src="deathby.gif"><br>
<h3>Ending written by <i>Nikunj R. Sanghvi</i></h3>
<p>
<!--Body text below this line-->

<B><I>Friday evening</I></B>
<br>
After further questioning, Greg and Asquith decided to call it a
day and return to the police station. Just as Greg entered his
cabin, the phone on his desk started ringing. Wearily, Greg
picked it up. "Sir, it's Chief Inspector Palgrave on the other
end," said his secretary.
<P>"Ok, pass the line."
<P>"Greg, its all over," announced  Palgrave "All's well that
ends well and rightly so. I'm sorry I had to hide some vital
details from you."
<P>"What's over ? I'm sorry sir, I don't have the faintest idea
what you're speaking about," replied a nonplussed Greg.
<P>"Greg, Tom wasn't murdered at all - the corpse that you saw
was of some poor soul who had died that very afternoon," Palgrave
said. "But I can't reveal more on the phone. If you could come
over now, we could have a detailed talk."

<P>Later, over a cup of coffee, Palgrave made the revelation.
"You may not be knowing this, but Tom Rathbone was one of the
most respected investigative reporters here. He was currently
investigating some shady transactions carried on by a syndicate
of investment banks, chief among them being the Glarings Bank. It
seems that the top management of these banks had used bank funds
to indulge in massive speculation in the stock and bullion markets
of Europe and Asia. The brains behind this operation, which
was in outright contravention of the law, was one Rick Freeson.
Now, Tom was digging up the facts, when he caught scent of the
wheeling and dealing going on. Somehow, the people at Glarings
got wind of Tom's activities. They were understandably displeased;
their stakes seem to be so high that they've hired a
hit man to do away with Tom."
<P>"The Glarings Bank hired a hit man! Unbelievable!" exclaimed
Greg.
<P>"Well, not the bank exactly, but Freeson,"replied the Chief
Inspector, "Freeson apparently had his hand too deep in this. Tom
came to know this when he narrowly missed being the victim of a
hit-and-run car accident. He immediately contacted us and explained
the situation to me. He accepted that many of his findings
were vague and he needed a few more days to gather the
proof. That was on Monday evening. On Tuesday, Tom closely escaped
another murder attempt, this time at his house. This put me
thinking and I formulated a plan to buy time for Tom, till he
collected the proof he needed."
<P>"We contacted the senior editorial staff of <I>The Economist</I>
and told them about our plan. We would fool others into believing
that Tom had been murdered. Wednesday night, I transported a body
from the morgue that resembled Tom; I had it stowed inside a
truck parked outside The Economist Tower. It was Strachey who
made the hoax call at midnight, diverting the guard. During
that time, Tom was quickly whisked into a waiting
police car while we
planted the corpse near the statue. Strachey had it all neatly
arranged - the statue was levered using a pebble and a crowbar.
One of our boys gave a heave and that was that."
<P>"Oh, now I see, that corpse had been disguised in Tom's
clothes. The senior editors identified the corpse as Tom's and we
had taken away the body before anyone else could have a look."
<P>"Precisely," said the Chief Inspector, "our entire plan was
to convey the news that Tom had died, to the public in general and
the people at Glarings in particular. Freeson would breathe easy
and call off the hit man. This gave Tom the valuable time that he
needed. Tom is operating from a hideout in the suburbs, that I've
reserved for him. Yesterday, he and Geoffrey spent the entire day
unearthing the vital information. Just an hour ago, I received a
fax from him, giving me all the facts needed to proceed on these
banks. Greg, so now we have them in our hands."
<P>"Quite an interesting turn in the case, from a simple murder
to a white collar crime involving some of Britain's oldest and
most respected banks. You had the rest of us fooled," admitted
Greg sheepishly.
<P>"The secrecy was vital for our plan, Greg. Anyway, tomorrow
we have a lot of action on our hands. Here's a preliminary list
of the big shots involved," said Palgrave, handing over a piece
of paper, on which he had scribbled some names."So catch a good
night's sleep, 'cos tomorrow promises to be a hectic day."
<P>
<B><I>Saturday morning</I></B>
<BR>
The morning went quickly and by afternoon, the police had rounded
up most of the directors, as well as Freeson and his accomplices.
Their faces were a mixture of amazement, consternation and pure
shock as they read the arrest warrants.
<P>Freeson knew that it was all over when he saw the warrant
proclaiming him guilty not only of financial crimes, but also of
attempt to murder. Under interrogation, he spilled the beans.
"Yes, we were carrying on massive speculation in the stock and
bullion markets. Two weeks ago, Henry Lathbury from <I>The Economist</I>
approached me, saying he had vital information, which he could
part with, for a price. A hundred thousand pounds later, he told
us that Mr.Tom Rathbone had incriminating evidence about our
speculative transactions, and was going to publish it in <I>The
Economist</I>. Also, he could not be bought with money. At that
stage, we could least afford a public disclosure - it was a
question of billions and the fate of some of the best financial
institutions of England was involved. We unanimously decided that
Tom had to be done away with. But, my man had tried twice and
failed both times, and he says that this murder was not done at
his hands."
<P>
<B><I>Saturday evening</I></B>
<BR>Later that day, the hit man as well as Mr Lathbury were
held.
<P>A party was held in honour of Tom and all <I>The Economist</I> staff,
as well as Palgrave, Greg and Asquith were present.
<P>Everybody congratulated Palgrave on his brilliant plan.
<P>"Excuse me, sir" said Asquith, "but was this the best way to
protect Tom? And what about the e-mail received by Julia?"
<P>"Giving police protection to Tom would have aroused suspicion
in the mind of Freeson, and he could've turned even more
aggressive," replied Palgrave.
<P>"As for the e-mail, that was just made up by me, when
Edward told me that we were doing this just to buy time," said
Julia.
<P>Suddenly, a loud crash diverted everyone's attention. It was
Greg, who rushing out to meet an urgent call, had crashed into
the 'Pursuit Of Reason'.

<!--Body text above this line-->
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
