</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Death by the invisible hand</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="story.gif" width="285" height="28" alt="">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<img src="deathby.gif"><br>
<h3>Ending written by <i>Jason Modesto</i></h3>
<P>
<!--Body text below this line-->
<B><I>Friday Evening</I></B>
<BR>"My apologies for keeping you waiting," sighed the exasperated

editor.  "I don't need to tell you what a hectic week it has been. 
Was it too much to ask for a slow news Friday?  It appears that Alan 
Greenspan casually told his waiter that his coffee was too strong.  
Apparently, someone at a neighboring table thought he said that the 
ECONOMY was too strong.  Needless to say, New York stocks took a sharp 
dive before the steak was even served.  Oh well, why have you gathered 
the entire staff here?"
<P>"Well actually," explained Asquith, "we couldn't begin without 
you.  We have reason to believe you murdered Rathbone to preserve your 
domination of the editorial room."
<P>"That's preposterous," bellowed the incredulous editor.  "I have 
been the voice of sanity at those meetings!  Would someone here please 
vouch for my honour?"
<P>Silence.
<P>"Anyone?" begged the editor.
<P>"Well," offered the finance editor, "I have never seen him lose 
his temper or appear out of control.  Occasionally he'll look stressed 
when faced with breaking news or a pressing deadline, but that is always 
ameliorated when he,...ahem, helps himself to the many young female 
secretaries he has carefully accumulated."
<P>"I...I...uh, I don't know what you're talking about," retorted 
the blushing editor.
<P>"He has the libido of a royal," added the clearly envious 
finance editor.  "He doesn't even have the energy left over to even think 
about murder.  His weakness for the fairer sex is his only character 
flaw, if you would even call it one."
<P>"In my estimation, being a snitch is a more serious character 
flaw," said the annoyed editor.  "If word of this gets to the Fleet 
Street reporters hovering outside this building, this publication will 
be further diminished."
<P>"On the other hand, it might shift media attention away from the 
fact that there is a murderer in this very room," said an impatient 
deputy editor.
<P>Greg took his cue to redirect the discussion.  He motioned to 
Asquith that his "intellectual" theory was going nowhere, and now Greg 
would proceed with his own, more traditional, murder theories. 
<P>"Rathbone was a mere journalist," argued Greg.  "How could he 
afford such lavish clothes?  How much are journalists paid?"
<P>"Not nearly as well as the editors," said the upset journalist 
Henry Lathbury.
<P>"Wonderful, now everyone is joining the mutiny against me.  I'll 
have you know, Henry, that working at the internationally acclaimed 
<I>Economist</I> is a privilege in itself," said the beseiged editor.
<P>"Unfortunately, all of the,...ahem, 'benefits' accrue to your 
pants," muttered the finance editor.
<P>Greg ignored the gossip, and instead focused on the income 
issue.  "So how could he afford that cashmere coat?"
<P>"He couldn't."  It was said so meekly that, at first, no one 
knew who said it.  "It was a gift.  I gave it to him."  The voice 
belonged to the Britain editor, Dr. Sophie Hamilton.
<P>Greg approached with tact.  "Is there something you wish to tell 
us?"
<P>"Tom and I," began an emotional Dr. Hamilton.  She stared at the 
floor and brought her head up again.  "Tom and I were lovers ever since 
we hired him.  He was intelligent, daring, and passionate; not like the 
careful, and 'rational' dismal scientists that populate this place.  I 
was with him on that last night.  He made a prank call to remove the 
security guard as he set out to vandalize 'Market Forces.'  I was his 
lookout."
<P>"Why would he do such a thing?" enquired Greg.
<P>"He was a rebel," she replied.  "That's why I loved him.  It was 
a political as well as an aesthetic statement.  I enjoyed the excitement 
of being free.  He enjoyed dressing up for the clandestine operation in 
his coat and gloves."
<P>Asquith saw an opportunity.  "So you decided to murder him 
because you feared that he was dominating the meetings.  He was a 
potential roadblock in your career path.  Afterall, you are young, 
smart, ambitious, and so was he."
<P>"I was his biggest champion," she replied.  "I defended him in 
the meetings, and constantly shifted assignments to him."
<P>"Don't be silly, Asquith," said Greg.  "She obviously murdered 
him because while she was showering gifts on him, he was showering 
attention on other women, such as Julia."
<P>"I didn't mind sharing him," she replied.  "It made him that 
much more desirable.  Besides, I DIDN'T murder him.  While I was the 
lookout, I leaned against the side of 'Market Forces', and to my shock, 
the wobbly thing tipped over and crushed Tom to death.  His hand was 
free, but there was no pulse.  I panicked, fearing my reputation would 
be ruined if I was caught in this childish prank that ended in disaster.  
So I did something I don't normally do: I played dumb.  When we 
encountered the body, I was the first to identify it."
<P>"But you pointed the finger at Geoffrey?" asked Asquith, who was 
still not letting go of his theory.  "Kill TWO intellectual competitors 
with one stone, Dr. Hamilton?"
<P>"Geoffrey was never my intellectual competitor.  I just wanted 
to have Tom's death to have the intrigue and importance that would befit 
his brilliant mind and once-promising career.  I'm coming clean now to 
get our editor off the hook.  Now, Tom's death seems utterly boring."
<P>"Boring indeed," added Greg.  "Also unbelievable.  'Market 
Forces' has a rock-solid base.  One cannot lean on it to make it fall 
over.  One would have to jack it up beforehand and use a pebble to make 
it 'wobbly.'  This implies pre-meditation--not a mere accident.  
Asquith, I think we found our murderer!"
<P>"I didn't plant that bloody pebble.  YOU probably did!"
<P>"Madam, this is NOT Los Angeles," replied Greg.  "Accusing us of 
planting a bloody ANYTHING will not set you free." 
<P>"Hold it," begged Zoe.  "She might be telling the truth.  You 
see, I went to berate Tom for winding up Geoffrey.  Tom was delighted to 
see 'Fiscal Rectitude' destroyed; he said that it was the best 
contribution Geoffrey has ever made.  Moreover, he said it gave him an 
idea to do a number on 'Market Forces.'  He saw it as too massive to 
bring down, so he planned to deface it.  Tom thought that if enough 
'accidents' could happen to the artwork, they would stop displaying 
them.  He had to act soon because they were thinking about purchasing a 
new one.  He showed me the picture: two Laffer curves, side-by-side.  
The most pornographic thing I have ever seen.  Straight from the Benny 
Hill School of Design, if you ask me."
<P>"Tom hated the art because of politics," Zoe continued.  "I 
hated the art because they were so god-awful.  It was the only thing Tom 
and I had in common.  But I knew that merely defacing 'Market Forces' 
would not destroy it, because they would just paint over it--the 
Economist is legendary in its thriftiness.  I knew it had to be 
toppled over.  Geoffrey has an ample frame, but even he couldn't topple 
it during one of his rampages--not without first making the base 
unstable.  It nearly broke my back, but I managed to jack it up and 
lodge that pebble myself--just a little 'intervention,' if you will.  
Dr. Hamilton's accident is certainly plausible."
<P>"It's like I said before," said the relieved editor.  "There are 
no murderers here."
<P>"Apparently not," said a reluctant Greg.  "Plenty of 
skirt-chasers and mischief-makers, though.  Asquith, do you have the 
same empty feeling I have.  It was not intellectual, nor over love, nor 
over money.  It was just an improbable accident borne of a string of 
small decisions."
<P>"Just like real market forces," smiled Asquith.  "Of course, my 
parents told me that I am alive due to a happy 'accident' nine months 
before my birth."
<P>"Let's go drown that empty feeling.  It's the weekend.  You know 
what that means?"
<P>"Steak-and-kidney pie, I presume?" asked Asquith.
<P>"And a pint of bitter!"

<!--Body text above this line-->
