</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Death by the invisible hand</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="story.gif" width="285" height="28" alt="">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<img src="deathby.gif"><br>
<h3>Ending written by <i>Frank Ackerman</i></h3>
<p>
<!--Body text below this line-->
<P>But none of these questions, except perhaps the last, was to be
answered that afternoon.  As Greg and Asquith returned to the lobby, they
found much of the staff gathered around Isaac Webster, the normally
mild-mannered science and technology editor.  Webster, visibly distraught,
was gesturing toward the restored statue of "Market Forces" and talking in
an uncharacteristically loud and anguished tone:

<P>"If you paid more attention to our articles on complexity theory,
you'd recall that market outcomes are unpredictable in the presence of
increasing returns and system economies of scale.  And it's not just
markets that are unpredictable -- one of the classic experiments in
complexity shows that a single grain of sand dropped on a seemingly stable
pyramidal structure can trigger an avalanche.

<P>"So when I looked out the window here and saw our own pyramid, I
thought to myself, I can demonstrate the instability of market forces by
demonstrating the instability of 'Market Forces'."

<P>"Isaac, you're babbling," said Sophie Hamilton.  But it would take
more than a gentle interruption to stop Webster's passionate monologue.

<P>"After spending several weekends analyzing the geometry of 'Market
Forces'," he continued, "I found the exact spot where a single impact
could cause a dramatic turn of events.  I even picked out the perfect
pebble to drop on that spot -- though when I went back to look for it this
morning, the pebble was nowhere to be found.  It's almost as if someone
walked off with it.

<P>"I wanted to try the experiment for the first time when no one else
was around, in case it didn't work.  Midnight on Wednesday seemed like a
safe time.  The science and technology articles are always done by 5:30,
and I thought the rest of you would be out of here by 7:00 or 8:00 at the
latest.  But as soon as I dropped the pebble and 'Market Forces' began to
tilt, Rathbone came storming out of the building, muttering to himself
about a woman and paying no attention to his surroundings.  Of course,
complexity leads to path-dependent outcomes, but -- if only Tom had taken
the path to the right instead of the left!"

<P>"That's the story of his whole miserable life in a nutshell,"  said
Hodgskin with a snarl.

<P>Silence fell on the group for a moment, as Webster bent over, close
to tears.  Everyone else was too stunned to speak.  Then, as Greg and
Asquith moved toward the assembled crowd, Webster looked up with a
disturbing new gleam in his eye.

<P>"Maybe Rathbone didn't die in vain," he said.  "If his death helps
advance the state of scientific understanding, it's not a complete loss."
Louder and wilder now: "Can we imagine that our Tom, like Schrdinger's
cat, wasn't really dead until we observed him? Certainly not.  The fractal
instability of space-time that caused 'Market Forces' to teeter and fall
has finally laid to rest the outrageous Copenhagen interpretation of
quantum mechanics."

<P>"What a bore," said Zoe.  "What is he talking about?"

<P>Zoe was not alone in her bewilderment.  To his listeners, all of whom
possessed only modest backgrounds in the hard sciences, Webster seemed to
have swallowed a dictionary, and was spitting it back out, faster and
faster: "Under the now-vindicated many-worlds interpretation of quantum
indeterminacy, there is a universe in which black helicopters actually are
invading America, and another one in which Rathbone is alive and well,
advising a militant Labour prime minister on the creation of more
participatory forms of socialism..."

<P>"Hold it right there," snapped Greg, grabbing Webster firmly by the
wrist.  "Never mind your 'Copenhagen interpretations' -- I know when
someone's gone one Tuborg over the line.  We've got a nice, safe cell down
at the station where you can dry out overnight.  In the morning when
you're sober, you're going to tell us in plain English how and why you
killed Rathbone."

<P>With a farewell shout of "History is governed by chance, not
optimality; 'Market Forces' will fail again!", Webster was led away by
Greg and Asquith.

<P>Moments later, back in the editor's office, a bottle of whiskey was
out on the desk for the second time in less than 48 hours.  "The poor
bloke drove himself bonkers by thinking too hard, didn't he?", said Julia.
"If only he had stuck to those quaint little stories everyone could
understand about rare frogs or engineering marvels."

<P>"Still," mused the editor, "there's something unsettling in that
'many worlds' bit he was running on about.  Is it an unspeakable idea,
like protectionism, or just unthinkable?  How do we know which of the many
possible worlds this has become?  If Julia opens the curtains and we look
down at the street, will we see the comforting stability of 'Market
Forces', an invasion of black helicopters, or something else entirely?"

<P>Julia opened the curtains and everyone looked down at the street.


