<html><head><title>The likely winners</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>The likely winners</h1>

<p>SOME day in the far-distant future the luckiest net-heads will have fibre-optic cables pumping light-speed data straight from the Internet into their sitting rooms. But until then (digging up streets is expensive), keen surfers will have to make do with one or another of the technologies covered in this series of briefs. So which technologies are likeliest to be used?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In those countries with large, established cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> networks--America, Canada, Germany and a handful of others--cable modems will probably be the first high-speed technology to show up. Cable companies are eager to compete with telephone companies, and upgrading their networks to carry two-way data allows them to offer telephony, too. Where the cable companies lead, telephone firms will follow with high-speed <font size=-1>ADSL</font> (asymmetric digital subscriber line) connections over their own systems. But they will have to subsidise <font size=-1>ADSL</font> to start with, to match the cost of the technologically simpler cable modems. As the costs drop and use rises, <font size=-1>ADSL</font> will increasingly have an edge: unlike cable networks, the telephone companies do not need to share their bandwidth between many users.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;" Wireless cable", as digital radio transmission is known, may be the technology of choice for companies that want to enter this market but do not have existing networks of wires to build upon. But, while good for <font size=-1>TV</font>, this sort of wireless will rarely be the fastest choice for the Internet, mostly because it suffers even more than regular cable networks from the problem of shared bandwidth. For the peripatetic Internet user, packet radio will be a cheap alternative to sending data over cellular telephones, but only in the most technology-mad urban areas. This sort of data-only niche is too small to succeed elsewhere.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Today's satellite offerings may be too limited and expensive to tempt many Internet users, but tomorrow's might be better. Iridium and its kin will deliver e-mail anywhere, while Teledesic--if it works--promises to simulate the multimedia riches of fibre-optic cable in parts of the developing world that may not see the real thing for decades.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838422000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
