<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/30-03-96/sf2.html 199.173.162.110 19970215055951 text/html 7220
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 05:55:47 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:00 GMT
Content-length: 7033
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>SE suddenly arrived from nowhere to attack huge numbers of British cattle. It has barely been seen in other countries. Why Britain? Why now?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif" alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>


<h1>The British Desease</h1><p>BSE suddenly arrived from nowhere to attack huge numbers of British cattle. It has barely been seen in other countries. Why Britain? Why now? (See <a href="sf2.gif">chart</a>)

<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most people think that <font size=-1>BSE</font> came from sheep infected by scrapie. As meal containing bits of infectious sheep was fed to cows, they could have developed <font size=-1>BSE</font>. As bits of these cows were then converted into meal and fed back to other cows, the disease spread.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But why Britain? It is possible it was just a lightning strike of bad luck. But there are other explanations. Few places outside Europe suffer from scrapie in sheep and also raise large numbers of cattle. Within Europe, few countries have rendered down carcasses at low temperatures. And few countries have gone so far as to make 4-5% of their cattle rations from meat and bone meal. Britain has all three of these factors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Feeding herbivores boiled-down animals predates <font size=-1>BSE</font> by a few decades and is widespread. In the 1970s, however, rendering businesses switched from an old-fashioned technique that used a noxious solvent and high temperatures, to the American Carver-Greenfield process, which operates at lower temperatures and was meant to make meat and bone meal more nutritious and appetising.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Britain, however, renderers kept the temperatures unusually low--sometimes less than 100C (which is needed to kill even humble bacteria, let alone heat-resistant prions). In France and Italy, renderers heat the brew up to 130-140C--though even that, according to Bram Schreuder of the Institute for Animal Science and Health at Lelystad in Holland, may not destroy prions completely. A committee of its own experts warned the British government that low temperatures could be dangerous as early as 1980, six years before the first case of <font size=-1>BSE</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps, given modern farming methods, <font size=-1>BSE</font> was bound to crop up somewhere. Perhaps British farming cannot be blamed for that. But the British government deserves criticism for the way it has reacted to the disease.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As soon as other European countries suspected that animal meal might be spreading <font size=-1>BSE</font>, they banned it. France and Ireland (though not Switzerland) have from the beginning taken the further precaution of destroying all animals in any herd that has seen a case of <font size=-1>BSE</font>. In contrast, Britain's record has been mixed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In July 1988 the government was prompt to ban the use of cows and sheep to feed other cows and sheep. This was six months before a government committee set up to study the problem gave its report. In August 1988, the government insisted on the slaughter of infected animals and the destruction of their milk.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the July 1988 ban has not been fully enforced. Farmers, who often have a few months' supplies of meal, still had an incentive to get rid of it in the bellies of their cows. Even now, at the back of barns there could be contaminated feed. Worse, with lots of unusable bits of cow and sheep around, feed-makers may have been tempted to smuggle them into food. Nobody knows how much infected material was illegally included in meal. Some believe that offal has continued to be incorporated until recently. That would explain why the <font size=-1>BSE</font> epidemic in Britain has still not been brought under control. Though it has peaked, cases are being reported at the rate of over 70 a week.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If meal is still being infected, that is bad enough. But if the problem lies elsewhere, then the implications are no less disturbing. Any infection in younger cows--and there have been over 23,000 cases since July 1988--could mean either that the disease can be passed from cow to calf, or that it persists in the soil. Both these possibilities seem highly unlikely for <font size=-1>BSE</font>: of all non-inherited prion diseases only scrapie behaves in this way. But they cannot be ruled out because contaminated feed has obscured investigations into why young cows died.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As a result, doubts will remain about the policy of culling Britain's cattle. Calves or the soil might continue to harbour the disease. To eradicate the British herd could cost &#163;15 billion ($22.5 billion). The cull would certainly reduce the amount of <font size=-1>BSE</font>; whether it would restore consumer confidence is less certain.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Consumers are worried whether beef is safe to eat. Steak almost certainly is. The government has rightly pointed out that muscle (ie, meat) does not seem to carry <font size=-1>BSE</font>. Experiments on all forms of prion disease have not yet detected any infection in muscle. Even if there are nerves in the meat, they do not carry the disease because they are outside the central nervous system. The danger lies in eating pies, burgers and sausages which might have bits of infectious brain or spinal cord in them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Beef is safer than it was before the government acted. But it is impossible to be sure that butchers are keeping muscle separate and uncontaminated. It is also impossible to prevent a few infected animals ending up in slaughterhouses. Even if farmers send no ailing cows to market, some animals may be infectious without showing symptoms of <font size=-1>BSE</font>. Abattoirs have been prosecuted for ignoring the rules. And even honest slaughterhouses are messy places. Only in November 1995 did the government stop anyone stripping meat from cows' back-bones. It had found that small fragments of potentially dangerous spinal cord had been left attached to them. Mad-cow disease may not yet be out of the human food chain.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828136800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
