<meta name="description" content="Soros Foundations Network, Open Society Institute and National Foundations created and funded by George Soros">
<meta name="keywords" content="Open Society Institute, George Soros, Soros Foundations, National Foundations">
<title>National Foundations</title> </head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">
<font size = 2><a href="/textonly/tfound.html"><b>Text Only Menu</b></a></font>
<table cellpadding=6>                                                       
<tr>                                                                        
<td>                                                                        
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                             
<td>                                                                        
<img align=middle src="/images/found.gif" alt="National Foundations">    
</td>                                                                       
<td>                                            
<img align=middle src="/images/worlds.gif"> 
</td>                                           
</tr>                                                                       
</table>                                                                    
National Foundations of the Soros network currently operate in 
24 countries across Central and Eastern Europe, the former 
Soviet Union, 
<a href="/safrica.html"><b>South Africa</b></a>, 
and 
<a href="/haiti.html"><b>Haiti</b></a>. 
To select a foundation in 
a specific country, click on a country name below. 
<p>
The national foundations are autonomous nongovernmental 
organizations registered in their own countries and staffed 
by local professionals. The directors and program staff of 
each national foundation are accountable to a board of 
directors comprised of distinguished citizens from 
representative ethnic, political, geographical, and 
professional backgrounds.
<p>
<center>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/imagemap/world"><img src="world.gif" border=5 ISMAP></a>
</center>
<p>
The national foundations develop their own programs in 
support of the mission and strategic goals established by 
their directors and staff to build open societies in their 
countries. These programs vary greatly in nature and urgency 
from country to country. Some foundations, such as Georgia 
and Haiti, began their programs in 1995, hiring staff, 
developing priorities, and awarding their first grants. 
Others, such as Hungary and Poland, have been in the 
forefront of the movement toward open society since before 
the revolutionary changes of 1989.
<p>
With the cessation of war in the countries of the former 
Yugoslavia, the foundation in Bosnia and Herzegovina reports 
that, for the first time since its creation in 1992, it was 
able to switch from humanitarian projects to long-term 
programs aimed at helping rebuild education, independent 
media, and other fields devastated by the fighting.
<p>
<i>
The following list of national foundations by the year of their 
creation shows how quickly the network has grown since the breakup of the Soviet Union and the collapse 
of communism in Eastern Europe.
</i>
