<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<html>
<head>
<title> 
About This Site            
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" link="2F7348" alink="2F7348" vlink="5D8B6B">
<table cellpadding=6>                                              
<tr>                                                               
<td>                                                               
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                    
<td>                                                               
<img align=middle src="/images/tech.gif" alt="About This Site">  
</td>                                                              
</tr>                                                              
</table>                                                           
<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=6>
<tr>
<td><a href="wusage/index.html"><b>Site Statistics</b></a></td>
<td><a href="awards.html"><b>Awards</b></a></td>
</table> 
</center>
<p>
<h2>
About This Site
</h2> 
Because information is such an important part of an open society, we have created a host to serve the broadest possible
constituency. This includes those with only e-mail access as well as those with a WWW connection. Our WWW site is limited in its use of graphics to insure that those in the developing world with low speed internet connections also have an easy time accessing it. We are trying to insure that the entities who generate information for this server have the ability to update the data themselves as well. 
<p>
To achieve our stated goals, we designed our site in a rather interesting way using a mix of Internet tools: 
<p>
<pre>
	User Access (WWW)---} Gopher Server {---(Gopher Mail) User Access 
				   ^    
				   |
			   (G-Mail) User Update 
</pre>
<p>
As the diagram above indicates, we used a Gopher server as a primary engine to store data. This allows users with graphics or character-based WWW access as well as basic Gopher users to view information on our site. More significantly, we use
Gopher mail to facilitate access to our data for those who only use e-mail. Our information is therefore available via multiple
types of access. 
<p>
In order to insure that our constituent organizations in the field who generate the information for this system also have
maximum flexibility in defining its content, we use G-Mail to allow them to update their own data on the gopher. This also
insures that our small design team concentrates more on the extension of this host's offerings than in content generation and
management of local Foundation Information. As Internet connectivity has expanded, many Foundations have created their own sites as well and we have in turn linked to them. 
<p>
The site is intentionally minimalist on the graphics side to allow for low bandwidth access and text versions of WWW pages with the most graphics have been added. It may not be the prettiest WWW site you have ever seen, but we hope to make it one of the most functional in order to meet the information needs of our diverse constituency. The design has the added benefit of minimizing centralized data control and management, (also a function of an open society and a decentralized management structure). Welcome, we hope you enjoy it.
We are <b>always</b> adding new Information, feel free to look around.
<p>
Jonathan Peizer<br>
Chief Information Officer<br>
Open Society Institute<br>
<address> <a href="mailto:jpeizer@sorosny.org"><b>jpeizer@sorosny.org</b></a></address><p>

<h2>
About the Design Team
</h2> 
A lot of people have been working together to make this site possible:
<p>
<b>Anthony Galietti</b> -
UNIX and Internet Systems Administrator - Anthony is the first line of support for this Internet site. Anthony makes sure the servers are up, information is backed up, and the information is always up-to-date on this site.
<p>
<b>Horace Chang</b> -
Director of Systems - Responsible for our diverse network environment. 
<p>
<b>Bob Horvitz</b> - Internet Program Coordinator and Media Consultant Is responsible for coordinating development of all
our information servers around the network and analyzing what other neat resources are out there as well. He makes sure the
links are set correctly, and the message is consistent.
<p>
<b>Tim Cornish</b> - The original Internet Systems Administrator and Trainer - Tim implemented the gopher server engine and was the original first line of support. He has now moved on to a more aesthetic existence in Vermont. 
<p>
<b>Allen Wong</b> - Former Network Administrator - Initially coordinated our Novell/Unix/Apple network. 
<p>

Communications Department Helped us define the content and lay it out correctly for this rather diverse and decentralized
organization. Thank god WWW is relational!!!
<p>

The team is relatively small given this is one of many projects we are all involved in. However, we were able to put this together in a relatively short time (once we went on-line) because each person
came to the table with a different expertise. An important lesson for those of you who wish to create your own information
server. It requires: 
<p>
<ul>
<li>A person to market the concept and its uses to a diverse 
constituency 
<li>A person knowledgeable of content and how it should be organized A person to integrate the information services in a decentralized 
environment 
<li>A person to demonstrate the service and train others to use it A person to develop and administrate the various Internet 
information services 
<li>A network administrator to maintain and integrate the technical 
aspects of the service 
<li>A person with basic programming expertise 
<li>Users interested enough to test the Internet and the information 
services provided 
</ul>
<p>
Finally I'd like to thank our users, who are consistently adding to the quality and content of the site and our Internet/Automation coordinators around the world who create their own great sites and finally to you, the users of this web site who provide comments to help improve it.<p>
<center>
<A HREF="http://ugweb.cs.ualberta.ca/~gerald/validate/"><IMG
     SRC="/images/valid_html3.2.gif"
     ALT="HTML 3.2 Checked!"></A>

<A HREF="http://www.webtechs.com/html-val-svc/">
<IMG SRC="/images/valid_html-wilbur.gif" 
ALT="W3C Wilbur Checked!"></A>
