<DOCHDR>
http://server.soros.org:80/usprog.html 204.168.83.130 19970112092648 text/html 14444
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 12 Jan 1997 09:20:45 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html>                                                                          
<head>                                                                          
<title> About OSI's United States Programs                                      
</title>                                                                        
</head>                                                                         
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF"  text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                              <center><h2>About OSI's United States Programs</h2>
<h4>Existing programs concerning:</h4> 
<a href="/crime"><b>Crime and Prisons</b></a>/
<a href="/death.html"><b>Death and Dying</b></a>/
<a href="http://www.lindesmith.org"><b>Drug Policy</b></a>/
<a href="/emma_lazarus.html"><b>Immigration</b></a>
<p>
<h4>Other Program Interests:</h4>
<a href="#education"><b>Education</b></a>/
<a href="#health"><b>Reproductive Health and Choice</b></a>/
<a href="#arts"><b>Arts and Culture</b></a>/
<a href="#ethics"><b>Professional Ethics and Standards</b></a>/
<a href="#political"><b>Political Reform</b></a>
<p>
<a href="#principles"><b>Operating Principles</b></a>/
<a href="#approaches"><b>Operating Approaches</b></a>
</center><p>
Beginning in mid-1996, the Open Society Institute (OSI) undertook a significant
expansion of its programs focused on the United States. Why is an organization
that has traditionally been primarily concerned with countries making the transition
from repression to democracy now devoting substantial resources to the world's
leading democracy?<p>
The answer lies in the observation that the values of 
<a href="/faq.html"><b>open society</b></a>
are in disrepair in the United States. 
Schools in many inner-city communities are
barely functioning, leaving large numbers of children poorly educated and
unprepared for the future. An increasing reliance on imprisonment as the
response to crime has resulted in a soaring incarceration rate. Commercial
success has eclipsed other standards for judging achievement in fields such as
law, medicine, and journalism, to the detriment of professional ethics and
public confidence. The arts too have become increasingly subject to the
vagaries of the marketplace.<p>
Finally, in today's United States, democracy itself is not functioning very
well. A smaller proportion of the population votes than in other developed
countries. Political campaigns have become increasingly negative and divisive,
and running for office has become so expensive as to virtually exclude those
who eschew contributions from political action committees or who are not
themselves wealthy.<p>
<h2>Program Areas</h2>
In establishing new programs to deal with these concerns, the Open Society
Institute builds on two U.S.-focused programs, established in 1994: 
<a href="http://www.lindesmith.org"><b>The Lindesmith Center</b></a>, 
a research institute that seeks to broaden the debate on
drug policy and related issues; and the 
<a href="/death.html"><b>Project on Death in America</b></a>,
which works to enhance comfort, dignity, care and relief from pain for the
dying.  In 1996, OSI launched the 
<a href="/emma_lazarus.html"><b>Emma Lazarus Fund</b></a>
to assist
legal immigrants harmed by recent welfare reform legislation, and also the
<a href="/crime"><b>Center on Crime, Communities &amp; Culture</b></a>, 
a grantmaking, research, and
fellowship program that seeks to promote effective and humane responses to
criminal behavior and victimization.  In addition, OSI has established the
<a href="/fellow.html"><b>OSI Fellowships Program</b></a>
to support projects that foster the development
of open society worldwide and to help OSI develop new program areas.<br>
<br>
The following additional program areas are under development.  To receive
guidelines as they are developed, send an e-mail to:
<address><a href="mailto:usprograms@sorosny.org"><b>(usprograms@sorosny.org)</b></a></address>                                   
<p>
<a name="education"></a>  
<b>Education</b>:  OSI is developing guidelines for programs that seek to build
a stronger and more diverse constituency for effective, free, public education;
provide arts and enrichment programs, instruction and training in contemporary
science and technology; involve parents in their children's schooling; and
encourage and support good teaching.<p>
<a name="health"></a>  
<b>Reproductive Health and Choice</b>:  OSI is developing guidelines that aim
to reduce a rate of teenage pregnancy that is higher in the United States than
in any other developed country; enhance access to safe and effective
contraception for women of all ages; promote awareness about sex and
reproduction at the earliest appropriate opportunities; encourage sexual
responsibility in young men and boys; and protect women's control over their
reproductive lives, through support for abortion rights and contraceptive
advances.<p>
<a name="arts"></a>  
<b>Arts and Culture</b>:  In an environment where arts and cultural activities 
are increasingly marginalized by the commercial marketplace, OSI is 
interested in programs that support shared public cultural experiences, 
particularly among low-income communities; scout and support young talents; 
and restore a sense of civic obligation to support the arts.<p>
<a name="ethics"></a>  
<b>Professional Ethics and Standards</b>:  OSI is interested in programs that
aim to reverse the trend toward treating professions simply as businesses.  In
the law, OSI will consider programs that support changes in the content and
financing of legal education to encourage careers that serve the public
interest, particularly providing legal representation for the poor; that
strengthen pro bono activity by the private bar; and that counter restrictions
on legal advocacy for social change and mounting attacks on the independence of
the judiciary.<p>
In medicine, OSI will consider programs that help restore a professional
commitment to the care and treatment of all patients, regardless of means;
protect the confidentiality of the physician/patient relationship from new
assaults under managed care and other regulatory schemes; and deal with issues
of schooling and public interest work similar to those in the legal
profession.<p>
In journalism, OSI will consider programs that encourage more professional
responsibility without in any way infringing on First Amendment rights; provide
space for minority perspectives and analysis in a media marketplace where
control is increasingly centralized in a handful of large corporations; and
promote stronger coverage of community issues-- on radio and television, in
particular--in order to foster more informed civic participation at the local
level.<p>
<a name="political"></a>  
<b>Political Reform:</b>  OSI will consider programs that promote a
constitutional and practical system of election campaign financing that makes
it possible for citizens who are not wealthy, or tethered to powerful
commercial interests, to run for public office; programs that promote a less
cumbersome means of access to the ballot and voter registration; and electoral
practices that enhance civic participation.<p>
<a name="principles"></a>  
<h2>Operating Principles</h2>
The programs supported and operated by the Open Society Institute in the United
States will be diverse, eclectic, and fluid. But our activities will be
governed by a set of basic principles, including:<p>
<b>Fallibility</b>: The concept of open society is based on the recognition
that our understanding of the world in which we live is inherently imperfect.
As G.K. Chesterton said of Buddhism, open society is "not a creed, but a
doubt." Recognizing that human understanding will always be imperfect, OSI
opposes the notion that there is any single blueprint that can serve as a
solution to social problems. Foundations often forget that they are fallible;
grant applicants are unlikely to remind them.  In expanding its U.S. programs,
OSI will keep in mind that actions have unintended consequences and that good
intentions are not sufficient to ensure good results. In promoting the values
of open society, OSI will follow a process of trial and error rather than a
grand design.<p>
<b>Debate</b>: A society in which all ideas are subject to scrutiny and debate
is a society more tolerant of dissent and minorities, and one more conducive to
progress in social welfare and innovation in scholarship, science, and culture.
The Open Society Institute will work to strengthen public discourse,
particularly in areas thought to be taboo or where one side of the argument
dominates and drowns out the other, because suppressing discussion and
information exacerbates virtually every social crisis and impedes real
solutions.<p>
<b>Self-Government</b>: The Open Society Institute will focus on programs and
approaches that help people acquire or strengthen the ability to help
themselves. The Open Society Institute will be on the lookout for grassroots
initiatives and alert to the possibilities for replication in other
communities. Closely related to our interest in fostering debate and discussion
is our desire to enhance the capacity of marginalized groups to be heard -- to
affect public events and decisions through their own voices, and not simply
through reliance on others.<p>
<b>Strengthening Communities and Families</b>: "Community" can sometimes be a
code word for conformity or majoritarianism. The protection of individual
rights is the cornerstone of any open society, but no open society can thrive
if it is only a collection of self-interests. The Open Society Institute will
try to promote shared civic ethics and experiences, including support for
public art and culture and community service. The family is an element of civil
society that is sometimes overlooked. A focus on factors that undermine the
family might link work on teenage pregnancy rates that perpetuate a cycle of
ignorance and poverty; foster care policies that intervene and break up
families rather than offer support; schools that shut parents out; and a
criminal justice system that removes vast numbers of young men -- and,
increasingly, women -- from any meaningful family or community ties.<p>
<a name="approaches"></a>  
<h2>Operating Approaches</h2>
The programs supported and operated by the Open Society Institute in the United
States will also be guided by a set of basic operating approaches,
including:<p>
<b>Partnership</b>: Millions of dollars and hours have already been spent on
many of the areas in which OSI has chosen to work. Consequently, in many
instances, OSI will seek partnerships with existing organization or
individuals. To target resources effectively, OSI needs to know what has been
tried, what is working, what isn't, and where it is too soon to tell. In
addition, many areas, such as inner-city education, are so massive that no
single funder can have a significant impact operating in isolation.<p>
<b>Targeting</b>: Because the United States is such a vast country, OSI may, at
least initially, choose to focus on two or three cities and make a concerted
effort around only certain issues, such as education and criminal justice. In
selecting target cities, OSI will consider cities or communities of manageable
size, with promising possibilities for governmental, institutional, activist,
and philanthropic partners.<p>
<b>Services</b>: The Open Society Institute supports ideas and debate because
they are crucial to an open society and because they produce innovative and
novel approaches to serious social problems. But OSI's U.S. programs will focus
on supporting tangible programs, such as debate programs that foster
communication and advocacy skills in inner-city high school students;
transportation programs that make it easier for families to maintain ties with
their incarcerated relatives; needle exchange programs that reduce health harms
to addicts; hospices that ease suffering in the final days for the dying.<p>
<b>Investment in People</b>: The Open Society Institute's programs in the
United States will place a strong emphasis on education and training,
particularly of young people. Many of our new U.S. initiatives will provide
support for fellowships, internships, scholarships and research projects.<p>
<b>Affecting the Debate</b>: In selecting grantees, OSI will be particularly
responsive to those which have well-developed strategies for influencing public
awareness and discussion about the issues with which they are concerned, and
OSI will try to assist them in that regard. On all of the issues with which OSI
is concerned, the Institute will look for opportunities to advance new ideas in
the relevant community of leaders, scholars, and activists, through activities
such as roundtables, working groups, lectures, and seminars. To reach a broader
public, OSI will make use of new media such as the Internet, more traditional
means, such as pamphlets and other <a href="/publicat.html"><b>publications</b></a>.<p>
<b>Flexibility</b>: Whatever OSI's efforts to plan a program of activity in the
United States, important areas will inevitably be overlooked, or events will
add issues or shift priorities. In making preliminary choices among the many
issues pertinent to open society, OSI acknowledges that there are many other
issues that may deserve more focused attention in the future. The Open Society
Institute may also wish to support some institutions and initiatives that fall
outside our articulated areas of concern, or that play an important role in
fostering an open society across a number of areas of concern to us.
<hr>                                                                            
