<center>
<h1>Open Society Institute - Budapest</h1>
</center>
<blockquote>
The Open Society Institute-Budapest was established in 1993 to develop and 
implement programs in the areas of educational, legal, and social reform in 
<a href="/found.html"><b>                                                       
Albania, Belarus, Bulgaria, Bosnia & Herzegovina, Croatia, the Czech Republic, 
Estonia, Georgia, Haiti, Hungary, Kazakstan, Kyrgyzstan, Latvia, Lithuania,    
Macedonia, Moldova, Poland, Romania, Russia, Slovakia, Slovenia, South Africa, 
Ukraine, and Yugoslavia                                                        
</b></a>.                                                                      
These program are designed to complement the 
activities of the autonomous foundations created and funded by philanthropist
<a href="/gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a>
in those countries. The Open Society Institute-Budapest also 
provides administrative and financial support these foundations, which are 
linked together in an informal network. 
<p>
The Open Society Institute-Budapest 
Budapest supports a variety of other initiatives throughout Central and Eastern 
Europe and the former Soviet Union, with a strong emphasis on projects in the 
areas of human rights, ethnic and minority issues, civil society and women's 
issues. 
<p>
OSI-Budapest and its affiliated institutes are located in the 
<a href="/ceu.html"><b>Central European University</b></a>
complex in downtown Budapest, and their programs draw upon the 
university's resources. 
</blockquote>
<p>
OSI-Budapest programs and affiliated institutes include:<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/colpi.html"><b>Constitutional & Legislative Policy Institute</b></a> 
<li><a href="/epsu.html"><b>Education Program Support Unit</b></a> 
<li><a href="/ilgps.html"><b>Institute for Local Government & Public Service</b></a> 
<li><a href="/hesp.html"><b>International Higher Education Support Program</b></a> 
<li><a href="/osa.html"><b>Open Society Archives</b></a> 
<li><a href="/library.html"><b>Regional Library Program</b></a> 
<li><a href="/osimedia.html"><b>Regional Media Program</b></a>
<li><a href="/copress.html"><b>Regional Publishing Center</b></a> 
<li><a href="/cap.html"><b>Regional Scholarship Program</b></a> 
</ul>
<p>
<i><a href="/direct2.html#osi-budapest">OSI Budapest Staff Directory</a></i><p>
<i><a href="/faq.html">Frequently Asked Questions</a></i><p>

Open Society Institute - Budapest<br> 
Oktober 6. u. 12.<br>
Budapest, Hungary H -1051<br>
