<a name="annual"></a>
<h2>
From the 1995 Annual Report
</h2>

The Central European University (CEU) seeks to provide high-
quality, internationally recognized, postgraduate education 
in subjects particularly neglected or distorted over the 
last 40 to 70 years under the communist regimes of Central 
and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union. In addition 
to providing academic training, the university helps 
students find appropriate positions at institutions in their 
home countries, thus strengthening the development of open 
societies.
<p>
The CEU's faculty and students are a richly international 
body, drawn from over 47 countries in Eastern Europe, 
Western Europe, North America, China, and Africa. Each of 
the university's nine departments is able to grant up to 45 
full scholarships for students from the region, covering 
tuition, room and board, travel costs, and stipends, as well 
as up to two tuition waivers for students from the West.
<p>
In June 1995, the CEU graduated its fourth class of 243 
students representing 37 countries. Just under 450 students 
enrolled in the university's nine programs in the 1995-96 
academic year.
<p>
The CEU took several steps in 1995 toward consolidating its 
role as a leading academic institution in the region. The 
university opened a new teaching site in Poland where, since 
September, the department of sociology has operated in 
affiliation with the Institute of Philosophy and Sociology 
of the Polish Academy of Sciences. Further consolidating its 
presence in the region, the university received recognition 
from the governments of both Hungary and Poland.
<p>

Recognition as a Ph.D.-granting Institution
In February 1996, the Board of Regents of the State of New 
York, which charters the CEU, recognized the university as a 
Ph.D.-granting institution after a year-long evaluation. In 
a similar process, the Open University in England authorized 
the university, its international relations and European 
studies programs, and its program in nationalism to grant 
Ph.D. degrees.
<p>
An external review committee of leading medievalists 
evaluated the medieval studies program, which then was 
approved by the New York Board of Regents as a Ph.D. 
program. The master's program in economics was revamped for 
the 1995-1996 academic year. Students now spend a first year 
of introductory study at the University of Essex in the 
United Kingdom, then finish the program with a second year 
of transitional economics in Budapest.
<p>
European studies expanded its core program to form a new 
department in international relations and European studies. 
The new department helped introduce a student internship 
program with the 
<a href="omri.html"><b>Open Media Research Institute</b></a>.
<p>
In September 1995, the Centre for the Study of Nationalism 
launched a predoctoral fellowship program for CEU graduates. 
Ten students pursued this program during the academic year. 
The university experienced a great loss with the death of 
Ernest Gellner, director of the Centre for the Study of 
Nationalism, in November.
<p>
The Budapest campus moved from its former location in Buda 
to the heart of Pest. The administration is now housed in a 
fully restored 19th century palace while half of the 
academic departments and the CEU-Budapest library are 
located in a newly constructed ten-story tower designed by 
the Hungarian architect Laszlo Ivanyi. Other academic 
departments and services are located in an adjoining 
building which was renovated in 1995. In December, the CEU 
opened a 420-room residential and conference center on the 
outskirts of Pest.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   
<a name="press"></a>
<h2>
CEU Press                    
</h2>
The Central European University Press is the only publishing 
house working in the region dedicated to broadening the 
range of literature currently available in the English 
language on topics concerning Central and Eastern Europe. 
Its titles are directed toward scholars, policy makers, 
journalists, and the business community.
<p>
Among the highlights of 1995 were the publication of 
Socialism, Capitalism, Transformation, a volume of essays by 
Leszek Balcerowicz, architect of Poland's economic reforms, 
and a translation of Jerzy Szacki's most recent book 
Liberalism After Communism, the Polish edition of which was 
awarded Menzione Speciale by the jury of the Premio Europeo 
Amalfi. Two new series are being published in addition to 
the long-running CEU Privatization Reports. The first, 
Corporate Governance in Central Europe and Russia, is a 
joint World Bank/CEU Privatization Project initiative. The 
second, Central European Classics, is edited by Timothy 
Garton Ash and features English translations of some of the 
best Central and Eastern European fiction writers from the 
19th and 20th centuries.
<p>

A separate CEU Press Translation Project is administered by 
the 
<a href="copress.html"><b>Open Society Institute Regional Publishing Center</b></a>. 
The 
Translation Project supports the publication of 20 to 30 
translations in each participating country each year.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   
<a name="about"></a>
<h2>
About the University
</h2>
The Central European University (CEU), established in 1990 with 
study centers in Prague and Budapest, seeks to provide high-quality, 
internationally recognized, postgraduate education in subjects 
particularly neglected or distorted over the last 40-70 years under 
the communist regimes of Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union.
In addition to providing academic training, the University helps students find appropriate positions at institutions in their home countries, thus strengthening the development of open societies.<p>  
     
     
The CEU's decision to move the Department of Sociology from Prague to 
Warsaw in the fall of 1995, establishing it in collaboration with the Institute 
of Philosophy and Sociology of the Polish Academy
 of Sciences, underlines the importance the CEU places on its role as 
a pan-regional institution transcending national borders.<p>
     
The CEU's faculty and students are a richly international body, drawn 
from over 34 countries in Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union
as well as Western Europe and North America. As awareness of the CEU spreads, its application pool is be
coming increasingly diverse; the 1994-95 academic year included 
students from South Africa and China.<p>  
     
The University currently has eight master's departments. Beginning 
with the 1995-96 academic year, seven will be in Budapest (economics, 
environmental sciences and policy, history, international relations and European studies, legal studies, medieval studies, 
political science)and one in Prague (centre for the study of nationalism). All 
programs run for one academic year except economics, which 
will initiate a two-year transition economics program in 1995-96 with 
the first year at the University of Essex.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   
<a name="scholarships"></a>
<h2>
Accreditation and Scholarships
</h2>
     
In 1994, the University achieved nine accredited degrees in eight 
departments leading to MA, MSc or LLM degrees. Six programs are accredited by 
the Board of Regents of the State of New York, from which body the CEU also has a provisional five-year 
institutional charter until 1997; three others are accredited through 
universities in the UK (Sociology by Lancaster University; European Studies by 
the Open University; Environmental Sciences and Policy by the University of Manchester).<p>
     
Each department is able to grant up to 45 full scholarships for 
students from Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union (covering 
tuition, room and board, travel costs and stipends) as well as up to two tuition waivers for students from the West. Most 
departments normally admit a maximum of 50 students per year. English courses 
are given to all accepted applicants at the time of enrollment, predominately to strengthen academic writing skills.<p>
     
Scholarship programs enable excellent students from outside the 
region to study at CEU and CEU students to continue their graduate education at 
West European or North American universities. Tuition grants for students from the region are regarded as 'loans' so that 
those who do not return to the region to work are required to pay back their 
grants over a fixed period of time.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   
<a name="environment"></a>
<h2>
University Environment
</h2>
     
Each of the three study centers in Prague, Budapest, and 
Warsaw provides centralized classrooms, offices, a library, computing facilities
as well as language and computer training. In Prague, 
students live together on-site or in a nearby student dormitory; in Budapest, a well-equipped dormitory with library, 
computing, and sports facilities opened in 1995 together with a completely new 
campus site located in the heart of Pest on Nador utca. In
 Warsaw, the department will be housed with the Institute of 
Philosophy and Sociology in the Staszic Palace.<P>
     
The libraries are a central feature of the study centers; 
consolidation with other institutions will make it possible to enrich the CEU's 
collections and make new Western materials more widely available in the region, as in the case of the Medieval Studies Library, 
shared with the long-established Etvos Lorand University (ELTE) in Budapest. The
CEU also invests in CD-ROM and on-line access to international databases and shares these services with its academic 
neighbors.<p>
     
The University has its own publishing operation, the CEU Press, whose 
English language publications are distributed worldwide by Oxford University 
Press. In cooperation with local publishers, the CEU
 Press administers a Translation Project, which involves
 the translation and publication of key works from Western social 
science and humanities literature into the local languages of the region.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   
<a name="transition"></a>
<h2>
The Transition Project
</h2>
     
The Transition Project, which is affiliated with the CEU's 
political science department, aims at an interdisciplinary analysis of the 
transitions in East Central Europe, conducted by locally based economists, sociologists, political scientists, and legal 
experts.<p>
     
Research findings are utilized in the political science department's 
curriculum and made accessible to the academic public through working papers, 
colloquia, and conferences. On the basis of the research results, the project makes policy recommendations to the wider 
public of politicians, advisors, and businessman. The research aims at a 
comparative analysis of the transition processes in Poland
, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, and Hungary. There are three main 
research areas. They are defined further in the gopher option below.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   
<a name="privatization"></a>
<h2>
Privatization Research Project
</h2>
     
The CEU's Privatization Project seeks to establish a new 
institutional framework capable of recording, analyzing, and disseminating 
knowledge about the economic transition, as well as translating the information into practical policy prescriptions and actual assistance. The project also trains local personnel in 
public administration and the emerging institutional infrastructure of the 
market economy, as well as promotes new standards of responsible corporate behavior.<p>
     
The project has received wide recognition in scholarly circles and 
attracted a variety of collaborators from the United States and Western Europe, 
resulting in joint efforts with the World Bank, the 
United States Chamber of Commerce, and the European Bank for 
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD)). A number of governments have requested 
the project's assistance in such areas as the preparation of mass privatization programs (Poland, Romania), small business 
development (Russia), legal reform (Bulgaria), and international assistance 
(Russia).<P>
     
In cooperation with the Research Division of the World Bank (check 
original), the Project is conducting an extensive empirical and theoretical 
study of the emerging corporate governance structures in
 the region, including a survey of 450 enterprises in the Czech 
Republic, Hungary and Poland, a study of the postcommunist ownership structure, 
and a study of privatization investment funds in the Czech Republic and Russia. Other projects are defined more fully in the gopher option below:
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   
