<h2> <A NAME="fmalert"><img align=bottom src="/images/point.gif"></a>
<A href="/fmalert/index.html"> The Forced Migration Alert</a></h2>
<img align=left src="/images/human1.gif">
<blockquote>
The FM Alert is an electronic bulletin published by the Forced 
Migration Projects of the Open Society Institute, containing breaking news and updates on people, places and events that concern refugees and displaced persons. It is designed to compliment the in-depth stories featured in the bimonthly newsletter Forced Migration Monitor. FM Alert's electronic format aims to keep pace with developments, supplying widely accessible information in a timely fashion on a wide variety of topics. Stories in the bulletin will provide the international community with early warning of the forced movements of people, and suggestions of ways to ameliorate migration or refugee emergencies. The bulletin concentrates on developments in the former communist countries of Central and Eastern Europe, the former Yugoslavia, Haiti and Cuba.<p>
Latest stories include:
<ul>
<li><b>
UNHCR and IOM Solicit Money for a NGO Fund
</b>
<li><b>
Donor governments meet to discuss Bosnia's reconstruction
</b>
<li><b>
Repatriation Hopes Rise in Abkhazia
</b>
</ul>
</blockquote>
<A href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="TOP"></a>
<hr>
<h2> <A NAME="newsletter"><img align=bottom src="/images/point.gif"></a>
<A href="migmon.html"> Forced Migration Monitor </a>(full texts).</h2>
<blockquote>
<b>T</b>he work of the Forced Migration Projects is documented in this bimonthly publication. 
Topics covered include:<p>
<ul>
<li><b>Former Yugoslavia: Implementing Dayton</b>
<li><b>Kazakstan: State Building and Population Movements</b>
<li><b>The CIS Migration Conference</b>
<li><b>The Politics of Repatriation in the former Yugoslavia</b> 
<li><b>Forced Migrants in the Russian Federation</b> 
<li><b>Tajikistan After the Emergency</b> 
<li><b>Russian Federation Migration and Refugee Policy</b> 
<li><b>Citizenship and Statelessness in the former Soviet Union</b> 
<li><b>The Georgian-Abkhaz Conflict</b> 
<li><b>Crimean Tatars.</b> 
</ul>
</blockquote>
<A href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="TOP"></a>
<hr>
<A NAME="annual"></a>
<h2><img align=bottom src="/images/point.gif"> From the 1995 Annual Report</h2>
<blockquote>
The year 1995 was marked by the signing of the Dayton peace 
accords for the former Yugoslavia, an agreement between the 
United States and Cuba on Cuban asylum seekers, and 
preparations for the 1996 international conference on 
population displacements in the Commonwealth of Independent 
States (CIS). These events were central to the Forced 
Migration Projects' mission of encouraging early 
humanitarian responses to migration and refugee emergencies, 
advocating humane treatment and protection of those unable 
to return, and promoting measures aimed at averting the need 
to flee. 
<p>
<b>The Former Soviet Union.</b><br> 
Strengthening the role of 
nongovernmental organizations in the former Soviet Union is 
an important objective, not only because of the contribution 
of these organizations to resolving migration and refugee 
problems, but also because a thriving independent sector 
inherently strengthens the growth of civil society and helps 
prevent the causes of forced migration. Therefore, the 
Forced Migration Projects initiated an ongoing survey of 
local NGOs aimed at identifying potential partners in the 
region and exploring ways to enhance their work.
<p>
To create an interactive advocacy network for the area, the 
Forced Migration Projects appointed network members in 
Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Estonia, Georgia, Kazakstan, 
Kyrgyzstan, Latvia, Russia, Tajikistan, and Ukraine, while 
developing advisory and liaison relationships with 
governments and international organizations concerned with 
the region. The Forced Migration Projects made several 
research missions to the region and published reports of 
findings.
<p>
The regional conference on migration-related issues in the 
countries of the CIS could put these regional issues on the 
agenda of the international community and assist policy 
makers and donors in their efforts to address new 
responsibilities. A comprehensive, regional approach would 
include preventive and post-emergency strategies to address 
the evolution of humanitarian action from relief to 
rehabilitation as well as the promotion of respect for 
fundamental human rights. To encourage maximum participation 
by the independent sector, the projects initiated an 
informal conference preparation process, encompassing local 
and international NGOs and independent experts. Meetings to 
exchange information were conducted in Almaty, Kiev, Moscow, 
Novosibirsk, Tallinn, and Tbilisi. 
<p>
<b>The Former Yugoslavia.</b><br> 
In 1995, the Forced Migration 
Projects formed a Legal Policy Task Force for the former 
Yugoslavia. Comprised of lawyers from the region and 
international experts, the task force has focused on the 
establishment of the Commission for Displaced Persons and 
Refugees under the Dayton accords. The task force is also 
advocating for the reform of discriminatory legislation and 
practices in order to secure an environment that encourages 
return, not only to Bosnia and Herzegovina, but to all of 
the countries of the former Yugoslavia.
<p>
<b>Haiti and Cuba.</b><br> 
The projects have also addressed the 
situation of Haitian and Cuban asylum seekers. Our early 
focus on the monitoring of safe havens at the Guantanamo Bay 
naval base inspired the establishment of a Soros foundation 
in Haiti and contributed to the U.S. government's  decision 
to admit into the United States upwards of 20,000 Cubans. A 
mission of inquiry to Cuba in June 1995 provided a baseline 
to monitor the U.S.-Cuba migration accord. To deal with 
future crises, we are working for the establishment of a 
regional mechanism to provide a rapid, efficient, and humane 
response to migration and refugee problems in the Caribbean.
</blockquote>
<A href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="TOP"></a>
<hr>
<A NAME="about"></a>
<h2><img align=bottom src="/images/point.gif"> About the Projects:</h2>
<blockquote>
A multitude of ethnic tensions and hostilities has resulted in substantial population 
displacements in the countries of the former Soviet Union. Some 25 million Russians live 
beyond the borders of the Russian Federation, and nearly 70 million people live outside the 
republic of their ethnic origin. With over 130 ethnic groups in the former Soviet Union, and 
nationalism, secessionist movements, and discriminatory measures in evidence, the potential for 
further dislocation is enormous. Official systems responsible for meeting the needs of those 
forced to flee are embryonic and easily overwhelmed. Resources in the independent sector are 
diffused, and nongovernmental organizations are still in formation. In the meantime, suffering 
and loss of life continue.<p>
The Forced Migration Projects are action-oriented programs that monitor circumstances in the 
15 countries that emerged or re-emerged after the dissolution of the Soviet Union, in order to 
warn of forced movements and to identify conditions that may cause such dislocations, 
including armed conflict, human rights violations, economic underdevelopment, environmental 
degradation, and other failures of governance. The Forced Migration Projects seek to 
encourage early humanitarian responses to migration emergencies, advocate humane treatment 
and protection of the rights of those unable to return, and promote measures aimed at averting 
people's need to flee.<p>
Working toward a complete, interactive advocacy network involving each of the countries of 
the former Soviet Union, the Forced Migration Projects have appointed consultants in 
Armenia, Azerbaijan, Estonia, Georgia, Kazakstan, Kyrgyzstan, Latvia, Russia, 
Tajikistan, and Ukraine while developing advisory and liaison relationships with governments 
and international organizations concerned with the region.  The Forced Migration Projects 
have undertaken numerous missions to the region as well as a variety of efforts to promote 
better understanding of regional migration issues.<p>
While much of the work of the Forced Migration Projects has concerned the former Soviet Union, recent program activities have also concerned the former Yugoslavia as well as Cuba and Haiti.
</blockquote>
<A href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="TOP"></a>
<hr>
<h2> <img align=bottom src="/images/point.gif">
<A NAME="activities">Activities</a></h2>
<blockquote>
The Forced Migration Projects have ongoing activities in the region of the former Soviet 
Union, the region of the former Yugoslavia and in the Caribbean.<p>
<ul><li><b>International conference on migration-related issues<BR>in the region of
the former Soviet Union </b>
<li><b>Legal Policy Task Force for the former Yugoslavia</b>
<li><b>Haitian and Cuban asylum seekers</b>
</ul>
<HR>
<h4>International conference on migration-related issues<BR>in the region of the
former Soviet Union </h4>
<i><b>T</b>he Conference on Refugees, Returnees, Displaced Persons and 
Related Migratory Movements in the Commonwealth of Independent States and Relevant 
Neighboring States</i> is organized under the auspices of the Office of the United 
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, the International Organization for Migration, and 
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.  The conference is to occur
in May 1996 in Geneva, and the Projects plan to monitor follow up.<p>
In order to facilitate participation by nongovernmental organizations in the formulation of the 
conference's proposed Declaration of Principles and Plan of Action, the Forced Migration 
Projects organized a series of subregional meetings of local and international NGOs In Almaty, Kyiv, Moscow, Novosibirsk, Tbilisi, and Tallinn.  These meetings paralleled the 
preparatory schedule of the conference secretariat.  A full report of the
<A href="contents.html"> 
<b>proceedings</b></a> of these independent sector meetings is available.<p> 

The Forced Migration Projects have undertaken a survey of nongovernmental organizations 
active on migration issues in this region.  The results of this survey will be made available 
in a forthcoming report. 
<HR> 
<h4>Legal Policy Task Force for the former Yugoslavia</h4> 
<b>T</b>he Forced Migration Projects' work in the region of the former 
Yugoslavia through a Legal Policy Task Force for the former Yugoslavia, which was 
created in October 1995 to address protection and solutions for refugees and displaced 
persons.  The risk of persecution and lack of protective structures, 
the need for adequate living conditions, and the possibility of making claims for lost property 
all require monitoring.<p> 
A<A href="abstract.html"> <b>summary</b></a> of the Dayton Accords signed in 
Paris on December 14,1995, has been prepared by the Forced Migration Projects and includes 
a <A href="abstract.html#timeline"><b>selected timeline of significant 
dates</b></a> in the schedule of implemention of the Accords.  
Reports have also been prepared on 

<A HREF ="gopher://gopher.soros.org:70/00/General_Info/Reading/Migration/property.txt"><b>property laws in Bosnia and Herzegovina,</b></a>
 the recently established Commission for Real Property Claims of Displaced Persons and Refugees, and 

<A HREF ="gopher://gopher.soros.org:70/00/General_Info/Reading/Migration/citizen.txt"><b>citizenship laws in Bosnia and Herzegovina.</b></a>
<HR>
<h4>Haitian and Cuban asylum seekers</h4>
The Forced Migration Projects also work on migration and refugee issues 
relating to Haitian and Cuban asylum seekers.  A research mission to Havana and Camagey, 
Cuba, was conducted from June 25 - 29, 1995, to evaluate the refugee screening processes and 
monitoring procedures required by the May 1995 migration accord between the U.S. and 
Cuban governments.  Monitoring of this accord as well as of the safe haven arrangements for 
the asylum seekers has been ongoing.  A <A href="http://www.soros.org/haiti.html">
<b>national foundation in Haiti</b></a> has now been established.<p> 
The Forced Migration Projects has published a forward looking 
<A href="#special_reports"><b>special report</b></a> which addresses the need for a 
temporary refuge scheme for the Caribbean region.<p> 
</blockquote>
<A href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="TOP"></a>
<hr>
<A NAME="special_reports"></a>
<h2><img align=bottom src="/images/point.gif"> Special Reports</h2>
<blockquote>
The Forced Migration Projects issue special reports from time to time addressing a variety of 
timely issues relevant to the field.<p> 
<ul> 
<li><b>Repatriation in Georgia</b>
<li><b>A Proposal to Establish a Temporary Refuge Scheme in the Caribbean Region for 
Refugee and Migration Emergencies</b>
<li><b>Human Rights Education Bibliography</b>
</ul>
<HR>
<h4>Repatriation in Georgia</h4>
<b>I</b>n July 1995, the Forced Migration Projects published the first of a series 
of special reports on the problems of population displacement in the former Soviet Union. 
Entitled <A HREF = 
"gopher://gopher.soros.org:70/00/General_Info/Reading/Migration/repatriation_in_georgia">
<b>Forced Migration: Repatriation in Georgia</b></a>, the report examines 
the 1994 UNHCR plan to repatriate displaced persons, particularly Abkhazians, in the 
Republic of Georgia, and seeks to draw lessons from the difficulties encountered in promoting 
the return of displaced persons. 
<HR> 
<h4>Temporary Refuge Scheme for the Caribbean (Proposal)</h4> 
<b>T</b>he Forced Migration Projects seek to encourage policy makers and 
implementers in this region to fashion a conceptual framework to better manage refugee and 
migration emergencies.  Such a framework could promote stability, and avoid or ameliorate 
individual hardships.  In the report, <A href= "gopher://gopher.soros.org:70/00/General_Info/Reading/Migration/Carib_Refugee_Scheme.txt"> 
<b>A Proposal to Establish a Temporary Refuge Scheme in the 
Caribbean Region for Refugees and Migration Emergencies</b></A>, a set of principles 
is offered on the constituent elements of a temporary refuge scheme, including reception, ceilings, 
conditions of stay, duration of stay and solutions for those in need of new permanent homes.<p>
This report is also available in <A href=
"gopher://gopher.soros.org:70/00/General_Info/Reading/Migration/caribfre.txt"> 
<b>Franais</b></a> and in 
<A href="gopher://gopher.soros.org:70/00/General_Info/Reading/Migration/caribspa.txt"> 
<b>Espaol</b></a>.
<HR>
<h4>Human Rights Education Bibliography</h4> 
<b>T</b>he<A HREF = 
"gopher://gopher.soros.org:70/00/General_Info/Reading/Migration/Human_Rights_Biblio">
<b> Human Rights Education Bibliography</b></A> is a comprehensive resource 
of human rights education materials including lists of curricula and teaching guides; journal 
articles; professional training manuals; reference materials; and video and other media. In addition, 
there are sections on resources in Spanish as well as those that can be found on the Internet.
</blockquote>
<A href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="TOP"></a>
<hr>
