<a name="mission"></a>
<img align=left src="/images/n23.gif" hspace=20>   
<i>ABRAHAM HOUSE<br>BRONX, NEW YORK</i>

<h2>                                                    
MISSION STATEMENT
</h2>                                                   

Fear of crime, particularly violent crime, has become a hallmark of life in the
United States. While almost everyone is afraid of crime, research shows that
some communities, particularly low-income and urban minority communities,
represent a disproportionate number of both victims and perpetrators of crime.
To truly address the injurious impact crime is having on our entire society,
the problem must be approached and the solutions discovered community by
community. <br>
<br>
This is not an easy task. But we simply have no other choice. Crime, violent
crime, and violence are three separate, yet very real problems. Incarceration,
the indiscriminate response to these distinct problems, is not always the most
appropriate answer. A nation that incarcerates as many of its citizens as does
the United States cannot hope to remain an open society. We must find new
answers.<br>
<br>
The goal of the Center on Crime, Communities &amp; Culture is to create a
better understanding of and support for effective and humane responses to
criminal behavior and victimization. The Center seeks to turn the current
national debate on crime into an opportunity to reinvigorate basic principles
of individual rights and responsibilities, bolster community integrity, and
promote social innovation. The Center works toward this goal by seeking and
supporting outstanding and innovative programs in the field of criminal
justice; by performing policy and research work in areas of national and
international importance; and by providing academic and research fellowships to
individuals committed to becoming leaders in criminal justice.<p>
      
<img align=left src="/images/n10.gif" hspace=20>   
<i>HOUSE OF RUTH<br>BALTIMORE, MARYLAND</i>                

<h2>                                                     
GRANTMAKING                                              
</h2>                                                    
                                                         
The Center on Crime, Communities &amp; Culture funds outstanding service
programs; policy, advocacy and research projects; and initiatives in the arts
and humanities. The Center also seeks to establish funding partnerships with
other private and public organizations to support worthy projects. While our
grantmaking focuses on domestic initiatives, the Center welcomes funding
requests for efforts involving the international transfer or exchange of
knowledge, as well as for non-U.S.-based initiatives which broaden the
international criminal justice knowledge base. Most of the Center's
grants will be for $50,000 or less, with a duration of one to two years.<br>
<a name="funding"></a>
<h3>
Funding Priorities<br>
</h3>
DEVELOP practical alternatives and positive life opportunities for youth and
adults who are at risk of becoming involved or re-involved in the criminal
justice system<br>
<br>
ENABLE survivors of crime and their families to address the harms they have
suffered and to recover from those harms<br>
<br>
WORK alongside families and communities to reduce the harmful impact of
incarceration<br>
<br>
HELP prisoners, parolees, and probationers establish healthy, productive, and
crime-free lives through community-based sanctions, job training,
parenting-skills workshops, education and other avenues of self-improvement<br>
<br>
TRAIN correctional officers, judges, police officers, and other correctional
and law enforcement personnel to better understand and more effectively respond
to the needs of survivors of crime, criminal defendants, prisoners and their
families<br>
<br>
SEEK to decrease the number of people in prison or jail through innovations in
the criminal justice system or related social service fields such as mental
health<br>
<br>
REDRESS violations of the civil or human rights of prisoners or post-arrest
detainees<br>
<br>
EXPLORE the impact of media, film and other forms of expression on individual
and community perceptions of crime, violent crime and violence<br>
<br>
The Center also welcomes proposals that fulfill objectives not identified
above, but which are consistent with the Center's mission.<p>
<a name="selection"></a>
                                                         
<img align=right src="/images/n29.gif" hspace=20>   
<i>LEAP<br>NEW HAVEN, CONNECTICUT</i>                

<h3>
Selection Criteria
</h3>

DEMONSTRATED NEED for the proposed initiative <br>
RESPONSIVENESS of the proposed initiative to the needs of the target
population<br>
APPLICANT'S EXPERIENCE in providing services to the target population or
working in the relevant field<br>
CAPACITY of the applicant to fully and effectively implement the proposed
initiative<br>
QUALITY of the initiative's proposed evaluation procedures<br>
EVIDENCE OF COOPERATION with private organizations and government agencies to
maximize the potential of the proposed initiative<br>
POTENTIAL IMPACT of the outcome of the proposed initiative on the field of
criminal justice<br>
<a name="application"></a>
<h3>
Application Guidelines
</h3>
The Center has developed the following guidelines to ensure that all
applications are reviewed in an efficient and fair manner. These guidelines are
not meant to discourage applicants who have not sought funding from a
foundation in the past. The Center welcomes good ideas, vision and commitment,
and requests the cooperation, best efforts and patience of applicants during
the application process. The applicants must submit a letter of intent that
includes the following:<br>
<br>
A one-sentence description of the proposed initiative that states its goal and
the means the applicant will use to attain the goal <br>
<br>
A 2,000-word statement of the need or issue to be addressed; organizational
capacity or individual expertise; objectives; activities or methods;
deliverables or expected outcomes; and (when possible) an indication of
evaluation procedures and identification of an external evaluator <br>
<br>
Applicants for research funding must also include: a 200-word abstract of the
proposed project and citations for the three most relevant studies or other
pieces of scholarship<br>
<br>
A one-year budget with no more than 10 percent allocated to administrative
costs <br>
<br>
A list of current funders of the initiative and a statement indicating the size
of the organizational budget <br>
<br>
A one-page program implementation timeline <br>
<br>
No more than three two-page resumes of the director of the organization,
project director or the principal investigator, and two key staff members.<br>
<br>
The above materials must be submitted in 12-point type, single-spaced, with
standard one-inch margins. Applicants must provide one original and three
copies collated into four complete letters of intent. The name of the applicant
or project must appear in the upper-right-hand corner of each page of the
submission. U.S. public charities should include a copy of their IRS letter as
evidence of tax exempt status. Organizations must provide a copy of their most
recent annual report. Incomplete applications will not be reviewed. Additional
or appendix materials will not be accepted. Applications by fax will not be
accepted.<p>

<img align=right src="/images/n7.gif" hspace=20>   
<i>HOUSE OF RUTH<br>BALTIMORE, MARYLAND</i>                
                                                         
<a name="evaluation"></a>
<h3>
Evaluation Component
</h3>
Applicants are strongly encouraged to incorporate an external evaluation
component into their proposal and to identify an evaluator prior to requesting
funding. The Center will assist applicants who feel unqualified to design an
evaluation process and locate an external evaluator if the applicant's
initiative is otherwise judged to be worthy of support and if the applicant
expresses a commitment to undergo evaluation. Applicants in the arts and
humanities should propose measures of the potential impact of their project
which are appropriate to their field.<br>
<a name="grant"></a>
<h3>
The Grant Cycle
</h3>
The Center does not have a restricted grant cycle. Applicants may submit
letters of intent at any time. The Center will acknowledge the receipt of a
letter of intent in writing and inform applicants of the expected time frame
for a decision on funding. The Center may award grants based on the letter of
intent, or after inviting the applicant to submit a full proposal. All
applicants will be advised in writing of the Center's decision.<p>

<img align=left src="/images/n4.gif" hspace=20>   
<i>HOUSE OF RUTH<br>BALTIMORE, MARYLAND</i>                
                                                         
<a name="monitoring"></a>
<h3>
Monitoring and Grantee Reporting
</h3>
Grantees will be required to present written semi-annual reports on the
progress of their efforts. The Center will disburse grants in two equal
payments, one issued at the time the grant is approved and the second issued
upon review of the mid-year report. The Center's staff will make
individual arrangements with grantees whose grant periods are shorter or longer
than one year. Center staff members or their representatives may make
occasional site visits to grantees.<br>
<a name="training"></a>
<h3>
Trainings and Symposia
</h3>
From time to time, the Center may invite groups of grantees to gatherings for
training and technical assistance, or to enable them to pool their expertise
with others and explore specific topics or quandaries in the field of criminal
justice. Attendance at such gatherings is wholly at the grantee's
discretion and is not a requirement for the receipt of funds.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<hr>
<a name="research"></a>
<img align=right src="/images/n21.gif" hspace=20>   
<i>ABRAHAM HOUSE<br>BRONX, NEW YORK</i>                

<h2>
RESEARCH &amp; POLICY<br>
</h2>
Through the research and policy component of its work, the Center seeks to
redirect the public policy debate on criminal justice away from political
preferences and short-term solutions toward the best available evidence on what
the real issues are, what principles must be safeguarded when addressing these
issues and what individual and systemic approaches effectively resolve these
issues.<br>
<br>
THE CENTER WORKS TO ATTAIN THIS GOAL BY:<br>
<br>
CARRYING OUT SCHOLARLY RESEARCH in the criminal justice arena <br>
<br>
FACILITATING domestic and international information exchange on a range of
issues related to the criminal justice field, including crime deterrence,
economic development, prison industries, the use of fines and other civil
sanctions in criminal courts, domestic violence, correctional health care and
prisoners' reintegration into the community after release<br>
<br>
EXPLORING the social, economic and democratic implications of the continuing
expansion of prison and jail populations in the United States<br>
<br>
PROMOTING dialogue on criminal justice policy among diverse players including
politicians, victims/survivors' rights advocates, clergy, prisoners and
former prisoners, family members, researchers and academics, community-based
service providers, prosecutors, defense attorneys, members of the public, and
correctional, probation and parole officials <br>
<br>
WRITING Op-Ed articles and letters to the editor in a wide range of
publications<br>
<br>
IDENTIFYING and advocating for needed changes in the criminal and social
justice systems through a variety of avenues such as publishing original legal
and social science research<br>
<br>
PUBLIC SPEAKING at seminars and conferences; organizing symposia and
conferences; and producing Center publications
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<hr>
<a name="fellowships"></a>
<img align=left src="/images/n1.gif" hspace=20>   
<i>HOUSE OF RUTH<br>BALTIMORE, MARYLAND</i>                
<h2>
FELLOWSHIPS
</h2>
The goal of the Center's fellowship program;Soros Justice
Fellowships;is to allow legal, health care, mental health and other
professionals at various points in their careers to begin or broaden their work
in criminal justice.<br>
<br>
Individuals in the criminal justice field tend to receive little support or
recognition for the value and difficulty of their work. Participating in
systems which determine how to handle individuals who have allegedly violated
the law and others who have been the victims of crime is a difficult and often
saddening task. Justice is an elusive concept that people who work on the front
lines of criminal justice;in police cars, court rooms, jails, prisons,
domestic violence shelters and hospital emergency rooms;must define and
redefine each day, for themselves and for the society at large.<br>
<br>
Given the public's concern with crime, the ever-increasing direct costs
of expanding and maintaining the criminal justice system, as well as the
frequently ignored attendant costs of high incarceration rates on families and
communities, it is crucial that talented, well-trained and visionary
individuals work in the criminal justice field. Toward this end, the Center
offers two types of fellowships, tuition-based Student Fellowships and Senior
Fellowships for leading frontline practitioners.<br>
<a name="student"></a>
<h3>
Student Fellows
</h3>
The curricular component of the Soros Justice Fellowships program will be
piloted at New York University School of Law as a distinct grouping within the
existing Root-Tilden-Snow Scholarship Program. <br>
In the fall of 1996, Soros Justice Fellowships will be awarded to two
first-year law students who intend to pursue careers in a field related to
criminal justice. Fellowships will be awarded on the basis of academic
excellence and a demonstrated commitment to public service.<br>
<br>
Student Fellows will receive a three-year, full-tuition scholarship to law
school as well as stipends for summer internships in criminal justice agencies.
In addition to attending law school, Student Fellows will participate in an
ongoing tutorial which will take an interdisciplinary approach to criminal
justice practice, policies and management issues.<br>
<br>
Student Fellows make a binding commitment to work in the field of criminal
justice for at least three years upon graduation or repay the scholarship. <br>
<br>
For the purposes of the fellowship, `criminal justice` will be
defined to include work in juvenile justice as well as the judicial and
legislative branches of government. Fellows must meet certain academic, study
and work obligations in connection with the fellowship award.<br>
<br>
In early 1997, the Center will evaluate the pilot program and determine whether
to continue and expand the program. In 1997, fellowships may be available to
individuals who have been admitted to colleges and universities participating
in the fellowship programs. Institutions interested in joining the fellowship
program should contact the Center.<br>
<br>
Possible areas of expansion include, but are not limited to, graduate school
fellowships in the areas of economics, psychology, journalism and sociology,
and undergraduate fellowships for young adults who have been able to lead
productive lives after spending their childhood years in either the child
welfare or juvenile justice systems.<br>
<br>
Contact the Center to receive a list of participating institutions.<p>
<img align=left src="/images/n27.gif" hspace=20>   
<i>LEAP<br>NEW HAVEN, CONNECTICUT</i>                

<a name="senior"></a>
<h3>
Senior Fellows
</h3>
Senior Fellowships will be awarded to outstanding individuals working in
domestic and international criminal justice, and, when relevant, in other areas
such as the arts and humanities. Applicants will be required to outline a
specific project in their application. The Center will consider applicants from
both within and outside the United States. Fellowships will consist of a
12-month stipend, along with medical coverage and other benefits. Finalists
will be asked to provide information on their salary needs. As a rule, Senior
Fellows will be provided with office space at the Center and access to the
Center's computer and library resources. Applicants who reside outside
the New York area and who are unable to relocate for the term of the fellowship
may apply as non-resident fellows. For information on application guidelines
and deadlines, contact the Center. 
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<hr>
<a name="grantees"></a>
<img align=right src="/images/n28.gif" hspace=20>   
<i>HUNTINGTON HOUSE<br>NEW YORK, NEW YORK</i>                

<h2>
LIST OF GRANTEES
</h2>
As of September 1996, the Center on Crime, Communities &amp; Culture had made
roughly $1,000,000 in grants to more than 20 organizations including:<br>
<br>
<b>Women's Prison Association and Home</b><br>
New York, New York <br>
$75,000 to develop a strategic plan for the enhancement of services at the
Sarah Powell Huntington House, a supportive housing program for homeless female
ex-offenders seeking to reunite with their children and to promote family
reunification via a wider range of services for children and youth, mothers and
other family members.<br>
<br>
<b>House of Ruth</b><br>
Baltimore, Maryland<br>
$62,273 to provide counseling and other clinical services for children of
domestic violence survivors and children of batterers, who have often witnessed
the abuse of a parent and have been abused themselves.<br>
<br>
<b>Abraham House</b><br>
Bronx, New York<br>
$56,000 to provide general support for a residential facility that offers a
range of services to first-time, non-violent offenders. Services include
individualized GED preparation, English as a Second Language instruction, job
placement, counseling and services for inmates' families, such as food,
clothing and other emergency <br>
assistance.<br>
<br>
<b>Center for Alternative Sentencing</b><br>
and Employment Services (CASES)<br>
New York, New York<br>
$51,900 to establish the `Work Apprenticeship Program,` an
alternative-to-incarceration program which will help academically promising
young felony offenders to identify and pursue career paths by combining job
skills, internships in professional work sites and mentoring. (Challenge
grant.)<br>
<br>
<b>Educational Law Center</b><br>
Philadelphia, Pennsylvania <br>
$50,000 to establish a collaborative project with the Juvenile Law Center in
Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. The project will address the denial of appropriate
educational opportunities to children who are in, or who are threatened with,
juvenile justice or criminal justice proceedings.<br>
<br>
<b>Juvenile Law Center</b><br>
Philadelphia, Pennsylvania <br>
$50,000 to establish a collaborative project with the Educational Law Center in
Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. The project will address the denial of appropriate
educational opportunities to children who are in, or who are threatened with,
juvenile justice or criminal justice proceedings.<br>
<br>
<b>Leadership, Education and <br>
Athletics in Partnership (LEAP)</b><br>
New Haven, Connecticut<br>
$50,000 to design and implement the `Creating a Safe Connecticut for Our
Children` program which will provide academic enrichment after school
hours, mentoring, and leadership programs for at-risk youth in New Haven,
Hartford and New London.<br>
<br>
<b>National Funding Collaborative on Violence Prevention</b><br>
Washington, DC<br>
$50,000 to develop a coordinated and effective national violence-prevention
movement through local advocacy, public education and prevention efforts in
Oakland, California; Santa Barbara, California; San Antonio, Texas;
Spartanburg, South Carolina; Rockford, Illinois; New Orleans, Louisiana;
Minneapolis, Minnesota; Flint, Michigan; Knoxville, Tennessee; New Haven,
Connecticut; New York, New York; and Washington, DC. (Collaborative funders:
U.S. Department of Justice, U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development
and 15 private foundations and corporations.) <br>
<br>
<b>The Osborne Association</b><br>
New York, New York<br>
$50,000 to replicate the `Family Works` program at Woodbourne
Correctional Facility, a medium-security men's prison in upstate New
York. The program will address the concerns that children face after a father
is imprisoned by providing: parenting education for pris-oners; a
children's visiting center at the prison; and family support and
counseling for the prisoners and their family members. (Collaborative funder:
New York State Department of Correctional Services.)<br>
<br>
<b>The Sentencing Project</b><br>
Washington, DC<br>
$50,000 to provide general support for communications, research, public
education and outreach work on a wide range of criminal justice issues. <br>
<br>
<b>Single Parent Resource Center &amp; WomenCare</b><br>
New York, New York<br>
$50,000 to provide general support for `Healthy Horizons`, a
collaborative program that provides incarcerated mothers with linkage to health
care providers in the community; mentoring and post-release family
reunification; and other support services. <br>
<b>Youth Law Center</b><br>
San Francisco, California<br>
$50,000 to support advocacy for improved services and conditions for children
confined in juvenile justice facilities, and public education for the
preservation of a criminal justice system which recognizes the difference
between youth and adult offenders.<br>
<br>
<b>Rural Opportunities</b><br>
Albion, New York <br>
$49,442 to create a program at Albion Correctional Facility to help female
inmates address sexual abuse, sexual assault, family violence and parenting
issues through individual and group counseling. A component of the program will
provide education and sensitivity training for correctional officers.<br>
<br>
<b>Summit County Sheriff's Office</b><br>
Akron, Ohio<br>
$44,000 to expand an innovative community psychiatry program in a county jail
in which a psychiatrist trains medical students in their resident year to treat
mentally ill inmates. The program will also cross-train law students alongside
medical students about the treatment needs of mentally ill defendants and the
application of competency laws. <br>
<br>
<b>Citizens United for the Rehabilitation</b><br>
of Errants (CURE)<br>
Kalamazoo, Michigan <br>
$41,704 to write and print self-help literature for prisoners and their
families in eight states on a wide range of issues, such as planning for
release back into the community and maintaining family ties during
incarceration.<br>
<br>
<b>New York City AIDS Fund</b><br>
New York, New York<br>
$40,000 to fund direct care services, HIV prevention, advocacy, and public
policy programs in New York that serve prisoners, former prisoners and other
high risk populations. (Collaborative funders: New York Community Trust and 13
other corporations and foundations.)<br>
<br>
<b>The Fortune Society</b><br>
New York, New York<br>
$25,000 to support a portion of the salary and related expenses of a teacher in
The Fortune Society's Education Unit, which provides a range of highly
individualized educational programs in math, English, English as a Second
Language and computer skills to ex-offenders.<br>
<br>
<b>The Fountain for Youth</b><br>
New York, New York<br>
$25,000 to launch a citywide violence prevention program for youth in New York
City through three major activities: a leadership training institute; a
membership coalition of New York residents to advocate for policies and
programs that meet young people's needs; and a media campaign that will
advocate for a balanced portrayal of youth, increase young people's
access to the media and produce positive images of youth.<br>
<br>
<b>Canadian AIDS Society</b><br>
Quebec, Canada<br>
$12,878 to support public education in the United States on policy and
programmatic advances in international penal reform, through the distribution
in the United States of the `Discussion Paper on AIDS/HIV in Canadian
Prisons.`<br>
<br>
<b>Youth Law Center</b><br>
San Francisco, California<br>
$9,781 to support research and public education on the waiver of juveniles into
adult courts, and the development of case studies on the effect of this
practice on young people.
<p>
<img align=right src="/images/n24.gif" hspace=20>   
<i>HUNTINGTON HOUSE<br>NEW YORK, NEW YORK</i>                
