<table border=4>

<tr>
<td rowspan="4">
<h2 align=center valign=middle><a href="#summary">Summary of Program</a></h2>
</td>
<td rowspan="4">
<img src="uic.gif" alt="#" border=0 align=center>
</td>

<td colspan="2" valign=bottom>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<b><a href="gopher://gopher.soros.org/0/General_Info/Jobs/uic_062796.txt"><blink><font color="FF0000">Job Opportunity</font></blink></a></b>
</td>
<td>
<b><a href="#mission">Objective</a></b>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<b><a href="#univlist">List of Universities</a></b>
</td>

<td>
<b><a href="/uicmap.html">UIC Map</a></b>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<b><a href="#grants">Grants Competitions</a></b>
</td>
<td>
<b><a href="http://www.soros.org/press.html#internet">Press Releases</a></b>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="4" valign=bottom>
<h3 align=center><a href="internet.html">Regional Internet Program</a></h3>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
<h2><a name="mission"></a><b>Objective:</b></h2>

<p>
The University Internet Center (UIC) is a campus-based entity providing the campus and off-campus communities with access to two types of resources: (a) financial and programmatic opportunities from the Open Society Institute (b) information globally available on the Internet.</p>


<h2><a name="summary"></a><b>Summary of Program:</b></h2>

<p>

The UIC program was created by the Open Society Institute (OSI) as part of an ongoing effort to support communities involved in education and social activism in the Russian Federation. Throughout history, the advancement of democracy, civil rights, and equal opportunity, and the well-being of people and institutions involved in creativity and learning, have been deeply interdependent. The dramatic reduction in resources available for educational, cultural, artistic, and scientific purposes makes these possibilities increasingly less secure.  Particularly alarming is that due to the lack of resources, much of the Russian Federation is being left out of the information revolution taking place around the world. It was in response to these developments that the UIC program first arose.<p> 

At its essence, the UIC program has two central components: (a) providing 32 provincial universities in the Russian Federation with a fully equipped computing center and multi-media lab with complete access to the Internet (b) administering content based program initiatives for the university and larger community. OSI plans to support via the UICs various projects and programs in the humanities and social sciences, with a particular emphasis on education, independent media, arts and culture, civil society, and ecology. It is our hope that by establishing a presence in the farthest reaches of the country, these centers can better serve the needs and demands of the widest number of people and communities in the Russian Federation. <p> 


The UIC initiative has a program budget of $100 million to be spent over five years; it will be carried out in collaboration with the government of the Russian Federation which has pledged an additional $30 million earmarked for connectivity to the centers (either via satellite or fiber optic).  <p> 

<p> </p>



<h2><a name="univlist"></a><b>List of Universities:</b></h2>

<p>The State Committee on Higher Education of the Russian Federation and
the Open Society Institute have agreed to the following list of 32
University Internet Centers. The first two centers, opened June 10, 1996,
are Yaroslavl State University (Yaroslavl) and Novosibirsk State
University (Novosibirsk). The third center was opened on October 29th at Dalnevostochny (Far East) State University (Vladivostok).  Approximately 10 - 12 centers will open in 1997. </p>

A <a href="uicmap.html">map</a> of the University Internet Centers 
is also available.<p><br>
<table border=1>
<tr>
<th width=300><br>University</th>

<th><br>City</th>

<th>Anticipated<br>Opening</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><a href="http://www.dcn-asu.ru/ENTRY.en.html">Altai State 
University</a></td>

<td>Barnaul</td>

