<html>
<head>
<title>Emma Lazarus Fund</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">
<table cellpadding=6>                                              
<tr>                                                               
<td>                                                               
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                    
<td>                                                               
<img align=middle src="/images/emma_lazarus.gif" alt="The Emma Lazarus Fund">
</td>                                                              
</tr>                                                              
</table>                                                           
<blockquote>                                                       
<h3>
The Emma Lazarus Fund Application Guidelines
</h3>
The Emma Lazarus Fund of the 
<a href="/osiny.html"><b>Open Society Institute</b></a>
is a $50 million
grantmaking program created to combat the unfair treatment of and
discrimination against aliens who are lawfully present in the United
States. The Fund also seeks to help those individuals become active
participants in American society. Named for the poet whose words adorn the
Statue of Liberty, the Fund was established in the Summer of 1996 in
response to welfare reform legislation that denies legal immigrants equal
access to a variety of public assistance programs. The discriminatory
provisions of the welfare reform laws reflect a broader trend of
increasing hostility toward newcomers to the United States. The Open
Society Institute believes this trend is antithetical to the values of an
open society, which is characterized by a reliance on the rule of law, a
diverse and vigorous civil society, and respect for minorities and
minority opinion. The Fund provides grants to nonprofit organizations that
help aliens who are lawfully present in the United States.  
<p>
<h3> 
Funding Priorities 
</h3> 
<b>Services:</b> Most of the Fund's grantmaking focuses on
organizations providing direct services to aliens who are lawfully present
in the United States. The areas of concentration are naturalization
assistance and legal services.  In both areas of concentration, the Fund
is primarily concerned with reaching individuals who have been adversely
affected by welfare reform. In the area of naturalization assistance, the
Fund supports activities related directly to the citizenship application
process, as well as English as a Second Language and civics instruction
associated with the preparation for the citizenship exam. In the area of
legal services, the Fund also supports organizations that provide other
immigration- related assistance to aliens who are lawfully present in the
United States. The Fund gives preference to proposals from organizations
that target vulnerable and hard-to-reach populations; that provide a broad
range of services; and that work in cooperation with other groups. Where
appropriate, the Fund supports grantmaking collaboratives or re-grant
programs. The Fund also supports technical assistance and training
services for immigrant organizations engaged in activities of interest to
the Fund. The Fund encourages all relevant organizations to work in a
coordinated fashion so as to increase the efficacy of grantee programs. 
<p>
<b>Advocacy and Policy.</b> The Fund supports organizations engaged in advocacy,
policy, and impact litigation strategies on behalf of aliens who are
lawfully present in the United States. The Fund supports organizations
working at the national, state and/or local level, primarily in the areas
of legal and welfare policy as they affect aliens. The Fund supports
public education and information dissemination campaigns related to the
impact of welfare reform on aliens who are lawfully present in the United
States, as well as campaigns to promote fair treatment of these populations. 
The Fund also supports a limited number of research projects related to
welfare and immigration policy, provided that the research has direct and
immediate relevance to the work conducted by the Fund's other grantees.
The Fund encourages all relevant organizations to work in a coordinated
fashion so as to increase the efficacy of grantee programs. 
<h3>
Application Guidelines
</h3>
Organizations interested in applying for funding should first submit a
two-page letter of inquiry along with a copy of their Internal Revenue
Service determination letter. The Fund will acknowledge receipt of all
inquiries promptly and will inform applicants of the expected time frame
for a decision. If the Fund invites a request for funding, a full proposal
and additional application materials will be required. Please do not send
full proposals or other unsolicited materials until requested to do so. 
<p>
The Emma Lazarus Fund makes grants only to tax-exempt organizations as
described in Section 501 (c) of the Internal Revenue Code. Except under
special circumstances, the Fund does not consider proposals for programs
consisting solely or primarily of conferences, television or radio
production, or publications. Additionally, it does not provide funding for
endowments, building construction or maintenance, annual fund appeals,
sectarian religious concerns, or political purposes such as lobbying,
propaganda or partisan political activity. The Fund does not make grants
to individuals, government entities or organizations based outside the
United States. 
<p>
Deadline: There are no deadlines for the submission of inquiries or of
invited proposals. Grant award determinations will be made on an ongoing
basis. 
<p>
For More Information contact Antonio Maciel at the<br>
Open Society Institute<br>
888 Seventh Avenue<br> 
New York, NY 10106<br> 
Tel: (212) 887-0167<br> 
Fax (212) 245-3429<br>
<address>E-mail <a href="mailto:lazarus@sorosny.org"><b>(lazarus@sorosny.org)</b></a></address>
</blockquote>                                                       
<ul>
<li><a href="gopher://gopher.soros.org:70/00/General_Info/Publications/Speeches/Immigrants_Burden.txt"><b>Immigrants' Burden by George Soros</b></a>
<li><a href="gopher://gopher.soros.org/0/General_Info/Press/Lazarus_Fund.txt"><b>Soros Pledges $50 Million to Aid Legal Immigrants</b></a>
</ul>
