<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT09-B18-192</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA064-000377-B044-16</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://server.soros.org:80/apply.html 204.168.83.130 19970112093251 text/html 3376
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 12 Jan 1997 09:26:48 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<html>
<head>
<title> Application Information
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="93242B" alink="93242B" vlink="AD5F5B">      
<table cellpadding=6>                                                    
<tr>                                                                     
<td>                                                                     
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                          
<td>                                                                     
<img align=middle src="/images/apply.gif" alt="Application Information"> 
</td>                                                                    
</tr>                                                                    
</table>                                                                 
The 
<a href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a> 
are independent entities with their 
own boards of directors, staff, program priorities, 
application guidelines, and grantmaking procedures. The 
majority of the national foundations award grants only to 
local organizations and individuals for programs in their 
country. Some award grants to foreign organizations working 
in partnership with local groups on local issues and 
problems. Potential grant applicants should contact specific 
national foundations for information about their application 
procedures.
<p>
The 
<a href="osiny.html"><b>Open Society Institute - New York</b></a>
and the 
<a href="osibuda.html"><b>Open Society Institute - Budapest</b></a>,
as well as the 
<a href="other.html"><b>other organizations</b></a>
and 
programs established by 
<a href="gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a>, 
also have their own 
criteria for proposals. Prospective grantees should contact 
the specific OSI program or other organization for 
information about how to apply for a grant. 
<p>
In general, all foundations and programs require standard 
application information, including:
<ul>
<li>the purpose of the grant (justification of need, 
specific goals, planned activities, excepted outcomes, and 
timeline for completion),
<li>contact person,
<li>qualifications of key staff,
<li>project budget,
<li>amount of funds requested. 
</ul>
<p>
In addition, applicants should be prepared to provide 
overall organizational and budget information, if 
applicable, as well as supporting 
documents, which in the United States would include a copy 
of the IRS determination letter confirming the 
organization's status under section 501(c) 3.
<p>
<h3><a href="gopher://gopher.soros.org/11/Prog_Cat_Info"><img align=middle src="/images/gopher.gif"> Application Information</a>
</h3>
<hr>                                                                            
