<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF South Africa - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Foundation - South Africa<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
The major focus of the Open Society Foundation for South 
Africa (OSF-SA) in 1995 was on promoting and building 
democracy at the grassroots level through support for voter 
education and training initiatives aimed at local government 
elections, which took place in November in all but two 
areas-Cape Town and war-torn KwaZulu Natal. The elections 
were peaceful and generally heralded as a success by 
international standards.
<p>
The exclusion of the majority of South Africans from 
participating in government structures during the apartheid 
era left a vacuum of professional experience at the local 
level. Foundation support for organizations such as the 
Association for Rural Advancement, Inlogov, Planact, and the 
National Women's Resource and Service Centre, all of which 
run training programs for local government councilors and 
officials, contributes to filling this vacuum and ensuring 
efficient local government in the future.
<p>
Throughout the year, the foundation continued its support 
for university-based programs offering diploma courses in 
local government and public administration. Included in this 
support was a contribution to the Joint University Public 
Management Education Trust. The Trust created a consortium 
of six graduate schools of local government to promote 
cooperation and the sharing of resources.
<p>
In the human rights arena in 1995, the foundation supported 
the Investigating Task Unit: Civilian Support Component, 
which is investigating the activities of the hit squads in 
KwaZulu Natal. Hit squads have operated from both inside and 
outside of state structures, preying upon members of 
opposing parties, political dissidents, and ordinary 
citizens during the apartheid era. During 1995, the Civilian 
Support Component hired a staff, established information 
systems, initiated investigations into killings, and helped 
prepare strategic cases for trial. 
<p>
Throughout 1995, the foundation continued its contribution 
to the development of transparent and open government 
through support for the Institute for Democratic 
Alternatives in South Africa (IDASA).  To promote 
understanding of and access to the changing legal and 
welfare systems of the new state, the foundation supported 
the Black Sash's Advice Centre initiative, which provides 
legal assistance in nine offices across the country. 
<p>
To combat the problem of homelessness, a $5 million grant 
was made to the National Urban Reconstruction and Housing 
Agency (NURCHA), an NGO established to help finance housing 
for the poor. This grant matched an equal sum committed by 
the South African government. In addition to the start-up 
funding, 
<a href="/gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a> 
pledged $50 million worth of loan 
guarantees contingent on NURCHA raising substantial funds 
from other sources. This grant and the loan guarantees, once 
matched, will enable NURCHA to assist in the construction of 
about 200,000 housing units for low-income families in South 
Africa over the next five years.
<p>
An estimated 60 percent of young people in South Africa are 
unemployed. Youth development, particularly training and job 
placement, therefore, continued to be a priority of OSF-SA. 
The foundation renewed its support for youth development 
programs, in spite of the collapse of a major national 
initiative, the National Youth Development Forum, which it 
had supported. The Forum had aimed to bring together young 
people from a variety of political backgrounds for job-
creation initiatives. 
<p>
In 1995, the foundation also dedicated significant resources 
to transforming the country's education system, a major 
national priority in the postapartheid era. In addition to 
funding a number of education support programs, we made 
plans for a major initiative to be launched in 1996 in 
conjunction with the 
<a href="/osibuda.html"><b>Open Society Institute - Budapest</b></a>.
This 
comprehensive new program, which will affect students at all 
levels, from kindergarten through university, will seek to 
improve the quality of math, science, and technology 
education. During its first two years, the $15 million 
effort will target Northern Province and Eastern Cape, two 
of the country's poorest provinces. Both regions face 
particularly tough problems in education, including the 
challenges associated with integrating former apartheid 
"homelands" into coherent educational systems created out of 
previously fragmented ones.
<p>
Initial activities are slated to include commissioning the 
development of syllabi and other teaching materials, teacher 
training initiatives, and community outreach efforts. The 
program will also work to develop the involvement of other 
NGOs in education initiatives in these areas. The foundation 
will seek cooperative funding from the South African 
government as well as from the private sector.
<p>
In addition to the initiatives described above, the 
foundation continued its significant support for the 
development of community radio stations, with a particular 
focus on educational programming.
<p>
<i>Michael Savage, Executive Director</i>
