<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF Haiti - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Foundation - Haiti<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 

The Fondation Connaissance et Libert was established in 
April 1995.  My first concern as executive director was for 
our seven-member board and small senior staff to discuss and 
understand the main philosophical concepts that guide the 
network of foundations established by 
<a href="/gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a>: 
transition, open societies, and empowerment.
<p>
In order to render these concepts operational, we had to 
give them meaning and coherence within our own political, 
economic, and cultural reality. This process led us to 
choose education as our main field of intervention. Haiti is 
a country with a long history of arbitrary rule and where 
today 85 percent of the population is illiterate and still 
struggling to gain access to the most basic rights of 
citizenship. In such a context, the process of transition 
toward democracy can only be understood if the children of 
this marginalized majority are given the means and skills to 
become responsible citizens. In 1995, the foundation gave 
grants to schools that seemed to share our vision for 
change.
<p>
At the same time, the foundation supported grassroots 
organizations in their attempts to reinforce and expand the 
skills and knowledge they need in order to help build an 
open society. A special fund was established to support 
small projects initiated by grassroots organizations. The 
foundation supported community radio stations, the only 
newspaper in the Creole language, experimental and 
alternative educational experiences (preschool, workshops, 
integration of blind children into mainstream schools), and 
a unique community library-entirely managed by a youth 
group-in a slum of Port-au-Prince. The latter has had such a 
positive impact on the youth group and the community that we 
hope that it may serve as a model for the foundation's 1996-
97 library program. 
<p>
Much of 1995 was taken up by the complex logistics of 
establishing an institution in a country lacking the most 
basic infrastructures, the need to develop an open society 
approach especially tailored to Haiti, and the 
identification of the best partners for launching the 
foundation's own programs.
<p>
<b>A Revolutionary Leap into the 21st Century</b><br>
In 1996, Fondation Connaissance et Libert will set up two 
additional libraries modeled on the youth group community 
library, although with a much enlarged collection, more 
sophisticated equipment, and the capacity to serve as a 
training ground for other interested groups. The approach 
and challenge here will be the integration of the library 
into the community through the empowerment of local children 
and youth by giving them access to the world of the written 
word and related activities (reading groups, debates, 
workshops). Partnerships are being negotiated with 
institutions for the training of local youths in community 
library management and in skills related to monitoring 
reading groups for children, for adults with special needs, 
etc. In that respect, we hope to get some support as well 
from the 
<a href="/osibuda.html"><b>Open Society Institute - Budapest</b></a>
<a href="/library.html"><b>Library Program</b></a>. 
Moreover, we are exploring the possibility of introducing 
the Internet to the foundation's libraries and eventually to 
others. If we succeed, this would constitute, for Haiti, a 
revolutionary qualitative leap into the 21st century.
<p>
In 1996, the foundation will also launch its own education 
program through three regional pilot projects-a commune in 
the north, a school complex in the central plateau, and a 
large community school in a remote town on the southern 
peninsula. The education program is modeled after the 
<a href="/aedp.html"><b>Albanian Education Development Project</b></a>.  
Like the program in 
Albania, our model will address teacher training and 
community involvement in education. A construction component 
of the program, although very much needed (all school 
infrastructures in Haiti are in deplorable condition), will 
be postponed until the foundation can find a partner willing 
to invest in this type of work. Finally, our education and 
library program will integrate three 
<a href="/osiny.html"><b>OSI-New York</b></a> 
regional 
programs: 
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step</b></a>, 
<a href="/youth.html#highschool"><b>Debate</b></a>, 
and 
<a href="/youth.html#health"><b>Health Education</b></a>.
<p>
We have chosen to focus on education through an integrated 
approach which allows us to tackle other major development 
issues in Haiti: reinforcement of civil society, 
environment, health, and the empowerment of women.
<p>
<i>Michele Duvivier Pierre-Louis, Executive Director</i>
<hr>                                                                       
