<html><head><title>                                                             
SF - Hungary - Report From Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>
<tr>
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>
<td><h1>
Soros Foundation - Hungary<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
Established in 1984, the 
Soros Foundation - Hungary
is the 
first in the network of national foundations created by 
<a href="/gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a>. 
In 1995, we identified five areas of priority 
for our work: higher education and scholarships; public 
education; arts and culture; health care and social welfare; 
and civil society.
<p>
<b>Higher Education.</b><br> Through the 
<a href="/hesp.html"><b>Higher Education Support Program</b></a>, 
the foundation funded a variety of programs to help 
restructure Hungary's higher education system. We sent 
researchers on scholarships to American and European 
colleges and universities, provided supplementary grants for 
living expenses to students with scholarships at foreign 
colleges, and helped scholars and scientists to participate 
in conferences and field trips abroad. The University and 
College Exchange Program supported the foreign exchange 
programs of various Hungarian higher education institutions. 
The foundation gave support to the publication of Hungarian 
scientific papers in prestigious international journals. 
Seven Student Advising Centers provided information about 
higher education and scholarship opportunities abroad.
<p>
<b>Public Education.</b><br> The goal of the Public Education 
Development Program, established in the beginning of 1995, 
is the democratization and development of the Hungarian 
public education system through reform of conventional 
teaching structures and methods. The foundation equipped 
classrooms in 85 schools with state-of-the-art computer 
technology (including Internet connectivity), created a 
textbook database, and organized teacher training. 
<p>
The regional 
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step</b></a> 
preschool program added 33 
classrooms to the 19 already established in Hungary. The 
Help for Disadvantaged Groups Program supported the 
preparation of curricula and course books, funded vocational 
training, and gave stipends to disadvantaged students at 
secondary schools. The foundation developed teaching 
materials for understanding prejudice and promoting 
tolerance, and a program for teaching democracy. Civic 
education involves students in shaping their school 
environment as well as their future in society.
<p>
We organized seminars and training courses for teachers of 
social studies, and developed management training programs 
in education to help school administrators perform their new 
professional responsibilities. The foundation helped 
establish six community schools, open to everyone; these 
schools focused on preserving cultural traditions, training 
jobless young people, and building community activities in 
Hungary. In a special environmental education project, 
children drew a map of Hungary identifying places of "joy" 
and "sorrow" from an environmental perspective. 
<p>
<b>Arts and Culture.</b><br> In 1995, the Library Support Program ran a 
competition for the restoration of documents from libraries, 
archives, and museums. Together with Arts International 
(USA) and the Budapest Municipality, the foundation 
announced a management training program for performing arts 
and visual art groups. The foundation also supported 
cultural journals, which are vital to spreading democratic 
civil thinking to all, and which cannot survive without 
subsidies anywhere in the world.
<p>
In book publishing, the foundation sought to make valuable 
Hungarian and foreign cultural and scientific works 
available to Hungarian readers at affordable prices. The 
Performing Arts Program was started in 1995 to support the 
production of contemporary dramas and promote cooperation 
between traditional and alternative theaters. Grants were 
given to support cultural events, conferences, concerts, and 
exhibitions.
<p>
<b>Health Care and Social Welfare.</b><br> The Health Care System 
Development Program started in 1995 to help modernize the 
Hungarian health care system by improving the quality of 
care and services, especially for disadvantaged children, 
handicapped people, homeless people, and refugees. The 
foundation supported the provision of meals for 
disadvantaged children in the primary schools as well as 
family counseling for the economically underprivileged.
<p>
<b>Civil Society.</b><br> The foundation helped NGOs by supporting 
training, and consultation/advisory services, and by 
developing communication networks. The Business Basics 
Foundation, supported by the foundation and the Know-How 
Fund of the British government, provided small and medium-
sized businesses in Hungary with training and consultancy 
services.
<p>
The Independent Ecological Center worked to promote 
innovative strategies for the prevention of pollution, 
create and strengthen NGOs in this field, and raise public 
awareness of environmental issues. 
<p>
<i>Eva Bakonyi, Executive Director</i>
<hr>                                                                  
