<html><head><title>                                                             
OSI - Moscow - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Institute - Moscow<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
I took up my position as executive director of the Open 
Society Institute - Moscow hoping to see the foundation act 
not only as a source of financing but also as a resource 
center and unifying force among Russian NGOs and various 
civic initiatives. The year 1995 was one of many changes as 
OSI-Moscow underwent major administrative reorganization and 
closely aligned its grant management structure with the 
<a href="/isf.html"><b>International Science Foundation</b></a>, 
another grantmaking entity 
sponsored by 
<a href="/gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a>. 
The restructuring helped 
streamline our grantmaking process to address Russia's
rapidly changing needs.
<p>
Throughout 1995, OSI-Moscow continued its main programmatic 
activities by supporting various initiatives in education, 
the arts, civil society, and media. While it is impossible 
to list all projects supported by OSI-Moscow in 1995, I 
would like to call attention to the Textbooks for Russian 
Schools Program, our most innovative new project in 1995. In 
fact, reform of humanities education in Russia was the 
foundation's top priority. In close consultation with the 
Ministry of Education of the Russian Federation, the best 
texts produced during the earlier Transformation of the 
Humanities Program were selected for large print runs. 
Through its experience with the textbook market, 
distribution systems, and the publishing industry, OSI-
Moscow became a leader among foundations in Russia in the 
production of educational materials. For the first time in 
the foundation's history, its books were sold to schools, 
distributors, and regional departments of education, 
ensuring that new materials reached students while promoting 
reform within the publishing industry. Over half a million 
books were sold in the western part of Russia. This model 
will be expanded in the future to cover texts for both 
secondary and higher education.
<p>

<b>Seminars for Young Scholars</b><br>
In the field of higher education, financial and 
organizational support was given to a series of seminars for 
young scholars in Moscow, Kazan, St. Petersburg, Yashkarola, 
and Samara. These seminars examined issues ranging from 
federalism in Russia to the structural problems facing 
institutions of higher education. The seminar program was 
carried out in cooperation with the Russian State University 
for the Humanities.  
<p>
Continuing an effort to support projects in the provinces, 
OSI-Moscow cooperated with the Moscow Musical Conservatory 
and the Union of Composers to create the Traveling Musical 
Academy Program. The academy offers provincial cities 
concerts every evening for a month combined with daily 
master classes by musicians and teachers.  Between 40 and 55 
musical events are held in the course of a single academy 
engagement. The academy encourages existing musical 
institutions and the creation of new organizations. In 
bringing world class performances to cities with an already 
developed musical infrastructure, the foundation promotes 
contacts among local musicians and Western and Russian 
musical communities.
<p>
In its willingness to support outstanding individuals in the 
cultural sphere, the foundation stands apart from most other 
foundations in Russia. The grant given to the great Russian 
animator Yuri Norshtein to complete his master work, a 
version of Gogol's "The Overcoat," is but one example of the 
foundation's efforts. The film is likely to become a classic 
within the great tradition of Russian animation. 
<p>

<b>Flak Jackets for Journalists</b><br>
The Moscow Charter of Journalists, a long-term partner of 
the foundation, continued to develop projects to raise 
professional standards and assist Russian journalists. In 
addressing a list of priorities set by the Charter, the 
foundation provided flak jackets on loan to journalists 
working in zones of conflict. Other funds provided financial 
support to the families of journalists killed on assignment 
in these areas.
<p>
The foundation also participated in the financing of "Turn 
On," a television series to encourage young people to take 
part in the electoral process. The program examined issues 
facing voters prior to elections for the state Duma. The 
program, modeled on MTV's "Rock the Vote," mixed
performances from popular musicians with informational 
broadcasting. 
<p>
Finally, the creation of civic centers in several Russian 
cities to consult and provide technical support to local 
NGOs and civic groups was a direct response to a need for 
provincial NGOs to coordinate their activities more 
effectively. Such initiatives on the part of the foundation 
reflect a process of evolution which will eventually place 
OSI-Moscow at the center of NGO development in the 
provinces.
<p>
<i>Vyacheslav Bakhmin, Executive Director</i>
