</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
OSI Moscow - Country Background
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3"
>                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>
Open Society Institute - Moscow<br>Country Background
</h1></td>
</table> 

Life in Russia at the beginning of 1994 was relatively calm after conflict in 1993 between 
President Yeltsin and his opponents in the Congress of People's Deputies had plunged Moscow into bloody 
chaos and pushed Russia to the precipice of civil war. But elections for a new State Duma were called, and 
on December 12, 1993, Russians voted for new deputies and a new constitution. While there was initial 
shock over the poor results of the reformist parties and the perceived success of ultra-nationalist Vladimir 
Zhirinovsky's Liberal Democratic Party, the threat that the LDP would play a significant role in the 
decisions of the State Duma lessened during 1994. The new constitution clarified lines of authority for the 
president and the Duma, and lent stability to Russia's political life.<p>
 
Throughout 1994, the government continued to battle inflation, and encouraging indicators appeared that 
the transition to a market economy was continuing. Although prices continued to rise, goods and services 
became more readily available. But in the beginning of October the ruble and financial markets dropped at 
breakneck speed, eventually leading to an investigation and the removal of the head of the Central Bank. 
And while the ruble dropped, the crime rate steadily rose, especially in Moscow, and organized crime in 
particular flourished. Several financial scandals involving investment houses and banks underscored the 
increasing risk of doing business in Russia.
<hr>
