<a name="annual"></a>
<h2>
From the 1995 Annual Report
</h2>
For the International Science Foundation (ISF), the year 
began with the successful continuation of projects funded by 
the ISF Long Term Grants aimed at supporting scientists 
involved in fundamental research in the former Soviet Union 
and Baltics, and ended with the completion of the 
foundation's mandate of transferring more than $130 million 
to the region. During a period of economic uncertainty, the 
ISF was able to provide direct assistance to more than 
20,000 scientists in 14 countries. 
<p> 
As the International Science Foundation looks ahead, it is 
both important and rewarding to review some of its 
achievements over the past year. The foundation had a 
tremendous impact in l995 with the creation and 
implementation of, among others, the following programs.
<p>
The 
<a href="/gap/index.html"><b>Grant Assistance Program (GAP)</b></a> 
offered reliable 
distribution and accounting services to other nonprofit 
organizations in the West conducting charity projects in the 
former Soviet Union in support of science and the 
humanities, education, culture, and humanitarian aid. 
Logistical assistance was provided to donors free of charge. 
In 1995 alone, GAP helped to manage 120 projects totaling 
over $3 million in direct grants or collaborative research 
projects funded by U.S. and European federal agencies (e.g. 
NSF, NIH, EPA, NASA), universities, NATO, and other 
organizations.
<p>
With a budget of $1.5 million, the 
Library Support Program 
sent over 115 different scientific periodicals worth $5.5 
million to about 400 libraries serving the public, 
universities, and other institutions. 
The program received journals through discounted 
subscriptions and donations from publishers and managed 
their distribution to 
recipient libraries. 
<p>
The Conference Travel Grant Program provided short-term 
fellowships for participation in professional meetings 
abroad. Since its inception, this program has helped nearly 
8,500 scientists to attend more then 2,000 conferences at a 
total cost of $13 million, $5 million of which were 
disbursed in 1995. Funding through this program covered per-
diem allowances and air travel arranged by the ISF's in-house 
travel staff at substantial discounts. 
<p>
Among the foundation's greatest achievements were the 
successful negotiations which resulted in the signing of 
seven unprecedented joint funding agreements with the 
governments of Belarus, Estonia, Georgia, Latvia, Lithuania, 
Russia and Ukraine. In these historic agreements, individual 
governments contributed funds totaling over $15 million to 
continue support of the ISF Long Term Research Grant 
recipients. As a result, the foundation distributed more 
than $30 million in additional funds, including $15 million 
in matching donations. Through these joint funding 
agreements, the foundation will continue to provide vital 
assistance to the region and encourage new approaches to 
funding and managing scientific research. 
<p>
The ISF will take a new direction in 1996. Under the 
leadership of Greg Johnson, the newly appointed executive 
director, the foundation will move toward a consolidation of 
duties and a strengthening of organizational links with 
other foundations supported by 
<a href="gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a>. 
As the 
countries of the former Soviet Union and the Baltics face 
new realities and obstacles, the ISF will continue to 
promote mutual cooperation and partnerships, furthering 
assistance effort in the region. 
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="about"></a>
<h2>
About the Foundation
</h2>

George Soros established the International Science Foundation (ISF) in December 1992 to help scientists of the former Soviet Union weather the economic crisis in the region without having to leave science or their countries and to encourage new approaches to funding and managing scientific research in the former Soviet Union.<p>

The ISF provides support for basic research by individual scientists, research teams, and research institutes and organizations. The ISF does not support applied or military research nor does it make any claims to intellectual property rights. The ISF operations in Russia are conducted through its Moscow office and branch offices in St. Petersburg, Novosibirsk, Vladivostok, and Yekaterinburg.<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="emergency"></a>
<h2>
Emergency Grants Program
</h2>

On 25 February 1993, the ISF announced its Emergency Grants Program. The program sought to distribute $500 grants to the most productive scientists of the former Soviet Union who had published a minimum of three articles in the leading open scientific journals during the past five years. Some 35,000 applications were received by the ISF, and as a result 26,145 scientists received individual one-time grants of $500 each, totaling more than $13 million. Of that number, 20,763 grantees were scientists from Russia.<p> 

<b>Conference Travel Grant Program. </b><br>
The program supports the exchange of ideas and information among scientists of the former Soviet Union and the international scientific community by underwriting participation in conferences, including travel expenses, hotel accommodations, and per diem expenses. Applications must come from conference organizers on behalf of researchers presenting oral papers or posted presentations. Researchers in the areas of applied, military, and conversion studies as well as scholars working in the humanities or social sciences are not eligible. In two years, the ISF has funded over 6,000 scientists to travel to scientific conferences around the world.<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="longterm"></a>
<h2>
Long-Term Research Grants Program
</h2>

This program provides funding for major research projects by individual researchers and research teams to cover the cost of laboratory and telecommunications equipment, materials, supplies, and travel. It is the biggest program implemented by the ISF, supporting some 3,550 research projects carried out by 15,000 scientists.<p>

By the end of 1994, the original funds allocated to the Long-Term Research Grants Program were distributed, but new funding arrangements will allow the program to continue until the end of 1995. At a meeting in March 1994, George Soros and Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin reached an agreement on joint funding of research projects submitted to the ISF. In accordance with this agreement and a subsequent ordinance, the government of Russia allocated $12.5 million with Soros matching the amount. As a result, the Long-Term Research Grants Program in Russia will have an additional budget of $25 million for 1995.<p>

According to the trilateral agreement signed by the International Science Foundation, the Ministry of Science and Technical Policy, and the Russian Foundation for Fundamental Research (RFFI), the additional $12.5 million allocated by Soros will be distributed proportionally among those holding ISF long-term grants in Russia. The ISF transferred to the RFFI all projects it has supported as well as 1,500 projects that were highly appraised by international experts, but were not awarded grants because of the lack of funds. The RFFI reviewed these projects and selected those it would finance from its own funds.<p>

The governments of the Baltic states, Belarus, Georgia, and Ukraine made their own contributions to the continuation of research in their countries. In each case these contributions were supplemented by matching grants from George Soros.<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="library"></a>
<h2>
Library Assistance Program
</h2>

Starting in 1991 economic constraints forced libraries throughout the former Soviet Union to curtail their subscriptions to foreign scientific periodicals. This limited access to Western scientific literature deprived scientists of the possibility of keeping up with developments in their fields of research and exacerbated their isolation from the international scientific community. The ISF Library Assistance Program was established in 1993 to make up for these shortages.<p>

Today the ISF manages regular deliveries of Western scientific journals to libraries and research centers throughout the former Soviet Union. The ISF offices in Russia serve as distribution centers for 353 libraries in Russia and 15 libraries in other former Soviet states. Most of the journals are distributed through the library networks of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Russian Medical Academy, Russian Humanitarian University, and the Siberian division of the Russian Academy of Sciences.<p>

As a result of successful negotiations with a number of US commercial and university publishing houses, the ISF obtained the 1993 and 1994 subscriptions at a big discount--$1.7 million for $6 million worth of scientific periodicals. In 1994 alone the Library Assistance Program distributed 98,000 copies of scientific journals.<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="telecommunications"></a>
<h2>
Telecommunications Program
</h2>

In collaboration with the Ministry of Science and Technological Policy of the Russian Federation, the Russian Foundation for Basic Research, and the Siberian Branch of the Russian Academy of Sciences, the ISF provides Russian research and academic communities with access to the Internet. As part of the program, the ISF is supervising the development of major infrastructure projects in Moscow, Novosibirsk, and Yaroslavl in Russia and in Kiev in Ukraine.<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="humanities"></a>
<h2>
Competition for Humanities Research
</h2>

In 1994, the ISF helped organize a competition for research projects in the humanities. The coordinating board reviewed over 2,000 submissions and selected 637 winning proposals. Among the winners were nearly 1,400 historians, linguists, archeologists, art critics, and other scholars engaged in basic research in the humanities.<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="discretionary"></a>
<h2>
Discretionary Grants
</h2>

In 1994, the ISF also awarded several noncompetitive grants. The Komarov Botanical Institute in St. Petersburg, for example, received a $500,000 grant to repair its building and save its herbarium and unique collection of plants. Discretionary grants also went to the scientific publication Khimiyaizhizn (Chemistry and Life) and to the special mathematics-oriented school #57 in Moscow.<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
