<html><head><title>                                                             
Stefan Batory Foundation - Poland - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Stefan Batory Foundation - Poland<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
After eight years of activity, the Stefan Batory Foundation 
is one of the largest and most important independent 
institutions in Poland. In 1995, the foundation concentrated 
its activities on transforming education, the promotion of 
culture and tolerance, the growth of civil society, and the 
development of democracy.
<p>
The modernization of education has always been a high 
priority for the Batory Foundation. This field requires a 
constant injection of innovation, experimentation, and 
reform that are incompatible with the bureaucratic 
structures of the state.
<p>
In 1995, the foundation continued to initiate and sponsor 
programs aimed at educational reform at all levels. The 
foundation offered fellowships and travel grants to Polish 
scholars traveling abroad and supported conferences 
organized in-country by various academic centers. The 
International Summer Schools were organized to familiarize 
teachers and scholars from postcommunist countries with the 
ways in which the disciplines of political science, 
international studies, and economics are taught or practiced 
in other countries. The Batory Foundation also supported 
professional training abroad for school teachers, and 
introduced three educational programs (Young Entrepreneurs, 
Entrepreneurship, and Debate Clubs) to elementary and 
secondary schools.
<p>
We continued to provide assistance to institutions, 
nongovernmental organizations, associations, and groups 
active in the realm of culture. Our support was offered for 
specific artistic projects, for the popularizing of the 
arts, and for the education and training of managers. We 
initiated cultural cooperation within Central and Eastern 
Europe and promoted our culture in the West. We also paid 
attention to the needs of national and ethnic minorities 
living in Poland by supporting cultural events which promote 
coexistence, tolerance, cultural pluralism, and mutual 
understanding. 
<p>
The foundation supported cultural journals, especially 
regional journals which keep readers in touch with national 
and world events while promoting local culture. We continued 
to support publishing activities by commercial publishers, 
focusing on books which serve the development of a 
democratic culture. 
<p>
Promoting development of civil society is one of the Stefan 
Batory Foundation's main objectives. It is hard to imagine a 
civil society without nongovernmental organizations through 
which citizens can advance common goals and common 
interests. The support of NGOs took the form of financing 
clearly defined programs and/or providing general support 
for NGOs that fulfill elements of our mission. Having 
initiated and tried out new programs, we often transfer them 
to 
already existing NGOs or spin them off to become new 
independent organizations.
<p>
<b>Combating Poverty and Violence Against Women</b><br>
We continued to support small, independent, local 
organizations that often are major actors in alleviating the 
social problems of transition, combating poverty, and 
providing welfare services to needy children and families. 
We also supported programs to protect the equal rights of 
women and prevent discrimination, violence, and sexual abuse 
in the home, in schools, and in the workplace. 
<p>
In addition, funding was provided for undertakings connected 
with local self-government, national minorities, cooperation 
in Central and Eastern Europe, and European integration.
<p>
A proportion of grants for education, culture, and civil 
society initiatives came from the Nongovernmental 
Organizations Support Fund, established in 1992. The fund 
was conceived as a response to the need, perceived by the 
foundation, for cooperation between nongovernmental 
organizations and financial and business institutions. In 
1995, many banks and companies responded to the foundation's
proposal to match every Polish zloty paid by them into the 
fund with one of its own. 
We believe that joint action can be more effective in 
building support for transformation processes and 
counteracting their side effects. 
<p>
To promote the idea of open society, the foundation 
established the Karl Popper Scholarship, to be given each 
year on a competitive basis to the authors of the three best 
book projects on subjects of importance to open society.
<p>
In 1995, the foundation reviewed 3,385 applications and 
awarded 761 grants to institutions and organizations and 
1,016 grants to individuals. More than 800 libraries 
received support for cultural journals. More than 400 
elementary and secondary schools were involved in 
foundation-supported programs. More than 200 journalists 
participated in training courses organized by the 
<a href="/osimedia.html"><b>Media Program</b></a>.
<p>
<i>Jacek Wojnarowski, Executive Director</i>
