<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF - Sofia - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Foundation - Sofia<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
In 1995, the Open Society  Foundation - Sofia celebrated its 
fifth year 
of operation. During those five years, we have spent nearly 
$15 million to support Bulgarian nongovernmental 
organizations, universities, libraries, economic reform 
initiatives, and arts and culture programs. Overall, the 
foundation has awarded grants to 5,000 Bulgarians in 
various professions to study abroad or participate in 
conferences. 
Over 2,000 undergraduate and graduate students received 
support to study in Bulgarian and foreign universities. Our 
Libraries Fund gave Bulgarian libraries 130,000 volumes of 
scientific and other specialized literature from foreign 
donors. With the Soros Center for Contemporary Arts, we have 
financed 600 projects in Bulgarian arts and culture. The 
foundation has also supported over 1,200 projects 
for economic and legal reform and the development of 
Bulgaria's
third sector. 
<p>
Throughout 1995, the foundation built its presence in the 
country by establishing new Open Society Clubs in the cities 
of Stara Zagora, Gabrovo, Veliko, Turnovo, Vratza. Clubs in 
Plovdiv, Varna, Sliven, Velingrad, and Rousse were 
registered as independent civil associations. The clubs 
diversified their memberships and expanded their funding 
sources to support projects ranging from a charity ball in 
Plovdiv, which raised money for a fund to support orphans, 
to a joint project for cultural exchange between the town of 
Sliven and the University of Trontheim, Norway, to the 
establishment of the first private radio station in the 
Pleven region. 
<p>
The Information Center's 10 regional offices expanded their 
activities, disseminating information about education, 
nongovernmental organizations, and scholarship opportunities 
in other parts of Europe for Bulgarians. In June, the center 
produced the first computerized database of Bulgarian higher 
education. At about the same time, the foundation became the 
first Bulgarian organization with its own 
<a href="http://www.osf.acad.bg/"><b>home page</b></a> 
on the World Wide Web. In 1995, the foundation's European Fund 
helped speed Bulgaria's integration into European social, 
political, and cultural structures through research and 
other initiatives. 
<p>
<b>Internet Links and Library Networks</b><br>
The Internet Program supported the first full Internet link 
of academic institutions in Sofia and continued to expand 
connectivity to academic centers in other cities. The 
Universities Fund held a competition for projects to develop 
local computer systems in universities. Major initiatives of 
the foundation included two specialized training seminars 
for managers of privatization funds, organized by the 
Economic Reform Fund, the Center for the Study of Democracy 
in Sofia, and the CEU Privatization Project in Prague. 
Nearly 50 of the country's major libraries were equipped 
with automated networks with the support of the Open Society 
Foundation - Sofia.
<p>
The Scholarships Fund supported over 200 students pursuing a 
range of disciplines at Bulgarian and foreign universities, 
including Oxford, Harvard, Johns Hopkins, the Central 
European University, Institut Superieur Economique-Brussels, 
and Conservatoire Nationale Superieure-Paris.. 
<p>
The OSF-Sofia International Exchange Fund helped over 200 
professionals in the fields of law, medicine, and economics, 
among others, travel to international conferences and 
seminars. The Open Education Center supported the 
establishment of more than 10 regional groups specializing 
in youth education programs. The Soros Center for 
Contemporary Arts (SCCA) organized "Bulgarian Medieval Town: 
Technologies," unique presentation of medieval crafts, as 
well as the first exhibition of Bulgarian video art. The 
Open Program supported initiatives carried out by various 
environmental groups concurrently with the Sofia meeting of 
the Ecology Ministers of Europe, the United States, and 
Canada in September 1995. The program also organized a film 
festival, featuring documentaries on Sarajevo and films 
sponsored by Human Rights Watch. 
<p>
OSF-Sofia manages a charity fund for talented children from 
orphanages established by the Bulgarian opera singer Raina 
Kabaivanska. 
The fund opened the first specialized school for these 
children in September at Stoikite, near the town of Smolyan. 
<p>
Despite the withdrawal of support from the government and 
hostile attacks from nationalistic and post-communist 
circles, the foundation in 1995 continued to take a leading 
role in developing civil society 
in Bulgaria.
<p>
<i>George Prohasky, Executive Director</i> 
