<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF Sofia - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Foundation - Sofia<br>About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

During the five years since the beginning of democratic changes in Bulgaria, political achievements have been more evident than economic or social progress. It is now clear that much needs to be done to attain the potential for open society.<p>

In the arena of politics, there is a fully established system of democratic multiparty elections, separation of powers, and adherence to democratic procedures within the framework of the constitution adopted in 1991. The December 1994 elections, which produced a socialist majority, did not attract international observers, an indication that the international community is satisfied with progress in the political sphere. The rule of law has had a more problematic recent history. Enshrined in the constitutional and legal system, it is still not a universal way of doing business; informal, backstage decision-making remains common. Law enforcement, oppressive under the old regime, has changed to inefficiency, leading to an explosive increase in crime and rising demands for law and order.<p>

The human rights situation in Bulgaria is seen by many as an achievement in the Balkan context. Following periods of friction in the 1980s, the different cultural, ethnic, and religious groups have reverted to their tradition of peaceful coexistence. In recent years, however, there has been a marked increase in hostility toward the Rroma.<p>

After a vigorous beginning in 1991-92, the transition to a free economy has slowed considerably. Some 90 percent of all productive property is still state-owned, although much of it is in the process of being privatized. Recent signs of economic recovery coexist with a continuing fall in living standards for the majority of the population.<p>

The clearest achievement in the area of civil society has been the appearance of some 1,000 independent newspapers and magazines, placing Bulgaria among the world leaders in press diversity. The problem for private businesses and NGOs is the limitations of the existing culture: lack of faith in individual ability, lack of individual responsibility, a group-centered way of life, suspicion of change, and distrust of outside (foreign) experience.
<hr>
