<html><head><title>                                                             
Open Estonia Foundation- From the Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Estonia Foundation<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
At present, the political and economic life of our small 
country is stabilizing. But the method for developing an 
open society has not yet been firmly established. Dangers in 
the short term might arise from a single, uncalculated, 
destabilizing step by the government. Therefore, the work of 
the Open Estonia Foundation (OEF) in reinforcing the 
structures of open society is of the utmost importance. This 
means both grantmaking and proactive involvement in all 
fields which relate to the creation of a society based on 
the rule of law, protection of human rights, and respect for 
human values.
<p>
Over the years, education has always been a top priority of 
the OEF. 
In 1995, the foundation administered more than 20 
scholarship and internship programs in Europe and the United 
States, supported a wide range of projects for the reform of 
higher education and secondary school curricula, and 
implemented the regional preschool program 
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step</b></a> 
in 
21 kindergartens, including 5 Russian-language 
kindergartens. The OEF also continued its support for the 
<a href="/youth.html#health"><b>Regional Health Education</b></a> 
and 
<a href="/youth.html#highschool"><b>High School Debate Programs</b></a>, 
and launched the High School Exchange Program. 
<p>
More than 200 Estonian and Russian-language schools use the 
Junior Achievement program to teach students how to run a 
business and compete in a free market economy. Support for 
the successful Active Learning In Action program, which 
involves more than 300 schools and 450 teachers, is 
producing innovative teaching methods using modern computer- 
and telecommunications-based techniques. 
<p>
Together with other foundations, the OEF supported a huge 
information systems development program in six Estonian 
libraries. The foundation's
<a href="/internet.html"><b> Internet Program </b></a>
supported the 
establishment of the Baltic Academic Network and Computing 
Services, as well as the Baltic Studies Network, which will 
offer distance-learning courses. At the end of 1995, the 
foundation announced a countrywide competition to establish 
Internet connections with NGOs, educational institutions, 
hospitals, and libraries.
<p>
A major concern for the foundation continues to be the 
integration of ethnic Russians and other minorities into the 
social, political, and economic life of the country. 
Residents with a limited knowledge of the Estonian language 
face major obstacles in obtaining citizenship. To assist 
people in meeting the language requirement, the OEF 
announced a competition for the best script and production 
of a TV program for teaching the Estonian language, which 
will be distributed free to TV stations, schools, and 
language centers. The foundation also supported intensive 
teaching of Estonian in the schools and the publication of 
an Estonian-language textbook. 
<p>
In 1995, the OEF supported nongovernmental organizations 
whose activities promoted democratic values. The foundation 
helped organize an international seminar on Regulating Civil 
Society, a workshop on the legal and fiscal environment of 
nongovernmental organizations in Estonia, and a seminar on 
philanthropy. The foundation's law program concentrated on 
the training of lawyers by supporting a visiting lecturers 
program, the publication of law textbooks, and the work of 
the Lawyers' Training Centre. With the help of the 
<a href="/ilgps.html"><b>Institute of Public Service and Local Government</b></a>, 
the foundation 
supported the translation of public administration textbooks 
and the introduction of public administration courses at 
Tartu University.
<p>
In 1995, the Open Estonia Book program translated and 
published six books by prominent Western authors, including 
Bertrand Russell, Carl Gustav Jung, Paul Valery, and Jacques 
Derrida. The foundation also supported a number of other 
cultural and publishing projects while the Soros Center for 
Contemporary Arts-Estonia promoted diverse arts activities.
<p>
The OEF kept in close contact with other Central and Eastern 
European countries through the 
<a href="/east.html"><b>East East Program</b></a>, 
supporting 
14 cooperative workshops and seminars on, for example, 
Russian-Estonian relations and civics education in the 
Baltic countries. Medical grants were awarded for training, 
health education, HIV-related issues, Medinet (a computer 
practice unit of the Medical Information Center), a project 
on modern gene diagnostics, and a database on genetic 
diseases.
<p>
The Open Estonia Foundation trusts that its activities have 
contributed to the transformation of Estonia and the region 
by equipping both individuals and the community at large to 
share in the responsibility of establishing an open society 
and shaping their future.
<p>
<i>Mall Hellam, Executive Director</i>
<hr>                                                                       
