<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
Open Estonia Foundation - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Estonia Foundation<br>About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

Open Estonia Foundation is an integral part of the rebuilding effort that is going on in the Republic of Estonia. Estonia was an independent state between the two World Wars and regained its independence again in 1991. To get rid of the "Soviet heritage" rebuilding the state, civil society, and the economy have been Estonia's most urgent concerns from that moment onward.<p>

The first parliamentary elections in 1992 led to the formation of a center-right government, which, under the eyes of a politically divided opposition and a free press, has pushed through reformist legislation. A major legislative concern was the Russian-speaking people who settled in Estonia during the Soviet regime and how they would be integrated into the social, political, and economic life of the country. As a result, Estonia has guaranteed ethnic Russians and other minorities equal human rights, social care, the right to an education in Estonian or Russian schools, cultural autonomy, the right to vote in local elections, and eventual citizenship on the basis of a rudimentary knowledge of the Estonian language and at least two years of residency. To assist people in meeting the language requirement, Estonia's government, with the help of foreign governments and NGOs, established language training centers and courses throughout the country.<p>

The economic priorities are structural reorganization of the economy, liberalization of trade, privatization and development of the private sector, elimination of barriers to competition, strict fiscal and monetary policies, reforming the banking sector, and development of a legislative base. Estonia has made rapid progress toward a market economy while at the same time generating a high rate of economic growth. The key elements have been a good monetary system without major exchange rate risks, a fully balanced budget, and an open economy.<p>

There are also negative sides to Estonia's development. Social tensions arising from the current distribution of income pose major problems. The state's role in business remains too high. The social security system and state departments operate on very tight budgets.
<hr>
