<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF - Lithuania - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Fund - Lithuania<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 

The Open Society Fund-Lithuania (OSFL) in 1995 confirmed its 
support for successful and effective programs and initiated 
a number of new projects with the common goal of helping the 
development of an open society. The foundation's main areas
of concern were education (from preschool to university), 
culture and the arts, publishing, legal reform, civil 
society, media and journalism, social services and youth, 
Roma, business and economics, Internet, and foreign travel 
and conferences.
<p>
The Transformation of Education Program concluded the first 
phase of its curriculum development and textbook project. 
Since its inception in 1993, the program has supported the 
authorship and publication of 90 original textbooks and 
teaching aids and 30 translations. Another 75 textbooks are 
nearing completion and will be published in 1996. By 
involving 22 publishing houses, the program also helped 
create new competitive conditions in the publishing and 
distribution of schoolbooks. In cooperation with 
<a href="/russia.html"><b>OSI-Moscow</b></a>, 
the foundation made Russian textbooks available to Russian-
language schools in Lithuania. 
<p>
School teachers have participated in various requalification 
courses and seminars, school leadership programs, and other 
innovative pedagogical projects. In early 1996, a new Inter-
university Educational Study Center was established with the 
aim of helping to modernize teacher training at pedagogical 
universities and colleges.
<p>
The New Educational Technologies Program played a key role 
in establishing a national, government-financed school 
computerization project, for which the foundation will 
provide teacher training and software development, and 
advance the Internet in the school system. Over 1,000 
teachers participated in computer literacy and Internet 
training programs. In preschool education, the foundation 
was instrumental in introducing modern methodologies at 
teacher training colleges, based on successful preschool 
pilot projects cofunded by the Egmont Fonden of Denmark and 
the 
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step</b></a> 
program. The 
<a href="/youth.html#highschool"><b>High School Debate Program</b></a> 
was expanded to include universities. The 
<a href="/youth.html#health"><b>Health Education Program</b></a> 
trained over 1,500 teachers on the implementation of 
a health curriculum focusing on alcohol and drugs, human 
sexuality, AIDS prevention, smoking, and nutrition; the 
program now reaches over 35,000 students.
<p>
<b>Stimulating Innovation, Experimentation, Exchanges</b><br>
The Cultural Program was restructured to place more emphasis 
on modernizing cultural infrastructures and training 
regional cultural workers. The foundation established a new 
Performing Arts Program to stimulate innovation, 
experimentation, and international exchanges. A new Open 
Society House was opened as a focal point for cultural and 
civil society events that promote open society. 
<p>
Through an open competition, the Law Program launched a 
project for the authorship of new, university-level legal 
textbooks. An Open Society Law Library, which opened in 
February 1995, provided the legal and academic community 
with a collection of Western legal works and periodicals. 
The Media Program established a new OSFL Journalism Center 
to provide in-service training for working journalists and 
media managers through courses and seminars in ethics, 
investigative journalism, public relations, media 
management, and computer applications. 
<p>
The Credit Union Project of the Business and Economics 
Program (cofunded by the Canadian Government) helped 
introduce new credit union legislation and created 
operating, accounting, and staff training systems. A number 
of credit unions will begin operating in 1996.
<p>
The Publishing Program continued to produce translations 
into Lithuanian of important works in political science, 
philosophy, history, and culture. Since its inception in 
1992, the program has helped publish 54 books, many of which 
are used as university textbooks. Another 60 titles are in 
preparation.
<p>
The 
<a href="/internet.html"><b>Internet Program</b></a> 
opened a community-oriented Dial-up 
Center in August 1995, offering free e-mail connections to 
noncommercial users. The strategy is to make Internet and e-
mail accessible to many new users, both individual and 
institutional, as a new avenue for building open society. 
The Internet Center provides technical assistance, training, 
and access to the Internet and offers new opportunities for 
civil society projects.
<p>
The board of directors and the foundation staff are taking 
into account the serious difficulties that the Lithuanian 
society is experiencing during this period of increasing 
disillusionment with the process of transition. We are 
committed to regularly reviewing the foundation's priorities
in order to better respond to the changing needs of the 
country, the society, and its institutions.
<p>
<i>Vytas Gruodis, Executive Director</i>
<hr>                                                                       
