Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF Lithuania - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Fund - Lithuania<br>About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

In March of 1990, Lithuania's first democratically elected parliament of the post-World War II era declared the re-establishment of the country's independence, which had been lost through forced annexation by the Soviet Union in 1940. The declaration of independence was followed by a year and a half of threats, intimidation, economic blockade, and violence by the Soviet Union on a population whose peaceful struggle for freedom was often called by Westerners the "singing revolution." Only after the Moscow putsch of August 1991 was Lithuania's independence recognized by the nations of the world. The last Russian troops left Lithuania in August 1993.<p>

The Soviets left behind a distorted and unbalanced economy, ecological problems, and, above all, deep social, moral, and psychological wounds in society. Even before international recognition of independence and the withdrawal of Russian troops, the country embarked on an energetic path of reform in education, economics, administrative structures, and social services. Lack of experience and the absence of a tried and proven formula for transforming a post-Soviet society made this reform process more difficult than anyone expected.<p>

The process was made even more difficult by a dramatic deterioration of the economic situation, typical for post-Soviet economies. The loss of Eastern markets for industrial and agricultural production, inefficient plants, a work ethic suffering from the Soviet heritage, difficulties in adjusting to an emerging free market system, all contributed to a drastic decline in real incomes, inflation, unemployment, and social problems.<p>

Nevertheless, the political system is stable, and the country is firmly committed to economic and social reform. Education and law reform are progressing. Independent media, especially the privately owned press and radio, are engaged in a vigorous competition and enjoy freedom of the press. Ethnic minorities represent only 20 percent of Lithuania's population, and minority relations are relatively problem-free. Privatization is well advanced, inflation is kept under control, the national currency is stable, and exports to the West are rising.<p>

Unfortunately, the vast majority of the population is still living under adverse economic conditions. Because of the economic slowdown and an inefficient tax system, the state budget is unable to provide sufficient funding for an adequate social safety net and for educational, social, cultural, and scientific institutions.
<hr>
