<html><head><title>                                                             
SFOS - Romania - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Soros Foundation for an Open Society - Romania<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 

1995 marked the fifth anniversary of the Soros Foundation 
for an Open Society. As an occasion for evaluating the past 
and planning 
for the future, the anniversary year resulted in 
organizational restructuring and a redefining of the 
foundation's strategy for accomplishing its mission. The 
process started with changes to the governing statutes of 
the foundation, incorporating new areas of activity recently 
developed by national and regional programs as well as a 
more complex and efficient managerial structure that would 
meet the demands of this increased activity. 
<p>
In 1995, responsibility for the overall management of the 
foundation was assumed by a management team that brought 
together the executive director, financial director, and the 
branch directors from Cluj, Timisoara, and Iasi. This was a 
successful experiment that increased the participation of 
representatives from all branches of the foundation in the 
overall decision-making process. 
<p>
After the restructuring, our next challenge was to redefine 
program and budget priorities. In its first five years, the 
foundation's strategy was simply to respond to requests from 
individuals and civic groups in the belief that support for 
nongovernmental initiatives strengthened civil society. 
<p>
In 1995, we decided it was time to take a more proactive 
role in establishing programs and goals on which to 
concentrate our resources and energies. Acknowledging that 
programs which aim at immediate and spectacular change can 
be unrealistic and the cause of much disappointment, we 
decided to focus on a few main areas of concern that offered 
the best possibility of stimulating long-term change and 
reaching as large a portion of the population as possible.
<p>
<b>Communication, Education, Civil Society</b><br>
In keeping with its more proactive stance, the foundation 
allotted most of its funding resources to the following 
three programs: communication, education, and civil society. 
We also supported, to a lesser degree, programs concerning 
culture and art, medical and health, and travel. 
<p>
By promoting access to information and communication, 
providing opportunities in education, and supporting the 
development of civil society, the foundation seeks to change 
the mentality of the past and at the same time to infuse 
society with new approaches based on critical thinking, 
pluralism, tolerance, and civic engagement.
<p>
In 1995, the foundation expanded its e-mail and Internet 
programs, providing the general public and specific 
institutions with greater access to information. Satellite 
antennas were installed in our offices in Bucharest, Cluj, 
Iasi, and Timisoara, establishing the technical basis for 
the development of e-mail connectivity in Romania. Now 
information about the foundation and its programs is 
available on the Internet at: 
<a href="http://www.soros.ro"><b>www.soros.ro</b></a> (national programs and Bucharest)
<a href="http://www.soroscj.ro"><b>www.soroscj.ro</b></a> (Cluj); 
<a href="http://www.sorosis.ro"><b>www.sorosis.ro</b></a> (Iasi); 
<a href="http://www.sorostm.ro"><b>www.sorostm.ro</b></a> (Timisoara). 
These home pages present general program information, a directory 
of the foundation's branch offices, an impact study on the 
foundation's five years of activity, the results of a Public 
Opinion Barometer program (public opinion polls), the e-mail 
addresses of our computer centers (one of the most 
successful programs of the foundation), and InfoSoros (the 
foundation's newsletter).
<p>
The Public Opinion Barometer surveys a representative sample 
of the population on a variety of issues from views on 
current living standards to expectations for the future, 
from opinions on government policies to perceptions about 
individual politicians. Widely disseminated, this data has 
attracted the attention of ordinary citizens and 
politicians alike.
<p>
The 
<a href="/osimedia.html"><b>Media Program</b></a> 
supports numerous projects aimed at 
improving reporting and access to information. The BBC 
School of Radio and Television in Bucharest, for example, 
trains broadcast journalists in the principles and practical 
skills of their profession, using recording and studio 
equipment purchased with support from the foundation. The 
Young Journalists Foundation organizes workshops and 
seminars and provides a strong voice for young working 
journalists who represent the media's future.
<p>
In the field of education reform, the foundation has teamed 
up with the Romanian Ministry of Education and other 
international organizations to provide a wider range of 
textbooks for teachers and students. The foundation has 
provided a computer science lab in at least one high school 
in each of Romania's 40 counties.
<p>
<i>Anca-Maria Harasim, Executive Director</i>
