<html><head><title>                                                             
SFOS Romania - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Soros Foundation for an Open Society - Romania - About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

Among Eastern European countries under communism, except perhaps for Albania, Romania had the most centralized and nationalized economic regime, the longest and most severe political repression, and the greatest restriction on freedom of expression. Alternative political forces were nonexistent. The communist party recruited 4.5 million members, approximately 50 percent of the active labor force. The economy was strictly centralized with few external connections and a low level of modernization. The living standard was among the lowest in Europe.<p>

The process of opening Romanian society is longer and much harder than it seemed in 1989. Political changes in the country have not resulted in significant economic changes, except for free initiative in trading. The future of Romania, either as an open and competitive society or a quasi-closed society lacking economic power, is still to be decided.<p>
<hr>
