<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
IRF - Ukraine - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
International Renaissance Foundation - Ukraine<br>Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
The priorities of the International Renaissance Foundation 
(IRF), 
redefined in 1995, are to foster the transformation of 
education, facilitate the development of civil society, and 
support economic reform and cultural initiatives. To promote 
the idea of an open society, the foundation established an 
Open Society Radio program, which is broadcast twice a month 
over the National Radio Network. We also began publishing 
monthly bulletins highlighting the work of organizations 
supported by 
<a href="/gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a> 
in Ukraine.
<p>
<b>Civil Society</b><br>
The foundation increased its efforts to promote the 
development of civil society with support for NGOs, economic 
education, training demobilized military personnel for 
civilian life, media, and youth. The NGO Program funded 75 
projects and provided financial support for the creation of 
resource centers for NGOs in Kyiv, Kharkiv, Lviv, and the 
Donetsk region. The Economic Education Program supported 72 
projects, including a contest for the best press coverage of 
economic reform in Ukraine, which resulted in 22 newspapers 
receiving grants.
<p>
The Retraining of the Military Program assisted 26,143 
servicemen, as well as members of their families. More than 
18,000 were retrained, and 7,857 found employment. With IRF 
assistance, former officers established new credit 
associations, investment funds, consulting firms, consumer 
societies, and industrial, service, and agricultural 
enterprises.
<p>
In 1995, the Mass Media Program facilitated the development 
of freedom of the press in Ukraine with support for both 
national newspapers such as <i>Narodna Hazeta</i>, <i>News From 
Ukraine</i> (Kyiv) and regional publications such as <i>Kamyaniy 
Brid</i> (Luhansk) and <i>Rodaen Krai</i> (Odessa). Support also went 
to nonstate television stations, e.g., the Nova Mova 
association.
<p>
The 
<a href="/youth.html"><b>Youth Program</b></a> 
supported 142 projects, including the 
establishment of a youth initiative servicing center, Hurt 
(Kyiv), which provides information and consulting services 
to youth organizations. The Women in Society Program 
established a women's civil rights center in Kyiv to 
stimulate cooperative efforts among female jurists and 
lawyers to insure legal and social protection for women.
<p>
<b>Education and Science</b><br>
The three-year-old Transformation of the Humanities Program, 
jointly launched by the IRF and the Ministry of Education of 
Ukraine, published 16 textbooks during 1995. The books, 
which attracted the attention of public education 
organizations and private publishers alike, were 
successfully tested in schools and institutions of higher 
learning.
<p>
The 
<a href="/issep.html"><b>International Soros Science and Education Program</b></a> 
has 
gained broad acclaim among educators and scholars in 
Ukraine. Twenty-one of the most distinguished Ukrainian 
scholars have received Soros Emeritus Professor grants. 
Based on the results of contests held in 1995, the 
foundation will award grants to 75 Soros Professors, 120 
Soros Assistant Professors, around 400 Soros Teachers, 140 
Soros Postgraduate Fellows, and over 350 Soros Students.
<p>
With the help of the Modern School Program, more than 600 
Ukrainian teachers learned new approaches to teaching. The 
<a href="/hesp.html"><b>Higher Education Support Program</b></a> 
provided funding for the 
publication of a handbook on Institutions of Higher 
Education in Ukraine. Computer classes were set up in Kyiv 
National University, Lviv University, and Kharkiv 
Polytechnical University. Through the Foreign Language Study 
Program, 31 students, postgraduates, and lecturers received 
grants for studying abroad. In 1995, 37 Ukrainian students 
were enrolled at the 
<a href="/ceu.html"><b>Central European University</b></a>, 
and 168 
applicants received grants for paying standard entrance exam 
fees.
<p>
The regional 
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step</b></a> 
preschool program, a comprehensive 
education and development program for children, is being 
tested in 20 kindergartens in Ukraine. Five hundred 
preschool educators received professional training through 
this program.
<p>
<b>Cultural Initiatives</b><br>
In 1995, with the support of the Open Society Institute, the 
IRF launched a new regional program, Cultural Ties, which 
will assist in the organization of international cultural 
events, such as festivals, conferences, competitions, and 
master classes, sponsored by the national foundation 
network.
<p>
Altogether, the foundation supported 107 cultural projects, 
including internship training for Ukrainian cultural 
workers, the establishment of cultural and artistic centers 
and information networks, and the publication of literature. 
In April 1995, the Open Library Program was launched to 
implement advanced library technologies, to help in 
completing book collections for the main libraries of 
Ukraine, and to exchange information and experiences. 
<p>
<i>Bohdan Budzan, Executive Director</i>
