<html><head><title>                                                             
Fund for an Open Society - Yugoslavia - Report from President
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Fund for an Open Society - Yugoslavia<br>A Report from the President of the Board
</h1></td>
</table> 
After a media campaign against the foundation in early 1994 
faded away, we not only continued but expanded our work. We 
believed our report of activities for 1995 would be similar 
to the reports of the other national foundations within the 
network. Unfortunately, this did not turn out to be the 
case. During March and April 1995, the foundation was faced 
with a new, much stronger campaign by the official media 
against 
<a href="/gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a> 
and the foundation itself. Once again, 
we received strong support from different institutions and 
individuals.
<p>
This show of support, however, which could have been a 
source of genuine satisfaction for everyone connected with 
the foundation, turned out to be an additional disadvantage 
in the foundation's relations with the powers that be. 
Following further attacks against the foundation, the 
Ministry of Culture of Serbia made a decision to revoke our 
registration. We appealed to the Supreme Court of Serbia 
while continuing our program activities. In February 1996, 
the Supreme Court upheld the revocation of the registration, 
and the foundation's activities had to be halted. After an 
internationally 
supported appeal, the foundation was allowed to reregister 
in June 
of  1996.
<p>
The foundation's activities in 1995 went far beyond our 
expectations. The combination of the media campaign against 
the foundation, the continuation of all our programs, and 
the announcement in September of a special, multimillion 
dollar program for refugee children in the former Yugoslavia 
made the foundation better known and respected than ever 
before.
<p>
Just two weeks before the beginning of the 1995 campaign 
against the foundation, we announced our programs in the 
country's major media outlets, asking publicly for proposals 
for the first time. We wanted the work of the foundation to 
become even more transparent, and to give virtually every 
institution, association, and individual in the country a 
chance to submit their ideas.
<p>
Some members of the foundation's board felt this request for 
proposals was one of the immediate reasons for the campaign 
against us. But it also resulted in an unexpected response: 
while the anti-foundation campaign was at its peak (in two 
months more than 400 attacks against the foundation were 
published or broadcast), we received over 1,200 proposals 
and applications. Although there was no doubt all these 
programs needed support, we also understood that this 
response represented a kind of civic resistance.
<p>
Despite an extremely difficult economic situation and a 
general clampdown on civil society, 1995 was marked by a new 
wave of proposals from 22 local papers, 6 youth papers, and 
43 weeklies and monthlies as well as 8 electronic media. The 
amazing increase of independent local papers that became 
apparent from the number of applications we received proved 
that there was an immense need for an alternative to 
government-controlled media. Toward the end of December, 
representatives of a number of independent newspapers met in 
Kragujevac, where they agreed to create their own 
association. 
<p>
The local papers were inspired by the example of the 
Association of the Independent Electronic Media, which has 
become one of the most successful media networks in the 
region. We find it especially significant that a number of 
local minority-language print media will participate in the 
new association of independent papers. In the upcoming year, 
we will provide significant support to these two 
associations. Using the Internet, we hope to improve 
communication among different media and other institutions 
and increase their access to information, breaking the 
internal and external isolation of people in the fields of 
science, media, culture, and the arts.
<p>
The arts and culture program proved to be effective in 
preventing official structures from controlling cultural 
life. Two alternative cultural centers were established in 
Belgrade, one in Novi Sad, and we hope to create similar 
centers in Podgorica and Prishtine. The Soros Center for 
Contemporary Arts is the only resort for dozens of visual 
artists who would be forced to leave the country, or give up 
their work without the support of this institution. The 
SCCA's first annual exhibition provoked great interest, 
especially among young people, who are hungry for new 
challenges in cultural and artistic expression. In the 
upcoming year, the foundation intends to concentrate even 
more on strengthening these alternative initiatives, since 
they are extremely important in maintaining the spirit of 
open society.
<p>
<i>Sonja Licht, President of the Board</i>
