<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF - Albania - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Foundation - Albania<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
The Open Society Foundation for Albania (OSFA) assists the 
democratic process in Albania by helping to create a strong 
civil society. 
The foundation's 11 program boards, made up of some of the 
country's most respected professionals, collaborate with 
foreign experts to design projects that meet the urgent 
needs of the country. Foundation initiatives such as the 
Media Training Center, Legal Documentation Center, Women's
Center, Youth Center, and the Albanian Research Center for 
Health were all created with the intention that they 
eventually become independent organizations.
<p>
In 1995, education remained the OSFA's major area of focus. 
We supported preschool, primary, secondary school, and 
university programs in Albania and provided graduate and 
postgraduate study opportunities abroad. The regional Step-
by-Step program introduced participatory preschool 
activities at five schools. The multiyear $9 million 
<a href="/aedp.html"><b>Albanian Educational Development Project (AEDP)</b></a>,
developed in conjunction with the 
<a href="/osibuda.html"><b>Open Society Institute - Budapest</b></a>
and 
the Albanian government, continued to fund curriculum 
development, community development, and school 
reconstruction for Albania's primary and secondary school 
system.
<p>
Through the 
<a href="/hesp.html"><b>Higher Education Support Program</b></a>, 
OSFA provided 
assistance for humanities and social science programs at the 
university level. This support included funding for the 
translation and publication of textbooks, staff training, 
and limited equipment purchases. In addition, OSFA 
established a student advising center and initiated a 
project to publish a guide to higher education in Albania.
<p>
In 1995, our Library Program focused on the training of 
librarians, book collection development, assistance to the 
Albanian Library Association, and the establishment of 
Albania's first open reading rooms. The program's objective
is to make increased amounts of information available to the 
general public and to provide free access to libraries. The 
foundation also supported book publishing, mainly through 
Books for an Open Society, the long-term goal of which is to 
translate and publish about 40 titles in subject areas 
ranging from economics to social anthropology. 
<p>
The foundation's Youth Program funded a book of stories and 
essays by young authors, high school cultural activities, 
youth newspapers, and debate contests. The High School 
Athletics Program, which engages some 1,500 boys and girls 
in sports, is a model program that the foundation hopes will 
be adopted by the Albanian Ministry of Education.
<p>
The foundation's Arts and Culture Program, which initially 
worked with the Academy of Arts to support the visual and 
performing arts, expanded its mandate in 1995 to assist 
cultural projects by other artists and institutions, 
particularly independent initiatives that promote cultural 
pluralism.
<p>
During 1995, the foundation supported Albanian Roma 
organizations, such as the <i>Amaro Dives</i> newsletter, and the 
teaching of the Roma 
language to Albanian Roma. The Health Program promoted 
public health, including alcohol and drug abuse prevention, 
and funded 
programs to help integrate the handicapped into society. 
<p>
The Legal Documentation Resource Center aided Albania's 
legislative process by making available international 
documents pertaining to issues such as electronic media, 
medical ethics, and environment protection. The center also 
published commentaries on the penal and procedural codes, 
and organized workshops on economic crime, medical ethics 
and law, and bankruptcy. The center gave support to 
associations of lawyers and for the creation of database 
systems in the courts, and it issued the first independent 
legal magazine in Albanian history.
<p>
The Media Program, one of the most ambitious of OSFA's
programs, dramatically increased its cooperation with 
international organizations. Currently, through joint 
funding, Albanian journalists are trained at the BBC, 
Deutsche Welle, and Reuters. The foundation has also 
organized programs with Article XIX, the Committee to 
Protect Journalists, USAID, VOA Europe, etc. Also, training 
and support for high school newsletters and university 
newspapers remain a major focus area. One of the most 
notable achievements of the year was the joint effort with 
<a href="/colpi.html"><b>COLPI</b></a> 
and Article XIX in assisting with the drafting of 
Albania's new Electronic Media Law.
<p>
<i>Avni Mustafaj, Executive Director</i>
