<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF Albania - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Foundation - Albania<br>About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

Albania is a typical post-communist society in which a dying system of values is being replaced by a new system of values through an intermediate process of continual reevaluation. The transition to a civil society with individual freedoms and a market economy faces huge, sometimes unpredictable difficulties due to the hard economic situation of the country, the lack of a developed democratic tradition, the backwardness of the political class, and unstable relations with neighboring countries.<p>

According to official data, production increased 8.1 percent during 1994. The privatization of land reactivated agricultural production while most industrial enterprises closed. The country's deteriorating infrastructure caused considerable hardship. Most towns had water for only two or three hours after midnight. During winter the towns and villages, which are inhabited by more than 60 percent of the country's population, were invaded by darkness because of a lack of electricity. The streets and schools were in very bad shape, and the telecommunications network was even worse.<p>

The political life of the country is characterized by a continuous tension between the party in power and the opposition. The defeat of the new constitution in a referendum on November 6th is a clear indicator that people are disillusioned with the methods of governing.<p>

One of the most important roles in opening up Albanian society is being played by media, which are becoming powerful supporters of civil society. More than 20 newspapers are published in Tirana, including seven dailies of more than 100,000 circulation. The Albanian press is dominated by the political parties while the state has a monopoly over television. Public information is limited by the lack of a distribution network in the villages, the state's information embargo, and the absence of independent centers of research and opinion.<p>

Legislative reform in Albania has replaced more than 80 percent of the old communist laws. In 1994, the legislature passed a new penal code and finalized a law on the education of minorities, bringing the issue into conformity with international standards. However, violations of human rights, including the use of violence by police and harsh conditions in prisons, remain a problem, exacerbated by the lack of an independent judiciary.
<hr>
