<head>                                                         
<title> Albanian Education Development Project                 
</title>                                                       
</head>                                                        
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">                                        
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                 
<tr>                                                           
<td valign=top><img align=middle src=logo.gif alt=#></td>      
<td><h1>                                                       
Albania Education Development Project
</h1></td>                                                     
</table>                                                       
<a name="top">
<center>
<b>
| <a href="#about">About the Project</a> | 
<a href="#links">Related Links</a> |
</b>
</center>

<a name="about">
<h2>
About the Project
</h2>
The 
<a href="albania.html"><b>Soros Foundation - Albania</b></a>,
with support from 
<a href="osibuda.html"><b>Open Society Institute - Budapest</b></a> 
launched the Albanian Education Development Project (AEDP)
in l994 with an initial multiyear commitment of $9 million.  AEDP
developed during l995 into one of the foundation networks 
major initiatives in educational change at the school level. 
Operating in Europes poorest country and within a society 
deeply affected by the regime of the past, the AEDPs 
programs have had to be both wide-ranging and targeted to 
fundamental, sustainable change in classroom conditions and 
childrens learning. Activities encompass three Cs
construction, curriculum, and community development linked 
to schools.
<p>
During l995, the AEDP completed emergency repairs and 
classroom refurbishment in approximately 50 schools, which 
provided basic access and a better learning environment for 
more than 20,000 children, as well as income-generating 
opportunities for Albanias emerging private industry. 
Facilities rehabilitation also served as an important base 
and catalyst for AEDPs other education and community-based 
activities. In cooperation with the Albanian Ministry of 
Education, World Bank, UNICEF, numerous bilateral donors, 
and others, AEDP helped facilitate nationwide curriculum and 
teaching reform through extensive training and program and 
materials development. A highly successful distance 
education program for teachers of history,  geography, 
English, and French was developed by AEDP and  broadcast 
countrywide as a cost-effective way to reach unqualified 
teachers and those in Albanias remote and mountainous rural 
areas.  AEDP, in partnership with the Catholic Relief 
Services, organized numerous programs to stimulate bottom-
up educational improvement led by Albanian teachers, 
parents, community and business leaders, and students 
themselves. Cofunding of AEDP activities by a wide variety 
of local and external donors during l995 is estimated at 
more than $1 million.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src=go_up_bt.gif alt=top></a>

