<html><head><title>                                                             
SF - Belarus - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Belarusian Soros Foundation -<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
The Belarusian Soros Foundation (BSF) strives to address the 
growing needs, trends, and upheavals occurring in 
contemporary Belarus. The foundation has become the unifying 
force for both domestic and foreign organizations supporting 
the development of an open society in Belarus. Its strategy 
is to assist individuals and groups that conceive and 
implement innovative initiatives in education, independent 
media, and civil society.
<p>
Economic collapse has affected the lives of almost every 
Belarusian, and the country is controlled by an 
authoritarian administration. Unfortunately, most 
international agencies and foundations (as well as the 
media) are neither equipped to work long-term in Belarus nor 
particularly enthusiastic about doing so.
<p>
In recognition of the need to expand its activities to more 
segments of the population, the foundation organized 
national competitions to select grantees for programs in 
education, arts, culture, economic reform, mass media, and 
other areas. These competitions have already had an enormous 
positive impact on individuals and institutions previously 
not directly affected by BSF's grantmaking activities. By 
using the grant competition model, the foundation has 
resolved many of its earlier internal problems. The 
competitions as well as the existing 
<a href="/osibuda.html"><b>Open Society Institute - Budapest</b></a>
and 
<a href="/osiny.html"><b>Open Society Institute - New York</b></a>
regional programs have generated much interest, support, and public 
debate concerning the foundation's work.
<p>
In each program category, experts from throughout Belarus 
were selected to assist the foundation in creating 
competitions that would promote the development of new 
methods to address critical issues in the republic. In order 
to attract the greatest number of applicants from all 
sections of the population, the competitions were announced 
via mass media throughout the republic. Expert jurors 
selected the projects which they considered to have the 
strongest long-term positive impact on the republic and 
recommended them for funding to the BSF advisory board. In 
total, BSF conducted over 26 competitions for funding in 
1995. Thousands of proposals were received, and hundreds 
were supported.
<p>
The national competitions in the areas of arts, culture, and 
mass media were the most successful. The competitions in 
arts and culture helped unify the resources of Belarusian 
intellectuals, helping them to persevere in their endeavors. 
The foundation's mass media competition, which was both 
timely and necessary, generated much controversy due to the 
government's efforts to eliminate the independent press. 
<p>
Given that funding has only recently been awarded via the 
competitions in medicine and ecology, it is difficult to 
assess their impact. However, both of these fields, which 
have had too little attention in the past, received an 
overwhelming number of proposals. BSF's
competitions in economic reform, youth programs, and 
education address areas of endeavor which are also essential 
to the establishment of open society.
<p>
<i>Peter Byrne, Executive Director</i>
