<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF - Bosnia and Herzegovina - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Fund - Bosnia and Herzegovina<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
During 1993 and 1994, all of the activities of the Open 
Society Fund - Bosnia and Herzegovina (OSF-BH) could be 
considered humanitarian aid of one sort or another-
assistance designed to help people survive the war. In 1995, 
with the Dayton peace accord, these efforts received less of 
our attention, and the foundation began to develop long-term 
programs in education, culture, independent media, and other 
fields. By the end of the year, the humanitarian aid 
programs were discontinued entirely. We hope we will never 
again have a need for such programs.
<p>
The most important undertaking during 1995 was the 
establishment of special-purpose institutions which 
conceive, implement, and coordinate a number of programs and 
projects in their specific fields. These include the Center 
for Management and Information Technology, the Media Center, 
and the Legal Center. The common objective of all of these 
centers is education and training aimed at developing 
relevant research and analysis and bringing Bosnia up to 
international professional standards.
<p>
The foundation's activities in 1995 were still limited only 
to the parts of Bosnia and Herzegovina accessible to its 
personnel. With the gradual cessation of war activities, it 
became possible to make a considerable step forward in 
supporting projects outside of Sarajevo, as the OSF-BH did 
in the Zenica, Tuzla, and Mostar regions. Also, during the 
severest blockade of Bihac, the foundation managed to 
deliver considerable quantities of food into the region, 
easing suffering there.
<p>
The war in Bosnia and Herzegovina has stopped, and we expect 
that 1996 will bring further positive changes. There is a 
fundamental need for a deep transformation of economic 
consciousness in our country. To help bring Bosnia into the 
mainstream of modern economics, we started the Management 
and Information Technology Center to educate economists.
<p>
<b>Covering Sensitive Issues in Free Bosnia</b><br>
The Media Center was established to increase professionalism 
among journalists and to raise local standards to those of 
contemporary media in other countries. One of the center's
major undertakings was the revitalization of the periodical 
Slobodna Bosna (Free Bosnia), which covers even the most 
sensitive social and political issues. By establishing its 
Law Center - which collects and disseminates information on 
law and the legal profession - the foundation is helping to 
prepare lawyers for the new roles they will play in both the 
public and private sectors during the country's transition
to democracy.
<p>
The foundation continued to support education at the 
university level as well as at the elementary and high 
school levels. In 1995, the Soros School of English was 
established while the previously instituted Computer School 
extended the scope of its work. In the field of culture, we 
supported a special project entitled "A Month of BH Culture
in the Czech Republic" and the Sarajevo Film Festival, as 
well as activities to improve the quality of teaching at art 
academies.
<p>
In 1995, we discovered that the many projects we implemented 
during the war had provided valuable lessons for peacetime. 
At the time of their creation, many of our programs 
represented efforts to maintain at least some semblance of 
civilized life in the face of the apocalyptic impact of war. 
These "pilot projects" demonstrated that we could make 
significant accomplishments in adverse circumstances, and 
encouraged us to continue our activities as conditions grew 
more favorable. Due to its success in implementing programs, 
the foundation has developed a solid reputation among the 
general public as well as among representatives of 
governmental and nongovernmental organizations.
<p>
We are aware, of course, that peace brings its own problems. 
In that respect, in 1996 the foundation plans to initiate 
programs for the social groups that were particularly 
threatened and deprived by the war. 
The foundation's presence in the parts of Bosnia and 
Herzegovina thus far inaccessible will certainly require new 
approaches. The time has come to start some serious thinking 
about these matters.
<p>
If the Dayton accord brings real peace and the beginning of 
a new era for Bosnia and Herzegovina, then we can state with 
confidence that the OSF-BH is ready-with regard to its
experience, personnel, reputation, and the results achieved 
so far-for new, positive developments, for the process of 
reintegration of this country into the regional and 
international communities. 
<p>
<i>Mirsad Purivatra, Executive Director</i>
<hr>                                                                       
