<DOCHDR>
http://server.soros.org:80/bosnia/bosncoun.html 204.168.83.130 19970112094624 text/html 3004
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 12 Jan 1997 09:40:22 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF Bosnia and Herzegovina - Open Society in a Time of War
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Fund - Bosnia and Herzegovina<br>Open Society in a Time of War
</h1></td>
</table> 

The year 1994 will be remembered in the history of Bosnia and Herzegovina as the third year of the aggression against the Bosnian people. The war and its horrors define the life and work of everyone in Bosnia.<p>

Now, realistically speaking, the true believers in open society in Bosnia and Herzegovina do not have strong arguments to make to the long-suffering people of the country who face extermination precisely because of their tolerance. To whom can they appeal? To whom in the world of the powerful can they point as a positive example? The only lesson Bosnians have gained in their dealings with world powers is that force is all that counts.<p>

It is difficult to uphold the most important values of an open society in the midst of a war when most people can think only about survival. It is certain that due to the inevitable militarism of the society, the space for democracy has narrowed. Nevertheless, the local government has continued to support the work of certain democratic institutions within the political system and even tried to reform the economy within the limitations of a country in a state of war.<p>

A number of factors influenced the situation in Bosnia during 1994. The Washington Agreement establishing a federation between the Croat and Bosnian people halted military conflicts while opening roads and telecommunications between the two countries. The growth of the Bosnian army into a respectable force stalled the military drives of the opposing Serbs. Experts and especially young people, however, continued to leave the country. The collapse of the UN mission represented the collapse of international policy on Bosnia and a betrayal of basic principles of democracy, pluralism, and multiculturism.
<hr>
