<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
OSI - Croatia - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Institute - Croatia<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
In 1995, the political situation in Croatia developed 
rapidly from one dominated by frustrated feelings of defeat 
and loss to one informed by the sudden restoration of 
Western Slavonia and the region around Knin. These events 
were followed by the disastrous revelation that almost all 
the Serbian population had fled those regions. Finally, we 
sadly witnessed instances of private revenge. Nevertheless, 
the Dayton peace agreement opened processes of normalization 
within Croatia and increased the demands of opposition 
parties, institutions, workers, intellectuals, students, and 
scholars for the restoration of civic values and greater 
transparency in public life. 
<p>
The Open Society Institute - Croatia began to find partners 
for its programs which promote democracy and a civil society 
built on freedom of speech, education, and communication, 
international openness, defense of human rights, and the 
rule of law. Programs in education, English and French 
teaching, library support, social sciences and humanities 
research, law, publishing, e-mail and Internet, cultural 
journals and independent media, conferences and travel, 
medical support, civil society, and social welfare sought to 
enhance or to preserve the principles and practices of open 
society throughout Croatia, in cities as well as smaller 
towns.
<p>
<b>A Platform for Promoting Open Journalism</b><br>
The Independent Media Program helped support the continued 
existence of a number of influential weeklies in spite of 
the antagonistic attitude of the government toward them. The 
presence and relevance of the Feral Tribune (Split), Vijenac 
and Arkzin (Zagreb), and Bumerang (Osijek) in their local, 
all-Croatian, or specific intellectual environments is 
constant and recognized. In addition, the ever-increasing 
informational influence of Novi List (Rijeka) presents a 
good platform for promoting open journalism. The 
foundation's partners in supporting alternative media 
include the European Union, European Council, the 
Westminister Foundation for Democracy, and The Press Now 
(Netherlands).  
<p>
The foundation's potentially very successful education 
programs-which seek to introduce new teaching methodology to 
preschools, 
primary schools, and high schools-were hindered 
unnecessarily due to the constant suspicions of the Ministry 
of Education and its excessive restrictions on their 
development. Programs such as Health Education for Teachers, 
which does not require official approval 
from the ministry, have succeeded in finding a welcome 
reception among participants.
<p>
The University Support Program provided assistance to 
individual scholars working on research projects, but, due 
to the resistance of the government, the foundation was not 
able to offer direct support to Croatian universities.
<p>
The Croatian Legal Center, which opened in September, 
quickly delivered its message to the public: Croatia can be 
a democratic country only if it recognizes the rule of law, 
including equal rights for all citizens. The center provides 
human rights counseling, monitors judicial proceedings for 
violations of rights, and engages in research and the 
dissemination of information on legal and legislative 
issues. The E-mail/Internet Program, which offers training 
courses and equipment grants, seeks to put more and more 
individual and institutional users onto computer networks. 
<p>
OSI-Croatia supported a well-structured cultural program, 
enhancing the musical education and performance capabilities 
of young, talented artists as well as providing instruments 
essential for high-class performances; supporting 
contemporary artists and art documentation activities 
through the Soros Center for Contemporary Arts; caring for 
aesthetic standards, for cultural heritage as a historical 
statement and obligation, and for theater, film, and drama 
as a stage for social sensitivity and sensibility.
<p>
We hope that the foundation will be able to continue these 
programs for some time in the future, aiding the evolution 
of open society in Croatia. The primary role of the 
foundation should vanish as its programs succeed, or it 
should change with future projects. At this moment, it is 
still a long road ahead of us.
<p>
<i>Karmen Basic, Executive Director</i>
<hr>                                                                       
