<html><head><title>                                                             
OSI Croatia - Country Background
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Institute - Croatia<br>Country Background
</h1></td>
</table> 

Since 1991, the war has shifted priorities from the democratization of society to a defense of national identities present in the collective memory since the beginning of the emancipation struggles at the turn of the century. For the past four years, life in Croatia has been characterized by the sudden impoverishment of the country by the destruction of war, the presence of hundreds of thousands of displaced people and refugees from Bosnia and Herzegovina, a disabled transportation system due to occupied territories, and, as a consequence, the reconfiguration of society and simplification of internal communications to basic questions about the state, national defense, and the populist politics of the ruling party.<p>

People reacted to these pressures in different ways. Some gave in to the new political convictions, some became homeless and traumatized, while others tried to continue the democratization of society that began in the 1980s.
<hr>
