<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF - Prague - From the Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Fund - Prague<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
Since 1992, the Open Society Fund - Prague has focused on the 
building of civil society, the development of education and 
culture, and the promotion of intellectual cooperation among 
Central and Eastern European countries. Our strategy is to 
target areas neglected by the government and other official 
structures. In 1995, OSF-Prague established three new civil 
society programs to provide support and training for 
community-based organizations that develop activities 
responsive to local needs. The long-term goal is to create a 
network of active, self-sustainable grassroots organizations 
that share successful programs and experiences with each 
other.
<p>
The Civic Education Through Czech Language Courses seek to 
provide the rising number of immigrants and refugees in the 
Czech Republic with basic information about the legal and 
social systems, human rights, Czech history, and Czech 
language training. In 1996, we plan to offer high school and 
university scholarships to refugees to help them integrate 
into Czech society. Another education program in 1995, the 
<a href="/hesp.html"><b>Higher Education Support Program</b></a>, 
promoted the advancement 
of higher education in the social sciences and humanities. 
The foundation also supported several promising projects in 
the areas of postgraduate education, distance learning, and 
teacher training.
<p>
Our long-term goal in education is to develop alternative 
methods of basic and secondary school education by 
identifying and supporting already existing initiatives, 
implementing new ones, and encouraging different forms of 
teacher training. More support will be provided in 1996 to 
educational cooperation with Central and Eastern European 
countries by supporting student exchanges and other forms of 
student mobility in the region.
<p>
<a href="/youth.html"><b>The Youth Program</b></a> 
helped to encourage open thinking, 
responsibility, and other qualities indispensable for an 
open, civil society among young people. One of the most 
successful activities was a training program for young, 
aspiring journalists, which we hope to develop further in 
1996. The foundation will also introduce a new program to 
provide support to organizations that assist young people 
who are particularly vulnerable due to their economic or 
minority status. 
<p>
In 1995, the foundation's Roma Program provided support to 
talented Roma students by offering them stipends for high 
school and university studies. The foundation funded a range 
of projects and training programs in culture and education 
with the aim of improving the situation of the Roma 
community as well as the majority population's perception of
the Roma. In cooperation with the Soros Roma Foundation and 
local partners, the foundation offered legal counseling to 
Roma experiencing problems with citizenship. 
<p>
Throughout 1995, OSF-Prague increased its efforts to find 
the best and most relevant partners for existing and future 
activities, to raise public awareness of open society, and 
to create a supportive environment for the foundation's 
work.
<p>
<i>Marie Kopecka, Executive Director</i>
