<DOCHDR>
http://server.soros.org:80/czech/czeccoun.html 204.168.83.130 19970112094835 text/html 2320
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 12 Jan 1997 09:42:33 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF Prague - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Fund - Prague<br>About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

Since the fall of communism in 1989, the Czech Republic has established basic democratic structures, including reintroduction of free elections on both national and local levels, the adoption of important economic legislation, and procedures for privatization. Macroeconomic statistics show promising results, but the price for most of this economic success is being paid by the neediest members of Czech society. Economic reform itself tends to be the only interest of the government, which leads to the neglect of other crucial fields such as education and the environment.<p>

In the Czech Republic, as elsewhere in the post-communist region, society still finds it difficult to cope with an increase in various forms of racial, ethnic, and political intolerance. The public in general does not understand or fully accept values such as democracy, spiritual, political, and economic plurality, social and economic justice, social responsibility, the widespread participation of citizens in public life, and limits on the prerogatives of the state versus the rights of ethnic, religious, and other minorities.
<hr>
