<DOCHDR>
http://server.soros.org:80/latvia/latvfoun.html 204.168.83.130 19970112094856 text/html 5802
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 12 Jan 1997 09:42:53 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
SF Latvia - Report From Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Soros Foundation - Latvia<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 

You begin, in the early spring of 1992, with no office, no 
telephone, no board of directors, and only a skeleton staff, 
in a country where the structures of statehood are barely 
six months old. You have only the trust that has been placed 
in you to give form to one man's vision.
<p>
Almost four years later, you would like to believe that the 
form-a thing now called the Soros Foundation-Latvia, with a
definite structure and established reputation-has managed 
both to make a difference in Latvia and to retain the 
initial enthusiasm and vision of its early days. 
<p>
Looking back over the past year, I recall several moments 
which stand out, tangible milestones which seem to give 
credence to the belief that, yes, the foundation has made a 
difference. One such moment was the Soros Foundation-Latvia 
Town Forum in April 1995, where 20 of the foundation's young 
scholarship students debated for two hours, in English, with 
<a href="/gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a>, 
the Prime Minister of Latvia, and two of 
Latvia's leading politicians. Not the most accommodating 
company, yet one left the debate with the distinct 
impression that the students had more than held their own, 
and that these new members of Latvian society will be 
Latvia's best guarantee of open society: erudite, involved, 
audacious, and probing; respectful and tolerant, yet not 
submissive. These future citizens and voters of Latvia will 
be difficult to manipulate, to cajole, or to buy with empty 
promises.
<p>
At such times, the foundation's focus on education as its 
number one priority seems more than justified, especially 
when this supposedly long-term investment ends up reaping 
visible returns in such a short span of time. 
<p>
Another conspicuous sign of the foundation's impact on
Latvian society came in distinctly provocative and concrete 
forms: here a five-star merry-go-round where Lenin's statue 
used to stand, here a vertically upright tramway car at a 
major Riga intersection, there a mythical Latvian folk 
hero's hat of gigantic proportions floating down the Daugava 
river. These were just a few of the artworks and 
installations exhibited at the SCCA-Riga's open air 
exhibition entitled "Monument," also supported by the 
foundation. These works were the outward manifestation of 
that which is "different," "provocative," "non-standard,"
and "incomprehensible" in Latvian society.
<p>
The exhibition served as a litmus test of the level of 
tolerance for the "other" which Latvian society has or has 
not achieved. In this case, the test proved that the Soros 
Foundation-Latvia's vision of an open society was not yet 
fully realized. At first thought, this was discouraging; but 
on second thought, I found it encouraging to know how far we 
had come and to realize what work remained to be done.
<p>
Four years after independence, and four years into the life 
of the 
Soros Foundation-Latvia, it has become increasingly evident 
that the key problems of Latvian society are not systemic 
and structural. 
On the one hand, well-conceived reforms have been put into 
place. On the other hand, these structures both serve and 
are served by a populace that is divided along one clear 
line: those with the capacity for individual critical 
thinking who understand that the present and the future is 
their responsibility, and those who wish for nothing more 
than to bequeath this responsibility to the state, to a 
strong leader, to prophets bearing promises, or to the next 
generation. Our goal is to ensure that the former group take 
precedence over the latter in ever-increasing numbers.
<p>
In the coming years, we will continue to work toward this 
goal; we will continue to fight for our principles. Yet, at 
the same time, two new major challenges emerge as we grow 
and become more structured. First, we must be wary of the 
dangers of complacency. A foundation such as ours is poised 
at the fault lines of society. Old tremors subside, while 
new cracks emerge. We must continue to apply the wisdom that 
comes with experience, but at the same time not lose the 
inquisitiveness and flexibility of our early years as a 
foundation. Second, we must ensure that the principles we 
prescribe are ones that we also practice. We trust that we 
have been, and will continue to be, acutely aware of the 
fact that fighting for one's principles and living up to 
one's principles are two inseparable goals.
<p>
<i>Vita I. Matiss, Former Executive Director</i><br>
(In June 1996, Vita Matiss stepped down; Vita Terauda is the 
foundation's current executive director.)
<hr>
