<html><head><title>                                                             
SF Latvia - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Soros Foundation - Latvia<br>About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

The Republic of Latvia's development as a civil society is perhaps bestillustrated by its acceptance in February 1995 as a member of the Council of Europe. Throughout 1994 the government of Latvia put into place the elements of a democratic, Western society, and at the end of the year the country was democratically governed and with a robust, mostly open market. Latvia was on its way to a stable economy and enjoyed a free and independent press, and, in most respects, the rule of law.<p> 
 
A key accomplishment in 1994 was the long-awaited adoption of regulations governing naturalization of noncitizens. The process of naturalization has already begun, and the law has been deemed internationally acceptable by the Council of Europe and other multi-national organizations. Although several international investigations (by the United Nations, the OSCE, and others) have found no systematic discrimination against non-Latvians or noncitizens in the country, the population remains riven by linguistic, ethnic, and national differences. The Soros Foundation-Latvia helps to address these issues through the Center for Human Rights and Ethnic Studies, the Ethnic Entente Program, and specific grants aimed at greater ethnic and multinational understanding. All Soros Foundation-Latvia grant, scholarship, and other programs are advertised in Russian as well as in Latvian.
<hr>
