<html><head><title>                                                             
OSI - Macedonia - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Institute - Macedonia<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
In September 1994, I gave the title "Narrow Road, Third 
Step" to the introductory text explaining the foundation's 
program and budget for 1995. At that time, I could not 
imagine how dramatic this year would be, both for the 
Republic of Macedonia and the Open Society Institute-
Macedonia. It seemed that with the signing of the 
Macedonian-Greek Agreement, the Republic of Macedonia would 
finally be free from the threat of war and enter the 
international community as an independent state. However, 
the attempted assassination of President Gligorov in 
October, 1995, showed that danger for a democratic Macedonia 
still exists. 
<p>
During 1995, OSI-Macedonia was subjected to a fierce 
campaign instigated by media close to the president and his 
cabinet. Among other things, the foundation and 
<a href="/gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a> 
were accused of putting pressure on the Macedonian 
government to legalize the so-called Albanian University in 
Tetovo. Even explicit and repeated statements by Soros 
explaining that he does not support Tetovo University 
because he believes it could lead to the disintegration of 
Macedonia did not help to silence the campaign.
<p>
In 1995, the foundation made a significant change in program 
priorities, placing the highest emphasis on education, 
instead of humanitarian efforts and support for the media. 
The regional preschool program 
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step</b></a> 
grew from 18 
groups in 1994 to 218 groups in 1995, encompassing 40 
percent of all children in kindergarten. The Active Learning 
Project initiated new teaching methodologies in 11 primary 
schools. More than 40 secondary schools received computer 
equipment. Through these programs, OSI-Macedonia became a 
valued and visible player on the education scene in 
Macedonia. Its relations with the national education 
authorities are positive and invite a deeper involvement in 
the restructuring of the educational system. Our partners in 
the field of education include UNICEF, the British Council, 
USIS-Skopje, and CEPES-UNESCO.
<p>
<b>Linking Private Radio Stations</b><br>
The Media Program helped establish direct links among 10 
private radio stations, giving the state radio serious 
competition. The foundation was very active in the public 
debate over the new telecommunications laws, attempting to 
ensure that they encourage rather than hinder private 
electronic media. We initiated a media monitoring program 
with the European Media Institute-Dusseldorf and began 
publishing the <i>Macedonia Media Bulletin</i>. Foundation support 
for the purchase of a small rotary press by Europe 92, a 
private printing house, made possible the existence of 
several alternative newspapers, including <i>Delo</i> in the 
Macedonian language and <i>Koha</i> in the Albanian language. 
<i>Dnevnik (The Daily)</i>  began publishing in early 1996, 
supported by a grant and a no-interest loan from OSI-
Macedonia.
<p>
Our first experience with giving loans was a credit line for 
small farmers who previously had received technical support 
from VOCA (Volunteers in Overseas Cooperative Assistance). 
The credits, with a maximum value of $5,000, are being 
repaid on time, making us optimistic about credit projects.
<p>
The 
<a href="/copress.html"><b>Publishing</b></a> 
and 
<a href="/osiart.html"><b>Arts and Culture</b></a> 
Programs played 
important 
roles in 1995, supporting the multicultural wealth of 
Macedonia. Translations from the classic languages into 
Macedonian represented 
a significant contribution to overcoming the marginalized 
status of 
the Macedonian language. The publication of the tragedies of 
the ancient Greek authors Sophocles and Euripides also were 
important in beginning to break down the artificial barriers 
between Greece and Macedonia.
<p>
Support from the Soros Center for Contemporary Arts-Skopje
made it possible for visual artists to express their 
creative potential at individual and group exhibitions in 
Macedonia and abroad.
<p>
Through the 
<a href="/east.html"><b>East East Program</b></a>, 
the foundation supported a 
program on "Advanced Conflict Resolution: Training for
Trainers from Albania, Macedonia, and Yugoslavia." The 
foundation also funded NGOs working on human rights, ethnic 
conflicts, women's rights, and the protection of the 
environment.
<p>
OSI-Macedonia supported a wide range of programs in 1995, 
and, as a result, played a significant role in supporting 
democratic, civil, and peaceful options in Macedonia.
<p>
<i>Vladimir Milcin, Executive Director</i>
