<html><head><title>                                                             
SF - Moldova - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Soros Foundation - Moldova<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
Support for education remained the highest priority of the 
Soros Foundation-Moldova in 1995. While successfully 
developing a large range of regional programs (
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step,</b></a> 
<a href="/english.html"><b>English Language,</b></a> 
<a href="/youth.html#highschool"><b>Debate,</b></a> 
<a href="/youth.html#youth"><b>Youth,</b></a> 
<a href="/youth.html#health"><b>Health Education</b></a>
), the 
foundation also initiated its own programs to help 
universities by funding internships abroad, publishing new 
textbooks, supporting postgraduate students, and offering 
scholarships. 
<p>
In the field of secondary education, the foundation 
continued its computerization program as well as teacher 
training programs and other activities. As part of a 
comprehensive program of modernization of education, the 
foundation also established an information center and funded 
curriculum development efforts. To strengthen cooperation, 
the foundation's educational programs are now supervised by 
a single educational board.
<p>
The independent media was another strategic area supported 
by the foundation. We continued to support the Independent 
Journalism Center, which operates as an information source 
and training base for the independent media. Training 
programs at the center include Local Election Coverage, 
Management of Print Media, TV News, Business and Economic 
Reporting, Photojournalism, Government and Public Affairs 
Reporting, and Radio. In print media, which is emerging as a 
viable market nationally, the foundation shifted its 
attention to support for local papers, awarding equipment 
and newsprint grants to three local independent newspapers.
<p>
The foundation supported independent radio stations by 
insuring access to information through subscriptions to news 
agencies, and by providing training and equipment donations. 
In the area of television, funding went for the creation and 
promotion of TV programs by independent journalists. The 
foundation also supported English-language scholarships for 
journalists, helped establish a press club, and organized 
competitions for investigative reporting.
<p>
<b>Developing Civil Society Despite Social Apathy</b><br> 
Human rights activities were the main focus of support in 
the area of civil society. The foundation awarded a grant to 
the Helsinki Committee for Human Rights to organize an 
international workshop on human rights in times of 
transition. The workshop's goal was to educate the public 
about international human rights law. Soros Foundation-
Moldova also financed a workshop on the teaching of human 
rights in secondary schools. Representatives of local 
universities, the Ministry of Education, and Amnesty 
International attended the workshop and discussed the 
development of curricula for human rights teaching. The 
program will continue in 1996 with the preparation of 
experimental materials. The foundation also supported a 
legal center which offers free legal advice to disadvantaged 
segments of the population, especially concerning human 
rights violations.
<p>
In supporting the development of civil society in Moldova, 
the foundation faces two major difficulties: the persistent 
notion that the state should be responsible for everything, 
including the survival of NGOs, and the disastrous economic 
situation, which causes social apathy and forces NGOs to 
seek support for institutional survival, rather than for the 
development of new programs.
<p>
Fifteen local NGOs received grants for various activities in 
education, the arts, ecology, etc. Support also went toward 
the publication of an NGO directory, and a meeting of NGOs 
from Moldova, Romania, and Ukraine to discuss environmental 
issues and policies. In 1995, with financial support from 
TACIS (Technical Assistance for the Commonwealth of 
Independent States), the foundation established the first 
NGO consulting and training center in Moldova.
<p>
The foundation's
<a href="/health.html"><b>medical programs</b></a> 
emphasized education with 
support going to training courses and medical journals. The 
Soros Foundation-Moldova participated with the national 
foundations in 
<a href="/slovakia.html"><b>Slovakia</b></a> 
and 
<a href="/romania.html"><b>Romania</b></a> 
in the Regional Hospital 
Project, which provided donated medical equipment and 
supplies, as well as training in their use, to hospitals in 
the three countries.
<p>
<i>Lorina Balteanu, Executive Director</i>
<hr>                                                                       
