<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF - Bratislava - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Fund - Bratislava<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
Since its inception in 1992, the Open Society Fund-
Bratislava has focused its activities on initiatives and 
programs in education, arts and culture, health and 
medicine, management, media, human rights, support of local 
NGOs, as well as cooperation with other Central and Eastern 
European countries. Our long-term goals are to develop a 
mosaic of grassroots organizations able to survive without 
substantial aid from OSF-Bratislava or foreign donors; to 
increase the educational level of the Slovak population; and 
to mitigate problems which arise from national, ethnic, and 
other kinds of intolerance.
<p>
In 1995, the foundation supported the civil society programs 
of a number of local NGOs, including the Milan Simecka 
Foundation, Jan Hus Foundation, Marai Sandor Foundation, 
Slovak Academic Information Agency, and the Forum 
Foundation.
<p>
In education, the foundation's
<a href="/hesp.html"><b>Higher Education Support Program</b></a> 
provided support through several important 
subprograms. The External Teachers Program helped 
universities stay in touch with competent teachers and young 
researchers who had left teaching for better-paying jobs. 
The universities hope to persuade these teachers to return 
when the pay and working conditions improve. The 
Postgraduate Teaching Support Program provided supplementary 
stipends to postgraduate students in order to inspire them 
to remain in academia. The International Cooperation Program 
provided small grants to academics to enable them to 
participate in important international seminars 
and conferences. 
<p>
The Graduate Studies Program, an OSF-Bratislava pilot 
project in its second year, awarded three-year postgraduate 
scholarships in fields such as science and technology, 
environmental studies, informatics, health and nutrition. 
The Travel Grant Program was expanded to include grants for 
students who have been accepted at Western Universities. The 
Open Libraries Program was established to help libraries 
with book, journal, and equipment acquisitions.The 
foundation established three e-mail/Internet programs in 
1995: Computer Acquisition for High Schools, Local Media 
Internet, and HealthNet. HealthNet, developed in cooperation 
with the 
<a href="/osiny.html"><b>Open Society Institute - New York</b></a>,
seeks to improve 
the quality of health care by 
providing networking opportunities to health professionals 
throughout Slovakia.
<p>
<b>Training for Preschool Teachers</b><br>
In 1995, we continued to support the implementation of 
curricular reforms in elementary schools, the training of 
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step</b></a> 
and Roma preschool teachers, and the teaching 
of foreign languages in elementary schools. We started a 
training program for young journalists, which will serve as 
a model for local governments. Hundreds of secondary schools 
were awarded grants for their extracurricular activities.
<p>
For the past three years, OSF-Bratislava has supported 
several summer camps for disadvantaged Roma children in 
Central and Eastern Slovakia. We also supported the work of 
four preschools for Roma children and mothers. The children 
have shown a remarkable rate of success in entering and 
remaining in elementary schools. Separate classes are held 
for mothers on health and educational issues. 
A number of scholarships were awarded to talented Roma 
students. INFORoma, a special center established with the 
foundation's help, documented Roma issues and provided 
assistance to refugees.
<p>
In cooperation with the Covenant College Quest Program and 
the Management Training Program, the foundation helped young 
Slovak business leaders learn more about economic reform via 
internships with small American businesses. In health and 
medicine, we supported a summer internship program for 
medical students at the Veterans Hospital in New York and 
provided grants for drug and alcohol education prevention 
programs.
<p>
In 1995, we held competitions to support the publication of 
original works by Slovak citizens in literature, poetry, and 
history, and the translation of essential texts in 
economics, philosophy, law, sociology, and political 
science. Our Media Program provided technical assistance for 
local newspapers, educational activities concerning media 
law, seminars for local journalists, and exchanges among 
Eastern European journalists. The Soros Center for 
Contemporary Arts in Slovakia supported a wide range of 
programs in the visual arts, performing arts and film, 
educational activities, lectures, and roundtable discussions 
on art philosophy. The foundation also provided assistance 
to community groups working to protect the environment.
<p>
<i>Alena Panikova, Executive Director</i>
