<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
OSF Bratislavia - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Fund - Bratislavia<br>About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

Slovakia, a small nation of 5.3 million, became independent in 1993 when it split from the former Czechoslovakia. As a newly independent nation, Slovakia faces intensified problems in its transition to an open, civil society. Repeated changes in the government have hindered reform efforts and led to a critical economic situation, especially in education, health care, and culture. Budget restraints and gross underfunding of the country's social safety net have particularly affected early childhood education and higher education. National minorities, including Hungarian, Rroma, Polish, Ukrainian, Czech, and Ruthenian, make up approximately 20 percent of the population. Despite alarming signs of tension and  
antagonism among these groups, no major conflicts have arisen.<p>  
  
Despite a lack of legislation fostering the growth of not-for-profits, NGOs in Slovakia are thriving and play an influential role in the development of Slovak society. Civic organizations carry out independent programs in social welfare, education, human rights, local government reform, independent media, health care, and minority rights.
<hr>
