<html><head><title>                                                             
OSI - Slovenia - Report from Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Institute - Slovenia<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
Economic prosperity and open society do not always walk 
hand-in-hand. Slovenia, already relatively rich when it was 
part of the former Yugoslavia, has become even wealthier in 
the past few years. The process, however, has not been 
accompanied by the development of open society. In fact, 
growing intolerance and latent nationalism have increasingly 
come to characterize Slovenian society.
<p>
One of the foundation's key programs in 1995 was the 
Humanitarian Help Program, which allowed refugees from 
conflict throughout the former Yugoslavia to participate in 
educational, cultural, and other programs. Due to our 
efforts, all qualifying refugee students are enrolled in 
universities and receive free health insurance and meals. 
Although we lacked the funds to pay the fees for 111 
postgraduate students from Bosnia and Herzegovina, we 
persuaded some faculties to reduce the fees and the Ministry 
of Science to make up the difference. 
<p>
Slovenia's only secondary school with a special program for 
refugees continued its operations for a third year with our 
support. Foundation-supported legal counseling for refugees 
expanded to include a total of six offices across Slovenia. 
Cultural programs organized by refugees are now up and 
running in nine refugee centers. At the end of the year, we 
opened a 
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step</b></a> 
class for refugees, providing the 
children with an opportunity to interact with Slovene 
children every day and feel more a part of the community.
<p>
The foundation was a leader in bringing computer technology 
services to an eager public through its funding of the 
Internet Training Center, Digital Media Lab, Network Arts, 
Research Center, and Student Resource Center. The foundation 
worked in partnership with the Ministries of Education and 
Culture and the Students Organization of Ljubljana 
University to connect schools to academic computer networks. 
<p>
In 1995, we continued to assist smaller publishers, 
encouraging them to publish younger and less-established 
authors as well as translations of relevant contemporary 
works. We organized nine small publishers into a publishing 
group called Indeks, which has become a important voice in 
the industry. We held a competition for anti-fascist comic 
strips and helped publish the most successful examples. In 
support of independent media, we focused on projects that 
provide access to and develop alternative sources of 
information. We also supported particular radio programs 
that promote open society views, values, and approaches. 
Encouraged by the success of the Ljubljana Desktop 
Publishing Laboratory, we opened another center in Maribor.
<p>
In our civil society program, we continued to support human 
rights programs and other NGOs. In December, we opened a 
legal center to offer advice to refugees, NGO leaders, and 
others. Troubled by the fact that the government is 
reorganizing some of its services and calling these new 
agencies "foundation," we began preparing an effort to 
stimulate a wide public discussion about philanthropy, the 
role of NGOs, and the values of open society. 
<p>
<i>Alja Brglez, Executive Director</i>
