<DOCNO>WT09-B18-264</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA064-000378-B002-200</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://server.soros.org:80/slovenia/slvncoun.html 204.168.83.130 19970112095238 text/html 3385
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 12 Jan 1997 09:46:13 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
OSI Slovenia - Country Background
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Institute - Slovenia<br>Country Background
</h1></td>
</table> 

Secession and the pressures of building a state have delayed the passage of laws to regulate the transition in Slovenia. The absence of regulations severely obstructs the activities of educational, scientific, cultural, and artistic institutions, and the media. Nongovernmental organizations are forced to adapt to changing times without guidance. When appropriate regulations are passed, these organizations will have to reorganize in a relatively short time. OSF-Slovenia is assisting NGOs in developing the necessary legal competence and operational skills to meet their present and future situations creatively, to avoid confusion, and to recognize and use the opportunities open to them.<p> 
 
Recently passed laws open many new possibilities for nongovernmental organizations. For example, private and independent public schools and universities with their own curricula and programs are now legally possible. New laws promise more competition, yet power relationships remain unchanged. The universities, the national cultural and scientific institutions, and the government-controlled media (TV, national radio, daily newspapers) still possess the clout to block competition. Rare cases of governmental support to new dynamic entities are due more to enlightened individuals and small groups within the administration than to systemic policies and practices.<p> 
 
Independence of the media is a relatively new concept in Slovenia. The new law on the media, presently being adopted, still authorizes state subsidies for the national radio and television network. Independent media, on the other hand, must rely for their financing on advertising provided by a few large advertising agencies. The agencies have ties to political parties and lobbies, which gives these groups a measure of indirect control.<p> 
 
The financial situation of most NGOs is dire. Government support is mostly directed toward the "national" institutions inherited from the previous system. These institutions are overstaffed and used to relaxed financing and the absence of any real control. The more creative "non-national" entities are seriously marginalized and underfinanced.
<hr>
