Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
SF - Kazakstan - Report From Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Soros Foundation - Kazakstan<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 

The Soros Foundation-Kazakstan (SFK), established in 1994 
and registered in 1995, concentrated on education, library 
support, English-language instruction, arts and culture, 
third sector development, and conference and travel 
programs. In its priority area of education, the SFK took a 
multilevel approach, acknowledging the necessity of 
introducing new materials, new methods, and new disciplines 
in grade school, secondary school, and university programs.
<p>
At the Kazakstan Institute of Management Economics and 
Strategic Planning (KIMEP), which offers previously 
unavailable graduate degrees in economics, public 
administration, and business taught in English by foreign 
faculty, the foundation selected Soros Scholars based on 
need and academic achievement. In 1995, the SFK spent its 
entire English-language budget on training local English-
language instructors and setting up the English-language 
curriculum at KIMEP. 
<p>
At KIMEP, the foundation also established an education and 
cultural advising center, which works with the regional 
Peace Corps offices and Kazak educational administrative 
contacts to distribute information about opportunities for 
foreign study, scholarships, grants, and professional 
development programs abroad. The center was so successful in 
1995 that the foundation received a USIA grant to expand its 
operation in 1996.
<p>
Because secondary schools are extremely underfunded in 
Kazakstan, the SFK held two grant competitions for schools 
that wanted to adopt innovative educational approaches. 
Twenty-six grants were awarded for the 1995/96 academic year 
to support material and methodological changes within the 
school system through projects designed and implemented by 
the schools themselves.
<p>
In a pilot program for 20 school teachers, the foundation is 
introducing a new approach to teaching art centering on 
student perceptions, rather than teacher knowledge. Such an 
approach helps establish a more open and accepting rapport 
between teacher and pupil. If the pilot program is 
successful, the foundation will provide similar training to 
another 60 teachers throughout Kazakstan.
<p>
Schools at all levels in Kazakstan suffer from a shortage of 
textbooks. The SFK ordered 16 different books from other 
national foundations for testing in Kazakstan schools. In 
addition, the foundation held its first textbook 
competition, with an expert jury accepting 18 titles for 
publication and suggesting revisions of 30 additional works-
in-progress. In 1996, the SFK will focus its textbook 
competitions on Kazak-language instruction for native and 
non-native speakers, Kazakstani history, and Kazakstani 
literature. In conjunction with support to schools, the 
foundation provided subscriptions to Western journals to six 
central libraries, purchased a linguistics and philology 
collection for the Institute of Linguistics, and awarded 
travel grants to Kazakstani librarians to study library 
science abroad.
<p>
In the area of arts and culture, the SFK supported 10 
Kazakstani artists by publishing a catalog of their works, 
which will be sent to museums and libraries around the 
world. The foundation supported the creation of a new 
Kazakstani soap opera that dealt with current social issues, 
such as privatization and interracial tension, in a form 
that has wide public appeal. The experience also showed 
Kazakstani film crews, writers, and actors how to put 
together a television program in accordance with Western 
production standards. 
<p>
Through the Civil Society Program-the Third Sector
Initiative, the SFK provided 10 grants to NGOs for a range 
of social initiatives, including education for diabetics, 
the creation of a center for folk singer/narrators, and 
funding for the local Helsinki Watch committee. Support for 
local nongovernmental organizations is important to 
spreading the ideals of open society throughout Kazakstan.
<p>
Through the regional 
<a href="/east.html"><b>East East Program</b></a> 
and the Travel Grant 
Program, the foundation sponsored over 131 Kazakstan 
participants at major international conferences and 
scholastic programs in the humanities and social sciences. 
These extraordinary opportunities for citizens of Kazakstan 
to travel, study, and lecture in another country help them 
understand how their country is perceived abroad and 
encourage them to participate in working to encourage open 
society at home.
<p>
In 1995, we also implemented an e-mail/Internet program. 
Computer modems and software were purchased in preparation 
for a nationwide open competition which will give 30 schools 
across Kazakstan access to e-mail and Internet. In the first 
part of 1996, 15 schools will go online. Children from those 
schools will train students in the next 
15 schools.
<p>
In 1996, the SFK will initiate an independent film and media 
program, a legal reform program, a 
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step</b></a> 
preschool 
program, and a grassroots model school project.
<p>
<i>George Zarubin, Executive Director</i>
