</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
SF Kazakstan - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Soros Foundation - Kazakstan<br>About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

Kazakstan had independence thrust upon it in 1992 with the dissolution of the Soviet Union. Like most other former Soviet republics, Kazakstan inherited a fragmented economy, an authoritarian tradition, a bloated bureaucracy, widespread corruption, and a politically and economically disenfranchised and uninvolved citizenry. While its highest leadership appears committed to reconfiguring the economy on a private basis and has attracted a number of foreign companies in search of joint ventures, progress in privatization is slow and many agreed-upon projects are as yet unrealized owing to intragovernmental conflicts, an uncertain regulatory environment, and complex geopolitical relations.<p> 
 
Living conditions for most people in the country are stark, and many technically trained ethnic Germans and Russians are returning to their ancestral homelands. The state cannot find the means to provide adequate education and health care to the general population, much less to fund research and cultural activities.<p> 
To date, the country has enjoyed overall political stability in spite of continual parliamentary crises. The economic situation, however, is exerting pressures on the political system and complicates the task of those seeking to build democracy. While relations among ethnic groups are largely amicable, there are nationalist elements ready to exploit the worsening economic conditions for their own ends.
<hr>
