<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html><head><title>                                                             
SF - Kyrgyzstan - Report From Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Soros Foundation - Kyrgyzstan<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 

The mission of our foundation is to support the development 
of open society in Kyrgyzstan. We have chosen to focus our 
efforts on the field of primary and secondary education, and 
our goal is to seek and support initiatives that improve the 
quality and openness of our schools. We believe intelligent 
and tolerant kids are the best insurance for a better 
future. The end of 1995 marked the completion of just over 
one year's activity for our foundation. During this time, we 
initiated programs whose results we can already measure, and 
we prepared the ground for projects which will bear fruit 
for some years to come. 
<p>
In 1995, over 90 percent of our budget went to support for 
educational initiatives. The strategy of the foundation is 
to tie as many of our 
other programs as possible to our work in primary and 
secondary education. The result is a diverse but unified 
approach to educational reform in Kyrgyzstan which takes 
advantage of the traditional respect in Kyrgyz society for 
education, as well as the willingness among Kyrgyz teachers 
and school administrators to explore and refine new 
approaches to learning.
<p> 
<b>A Network of Pilot Schools</b><br>
The heart of our foundation's work is a network of pilot 
schools established in November 1994. The foundation began 
with 25 pilot schools, and in 1995 the number was increased 
to 43. We have provided these schools with leadership 
training, updated textbooks, computer and other technical 
equipment, multimedia educational programs, debate clubs, 
language resource centers, and young journalist clubs. We 
have also supported the development of innovative approaches 
to education at these schools. Our English Language Program 
has focused on introducing new textbooks into the pilot 
schools, training teachers in how to use them, and providing 
each school with the equipment necessary to incorporate 
video technology into the education process. The Education 
Abroad Advising Center has conducted seminars for pilot 
school teachers on how to help students take advantage of 
opportunities to study abroad. 
<p>
We have provided several pilot schools with e-mail, and, in 
1996, our goal is to expand e-mail and Internet access to 
all of the pilot schools. In 1996, the foundation will equip 
the schools with computer classrooms, support the 
development of more interactive methodologies of teaching, 
and promote the increased involvement of parents in the 
education of their children. By the end of 1996, we expect 
to be working with 50 schools all together.
<p> 
Encouraging parental involvement is one of the central 
characteristics of the 
<a href="/youth.html#preschool"><b>Step-by-Step</b></a> 
program. In 1995, the 
foundation introduced Step-by-Step into seven kindergartens, 
involving a total of 362 children. 
The goal is to help local preschool educators develop 
methods for 
cultivating the creativity and individuality of children. In 
1996, we will be exploring ways to ease the transition of 
pupils from Step-by-Step into elementary schools by 
encouraging enrollment directly into the pilot schools.
<p>
<b>Feeding the Country's 'Information Hunger'</b><br>
In the field of higher education, the foundation organized a 
series of seven seminars for young university faculty 
members and advanced graduate students on topics ranging 
from political science to pedagogy. The seminars, conducted 
by teams of lecturers from the United States, Eastern 
Europe, and the former Soviet Union, gave Kyrgyz academics 
access to information and ideas otherwise unavailable in 
this period of "information hunger." To support higher 
education, we conducted a textbook writing competition, 
which resulted in the publication of four titles. In 1995, 
we published an additional seven books by standard contract, 
and, in 1996, we will publish at least 21 books, 10 of which 
were winners of the 1995 textbook competition. 
<p> 
In addition to laying the foundation for Internet 
connectivity in the pilot schools, our 
<a href="/internet.html"><b>Internet Program</b></a> 
brought e-mail and future Internet access to three medical 
institutions and three newspapers. We also established two 
medical resource centers for surgical techniques. 
And, we have supported the establishment of a center for the 
study of Kyrgyz in a Russian-language high school, as well 
as a center for the study of Russian in a Kyrgyz-language 
high school. In 1996, while maintaining our emphasis on 
primary and secondary education, we will continue to expand 
our work in the fields of medicine, civil 
society, and the arts.
<p> 
<i>Chinara Sh. Jakypova, Executive Director</i>
<hr>                                                                       
