<html><head><title>                                                             
SF Kyrgyzstan - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Soros Foundation - Kyrgyzstan<br>About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

Under the Soviet Union, Kyrgyzstan had the tender russified name of Kirghizia. Upon gaining its sovereignty, the country changed not only its name but its character. The totally apolitical Kirghizia turned into the mobile and appealing-to-the-West Kyrgyzstan. It is here that the ideas of open society and democracy have grown more successfully than in many neighboring countries. Kyrgyzstan's independent newspapers periodically shock other commonwealth brethren with their utter explicitness of expression.<p>

This phenomenon can be explained simply enough: Kyrgyzstan has always valued education, and the country's women have always enjoyed a degree of equality. Under Soviet rule, many of Kyrgyzstan's citizens, most of them women, graduated from prominent Russian colleges and universities. This is the hidden spring of Kyrgyzstan's prompt and successful switch to democracy.<p>

Political considerations have always influenced the learning of  foreign languages. During the Cold War, German was the favored language. As a result, independent Kyrgyzstan has found itself practically incapable of directly communicating with the outer world. English language courses and tutoring have become a growth industry. New textbooks are sorely needed. Would-be capitalists and students, free of "young pioneer" organizations, still learn English from Lenin's biographies.<p>

Language problems also occur among the Kyrgyz, many of whom speak different languages, the urban Kyrgyz primarily Russian, rural residents only Kyrgyz. During the nationalist period of the early 1990s, when only the state language (Kyrgyz) was permitted, people of Russian origin had to master the language in a ridiculously short time. The language problem undoubtedly added to the outward migration of local Russians intimidated by the aggressiveness of the rural young who had gathered in urban areas in search of employment.<p>
<hr>
