<html><head><title>                                                             
Open Society Georgia Foundation- From the Director
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Georgia Foundation<br>A Report from the Executive Director
</h1></td>
</table> 
For the Open Society Georgia Foundation (OSGF), 1995 was a 
year of growth and development. Administrative structures 
were put in place, a staff was hired, and a strategy for 
growth was developed. All this positioned the foundation to 
become an important partner in Georgia's transition toward
an open society. 
<p>
The foundation operated under difficult circumstances in 
1995. The government was supportive and helpful, but the 
economy presented severe problems. Energy shortages and a 
virtual breakdown of the country's infrastructure meant that 
OSGF began its activities in January with no heating, no 
gas, and very little electricity. Telephone communication 
with the outside world was unreliable, at best. 
<p>
While 1995 was, in effect,  OSGF's first year, the same 
cannot be said of the programs of the 
<a href="/ceu.html"><b>Central European University</b></a> 
and the 
<a href="/issep.html"><b>International Soros Science Education Program</b></a>, 
both of which have been active in Georgia for over 
two years. With the arrival of the foundation, however, 
these programs were merged into the larger administrative 
structure of OSGF. 
<p>
The foundation began 1995 with an intensive staff training 
program, developed by OSGF's head program coordinator. The 
training introduced staff to the network of foundations 
created and funded by 
<a href="/gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a>
and to the ideals of an 
open society. Staff learned what it means to be a 
coordinator, their responsibilities as representatives of a 
foundation espousing open society, and the importance of 
each person's contribution to the working of the foundation. 
<p>
An organizational structure was created to answer the many 
technical, administrative, financial, and program needs that 
arose. Managers were appointed to head various areas of work 
and given the freedom and responsibility to oversee the 
functioning of their areas. 
<p>
In the first half of 1995, a small group of representatives 
of the organizations that jointly founded OSGF governed our 
activities. As our activities unfolded-the first project 
proposals were reviewed in April-and news of the foundation 
spread, the need for a more formal governing structure grew. 
In September of 1995, the foundation appointed an executive 
board and formed review commissions for the four major 
program areas of education, English language, arts and 
culture, and mass media. 
<p>
<b>Computer Classes and Advice for Students</b><br>
In 1995, OSGF supported a total of 106 projects within its 
four program areas. The foundation created computer classes 
in several 
schools, funded independent newspapers and radio stations, 
established teacher training courses for English-language 
teachers, and reawakened the arts and culture community by 
offering grants in an area that receives virtually no 
funding from the government. In the fall, OSGF opened an 
International Student Advising Center and began a travel 
grants program. 
<p>
The 
<a href="/osiart.html"><b>Arts and Culture Program</b></a> 
supported several expeditions 
by archeologists and ethnographers to study ancient 
monuments, churches, and other sites, including an 
expedition to Turkey to record the Georgian monuments that 
remain on Turkish soil from hundreds of years ago. The 
<a href="/english.html"><b>English Language Program</b></a> 
supported the establishment and 
development of the English Teachers' Association of Georgia,
a summer teacher training course, and programs of English 
for NGOs and scouts. The Mass Media Program supported a 
respected newspaper, Seven Days, with a technical grant and 
funded an informational program at the environmental radio 
station Green Wave.
<p>
OSGF organized and hosted several Internet roundtable 
meetings in the spring and summer of 1995, bringing together 
a community of people interested in e-mail and Internet and 
stimulating a dialogue on the topic. In response to a demand 
for assistance, OSGF created the 
E-mail Starter Kit (ESK) Project, the goal of which was to 
promote 
e-mail connectivity through competitions organized for 
educational establishments, mass media, nongovernmental 
organizations, and 
others. The project awarded a total of 20 ESK grants in 
Georgia.
<p>
At the end of the year, an opinion poll conducted by a local 
television program voted OSGF the most popular funding 
organization in Georgia. In 1996, the foundation plans to 
establish new programs and to participate in additional Open 
Society Institute regional programs. 
<p>
<i>Ulana Trylowsky, Executive Director</i>
<hr>                                                                       
