<html><head><title>                                                             
Open Society Georgia Foundation - About the Country
</title></head>                                                                 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>                                                  
<tr>                                                                            
<td><img src="/images/logo3.gif"></td>                                          
<td><h1>                                                                        
Open Society Georgia Foundation<br>About the Country
</h1></td>
</table> 

The nationalist outbursts and ethnic conflicts of recent years brought about great changes in Georgia's internal and foreign policies. Relations with Russia became more careful, more balanced and realistic. The result was an easing of ethnic conflicts, a willingness to find peaceful solutions to problems, the transfer of Georgian-Abkhazian political negotiations from Geneva to Moscow, and a bilateral thaw in Russian-Georgian mass media.<p>

Internally, the situation is more complicated. The political status of both South Ossetia and Abkhazia are unclear, and, accordingly, the state administration of the whole of Georgia is tentative. The work of parliament, in spite of help from different organizations, is inefficient. There is no political party capable of winning elections and carrying out serious economic reforms since the mentality of the major part of the population is paternalistic--they are waiting for a savior.<p>

The economy of Georgia was deeply integrated into the economy of the USSR. After the dismantling of the Soviet Union, these economic ties were also severed, and the result was the total collapse of the Georgian economy. The country produces no energy. Georgia cannot obtain oil from Russia, and it cannot pay its debts to Turkmenistan for natural gas. A number of regions have been without electricity for almost three years. Industry is almost at a standstill. Qualified workers are leaving the country. Many plants have been looted, many have grown obsolete. The lack of preparation for the decollectivization of agriculture destroyed many necessary and traditional areas of the economy. The private sector, however, did succeed in capitalizing on the need for petrol and liquid gas, allowing some entrepreneurs to grow very rich, becoming magnates in their fields.
<hr>
