<html>
<head>
<title> East East Program
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">   
<table cellpadding=6>                                                 
<tr>                                                                  
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                       
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/east.gif" alt="East East Regional Program">         
</td>                                                                 
</tr>                                                                 
</table>                                                              
<a name="top"></a>
<center>
| <a href="eastcoor.html"><b>Program Coordinators</b></a> |
<a href="eastca95.html"><b>1995 Program Calendar</b></a> |
<a href="eastpr95.html"><b>1995 Project Analysis</b></a> |
<a href="eastca96.html"><b>1996 Program Calendar</b></a> |
</center>
<p>
The East East Program encourages the exchange of ideas and 
open dialogue among institutions and individuals in Central 
and Eastern Europe to share and learn from one another's
experiences in the post-communist transition. The program 
focuses on developing skills for identifying and addressing 
problems common to post-communist societies and provides 
ongoing and often new channels of communication.
<p>
In 1995, the East East Program emphasized efforts to raise 
public awareness and consciousness of current problems and 
needs of societies in transition in Central and Eastern 
Europe. The strength of the program is its ability to bring 
together people from the region who wish to learn from each 
other's experiences and help each other in these turbulent 
times of transition. The East East Program is a starting 
point for collaboration, provides a framework for regional 
cooperation and mutual dialogue, and creates conditions to 
address problems by bridging communication gaps and 
reestablishing links through innovative communication.
<p>
Throughout 1995, the East East Program evaluation team of 
five program coordinators from the 
<a href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a> 
provided an ongoing monitoring, internal evaluation, and 
advisory mechanism for the program as well as guidance for 
the program's strategic development and direction. The 
results of the team's comprehensive evaluation of the 
program provided the basis of discussion for the annual 
program coordinators meeting convened in Bled, Slovenia, in 
June 1995.
<p>
East East Program projects are designed broadly within the 
following areas: civil society and infrastructure 
development; societies in transition: information exchange 
and processes of reform; human rights, ethnic relations and 
cultural diversity; community development; social welfare, 
health, and environment; and cooperation in cultural 
research and education. The East East Program seeks to 
develop and sustain substantive, long-term initiatives and 
to strengthen and promote collaborative relations and 
intraregional networks in a practical approach to solutions 
to the complex problems faced by societies in transition.
<p>
In 1995, the East East Program supported over 200 projects 
on a wide range of topics throughout the foundation network.  
A seminar on fundraising for NGOs, hosted by the 
<a href="czech.html"><b>Open Society Fund - Prague</b></a>,
sought to strengthen the professional 
skills of fundraisers in Central and Eastern Europe and to 
increase the capacity of the not-for-profit sector to 
generate its own funding and to move toward greater self-
reliance within the region. Another seminar, entitled 
"Otherhood and Nation," hosted by the 
<a href="slovenia.html"><b>Open Society Institute - Slovenia</b></a>
attempted to initiate dialogue and 
debate in addressing the rise of nationalism in the 
post-communist transition.
<p>
"Better Perception for the Future: Information Exchange," an
initiative of the 
<a href="moldova.html"><b>Soros Foundation - Moldova</b></a>
provided 
participants from Moldova, Romania, Bulgaria and Ukraine an 
opportunity for exchange visits to facilitate the sharing of 
experiences in analyzing reform processes and changes in 
social consciousness in the post-communist transition and to 
create channels of constructive interaction and information.
<p>
The 
<a href="poland.html"><b>Stefan Batory Foundation</b></a> 
organized a series of seminars 
and training sessions to address the role of local 
government. The program included visits of representatives 
of local governments from Belarus and Ukraine to Poland to 
observe elections and meet with members of Polish local 
governments. An ongoing series of training workshops in 
Poland and Ukraine, "Central and Eastern European Trade 
Unions in the Process of Economic  Transformation," provided
Belarusian and Ukrainian participants with information on 
methods of transformation of Central and Eastern European 
economic systems, strategic directions of transformation, 
foundations of economic and political reforms, and rules and 
roles of worker unions' leadership.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
