<html>
<head>
<title> Regional Children and Youth Programs
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">   
<table cellpadding=6>                                                 
<tr>                                                                  
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                       
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/youth.gif" alt="Regional Children and Youth Programs">
</td>                                                                 
</tr>                                                                 
</table>                                                              
<a name="top"></a>
<center>
<b>
| <a href="#preschool">Regional Soros Preschool Project</a> |
<a href="#highschool">Regional High School Debate Program</a> |<br>
| <a href="#secondary">Regional Secondary School Scholarship Program</a> |
<a href="#health">Regional Health Education Program</a> |<br>
| <a href="#youth">Youth Program</a> |
<a href="#links">Related Links</a> |
</b>
</center>
<p>
The mission of the Regional Children and Youth Programs is 
to provide young people with the opportunities and resources 
to help them participate fully in an open society. The 
programs encourage critical thinking; teach decision-making 
skills; expose students to cultures other than their own to 
promote tolerance; initiate school reforms that foster 
cooperation between students and teachers; and provide 
access to information and innovative teaching methodologies.
<p>
<a name="preschool"></a>
<h2>
Regional Soros Preschool Project (Step-by-Step)
</h2>
The Regional Soros Preschool Project (Step-by-Step) is a 
comprehensive education reform program that promotes 
innovative teaching methods and a community-based approach 
to services for children up to eight years old. The 
curriculum for the project was developed by Children's
Resources International, and subsequently adapted to local 
conditions by early childhood experts in each country. The 
project stresses active learning, decision making, 
individualization of the teaching process, and parental 
involvement. In 1995, the project expanded to 966 
kindergarten classrooms, serving 23,225 children in 18 
countries, and focused on the needs of underserved children 
in the region-children living in poverty, ethnic minorities, 
Roma, and children with disabilities. The model classrooms 
developed for the program will be used as teacher training 
sites in order to make the methodology available on a wide 
basis.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="highschool"></a>
<h2>
Regional High School Debate Program                                        
</h2>
The Regional High School Debate Program provides a forum for 
secondary school students to develop sophisticated 
communication skills, interest in and understanding of 
current social and political events, tolerance for different 
ideas, and an opportunity to discuss controversial issues in 
an educational yet competitive setting. Each country 
maintains a national center to train debate team coaches and 
provide students with research materials. In each country, 
students debate in their native language in tournaments 
throughout the year that culminate in a national tournament 
at the end of the school year.  In 1996, students and 
teachers from all 21 of the countries that participate in 
the program will attend the annual Regional Debate 
Competition, which will be conducted in English.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="secondary"></a>
<h2>
Regional Secondary School Scholarship Program
</h2>
The Regional Secondary School Scholarship Program is an 
academic scholarship initiative that gives high school 
students from Central and Eastern Europe an opportunity to 
study in the United States or England. Each year, through 
open, merit-based competitions, the program awards one-year 
scholarships to the best American and British schools, one-
semester and one-year programs at U.S. schools, and summer 
academic programs. In 1995, 372 students were selected, 49 
for a full year of study in Britain, 113 for a year and 128 
for a semester in the United States, and 82 for the summer 
program. Plans for 1996 include providing Roma students with 
scholarship opportunities, adding participation in community 
service to the scholarship requirements, and establishing 
alumni networks to promote the continued participation of 
former students in open society programs.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="health"></a>
<h2>
Regional Health Education Program 
</h2>
The Regional Health Education Program is a teacher training 
program that introduces elementary and secondary school 
teachers to innovative ways of teaching their students about 
health. The five-part curriculum focuses on alcohol and 
other drugs, human sexuality, AIDS, smoking, and nutrition, 
with supplemental activities on the environment and conflict 
resolution. In 1995, the program conducted 691 workshops and 
trained 20,515 teachers. In four years, one million students 
have participated in the programs. 
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="youth"></a>
<h2>
Youth Program                     
</h2>
In 1995, the Youth Program of the Open Society Institute 
joined with 
<a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/iearn/"><b>
I*EARN (the International Education and Resource 
Network) 
</b></a> 
to launch an initiative to enable schools within 
the region to participate in global educational 
telecommunications projects. The project also allows for 
cooperation in traditional academic subject areas such as 
math and science. I*EARN is active in countries from seven 
continents. In 1995, the project was introduced in Bulgaria, 
the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Kyrgyzstan, Latvia, 
Lithuania, Romania, and Slovenia. The Youth Program has made 
a commitment to I*EARN
to expand their project in 1996 to include additional 
countries within the Soros foundations network. 
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
