<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<html>
<head>
<title> Regional English Language Programs
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">   
<table cellpadding=6>                                                 
<tr>                                                                  
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                       
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/english.gif" alt="Regional English Language Programs">
</td>                                                                 
</tr>                                                                 
</table>                                                              
<a name="top"></a>
<h2>
About the Program
</h2>
The 
<a href="osiny.html"><b>Open Society Institute - New York</b></a>
supports two different yet complementary English language programs: 
<a href="#selp"><b>SELP (Soros English Language Program)</b></a>
and 
<a href="#spelt"><b>SPELT (Soros Professional English Language Teaching)</b></a>.
The mission of the two programs is to provide English 
language support to other foundation programs and to raise 
the general level of English usage in the countries of the 
region so that new generations will be able to communicate 
easily and successfully with people worldwide.
<p>
<a name="selp"></a>
<h2>
Soros English Language Program
</h2>
English language programs were introduced because the 
<a href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a> 
recognized that many people have 
difficulties participating in educational programs and 
international events that require a fairly advanced command 
of English. In many countries of the foundation network, 
foreign language teaching and learning were crippled by the 
long years of isolation from the international community. 
Therefore, local educational institutions at all levels, 
both state-owned and private, have had little to offer in 
improving the acquisition of practical foreign language 
skills.
<p>
The Soros English Language Program (SELP) was established to 
support a range of activities from independent schools of 
English to training courses for English-as-a-Foreign-
Language (EFL) teachers to the upgrading of university 
English departments to preparation for EFL examinations. In 
addition to English for academic purposes, SELP organized 
courses in business English, journalistic English, and 
military English to improve the foreign language 
communicative competence of participants in other foundation 
programs. SELP developed a number of programs in 
collaboration with other international governmental and 
nongovernmental organizations, including but not limited to 
the British Council and USIA.
<p>
In 1995, three EFL schools established by the foundations 
became self-supporting (two schools in Lithuania and one in 
Ukraine). Another significant event in 1995 was the 
introduction of other foreign languages into the SELP 
curriculum. French courses were started in Lithuania, and 
the teaching of German and French was begun in Ukraine.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="spelt"></a>
<h2>
Soros Professional English Language Teaching Program 
</h2>
SPELT is an English language program that seeks to bring 
modern teaching methodologies to the region. SPELT also aims 
to inspire a dramatic change in the rigid teacher-student 
relationships characteristic of the former communist 
educational systems. As a cross-cultural educational program 
run in collaboration with official educational institutions, 
SPELT tries to increase international communication and 
foster diversity and understanding of other cultures.
<p>
To achieve these goals, specialists in EFL teaching are 
recruited by the University of Montana in the United States 
and sent to teach in secondary schools, teacher training 
colleges, and university departments in cities and towns 
throughout the region.
<p>
The 
<a href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a> 
advertise the availability of SPELT 
Teaching Fellows. Local schools pay teacher's salaries, 
provide housing, and appoint a "buddy" teacher to provide 
support. SPELT Teaching Fellows teach English side by side 
with local teachers. In addition, they offer teacher 
training workshops after school and on weekends to help 
local teachers acquire experience with new teaching 
techniques.
<p>
This program was started in 1990 with seven teaching fellows 
going to Hungary. In 1995, the program supplied 81 teaching 
fellows to schools in 15 countries. The participating 
countries in the academic year 1995-96 were Bulgaria, Czech 
Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Kazakstan, Kyrgyzstan, Latvia, 
Lithuania, Macedonia, Moldova, Poland, Romania, Slovakia, 
Slovenia, and Ukraine.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<p>                                                                             
