<p>
<a name="about"></a>
<h2>
About the Program
</h2>
Working with the 
<a href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a>,
other NGOs, and 
governmental agencies, the 
<a href="osiny.html"><b>Open Society Institute - New York</b></a>
develops, funds, and operates a variety of programs aimed at 
improving the health and well-being of people in Central and 
Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union. The emphasis of 
the programs is on public health issues such as primary 
care, prevention, substance abuse, and care for the mentally 
and physically disabled. 
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="salzburg"></a>
<h2>
Salzburg Medical Seminars Program
</h2>
The Salzburg Medical Seminars Program, directed by 
physicians from Austria and the United States, provided a 
forum for the discussion and promotion of a range of health 
issues. In 1995, 360 health care providers from 17 countries 
attended seminars in anesthesiology and intensive care, bone 
and joint surgery, cardiology, diagnostic imaging, community 
health care and family medicine, neurology, neurosurgery and 
brain trauma, pediatrics, emergency care in pediatrics, 
pediatric surgery, psychiatry and psychotherapy, and 
urology.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="schweitzer"></a>
<h2>
Schweitzer Seminars for Physicians Program
</h2>
OSI and the <a href="http://members.aol.com/asih1/">Schweitzer Institute for the Humanities</a> 
developed the Schweitzer Seminars for Physicians Program to 
reorient physicians in the region toward a systems approach 
to health care delivery by encouraging dialogue among 
clinical and nonclinical health professionals in structured 
problem-solving seminars.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="training"></a>
<h2>
Regional Medical Training Program
</h2>
To improve clinical care in the region, the Regional Medical 
Training Program for Physicians provided medical training 
opportunities by sponsoring internships in the U.S. and 
establishing training centers in the region. By the end of 
1995, the three-year-old program had trained 108 physicians 
from 12 countries in medical specialties ranging from 
diagnostic ultrasound to pediatric surgery. In 1996, the 
program will focus on training in public health policy, 
family medicine, pediatrics, and obstetrics/gynecology.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="harm"></a>
<h2>
Harm Reduction Initiatives
</h2>
The goal of the Harm Reduction Initiatives as Drug Policy 
Alternatives Program is to minimize the social and health 
problems associated with illegal drug use and drug control 
policies. In collaboration with 
<a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/lindesmith"><b>The Lindesmith Center</b></a>,
the 
program sponsored initiatives that address local drug 
problems through innovative measures based upon "harm 
reduction" approaches and practices. 
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="grants"></a>
<h2>
Disabilities Grants Program
</h2>
The Disabilities Grants Program sponsored projects promoting 
self-help initiatives among the disabled and providing 
educational opportunities and vocational training for people 
with disabilities. The program seeks to create a network of 
mental disability advocates and help end the segregation and 
institutionalization of people with mental retardation.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="health"></a>
<h2>
Health Care Initiatives Program
</h2>
In 1995, the Health Care Initiatives Program was launched in 
coordination with the national foundations, and grants were 
allocated to projects focusing on public health issues, 
medical information systems, and health care management. The 
program awarded grants for a modern birthing facility in 
Cluj, Romania, a children's dental clinic in Belarus, and a 
project to improve eye care services in Albania.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<a name="cdrom"></a>
<h2>
CD-ROM Regional Program
</h2>
The CD-ROM Regional Program keeps 23 major medical libraries 
in the region abreast of the latest developments in medicine 
and research through the distribution of CD-ROM hardware, 
software, and database updates of Medline. In 1995, the 
pilot HealthNet Slovakia Project began creating a network of 
hospitals, clinics, general practitioners, and health care 
institutions connected via the Internet to promote 
communication as well as access to information. The Regional 
Hospital Project, a two-year pilot project in Moldova, 
Romania, and Slovakia, helped modernize hospitals by 
equipping them with medical supplies and reconditioned 
equipment donated by U.S. hospitals. 
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<p>                                                                             
