<head>
<title> Regional Scholarship Program                  
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">   
<table cellpadding=6>                                                 
<tr>                                                                  
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                       
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/cap.gif" alt="Regional Scholarship Program">
</td>                                                                 
</tr>                                                                 
</table>                                                              
<a name="top"></a>
<center>
| <a href="#about"><b>About the Project</b></a> |
<a href="#virtual"><b>Virtual University</b></a> |
<a href="#grants"><b>Supplementary Grants Program</b></a> | <br>
| <a href="#muskie"><b>Edmund S. Muskie Graduate Fellowships</b></a> |
<a href="#additional"><b>Additional Opportunities</b></a> |
<a href="#links"><b>Related Links</b></a> |<br>
| <img align=middle src="/images/wrldbk.gif"> <a href="newscap.html"><b>NewsCAP</b><i> - Newsletter of the Consortium for Academic Partnership</i></a> |
<p>
</center>
<p>
<a name="about"></a>
<h2>
About the Project
</h2>

In 1995, as part of its ongoing mission to respond to 
educational needs in the countries of Central and Eastern 
Europe and the former Soviet Union, the Consortium for 
Academic Partnership (CAP) established two new fellowship 
opportunities in the fields of environmental management and 
environmental law. The new program, consisting of 20 
fellowships in environmental management and 10 in 
environmental law, will include summer internships to enable 
grantees to experience the practical application of the 
theories and principles explored in their academic research. 
The first cohort of grantees will arrive in the United 
States in the fall of 1996.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="virtual"></a>
<h2>
Virtual University
</h2>
A prominent feature of CAP's regional scholarship programs 
is the Virtual University, which seeks to nurture lasting 
ties among grantees from the various countries of the region 
as well as between the scholars and their host universities. 
In previous years, Virtual University efforts focused on 
predeparture orientations and winter conferences, which gave 
fellows the chance to meet colleagues and discuss issues 
relevant to their home countries as well as to their 
personal experiences studying abroad. In 1995, CAP 
introduced a newsletter 
<a href="newscap.html"><b>NewsCAP</b></a>, 
which was distributed to 
over 2,000 current and former grantees, host universities in 
the U.S., UK, and Western Europe, and the national 
foundations. Reporting on CAP programs and activities and 
printing stories by grantees, the newsletter will become a 
chronicle of diverse educational experiences and 
international intellectual changes.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="grants"></a>
<h2>
Supplementary Grants Program
</h2>
The most emotionally powerful event of the year occurred in 
November in the city of Philadelphia, where the 
Supplementary Grants Program for Students from the Former 
Yugoslavia sponsored a gathering of grant recipients living 
in the United States. Modeled on similar highly successful 
meetings in Europe and the United Kingdom, the three-day 
session offered a variety of discussions and cultural 
activities for these students displaced by the war in 
Yugoslavia. Many of the students had not seen their 
colleagues since before the hostilities began, and indeed 
many had been unaware of the fate of close friends and even 
relatives who turned out to be grant recipients as well. The 
genuine spirit of friendship and joy generated by this 
reunion was deeply touching to all present, and served as an 
inspirational reminder of the tolerance and respect still 
alive in many people from this troubled region. 
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="muskie"></a>
<h2>
Edmund S. Muskie Graduate Fellowships
</h2>
In 1995, flagship programs such as the Edmund S. Muskie 
Graduate Fellowships and the Virtual University 
Undergraduate Exchange continued to produce challenging 
academic experiences for exceptional students from Poland to 
Kyrgyzstan. CAP continued to augment other Soros-funded 
efforts in higher education in the region through 
scholarship assistance to graduates from the 
<a href="ceu.html"><b>Central European University</b></a> 
as well as highly competitive four-year 
fellowships for undergraduate study at the American 
University in Bulgaria. 
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="additional"></a>
<h2>
Additional Opportunities               
</h2>
Three new host universities in the United Kingdom, the 
University of Edinburgh, the London School of Economics, and 
the London College of Law joined the universities of Oxford, 
Cambridge, Warwick, and Manchester to offer additional 
opportunities for advanced study in the humanities. CAP's
unique initiative on behalf of exiled students from Burma, 
organized in close cooperation with the 
<a href="burma.html"><b>Burma Project</b></a>, 
kept 
up support to those struggling to further their education 
despite difficult and desperate circumstances.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
