<head>
<title> Southern Africa Project
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">  
<table cellpadding=6>                                                
<tr>                                                                 
<td>                                                                 
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                      
<td>                                                                 
<img align=middle src="/images/southern.gif" alt="Southern Africa Project"> 
</td>                                                                
</tr>                                                                
</table>                                                             
<a name="top"></a>
<center>
<b>
| <a href="#about">About the Southern Africa Project</a>|
<a href="#goals">What are the goals of the project?</a>|
<a href="#eligible">Who is eligible for funding?</a>|<br>
| <a href="#osi">What is the Open Society Institute?</a>|
<a href="#apply">How do I apply for funding?</a>|
<a href="#send">Where do I send my application?</a>|
</b>
</center>
<p>
<a name="about"></a>
<h2>
     About the Southern Africa Project
</h2>
Since 1990, southern Africa has experienced a number of 
important changes in its social, political, and economic 
climate. In the past five years, Namibia won its struggle 
for independence from South African domination; South 
Africa's apartheid regime was dismantled and replaced with a 
nonracial democratic government; multiparty elections were 
held for the first time in Zambia and Zimbabwe; and a 30-
year-long dictatorship came to an end in Malawi. The most 
encouraging news came from Mozambique and Angola, where 
peace accords ended decades of war.
<p>
Peace, political liberalization, and greater margins of 
freedom of expression have enabled civil society to make 
some progress in the region. Independent media outlets, 
human rights organizations, and public policy research have 
multiplied. Regional exchanges of information, knowledge, 
and skills are slowly expanding. Even regional economic 
cooperation is being revived.
<p>
Despite these positive developments, outside assistance is 
desperately needed in order to sustain and further develop 
these achievements in the face of structural economic 
limitations and continued political instability. Poverty 
levels in most of the region's countries remain high, and 
government funding in the areas of health, education, and 
community development is grossly inadequate. Meanwhile, 
foreign aid to the region, from the United States and some 
European donors, is decreasing.
<p>
The Southern Africa Project represents a first step in 
increasing the 
<a href="osiny.html"><b>Open Society Institute - New York's</b></a>
involvement 
in sub-Saharan Africa. It will disburse grants exclusively 
to locally based initiatives. The project will be developed 
in coordination with the 
<a href="safrica.html"><b>Open Society Foundation for South Africa</b></a> 
and a board of advisors from the southern African 
region. Most of 1996 will be spent selecting advisory board 
members, defining the program's focus, and administering 
initial grants.
<p>
The project will focus primarily on supporting the 
development of an independent media, especially radio, and 
the dissemination of educational programming for the media 
on such issues as health and human rights at the grassroots 
level. 
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="goals"></a>
<h2>
     What are the goals of the project?
</h2>
     The Southern Africa Project supports organizations that cultivate the 
     development of independent media (especially radio) as well as 
     educational programming for the media on such topics as health care 
     and human rights. 
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="eligible"></a>
<h2>
     Who is eligible for funding?
</h2>
     The Project welcomes proposals from all countries in the Southern 
     African region. Initially, the Project will focus on Angola, Malawi, 
     Mozambique, Namibia, Zambia and Zimbabwe. Priority is given to 
     grassroots initiatives and innovative programs that contribute to the 
     development of a more diverse and vigorous civil society. 
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="osi"></a>
<h2>
     What is the Open Society Institute?
</h2>
     Based in New York, the Open Society Institute (OSI) is a nonprofit 
     foundation established in 1993 to promote the development of open 
     societies around the world. Toward this goal, the institute operates 
     and/or supports a variety of initiatives and projects in education, 
     independent media, legal reform and human rights. OSI is part of a 
     network of independent nonprofit organizations located in 22 countries 
     in Central and Eastern Europe, the former Soviet Union, Haiti, and 
     South Africa.
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="apply"></a>
<h2>
     How do I apply for funding?
</h2>
     Applications for funding should be mailed to the address below and 
     should include the following:
<br>
<ol>
<li> A statement that clearly describes the goals and objectives  of 
     your organization and/or project. The statement should also include 
     information about the organization and/or project's past activities 
     and accomplishments, as well as a description of how the planned 
     activity will be carried out.
<li> A list of your organization's executives, essential program 
     staff, and board members.
<li> A detailed budget that includes salaries, rent, equipment and 
     supplies, communications, travel, printing         costs, as well as 
     any other costs the project is likely to incur.
<li> A statement specifying how much money is being sought and over 
     what period of time funds will be  used and for what specific 
     activities. 
<li> A list of present and future sources of funding, if any, as well 
     as a plan for securing funding for future phases beyond the project 
     grant period.
</ol> 
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="send"></a>
<h2>
     Where do I send my application?
</h2>
<pre>
<b>
     Program Officer 
     Southern Africa Project 
     Open Society Institute 
     888 Seventh Avenue, 27th Floor 
     New York, N.Y. 10106  
     Telephone:  (212) 887-0631 or 887-0698 
     Fax: (212) 974-0367 
</b>
</pre>
<address> 
<img align=middle src="/images/mail.gif"> E-Mail: Ms. Kim Brice <a href="mailto:kbrice@sorosny.org"><b>kbrice@sorosny.org</b></a>
</address>    
