<head> 
<title> OSI Fellowships Program </title> 
</head> 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3"> 
<table cellpadding=6>
<tr> 
<td> <img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif"> 
<td> <img
align=middle src="/images/fellow.gif" alt="Fellowships Program"> </td>
</tr> 
</table> 
<center> <b>
CALL FOR APPLICATIONS AND NOMINATIONS 
</b> </center> 
<h3> Program Development Fellowships </h3> 
The Open Society
Institute (OSI) invites applications and nominations for Program
Development Fellowships. <p> 

Program Development Fellowships are awarded
to individuals on the basis of their qualifications to assist the Open
Society Institute in the development and implementation of new program
initiatives in the United States. For the Program Development Fellowships,
individuals may either submit their own applications or be nominated for
the fellowship. 
<p>
Program Development Fellows reside in New York for the period of the
fellowship, and are provided with an office and support services at the
Open Society Institute. Fellows also participate in a variety of programs
organized on their behalf. The Fellowships are awarded for a term of up to
18 months, and may be renewed for up to another 18 months. 
<p>
The Open Society Institute welcomes applications and nominations in the
following areas: 
<ul>
<li>inner-city problems that have contributed to the hardening of divisions
along the lines of race and class, including the failure to assist
families and to provide community support for education, resulting in the
inadequate preparation of large numbers of children for life; 
 
<li>the promotion of noncommercial approaches to culture, journalism, and
professions such as law and medicine; 
 
<li>the reinvigoration of professional, civic, and political ethics and
community service, with particular interest in political campaigns,
finances, and reform; 
 
<li>immigration, citizenship, and civic identity;
 
<li>the impact on the poor of the devolution of welfare responsibility to
the states; 
 
<li>alternatives to law enforcement in reducing the harm caused by drug abuse;
 
<li>the enhancement of comfort, dignity, relief from pain, and family
support for the dying; 
 
<li>the problem of crime and the increasing reliance on imprisonment that
has resulted in a soaring incarceration rate; 
 
<li>other crucial issues affecting the development of an open society in the
United States. 
</ul>
<h3>
How to Apply
</h3>

To apply, applicants should submit a resume with a cover letter of up to
1,000 words indicating the area or areas in which they wish to work and
the nature of their interest and expertise in the area. Applicants should
provide the names and contact information for three references, along with
information on the nature of the referees' relationship to the applicant.
Finalists for Program Development Fellowships will also be asked to
provide information on salary needs.  The Fellowship will provide medical
coverage and other benefits. 
<p>
<h3>
How to Nominate
</h3>
Persons wishing to nominate others for Program Development Fellowships
should submit to OSI a letter, not to exceed 1,000 words, which sets forth
the nominee's qualifications to assist OSI in developing new programs,
along with information about the nominee's work history and
accomplishments.  If OSI wishes to consider the nomination further, the
nominee will be contacted directly. 
<p>
<h3>
Review of Applications
</h3>

Applications for Program Development Fellowships will be reviewed by a
selection committee that includes members of the Open Society Institute
board of directors. 
<p>
<h3>
Application Deadlines
</h3>
Our 1997 deadline has not yet been determined, however will not occur 
before May 30th.
<p>
There is no formal application to fill out for our program. 
You need only to follow our guidelines.
<p>
If you would like our new and revised guidelines, which will be ready in a 
few months, please call 212-887-0119 to leave your name and address.  
You will be included in our mailing list and will automatically receive 
the guidelines.  Be advised that we will not fax any information; 
we will email you the guidelines if you clearly spell out your email address.
<p>
Submit applications or nominations in triplicate to:
<p>
<b>
OSI Fellowships<br>
Open Society Institute<br>
888 Seventh Avenue<br>
New York, NY 10106<br>
</b>
<p>
NOTE: Applications sent by fax or e-mail will not be considered. Finalists
for Program Development Fellowships will be invited to take part in
interviews. No information on the status of applications will be provided
prior to the public announcement of fellowship recipients approximately
three months following the application deadline. 
<p>
<center>
<b>
CALL FOR APPLICATIONS
</b>
</center>
<h3>
Individual Project Fellowships
</h3>
Individual Project Fellowships are awarded to writers, scholars, and
others from a range of professions pursuing research, writing, or other
efforts to foster the development of open society, either in the United
States or internationally, on the basis of proposals describing the
projects. 
<p>
Proposals may address any issues crucial to fostering the principles and
values of an open society either in the United States or globally. 
Broadly speaking, an open society is characterized by a reliance on the
rule of law, the existence of a democratically elected government, a
diverse and vigorous civil society, and respect for minorities and
minority opinions.  Areas of interest include: 
<p>
<ul>
<li>the management of the explosive growth of "mega-cities," improving the
effectiveness of intergovernmental institutions, and the promotion of
reproductive health and choice, in the United States and throughout the
world; 

<li>inner-city problems that have contributed to the hardening of divisions
along the lines of race and class and the inadequate preparation of large
numbers of children for life, including the failure to assist families and
to provide community support for education; 
 
<li>the promotion of noncommercial approaches to culture, journalism, and
professions such as law and medicine; 
 
<li>the reinvigoration of professional, civic, and political ethics and
community service, with particular interest in political campaigns,
finances, and reform; 
 
<li>immigration, citizenship, and civic identity;
 
<li>the impact on the poor of the devolution of welfare responsibility to
the states; 
 
<li>alternatives to law enforcement in reducing the harm caused by drug abuse;
 
<li>the enhancement of comfort, dignity, relief from pain, and family
support for the dying; 
 
<li>the problem of crime and the increasing reliance on imprisonment that
has resulted in a soaring incarceration rate; 
 
<li>other crucial issues affecting the development of an open society in the
United States and internationally. 
</ul>
<h3>
Individual Project Fellowships 
</h3>
Individual Project Fellowships are awarded for a term of up to 18 months,
and may be renewed for up to another 18 months.  Applicants should submit
a proposal which includes: 
<ol>
<li>
a project summary of 200 to 400 words;

<li>
a project description of between 2,000 and 4,000 words;

<li>
a description of the goals of the project, the method of carrying it
out, and its relationship to work that has been done and is being done in
the field; 

<li>
a budget proposal that states research and travel costs and related
expenditures.  Individual Project Fellowship awards will range from
$15,000 to $100,000 for a term of up to 18 months. The budget may not
include institutional overhead costs. Other actual or potential sources of
funding must be disclosed. If the budget proposal includes a request for
salary, the availability of a concurrent salary from any other institution
(including sabbatical salaries) or of book advances must be disclosed; 

<li>
two letters of reference, to be mailed under separate cover directly to
the Open Society Institute, and a copy of the candidate's resume. 
</ol>
<h3>
Application Deadlines
</h3>
Our 1997 deadline has not yet been determined, however will not occur 
before May 30th.
<p>
There is no formal application to fill out for our program. 
You need only to follow our guidelines.
<p>
If you would like our new and revised guidelines, which will be ready in a 
few months, please call 212-887-0119 to leave your name and address.  
You will be included in our mailing list and will automatically receive 
the guidelines.  Be advised that we will not fax any information; 
we will email you the guidelines if you clearly spell out your email address.
<p>
<p>
Submit applications in triplicate to:
<p>
<b>
OSI Fellowships<br>
Open Society Institute<br>
888 Seventh Avenue<br>
New York, NY 10106<br>
</b>
<p>

NOTE: Applications sent by fax or e-mail will not be considered.
<p>
<h3>
Review of Applications
</h3>

Applications for Individual Project Fellowships will be reviewed by a
selection committee that includes members of the Open Society Institute
board of directors.  Consultants with knowledge of the field addressed by
Individual Project Fellowship proposals may be asked for comments to be
submitted confidentially to the selection committee. 
<p>
No information on the status of applications will be provided prior to the
public announcement of fellowship recipients approximately three months
following the application deadline. 
<p>
