<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html>                                                                          
<head>                                                                          
<meta name="description" content="Constitutional and Legislative Policy Institute (COLPI), Soros Foundations Network, Open Society Institute and National Foundations created and funded by George Soros">               
<meta name="keywords" content="Constitutional and Legislative Policy Institute (COLPI), Open Society Institute, George Soros, Soros Foundations, Open Society Institute - Budapest">                                     
<title> 
Constitutional and Legislative Policy Institute (COLPI)
</title>                                                                        
</head>                                                                         
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table cellpadding=6>                                                 
<tr>                                                                  
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                       
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/colpi.gif" alt="Constitutional and Legislative Policy Institute">
</td>                                                                 
</tr>                                                                 
</table>                                                              
<a name="top"></a>
<center>
<b>
|
<a href="http://www.osi.hu/colpi">COLPI Web Site</a> |
<a href="#development">Development of Legal Institutions</a> |
<a href="#education">Legal Education</a> |<br>
|
<a href="#civil">Development of Civil Society</a> |
<a href="#other">Other Activities</a> |
</b>
</center>
<p>
The Constitutional and Legislative Policy Institute (COLPI) 
helps countries in Central and Eastern Europe and the former 
Soviet Union develop into states based on the rule of law. 
The institute's activities and projects in 1995 were aimed 
at supporting legal institutions and processes that 
ultimately create and maintain effective and accountable 
government. These activities include the development of 
legal institutions, legal education, and civil society. The 
institute is committed to working with local not-for-profit 
organizations, universities, government officials, and other 
foreign assistance organizations seeking to promote similar 
goals and initiatives.
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a><p>
<a name="development"></a>
<b>Development of Legal Institutions</b><br>
A rule-of-law state requires, at minimum, a set of 
institutional arrangements, constitutions, laws, and a 
judicial system. The precise shape and characteristics of 
these institutions will vary according to the public 
policies, political dynamics, and legal traditions of each 
country. 
To limit the arbitrariness of state action, these 
institutions should be well-crafted, with transparent, 
workable guidelines and regulations. 
By providing technical and expert assistance, COLPI seeks to  
ensure that the development of these institutions is 
consistent with international standards.
<p>
In 1995, the institute began a comprehensive research 
project on administrative law reform, an area designated by 
many as the target of second generation legal reforms. This 
research will be used as basic reference materials for 
governments in the region as they reform their systems. 
Other projects undertaken in 1995 included providing 
technical and expert advice on Albania's Mass Media Bill, 
the Latvian Criminal Code, and the Constitutional Court Bill 
in Georgia.
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a><p>
<a name="education"></a>
<b>Legal Education</b><br>
Crucial to the aim of decreasing the arbitrariness of state 
action is quality legal education of law professionals, both 
in government (judges, legislators) and outside (law 
faculty, law students, private lawyers). Having well-trained 
government lawyers, particularly judges, helps ensure that 
the rules by which the state regulates social and economic 
behavior and resolves disputes are clear and known to the 
population. Well-trained lawyers outside government play a 
significant role in checking excesses of state power, either 
by challenging state actions or by working to improve the 
legal system. 
<p>
In 1995, COLPI was involved in judicial training programs in 
Bulgaria, Hungary, and Latvia. A workshop in Eger encouraged 
judges to apply Hungarian constitutional principles in their 
resolution of individual cases. The institute organized 
short term training sessions on English legal terminology 
and substantive legal topics for law students in Lithuania, 
Ukraine, and Tajikistan. A three-week faculty training 
session in Budapest for law faculties from Ukraine, Belarus, 
and Moldova focused on teaching methodologies and pedagogy 
in legal education.
During 1995, COLPI worked closely with the Donetsk Human 
Rights School in drafting a human rights curriculum and 
organizing five training sessions for high school teachers 
in Donetsk Oblast, Ukraine. The institute, in collaboration 
with the Center for International Documentation and Economic 
Crime in Cambridge, UK, organized a training seminar on 
corruption and economic crimes for leading prosecutors from 
East Central Europe and the former Soviet Union.
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a><p>
<a name="civil"></a>
<b>Development of Civil Society</b><br>
The development of civil society, particularly in the legal 
sector, is the third component that is crucial in assuring 
that the state does not abuse its power or exercise it 
arbitrarily. Nongovernmental or grassroots organizations 
perform at least two significant functions. First, such 
organizations can directly challenge governmental actions. 
Second, these organizations can play a constructive role in 
the structural reform process by initiating or lobbying for 
new legislation. COLPI will support NGOs that provide legal 
services to vulnerable groups-such as human rights victims 
and the disabled-and legal training to members of the legal 
profession. In the fall of 1995, for example, COLPI, the 
International Helsinki Federation, and the International 
Human Rights Law Group held a workshop to train human rights 
organizations.
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a><p>
<a name="other"></a>
<b>Other Activities</b><br>
COLPI has also helped the national foundations in Albania, 
Belarus, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Kazakstan, 
Lithuania, Moldova, and Romania develop their own law 
programs. In 1995, COLPI published <i>Corruption and Democracy</i>,
based on papers presented at a conference the previous year 
on "Political Institutions, Processes, and Corruption in 
States in Transition," and prepared for publication a 
handbook outlining cases of the Hungarian Constitutional 
Court. The book aims to increase awareness of constitutional 
principles among Hungarian judges, many of whom received 
their legal training prior to the establishment of the 
Constitutional Court.
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a><p>
<center>                                                                        
