<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html>                                                                          
<head>                                                                          
<meta name="description" content="Education Program Support Unit (EPSU), Soros Foundations Network, Open Society Institute and National Foundations created and funded by George Soros">               
<meta name="keywords" content="Education Program Support Unit (EPSU), Open Society Institute, George Soros, Soros Foundations, Open Society Institute - Budapest">                                     
<title>
Education Program Support Unit (EPSU)
</title>                                                                        
</head>                                                                         
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table cellpadding=6>                                                 
<tr>                                                                  
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                       
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/epsu.gif" alt="Education Program Support Unit">
</td>                                                                 
</tr>                                                                 
</table>                                                              
<a name="top"></a>
     
Quality education beginning at the preschool level is 
crucial to development of open society. Students who are 
encouraged to become active participants in their own 
education, express and support their own theories, and make 
educated choices in learning options, are likely to carry 
the values of discourse, respect for the rights of others, 
and participation in democratic processes into their adult 
lives. To support and develop education for an open society, 
<a href="osibuda.html"><b>OSI-Budapest</b></a> 
and the network of 
<a href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a>
created 
and funded by 
<a href="gsbio.html"><b>George Soros</b></a> 
invested tens of millions of 
dollars in education programs for primary and secondary 
schools in 1995. 
<p>
The countries of Central and Eastern Europe and the former 
Soviet Union are faced with educational needs ranging from 
simply keeping education alive, to retraining teachers and 
developing new curricula, to providing schools with 
computers and access to the Internet. While not all 
foundations focus on education to the same extent, the 
network, both in regional programs and national foundation 
initiatives, places a great emphasis on programs for school-
aged populations. 
<p>
The Education Program Support Unit (EPSU) was formed in mid-
1995 to help the foundations maximize the impact of their 
programs in primary and secondary education. In September 
1995, the EPSU hosted "Education for an Open Society" in 
Budapest. This conference, attended by education 
coordinators from the national foundations, was held to 
clarify the role of the foundations in education, build 
closer collaboration among foundations, and develop an 
exchange of ideas, practical models, and tools useful for 
education programs. Conference participants identified three 
priorities for their work in education: promoting and 
providing an example of open society in education; building 
partnerships with donors, ministries, and communities; and 
achieving sustainability for programs introduced by the 
national foundations.
<p>
The Education Program Support Unit sponsors seminars and 
workshops on specific topics, promotes information exchange 
among the foundations, and provides access to resources. As 
an initial response to the need for increased information 
exchange within the network, the unit disseminated the first 
issue of Open Society Education Update 
via e-mail in December 1995. This newsletter, issued 
periodically and distributed throughout the network, focuses 
on national foundation education initiatives and possible 
areas of cooperation among the 
foundations.
<p>
At the request of individual foundations, the unit directly 
assists in developing or rethinking education programs. 
Drawing on expertise within the network and using outside 
specialists when necessary, the EPSU helps foundations 
evaluate the needs in a particular country's education 
system, consider the impact of existing programs, and assist 
in developing new programs and modifying existing programs. 
In 1995, the EPSU provided direct assistance in program 
development to foundations in 
<a href="albania.html"><b>Albania</b></a>, 
<a href="bosnia.html"><b>Bosnia and Herzegovina</b></a>, 
<a href="kazakh.html"><b>Kazakstan</b></a>, 
<a href="kyrgyz.html"><b>Kyrgyzstan</b></a>, 
<a href="lithuan.html"><b>Lithuania</b></a>, 
<a href="macedon.html"><b>Macedonia</b></a>, 
<a href="moldova.html"><b>Moldova</b></a>, and 
<a href="russia.html"><b>Russia</b></a>.
<p>
<center>                                                                        
