<head>                                                                          
<meta name="description" content="Institute For Local Government and Public Service - ILGPS, Soros Foundations Network, Open Society Institute and National Foundations created and funded by George Soros">               
<meta name="keywords" content="Institute For Local Government and Public Service - ILGPS, Open Society Institute, George Soros, Soros Foundations, Open Society Institute - Budapest">                                     
<title>
Institute For Local Government and Public Service - ILGPS 
</title>                                                                        
</head>                                                                         
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table cellpadding=6>                                                 
<tr>                                                                  
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                       
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/ilgps.gif" alt="Institute for Local Government and Public Service">         
</td>                                                                 
</tr>                                                                 
</table>                                                              
<a name="top"></a>
 
The euphoria of wresting national independence and personal 
freedom from centralized control has been replaced in much 
of Central and Eastern Europe by anxiety about finding a way 
to responsibly and effectively exercise those freedoms. 
Local governments and universities face especially harsh 
challenges in this regard. 
<p>
For local governments, this anxiety is intensified by the 
scarcity of fiscal resources; the demands of integrating 
into a competitive world economy; the pervasive changes in 
attitude required to transform sociopolitical cultures that 
generally lacked individualism and decentralized decision 
making; and the tenacity of centralized control accompanied 
by the shift of responsibility to local and regional 
governments to provide public services.
<p>
Notwithstanding such difficulties, enormous energy is 
exerted by advocates of local self-determination, by local 
legislative and administrative public servants, and by 
public administration educators throughout the region.  The 
Institute of Local Government and Public Service (ILGPS) was 
created to assist them during this transitional period by 
helping to institutionalize the existence of and capacity 
for local self-determination. Charged with the primary 
mission of promoting local government reform, ILGPS 
completed its second full year of operation in 1995 by 
emphasizing initiatives in public administration education, 
training for local public servants, and the creation of the 
preconditions for local self-governance.
<p>
The institute's additional mission is to help enhance the 
administration of institutions of higher education, with 
special but not exclusive attention to those singled out for 
assistance by 
<a href="hesp.html"><b>International HESP</b></a>. 
The emphasis has been on 
direct assistance to enhance the capacity of selected 
universities within the general objective of establishing a 
professional culture of higher education leadership that 
extends beyond central education ministries.
<p>
University administration, also hampered by a lack of funds, 
faces the additional hindrances of the continuing 
overspecialization of education, a lack of professional 
managerial preparation of those in leadership positions, and 
the contradictory demands of centralized regulatory control 
balanced against localized economic dependency. 
<p>
The institute's strategy is to establish and strengthen 
institutional capacity in the region to address issues of 
local government reform and university administration 
reform. Tactics include close working collaborations with 
the 
<a href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a> 
and identifying motivated 
individuals and projects with the potential to enhance 
institutional capacity. Some initiatives are multinational 
in scope, others are local pilot demonstrations of solutions 
that might be applicable regionally, still others are 
country-specific responses to indigenous needs.
<p>
In the field of public administration education, ILGPS 
during 1995 helped to create an operating network of 
institutes and schools of public administration throughout 
the region; provided advice on public administration 
curricula in more than a dozen countries; instilled case 
study teaching and writing skills in public administration 
educators from throughout the region; and provided a 
postgraduate summer program in the 
<a href="czech.html"><b>Czech Republic</b></a> 
for Masters of Public Affairs degree students from more than ten 
countries. 
<p>
The training of local government public servants, and 
especially the preparation of training materials and the 
training of trainers, was provided to municipal executives 
in Russia, municipal legislators in 
<a href="romania.html"><b>Romania</b></a> and 
<a href="moldova.html"><b>Moldova</b></a>, and 
a variety of public servants in 
<a href="slovakia.html"><b>Slovakia</b></a> and 
<a href="belarus.html"><b>Belarus</b></a>. 
Recognizing that public administration education and civil 
servant training are not, in and of themselves, sufficient 
to achieve local government reform, ILGPS increasingly 
coupled education and training initiatives with efforts to 
promote local governance. This approach was evidenced by 
civic and local self-determination advocacy projects 
underway in 
<a href="slovakia.html"><b>Slovakia</b></a>, 
<a href="belarus.html"><b>Belarus</b></a>, and 
<a href="albania.html"><b>Albania</b></a>.
<p>
In university administration, ILGPS helped to improve the 
long-term financial planning of 14 higher education 
institutions from ten countries; to enhance self-assessment 
and associated accreditation knowledge of universities from 
the Czech Republic and Slovakia; and to develop the skills 
of university outreach officers. Among other initiatives in 
1995 were the creation of a network of university 
administrators in Romania, enhancement of financial planning 
expertise at the University of Vilnius, and improvements in 
the administration and strategic planning of universities in 
Kyiv, Minsk, and St. Petersburg.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
