<a name="about"></a>
<h2>
About the Program
</h2>
The International Higher Education Support Program (HESP) 
supports the development of higher education in the 
humanities and social sciences in Central and Eastern Europe 
and the former Soviet Union. This is achieved through 
programs designed to help institutions and scholars in the 
region to integrate more fully into the international 
academic community. International HESP also helps 
universities and institutions of higher education in the 
region to become internationally recognized centers of 
excellence in teaching and research. International HESP 
program activities are divided into the three broad 
categories described below.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<p>
<a name="support"></a>
<h2>
Supported Institutions 
</h2>
In 1995, International HESP provided support to more than 20 
universities, university departments, and institutes 
throughout Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet 
Union. International HESP builds networks among these 
Supported Institutions and programs to create international 
partnerships and encourage the exchange of ideas, faculty, 
and students. International HESP funds supported everything 
from general operating costs to student stipends. Activities 
focused on supporting the internationalization of regional 
curricula, faculty, and network development. A Regional 
Mobility Scheme, introduced in 1995, provided support for 
academics from across Central and Eastern Europe and the 
former Soviet Union to visit the 
<a href="ceu.html"><b>Central European University</b></a>
in either Budapest, Prague, or Warsaw. In 1996, Inter-
national HESP introduced additional Mobility Schemes for 
Supported Institutions to increase the regional mobility of 
students, faculty, 
and staff.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<p>
<a name="regional"></a>
<h2>
Regional Programs
</h2>
Regional Programs focus on transitional development and help 
maintain an environment in which academics can pursue 
scholarly activities in their own countries while keeping in 
touch with international developments in their field. The 
two primary regional programs are the Civic Education 
Project and the Research Support Scheme.
<p>
<b>The Civic Education Project (CEP)</b> assists reform efforts 
underway in the social science departments of various 
universities in the region. 
The project's Visiting Lecturer and Eastern Scholar programs 
send Western-trained scholars to universities throughout the 
region. The Eastern Scholar program focuses on the placement 
of Western-trained East European academics as Civic 
Education Project lecturers in the countries of the region. 
CEP lecturers teach courses in their specialties in English, 
French, German, and, in some cases, the local language. In 
addition, they cooperate with their host universities to 
improve social science education by assisting in the design 
of new curricula, developing local-language teaching 
materials, securing book donations, seeking research funds, 
and identifying opportunities for talented faculty and 
students to receive training abroad.
<p>
<b>The Research Support Scheme (RSS)</b> supports individuals and 
groups of scholars who wish to carry out innovative research 
in the social sciences and humanities on Central and Eastern 
European issues. Preference is given to groups of 
researchers with participants from two or more countries who 
are studying a generic issue or a particular theme from a 
multinational perspective. Interdisciplinary research is 
encouraged. The RSS grantees carry out new and exploratory 
international research work in fields vital to the 
development of education in the region. In 1996, 
International HESP will implement the RSS Fellowship 
Program, which will enable universities in the region to 
appoint former RSS grantees to teach courses based on their 
research. The program is designed to utilize the growing 
pool of researchers in the region and to provide access to 
the results of research to a wide audience. The RSS receives 
more than 1,200 applications a year, and awards grants to 
roughly 20 percent of applicants.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<p>
<a name="ceu"></a>
<h2>
Cooperation with the Central European University (CEU)
</h2>
A number of International HESP programs utilize and 
strengthen CEU expertise by enabling close cooperative 
contacts with regional universities and scholars. The 
Curriculum Resource Center, one of the most successful of 
these programs, invites teachers who are establishing new 
programs and developing curricula at their home institution 
to the CEU for intensive week-long periods of syllabi 
review, library work, and meetings with CEU faculty and 
staff. The Popper Project furthers the teachings of Karl 
Popper by hosting workshops for teachers and translators on 
the problems of transforming closed societies into more open 
ones. The Inter-Regional Faculty Seminar on Gender and 
Culture gathers scholars from the region to explore and 
reconceptualize issues of vital importance in gender and 
women's studies.
<p> <a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<p>
