<html>                                                                          
<head>                                                                          
<meta name="description" content="Open Society Archives, Soros Foundations Network, Open Society Institute and National Foundations created and funded by George Soros">               
<meta name="keywords" content="Open Society Archives, Open Society Institute, George Soros, Soros Foundations, Open Society Institute - Budapest">
<title>
Open Society Archives
</title>                                                                        
</head>                                                                         
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table cellpadding=6>                                                 
<tr>                                                                  
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                       
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/osa.gif" alt="Open Society Archives">         
</td>                                                                 
</tr>                                                                 
</table>                                                              
<a name="top"></a>

Founded in Budapest in 1995, the Open Society Archives has 
three missions: to establish and maintain a research center 
focusing on communism, the Cold War, and human rights 
issues; to provide records and information management 
support to the Soros foundation network; and to provide 
support for archives and preservation activities in Central 
and Eastern Europe.
<p>
A samizdat document from Russia, a statement by Czechoslovak 
Roma in support of the Dubcek government in 1968, an 
authentic Polish joke-these are just a few of the items held
by the Open Society Archives, which include the records of 
the Research Institute of Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty 
(RFE/RL). Throughout late autumn and winter of 1995, the 
archives received a steady stream of research requests and 
visits. Anyone may apply to use its resources and 
noncirculating library.
<p>
In 1995 and the first half of 1996, the archives' first
priority was to establish basic intellectual control over 
its documents, including audiovisual materials, microfilm, 
and microfiche, through a program of arrangement, 
description, and relocation. The initial work concentrated 
on the Bulgarian, Hungarian, Polish, and Yugoslav files. 
<p>
As the Open Society Archives' operations and holdings 
constantly expand, one of the main activities throughout 
1995 was the development of new storage space. Coordinating 
with architects, 
<a href="osibuda.html"><b>OSI-Budapest</b></a>, and the 
<a href="ceu.html"><b>Central European University</b></a>, 
the archives plans to open a facility with 
exhibition areas, research rooms, offices, archival storage 
space, and archival processing areas on the same city block 
as the university.  
<p>
The Open Society Archives maintains an 
<a href="http://www.osa.ceu.hu"><b>Internet site</b></a> that 
presents information about the archives, how to gain access 
for research purposes, and descriptions of the archives and 
its library holdings. A special site provides technical 
information for archivists in both English 
and Russian. 
<p>
The archives will initiate several programs in the coming 
year, 
including "Managing Modern Archives," a summer course at
CEU; 
an oral history program of RFE/RL; a planned 1997 exhibition 
of 
nonconformist Russian art from 1956-1986; and a regional 
archival support program.
<p>
By the end of April 1996, the archives had 21 full-time 
staff members, three part-time members, and two academic 
advisors, among whom are specialists in electronic records 
management, audiovisual archives, archival description, oral 
history, and computer references services. Altogether 11 
different nationalities are represented by the staff. 
<p>
<center>                                                                        
