<html>                                                                          
<head>                                                                          
<meta name="description" content="Regional Library Program, Soros Foundations Network, Open Society Institute and National Foundations created and funded by George Soros">               
<meta name="keywords" content="Regional Library Program, Open Society Institute, George Soros, Soros Foundations, Open Society Institute - Budapest">
<title>
Regional Library Program
</title>                                                                        
</head>                                                                         
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table cellpadding=6>                                                 
<tr>                                                                  
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                       
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/library.gif" alt="Regional Library Program">
</td>                                                                 
</tr>                                                                 
</table>                                                              
<a name="top"></a>
<center>
<b>
| <a href="#about">About the Program</a> | <A HREF="#activities">Activities in 
1996</A> | 
<a href="#links">Related Links</a> | 
</b>
</center>
<p>    
Libraries in Central and Eastern Europe and the former 
Soviet Union face many problems as they adjust to 
decentralized management and attempt to provide open access 
to information. In some countries of the region, libraries 
have been neglected for decades. In others, libraries 
struggle to survive under newly constrained conditions.
<p>
In 1995, the Regional Library Program (RLP) developed long-
term plans for assisting the development of the region's
library and information infrastructure. The programs placed 
the highest priority on providing training workshops in 
management and automation. In 1995, the RLP sponsored three-
day management workshops for 20 librarians in 
<a href="albania.html"><b>Albania</b></a>, 
<a href="belarus.html"><b>Belarus</b></a>, 
<a href="bulgaria.html"><b>Bulgaria</b></a>, the 
<a href="czech.html"><b>Czech Republic</b></a>, 
<a href="estonia.html"><b>Estonia</b></a>, 
<a href="hungary.html"><b>Hungary</b></a>, 
<a href="latvia.html"><b>Latvia</b></a>, 
<a href="lithuan.html"><b>Lithuania</b></a>, 
<a href="macedon.html"><b>Macedonia</b></a>, 
<a href="moldova.html"><b>Moldova</b></a>, 
<a href="poland.html"><b>Poland</b></a>, 
<a href="romania.html"><b>Romania</b></a>, 
<a href="slovakia.html"><b>Slovakia</b></a>, and 
<a href="slovenia.html"><b>Slovenia</b></a>. 
The workshops were concerned with 
managing change in library and information services, project 
management, staff and personnel management, and collection 
development. 
<p>
Library automation has the potential to save time and money. 
In countries where libraries have operated with a system of 
closed stacks, automation also has the potential to quickly 
and cheaply multiply the amount of information a library can 
provide to its users both inside and outside the country. In 
1995, the RLP supported a number of small-scale automation 
projects. Before supporting library automation on a wider 
scale, however, the RLP is focusing on providing automation 
training workshops for librarians. During the past year, the 
RLP held such workshops in 
<a href="albania.html"><b>Albania</b></a>, 
<a href="estonia.html"><b>Estonia</b></a>, and 
<a href="ukraine.html"><b>Ukraine</b></a>. 
The RLP also supported the attendance of 24 librarians at 
the 1995 Fifth World Congress of Slavic Librarians and 36 
librarians at the International Federation of Library 
Associations' Annual Meeting. In addition, the RLP supported 
28 collaborative projects between institutions in the region 
and their counterparts in the West, including exchange 
programs, seminars and workshops, and collaborative 
research.
<p>
At the beginning of  1995,  the Regional Library Program 
took over responsibility for the Library of Congress/Soros 
Fellows Program. Over the past three years, the Soros 
Fellows Program had sponsored 12 librarians from the region 
to study at the Library of Congress for three months. In 
1995, the Library of Congress proposed adding a new work-
study component to the program. Through this program, the 
librarians from the region will be placed within libraries 
throughout the Washington, DC, metropolitan area for a 
period of three weeks.
<p>
Following the example of the Library of Congress/Soros 
Fellows Program, a similar program was initiated in 
cooperation with the British Library. During its first year, 
this program was limited to four librarians from Russia. The 
RLP, however, would like to offer this program to librarians 
from other countries, and the British Library has agreed to 
accept two librarians from two countries each year. In 1996, 
librarians from Albania and Lithuania will participate in 
the program.
<p>
Working in conjunction with the 
<a href="isf.html"><b>International Science Foundation</b></a>, 
the RLP also supported a program to provide 
libraries in the region with important Western scientific 
journals. The International Science Foundation supported the 
purchase of journals within the former Soviet Union, while 
the RLP funded a similar journal donation program for ten 
countries outside the former Soviet Union- Albania, Bulgaria,
Croatia, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Macedonia, Poland, 
Romania, Slovakia, and Slovenia.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<hr>
<a name="about"></a>
<h2>
About the Program
</h2>
The Regional Library Program (RLP)  supports and advances all aspects of 
information science in 
Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union.  The RLP was established
as a separate
 program in February 1994. Previously the <a href="hesp.html"><B> Higher
Education Support Program</B></a > 
(HESP) had funded library projects. 
     
<P><B><U>Application Guidelines</U></B><BR>
The RLP only funds proposals that have been endorsed by the <a 
href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a> and have received matching  
funds. Application requirements are listed in calls for proposals issued by 
the RLP and 
advertised by the national foundations. The RLP's training and fellowship 
programs are also advertised by 
participating national foundations.</P>
     
<P><A HREF="coorlist.html"><B>Library coordinators</B></A> in the national 
foundation offices implement the Regional
Library Program on the national level.</P> 
<hr>
<a name="activities"></a>
<H2>Activities in 1996</H2>
<H3>Matching Funds Grants Program</H3>
<P> The RLP has been allocated $2 million to provide matching 
funding for proposals which have been endorsed by the national foundations. This
program can support 
proposals in all fields of library and information science, including automation
 and  collection development.  In addition, the RLP can to collaborate with
foundations both inside and outside of 
the Soros network to support proposals, on a matching funds basis, which have 
been endorsed by the 
national  foundations.  Those proposals which can demonstrate the highest level 
of matching funds 
are likely to be more favorably reviewed.  The RLP wishes to support projects 
primarily in the following areas: </P>
<OL>
<LI> <B>Library Automation.</B>  The RLP will support automation proposals from 
the 
 national foundations up to a grand total of $1,000,000 on a matching funds
basis.  In order 
 to encourage a range of projects, the RLP aims to support five projects at a
maximum of 
 $100,000 and a further ten projects for up to $50,000.
<P></P>
<LI> <B>Collaborative Projects.</B> The RLP will support collaborative proposals
from 
 the national  foundations up to a grand total of $800,000 on a matching funds
basis.  
 Projects in the range of $20,000 - $50,000 are anticipated.
<P></P>
<LI> <B>Collection Development.</B>  $200,000 is available for this purpose, but
the RLP will 
 not contribute more than $20,000 towards a single project.  For every three
dollars 
 that the national foundations or outside organizations are willing to
contribute to library collection development 
 proposals, the RLP will contribute a further one dollar. (1:3)
</OL>
<P></P>
<Center><A HREF="96mfcall.html"><B>Call for proposals: Matching Funds Grants 
Program</B></A>  (Deadline:
 October 11, 1996)</Center>
<P></P>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<hr>
<P></P>
<H3>Training Workshops</H3>
<UL>
<LI>        <B>Management and  Automation Workshops.</B><BR> Each country 
participating
   in the RLP has received or will receive both a management training workshop
and 
  an automation training workshop. These workshops are coordinated locally by
the 
   library coordinators within the national foudations.
<P></P>
     
<LI>  <B>Specialists Workshops.</B><BR> These are intended to build upon the 
series of  
  management and automation workshops above. Topics might 
  include: digitization, fundraising, intellectual freedom and access, grant 
  writing, retrospective conversion, document delivery, data conversion, 
  MARC, and CD-ROM networking.
</UL>
<P></P>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<hr>
<P></P> 
 <H3>Targeted Meetings</H3>
 <P>As part of its training program, the RLP sponsors the attendance of
middle-management
  librarians at selected conferences with particular relevance. In 1996, the RLP
 identified two major international 
 conferences to support:</P>
<P></P>
<UL>
<LI>  <B>Crimea 96 Conference in Foros, Ukraine, 1-9 June.</B><BR>The RLP 
sponsored
  thirty participants to the value of $500.  Remaining costs were  covered by
the national  foundations, a home institution,
   or alternative sources. 
<P></P>
<LI>  <B>American Library Association's Annual Conference, New York  
  City, 4-10 July.</B><BR>The RLP  sponsored 20 participants to the value of 
  $1,000.  Remaining costs were covered by the national foundations, a home
institution,
   or alternative sources.  
</UL>
<P></P>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<hr>
<P></P> 
<H3> Automation Conference</H3>
<P>The Regional Library Program and the
<A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/libraries/en/cee/homecee.html"><b>European Commission</b></A> 
jointly sponsored
an International Conference on Library Automation in Central & Eastern Europe,  
 held in Budapest from April 11-13, 1996. The goal of the conference was to
afford an opportunity for practising librarians 
from Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union to meet colleagues 
from across Europe and to share experiences and opportunities for collaboration 
in the areas of library automation, bibliographical standards, retrospective 
conversion, and document delivery.</P>
     
 <P> The conference program included presentations and workshops from Western
European
 librarians currently working on EU-funded projects and studies of potential
relevance and 
interest to librarians from Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet 
Union,
 as well as presentations by librarians within the region.</P>
     
<P></P>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<hr>
<P></P> 
 <H3>Electronic Document Delivery</H3>
 <P>To achieve the goal of providing researchers with access to all the
information they require 
 through a single terminal, it will be necessary to have the printed 
 material in electronic (digital) form, and to have in place 
 the electronic infrastructure for the delivery of the digitized material. While
the 
 Internet is becoming more readily available, there is much to be done to
develop 
 the necessary technical tools which might be used by libraries to send and
receive 
 electronically transmitted articles.</P>
     
 <P>During 1996 the RLP Board intends to determine a detailed strategy in this
area, which will encompass several distinct 
 areas relating to the development of the "Virtual Library": (a) electronic
document 
 and article delivery to Eastern European libraries working in collaboration
with 
 commercial vendors; (b) conversion into electronically readable form of
backruns 
 of journals out of copyright, and subsequent distribution of the digitized
product 
 to the academic community; (c) creation of an experimental electronic journal
of 
 relevance to libraries in the region.  
 </P>
<P></P>
<Center><A HREF="96edcall.html"><B>Call for proposals: Electronic Document 
Delivery</B></A>  (Deadline:
 October 11, 1996)</Center>
     
<P></P>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<hr>
<P></P>
 <H3>Preservation & Conservation</H3>
 <P>Conservation is an international problem for all libraries and there is a
need 
 in the region for the development of efficient and productive centers for book 
 preservation, workshops for repair, modern chemical facilities for paper 
 strengthening and conservation,  and mass deacidification facilities to stop
the slow 
 deterioration of 19th and 20th century holdings. The development of a training
program
 in preservation and conservation will be a high priority in 1996.</P>
<P></P>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<hr>
<P></P>
 <H3>Library Information Science Fellows Programs</H3>
<UL>
<LI>  <B>Library of Congress/Soros Intern Program</B><BR>
  The Library of Congress/Soros Intern Program sponsors twelve  
  librarians from the region to study at the <A HREF="http://lcweb.loc.gov/"><B>Library of Congress</B></A> for
  three months.  In 1996 the Library of Congress has added a new  work/study
element to  
  the program.  Through this program, the interns are placed within libraries 
  throughout the Washington, DC area for three weeks.
<P></P>
<LI>  <B>British Library Fellows Program</B><BR>
  Following the example of the Library of Congress program, a similar program
was 
  started in cooperation with the<A HREF="http://portico.bl.uk/"><B> British
Library</B></A> in 1995. The Library agreed to accept  
  two librarians from two countries each year. In 1996, librarians  
  from Albania and Lithuania participated in the program.
<P></P>
<LI>  <B>RLP Professional Scholarships</B><BR>
  During 1996 the RLP intends to offer to professors in schools of   
  librarianship in the region the opportunity to spend up to three months or  
  one semester at a library school in Western Europe or the USA.    
  Consultation has started with possible host institutions and once these  
  have been agreed, a call for applicants will be made to the national
foundations.
</UL>
<P></P>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
