<a name="about"></a>
<h2>
About the Program
</h2> 
The Regional Media Program assists the 
<a href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a> 
in developing and designing their media programs, which 
offer a wide variety of support to independent media in 
Central and Eastern Europe, the countries of the former 
Soviet Union, and South Africa. 
<p>
The Regional Media Program's goal is to foster better 
communication and cooperation among the national foundations 
and to help connect those organizations with potential 
outside partners. The Regional Media Program itself 
cooperates with a variety of other groups that support 
independent media.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<p>
In 1995, the Regional Media Program provided support in the 
following areas:
<p>
<a name="training"></a>
<h2>
Training and Development 
</h2>
	Open Channels, a project of AMARC-Europe, the regional 
arm of the World Association of Community Radio 
Broadcasters, featuring training and networking programs for 
local radio broadcasters, including study tours of 
established stations in Western and Eastern Europe.
<p>
	A year-long radio and television training program for 
journalists and technicians from Belarus, Moldova, and 
Ukraine, a cooperative effort of the International Media 
Center in Kyiv and Internews Network.
<p>
	A community radio support program in South Africa, 
designed for 
<a href="safrica.html"><b>OSF-South Africa</b></a>,
including planning and 
development, equipment, training, and program production.
<p>
	A radio training program organized by the national 
foundation in 
<a href="romania.html"><b>Romania</b></a> 
and the Center for Independent 
Journalism in Bucharest.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<p>
<a name="conferences"></a>
<h2>
Conferences
</h2>
	European Colloquium of News Agencies, bringing together 
representatives from state and independent news agencies to 
enable networking, discussion of common issues, and 
potential cooperation.
<p>
	First International Festival of Local TV Broadcasters, 
Kosice, Slovakia. Organized by City TV Foundation in Kosice, 
this first-ever event in Slovakia featured screenings, 
programming exchanges, workshops, a program competition, and 
an equipment fair for local broadcasters from throughout 
Europe.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<p>
<a name="fellowships"></a>
<h2>
Fellowships/Internships
</h2>
	Alfred Friendly Fellowships for journalists from 
Armenia, Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, and Estonia, 
consisting of six-month residencies at major print media 
organizations in the United States.
<p>
	Internship at the Lewiston Sun-Journal in Lewiston, 
Maine, for Dorian Ciocanu, a Moldovan print journalist.  
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
<p>
<a name="news"></a>
<h2>
News Exchanges
</h2>
	Continuing support for BalkanNet, an electronic-mail 
news exchange in the former Yugoslavia.
<p>
	Internews Network project, involving programming 
exchange, training, equipment, and technical support, 
designed to boost independent news programming at television 
stations in Azerbaijan, Armenia, Georgia, and southern 
Russia.
<p>
In 1995, the Regional Media Program helped establish the 
Media Development Loan Fund to support responsible, 
commercially viable independent media in an increasingly 
challenging and complex economic and political environment. 
The fund provides program-related investments-mainly low-
cost loans-to independent media organizations devoted to     
promoting democratic institutions and practices in their 
countries.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
