<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">                               
<html>                                                                          
<head>                                                                          
<meta name="description" content="OSI Regional Publishing Center, Soros Foundations Network, Open Society Institute and National Foundations created and funded by George Soros">               
<meta name="keywords" content="OSI Regional Publishing Center, Open Society Institute, George Soros, Soros Foundations, Open Society Institute - Budapest">
<title>
OSI Regional Publishing Center
</title>                                                                        
</head>                                                                         
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">                                                                               
<table cellpadding=6>                                                 
<tr>                                                                  
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                       
<td>                                                                  
<img align=middle src="/images/copress.gif" alt="Regional Publishing Center">
</td>                                                                 
</tr>                                                                 
</table>                                                              
<a name="top"></a>
<center>                                                                        
<b>                                                                             
| <a href="#translation">CEU Press Translation Project</a> | 
<a href="#support">Publishing Support Service</a> | 
<a href="#about">About the Center</a> | 
<a href="#links">Related Links</a> |                                            
</b>                                                                            
</center>                                                                       
<p>                                                                             
Books are an effective way to make the complex ideas and 
information needed by societies in transition permanently 
accessible to a large number of people. Publishing is thus 
an important component of many programs of the 
<a href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a>. 
The Regional Publishing Center was created in 
1995 to provide professional support for the publishing 
activities of the foundations and regional programs as well 
as to organize several new large-scale publishing projects 
of its own.  Some of these projects operate under the 
imprint name of the Central European University Press.
<p>
The Regional Publishing Center has two goals: First, to 
support the publication of books that promote critical 
thinking, high educational standards, intercultural 
understanding, and the values of open society. Second, to 
foster the development of a diverse and independent 
publishing industry, which is a vital component of civil 
society. 
<p>
<a name="translation"></a>
<h2>
CEU Press Translation Project
</h2>
Despite the changes in Central and Eastern Europe in recent 
years, there is still a drastic shortage of basic texts in 
the social sciences and humanities. These are books that 
play a vital role in any open society: they underpin higher 
education, sustain and enrich public discussions of social, 
political, and cultural issues, and provide the theoretical 
and practical knowledge needed for building new institutions 
and reforming old ones. In a majority of countries in the 
region, however, even the most fundamental texts in 
political science, economics, law, and sociology are 
unavailable in translation. The CEU Press Translation 
Project is an ambitious initiative designed to meet this 
need.
<p>
In 1995, the Translation Project was launched in 
<a href="albania.html"><b>Albania</b></a>, 
<a href="bulgaria.html"><b>Bulgaria</b></a>, 
<a href="poland.html"><b>Poland</b></a>, 
<a href="romania.html"><b>Romania</b></a>, and 
<a href="ukraine.html"><b>Ukraine</b></a>. 
In Romania, for 
example, a list of about 250 recommended titles compiled by 
CEU faculty was circulated to Romanian publishers. Through 
an open competition, 15 publishers were awarded grants to 
support the translation and publication of over 30 books 
from this list. These included classics by Kant, Weber, and 
Wittgenstein, core textbooks in economics, history, and 
sociology, and contemporary classics by writers like Michel 
Foucault, Hannah Arendt, and Isaiah Berlin. 
<p>
In 1996, the Translation Project will be extended to cover 
another 12 countries. Competitions for grants will be 
repeated annually, so that an average of 20 to 30 
translations will be published every year in each country.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="support"></a>
<h2>
Publishing Support Service
</h2>
In 1995, the Regional Publishing Center helped to manage or 
design publishing projects for national foundations in 
<a href="bulgaria.html"><b>Bulgaria</b></a>, 
<a href="georgia.html"><b>Georgia</b></a>, 
<a href="kazakh.html"><b>Kazakstan</b></a>, 
<a href="kyrgyz.html"><b>Kyrgyzstan</b></a>, 
<a href="moldova.html"><b>Moldova</b></a>, 
<a href="russia.html"><b>Russia</b></a>, and 
<a href="ukraine.html"><b>Ukraine</b></a>. 
The center also began administering a special 
program to support translations of the works of Karl Popper 
into local languages in Central and Eastern Europe and 
Central Asia. In 1996, the Regional Publishing Center will 
launch a Publishing Loan Fund and a Training Service to 
assist the development of the publishing industries in the 
region.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<hr>
<a name="about"></a>
<h2>
About the Center
</h2>
The OSI Regional Publishing Center operates under the imprint name of the Central European University Press. The program facilitates the publication, in the local languages of Central and Eastern Europe, of a wide range of books representing diverse ideas and perspectives. It also publishes, in English, books about Central and Eastern Europe for an international readership of academics, students, policy makers, journalists, and other interested individuals.<p>

Under the auspices of the Regional Publishing Center, the CEU Press is undertaking a broad-ranging translation project. The faculty of the <a href="ceu.html"><b>Central European University</b></a>, with help from the <a href="found.html"><b>national foundations</b></a>, has assembled for translation a long list of Western classics in the social sciences and humanities, especially titles considered relevant for societies in transition. The subjects covered are economics, political science, history, law, philosophy and sociology.<p>

Local publishers, many of whom are from the newly established private sector, undertake the publication of these books with financial assistance from the Regional Publishing Center. In this way the program supports the development of a strong and independent publishing industry.<p>

The first pilot project began in Romania in 1994 with over 30 titles selected for translation over a one-year period. Albania and Bulgaria were the next two countries to receive projects; other countries will be added in 1995. Collaboration with the <a href="hesp.html"><b>Higher Education Support Program</b></a> and the <a href="library.html"><b>Regional Library Program</b></a> assures that publishing expertise is shared and utilized effectively.<p>

In 1994, the CEU Press published a number of titles from the CEU Privatization Project, including two volumes of the Privatization Reports. Preparatory work was also undertaken in 1994 for the eventual publishing of the Radio Free Europe Archives on CD Rom.<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
