<a name="top"></a>
<center>
<b>
| <a href="#annual">From the 1995 Annual Report</a> |
<a href="#about">About the Institute</a> |
<a href="#publications">Publications and Programs</a> |<br>
| <a href="#subscription">Subscription Information</a> |
<a href="/press.html#omri">Press Release</a> |
<a href="http://www.omri.cz">OMRI Web Site</a> |
<a href="http://www.omri.cz/Publications/DD/Index.html">OMRI Daily Digest</a> |
</b>
</center>
<a name="annual"></a>
<h2>
From the 1995 Annual Report
</h2>
In its first full year of operation, the Open Media Research 
Institute (OMRI) has established itself as a recognized and 
respected center of research and publishing on Central and 
Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union. Built on the 
legacy of its predecessor organization, the Radio Free 
Europe/Radio Liberty Research Institute, OMRI became a 
totally private, nonprofit entity in 1995, extending its 
publishing base and inaugurating new initiatives and 
projects.
<p>
Establishment of OMRI's periodicals was a central activity 
in 1995, with the steady growth of existing publications as 
well as the launching of new products. Transition, a 
biweekly journal of news and analysis from the region, 
including articles, interviews, and special features, 
established a solid readership and enjoyed a 33 percent 
growth in subscriptions during the year. The OMRI Daily 
Digest, a six-page summary of the latest news from the 
region, also grew in popularity, especially its electronic 
mail version. A Russian-language version of the Daily Digest 
was made available through electronic mail providers in the 
former Soviet Union.
<p>
OMRI launched two new publications ventures in 1995: the 
OMRI Digest, a weekly newsletter covering economic and 
business news from the region; and periodic special reports, 
appended to the Daily Digest, providing more in-depth 
coverage to major ongoing events, such as the legislative 
election campaign in Russia and the implementation of the 
Dayton accords in Bosnia.
<p>
OMRI's reputation as a source of reliable, high-quality news 
and analysis of the region is evident not only in the 
growing popularity of its publications, but also in the 
range of educational and training projects it has initiated. 
In October, OMRI hosted a seminar for high-level official 
and nonofficial representatives from the region on the 
future of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in 
Europe. Senior diplomats, business leaders, and academics 
came to OMRI for roundtable discussions and briefings 
throughout 1995. OMRI analysts lectured at the 
<a href="ceu.html"><b>Central European University</b></a> 
and other universities.
<p>
Recognizing the importance of preparing rising generations 
of experts from the region, OMRI has been actively training 
students, journalists, and others in the skills of reporting 
and analysis. In an ongoing program, selected postgraduates 
from the region are matched with experienced OMRI analysts 
for ten months of on-the-job training. OMRI regularly lent 
its expertise to shorter training and information sessions 
for journalists and academics, including a workshop for 
local reporters covering minority issues, undertaken in late 
1995 with a grant from the UN High Commissioner for 
Refugees.
<p>
OMRI analysts have access to a wide variety of information 
collected from the region through specialized clipping 
services, document acquisitions, databases, and other media 
monitoring activities. The OMRI audience and opinion 
research department, based in Washington, DC, undertakes 
audience surveys and focus group studies together with 
analyses of audience media use in the former Soviet bloc. A 
recently initiated Distinguished Visitors Program will bring 
policy and academic experts to OMRI for lectures and 
discussions with OMRI analysts. 
<p>
In 1996, OMRI will continue to expand the reach of its 
publications and educational and training activities while 
deepening its commitment to comprehensive analysis of the 
issues and strengthening its links with institutions located 
or interested in the region.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   

<a name="about"></a>
<h2> 
About the Institute 
</h2> 
The Open Media Research
Institute is a research and publishing enterprise dedicated to studying
the changing societies of the former Soviet Union and Central and Eastern
Europe. It is a nonprofit public-private venture, funded jointly by the
United
 States Board for International Broadcasting and the <a
href="osiny.html"><b>Open Society Institute</b></a>, that has assumed and
expanded many of the functions of the now-closed Radio Free Europe/Radio
Liberty Research Institute.<p>

OMRI has a three-fold mission: to inform people worldwide about regional
affairs through the regular publication of analyses and news; to maintain
and make accessible the extensive Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty
Archives; and to train analysts and journalists from the region. Its home
offices are in the United States, with research offices in Prague.<p> <a
href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 

<a name="publications"></a>
<h2>
Publications and Programs
</h2> 
The institute's flagship publication is
Transition: Events and Issues in the Former Soviet Union and East Central
and Southeastern Europe, a journal of analysis and news focusing on
political, social, economic, military, foreign, media, legal, and 
cultural affairs in the region. Transition carries periodic special 
sections on
such topics as the media, foreign affairs, and the social costs of
transition. OMRI also publishes the OMRI Daily Digest, a six-page
compendium of news briefs compiled from a wide range of regional and
international sources. It is available each weekday free of charge on the
Internet.<p>

Future publications will include a media monitoring digest, a regional
news digest, and up-to-date handbooks. OMRI is also developing a network
of information sources throughout the region for monitoring media and
human rights issues. As well as publishing its research, OMRI cooperates
with RFE/RL broadcasters, providing them with research reports, program
briefs, press monitoring, and other services.<p>

As custodian of the vast RFE/RL archives, OMRI maintains materials older
than five years in a Budapest center in cooperation with the <a
href="ceu.html"><b>Central European University</b></a>. Newer materials
are housed in OMRI's Prague facility. The more
 than 15 million items document communist rule and the struggle for change during the post-World War II era in Eastern and Central Europe. The institute's collection of newspapers, periodicals, clippings, samizdat, and biographical holdings is open to the
 public; OSI has committed a minimum of $15 million over the next four
years to support this project.<p>

OMRI offers an internship program in cooperation with the Central European
University to train analysts from Central and Eastern Europe and the
former Soviet Union. OMRI will sponsor conferences and seminars treating
topics of current importance, including one on the role of former
dissidents in contemporary society and another on the media in Eastern
Europe and the former Soviet Union.<p> <a href="#top"><img align=middle
src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 

<a name="subscription"></a>
<h2> 
Subscription Information 
</h2>

To subscribe to Transition, please write, fax or send an e-mail request to:<p>
OMRI-Subscriptions Department<br>
Motokov Building<br>
Na Strzi  63<br>
140 62 Prague 4<br>
Czech Republic<br>
fax: (42) (2) 6114 3323<p>

For Transition: 
<a href="mailto:transition@omri.cz"><b>transition@omri.cz</b></a><p>

For OMRI Daily Digest:
<a href="mailto:omripub@omri.cz"><b>omripub@omri.cz</b></a><p>

Transition subscription rates are as follows:
<ul>
<li>Regular rate:                 $175/year
<li>Student rate:                 $85 (with certification of status) Multiple 
<li>subscriptions rate (five or more):     $130/year each
</ul>
<p>
Readers in the former Soviet Union or the following countries-- Albania, 
Bulgaria, Croatia, Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Macedonia, Poland, 
Romania, Serbia/Montenegro, Slovakia, and Slovenia--may apply for 
significantly reduced subscription rates. Phone, fax or email the 
Marketing Director for more details.<p>

The OMRI Daily Digest is available free of charge via the Internet. 
Those who do not have access to e-mail may contact OMRI for applicable 
fax and postal mail rates.<p>

Subscribe electronically by following these instructions: <ol> <li>Write
an e-mail message to: <a
href="mailto:listserv@ubvm.cc.buffalo.edu"><b>listserv@ubvm.cc.buffalo.edu</b></a>
<li>Leave the subject window blank <li>In the message area write:
subscribe OMRI-L yourfirstname yourlastname <li>Send the message. </ol>
<p> You should receive a confirmation message if your attempt was
successful. The Daily Digest will then be sent to you via e-mail every day
in two parts. If you have problems, notify OMRI at omripub@omri.cz.<p>

OMRI is a comprehensive resource for reliable information on Eastern
Europe and the former Soviet Union. Its basic objective is to support the
continuing evolution of the countries of this region toward stable
democratic systems and free market economies. 
 To these ends, we welcome suggestions concerning publications, archives
and other resources and programs.<p> <a href="#top"><img align=middle
src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a> 
