<a name="top"></a>
<h2>
From the 1995 Annual Report
</h2>
Two organizations involved in providing managers and 
professionals with the skills necessary to function and 
compete in a free market economy are the East-West 
Management Institute (EWMI) and the Soros Business and 
Management Foundation (SBMF). These foundations operate 
throughout the region and offer the following programs.
<p>
<b>Internships.</b><br> The EWMI places competitively selected managers 
and professionals with international companies and 
organizations worldwide to receive on-the-job training 
internships. Several current programs also offer an academic 
component to complement the practical training. Hundreds of 
internships have been arranged for professionals in 
financial services, legal services, business management, 
public administration, and human services. In 1995, the EWMI 
administered 13 programs in 15 countries, providing training 
to over 435 interns with organizations in the United States 
and Canada.
<p>
<b>Management Training.</b><br> The business education program of the 
EWMI designs and implements business management and finance 
training programs. This program cooperates with Western 
academic institutions to develop course materials in 
accounting, finance, management, business, corporate 
governance, and public policy. These materials are used to 
train and retrain managers and professionals from private 
and entrepreneurial enterprise environments, as well as 
federal and municipal government institutions and the 
military. In 1995, a total of 350 trainers in Russia and 
Ukraine were instructed in Western accounting skills. In 
1996, the EWMI plans to enlarge the program to include 
Moldova and other countries in the region.
<p>
<b>Junior Achievement.</b><br> The EWMI develops, coordinates, and 
implements the distribution of Junior Achievement programs 
for high school students. This program comprises bilingual 
curricula and computer software for management simulation 
exercises that allow students to run their own businesses 
and learn the basics of a free market economy. In 1995, the 
EWMI awarded grants to four developing Junior Achievement 
programs in Eastern and Central Europe and the Newly 
Independent States, and assisted in program implementation 
in six other countries. During the year, over 30,000 
students in the region participated in Junior Achievement 
programs.
<p>
The EWMI has also developed a program titled the 
Fundamentals of a Market Economy, which targets the working 
adult population and professionals. In 1995, the program was 
piloted in two countries, with more pilots scheduled for 
1996.
<p>
<b>Privatization Policy and Training.</b><br> In 1995, the EWMI was 
awarded a contract by the United States Agency for 
International Development to carry out privatization policy 
and training projects in Eastern and Central Europe and the 
Newly Independent States. The first projects, initiated in 
the fall of 1995, are aimed at post-privatization 
restructuring work in Hungary and Moldova.
<p>
<b>Computer-based Training.</b><br> The Soros Business and Management 
Foundation develops multimedia, CD-ROM, and Internet 
computer-based training courses in order to reach a broader 
audience of professionals and technicians. The first course, 
a computer-based accounting course targeted to provide 
training to the personnel of the Russian State Tax Service, 
is scheduled to be completed by the fall of 1996. The second 
course in auditing is currently in the initial stages of 
development. The United States Agency for International 
Development and the U.S. Department of Treasury are co-
funders of this project and they, as well as OECD, further 
support the project by providing content and technical 
contributions.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   
