<a name="top"></a>
<h2>
From the 1995 Annual Report
</h2>
The mission of the International Soros Science Education 
Program (ISSEP) is to preserve excellence in science 
education in Russia and other newly independent states by 
supporting and encouraging the work of teachers, professors, 
and students. ISSEP is funded by the 
<a href="osiny.html"><b>Open Society Institute-- New York</b></a>.
<p>
<b>Soros Teachers.</b><br> To choose the best high school teachers of 
mathematics, physics, chemistry, and biology in 1995, ISSEP 
polled more than 31,000 students at 140 universities in 
Russia, Belarus, Ukraine, and Georgia. From more than 60,000 
names, over 4,000 teachers were chosen for Soros Teacher 
diplomas and stipends. Several hundred received the title of 
Soros Emeritus High School Teacher.
<p>
<b>Soros Professors.</b><br> 1,233 professors and 1,221 associate 
professors from 64 and 77 cities, respectively, competed in 
Russia for the university professor awards. More than 25,000 
students in 267 universities were polled to evaluate the 
candidates. The result: 389 Soros Professors and 394 Soros 
Associate Professors in Russia, and 85 Soros Professors in  
Ukraine, 30 in Belarus, and 12 in Georgia. Almost 75 retired 
professors with exceptional achievements and worldwide 
reputations were awarded Soros Emeritus Professor stipends.
<p>
<b>Soros University Students.</b><br> More than 5,000 of the best 
students of theoretical disciplines have received stipends 
as Soros Graduate Students and Soros Undergraduate Students 
based on their participation in scientific research, 
publication of scientific articles, and presentation of 
scientific reports at international and national 
conferences, symposia, and congresses. By the end of 
November 1995, ISSEP had received reports from 1,108 Soros 
Students. During the period of their grant, these students 
participated in 695 scientific conferences (205 
international and 98 national scientific meetings and 392 
student scientific conferences), submitted 394 scientific 
articles for publication (205 of which have already been 
published), and they are participating as team members in 
scientific work in 478 projects awarded with scientific 
grants. Of the 1,108 students, 778 students received 
straight A's on their last examinations and 411 students are 
actively involved in volunteer work with high school 
students.
<p>
<b>Soros Conferences.</b><br> In almost 50 cities all over Russia, 
ISSEP organized special Soros conferences of teachers, at 
which Soros Professors delivered lectures on the latest 
achievements in their scientific disciplines. Many of the 
lectures will be published by the Soros Educational Journal, 
which put out its first issue in December of 1995. The 
journal, consisting of articles on the basic sciences, will 
be distributed free to libraries of all high schools, 
universities, and vocational schools in Russia.
<p>
<b>Soros Olympiad for School Children.</b><br> More than 7,000 of the 
best high school students participated in the Soros Olympiad 
for School Children. The competition prepared students for 
the 1995 International (UNESCO) Olympiads in chemistry, 
biology, physics, and mathematics. Of the total of 19 medals 
received by the official Russian team, 4 were captured by 
winners of the Soros Olympiads.
<p>
ISSEP awarded almost $700,000 in small grants to Russian 
high schools with more than four Soros Teachers. Five high 
schools qualified for the top award of $8,000 for having 
more than ten Soros Teachers. All 3,300 Soros Teachers in 
Russia helped select the best 20 textbooks in mathematics, 
physics, chemistry, and biology. More than 500,000 copies of 
these textbooks were published and donated to Soros Teachers 
around the country.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   
