<head>
<title>
Soros Training for Economic Transformation Network
</title> 
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" text="000000" link="2A4572" alink="2A4572" vlink="587CA3">
<table cellpadding=6>                                                
<tr>                                                                 
<td>                                                                 
<img align=middle src="/images/logo3.gif">                      
<td>                                                                 
<img align=middle src="/images/stetn.gif" alt="Soros Training for Economic Transformation Network">
</td>                                                                
</tr>                                                                
</table>                                                             
<a name="top"></a>
<h2>
From the 1995 Annual Report
</h2>

The transformation of the former communist economies of 
Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union into 
modern economies is one of the great challenges of the late 
20th century. These economies are undergoing privatization 
of state enterprises on an unprecedented scale. One of the 
most critical problems facing economies in transition is the 
lack of trained personnel knowledgeable in the techniques 
required to operate in both the private and public sectors 
of the modern market economy.
<p>
The Soros Training for Economic Transformation Network 
(STETN) attempts to fill this knowledge void. STETN is 
involved in the training of public officials responsible for 
designing and implementing privatization policies as well as 
individuals in the newly emerging private sector. STETN 
cooperates with constitutional bodies in the promotion of 
economic transformation.
<p>
STETN consists of the Institute of Privatization and 
Management in Moscow; the Institute of Privatization and 
Management in Nizhny Novgorod, Russia; the International 
Centre of Privatization, Investment, and Management in Kyiv, 
Ukraine; the Institute of Privatization and Management in 
Minsk, Belarus; and the International Centre for Market 
Economy-ARMAN in Almaty, Kazakstan.
<p>
The members of the network all seek to build a coalition of 
reform-oriented policy makers through organizing seminars 
and facilitating nonpolitical discussion about the course of 
reform; to assist government agencies in their regulatory 
efforts through presenting the experience and achievements 
of other countries; and to build knowledge and a sense of 
professional standards among managers and consultants 
working to achieve reform at all levels of the economic 
system.
<p>
During the last three years, STETN has trained over 32,000 
people from the government and business communities of the 
Russian Federation, Ukraine, Belarus, and Kazakstan. The 
network's annual training capacity is 7,000 participants in 
the Russian Federation, 4,000 to 5,000 in Ukraine, 2,500 in 
Belarus, and 3,000 in Kazakstan. About 100 full-time staff 
and 500 part-time instructors are employed by the five 
institutions.
<p>
STETN centers in Belarus, Kazakstan, Russia, and Ukraine 
have received in-kind donations from the Know How Fund 
(Great Britain), Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Germany), 
USAID, the World Bank, Economic Development Institute, 
European Community TACIS, and CIDA Canada. About 50 percent 
of program financing comes from the training participants.
<p>
STETN training activities include the following programs:
<p>
<b>Methodology of Privatization.</b><br> Policy-making conferences and 
information seminars on privatization methodology are 
conducted in all countries. In 1995, such meetings played an 
important role in Ukraine as privatization moved from 
concept to implementation.
<p>
<b>Corporate Governance.</b><br> The institutions offer programs in the 
preparation of supervisory board members of joint stock 
companies. Although there is still too little interest in 
new forms of property management, several hundred people 
received training in this program area in 1995.
<p>
<b>Corporate Restructuring.</b><br> Restructuring is an important step 
in making enterprises work in newly created market 
conditions. Programs conducted under this heading are doing 
well in Russia and Ukraine.
<p>
<b>Securities Market Financial Intermediaries, Investment 
Funds, and Trust Companies.</b><br> These seminars are quite popular 
in all of the countries participating in STETN's programs. 
They help design policy as well as prepare new professionals 
for the emerging market.
<p>
<a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>   
