<br>
An Update on U.S. Programs<br>
by Gara LaMarche, Director of U.S. Programs<br>
<br>
The latter half of 1996 was a period of growth and increasing activity for the
Open Society Institute's (OSI's) U.S. programs. Additional staff  joined the
Institute, new initiatives were launched, and existing programs were
expanded.<br>
The Center on Crime, Communities &amp; Culture, launched last spring, completed
an initial round of grants, gave scholarships to two law students, and
published a research report on mental illness in jails. As with the Project on
Death in America in its field, the Center is emerging as a leader among funders
in criminal justice (an underfunded and politically unpopular area) and seems
likely to embolden other funders to rethink their commitment to the field.
Nancy Mahon, who came to OSI from the Osborne Association, where she was
director of research, policy, and planning, is the Center's director.
<br>
In an initiative announced at the end of September, OSI committed $50 million
to establish the Emma Lazarus Fund, which assists legal immigrants adversely
affected by recent welfare legislation and promotes fair treatment of
immigrants and refugees. The Fund provides grants to groups that help
immigrants become full participants in American society as well as to groups
that promote immigrants' rights through public information campaigns and in the
courts. Antonio Maciel, formerly with the Joyce Mertz-Gilmore Foundation and an
attorney with the Immigrants' Rights Project of the American Civil Liberties
Union, joined OSI to direct the Fund. <br>
Late in October, OSI made its first major U.S. grant in the area of education,
with a three-year, multi-million dollar commitment to the Algebra Project, a
nationwide network that promotes mastery of algebra by all children, especially
those in inner-city and rural schools. The funds will allow the Algebra Project
to expand training and technical support for its activities.<br>
In the coming months, the Institute is considering grants to strengthen state
and local groups dealing with the devolution of welfare responsibility from the
federal government to the states. The Institute also plans to support groups
working to reduce teenage pregnancy and reduce the influence of money in
political campaigns, and will soon select the first recipients of new Open
Society Fellowships. Future OSI initiatives will deal with inner-city problems
that contribute to the hardening of divisions along the lines of race and
class; the promotion of noncommercial approaches to culture, law, medicine, and
journalism; and the reinvigoration of professional, civic, and political ethics
and community service. <br>
The Institute's two initial U.S. programs are playing critical roles in
important public policy debates. In a climate of growing public support of more
sensible drug policies, the Lindesmith Center, established in 1994, will
shortly publish Marijuana Myths, Marijuana Facts, a well-documented book
designed to counter the misinformation which pervades the debates over
marijuana. The Project on Death in America, established in 1993, filed an
amicus brief in two Supreme Court cases concerning physician-assisted suicide.
The brief argues that the Court should not find a constitutional right to such
assistance until we, as a society, have instituted adequate safeguards to
ensure that people considering suicide are not motivated by the failure of
doctors to treat their pain or depression, or by economic fears.<br>
I joined the OSI staff at the end of May as director of U.S. programs. Prior to
coming to OSI, I spent 20 years working with civil liberties and human rights
groups, including the American Civil Liberties Union and Human Rights Watch.
Other new U.S. program staff include Beth Breger, program officer for
education, formerly with OSI's Education Support Unit; David Condliffe, senior
adviser, formerly executive director of the Drug Policy Foundation; Erlin
Ibreck, program officer dealing with teenage pregnancy and reproductive health
and choice, formerly a program officer with the Aaron Diamond Foundation and
former Deputy Coordinator of the New York City Mayor's Office of Adolescent
Pregnancy and Parenting Services; Karma Kreizenbeck, program officer for
fellowships and communications, formerly director of programs for the
Lindesmith Center; and Catherine Samuels, director of the Legal Profession
Program, formerly a partner in the law firm Schulte, Roth &amp; Zabel and
currently chair of the NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund.<br>
<br>
<br>
The Voices of Debate<br>
The Karl Popper Debate Camp <br>* Celakovice, Czech Republic<br>
by Kimberly Iowaka Barber<br>
<br>
Is a zebra a white animal with black stripes or a black animal with white
stripes?" The question came once, and then again, more emphatically, from the
tall, slender adolescent standing before me. Never having thought seriously
about zebras, I dodged the question by offering up a standard response: "That's
kind of like which came first, the chicken or the egg," I ventured, hesitant.
But as would be demonstrated repeatedly over the course of the next week, when
you're talking with a debater, the "standard response" just won't do. In such
company, answers must be carefully formulated, built on sound logic and solid
evidence.<br>
After a few moments, the student let me off the hook and his face erupted into
a broad smile. "Welcome to the world of debate," he said. "Don't feel bad about
the zebra thing. My name is Kert Lobu and I am from Estonia. The zebra is our
team mascot. For us, this creature symbolizes the importance of debate. If you
make a statement that something is either black or white then you must be
prepared to build your case and be cross-examined. In the end, you must also be
willing to admit that nothing in this world is black or white. It's all shades
of gray."<br>
My young Estonian interlocutor was one of 65 high school students and 64
teachers who attended the Second Annual Karl Popper Debate Camp and Tournament,
held at the Czech Management Center in Celakovice, Czech Republic. The camp is
organized each summer by the Open Society Institute's Regional High School
Debate Program, which began as a pilot project in Hungary in 1993 and now
operates in 22 countries including: Albania, Belarus, Bosnia &amp; Herzegovina,
Bulgaria, Croatia, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Kazakstan, Kyrgyzstan,
Latvia, Lithuania, Macedonia, Moldova, Poland, Romania, Russia, Slovakia,
Slovenia, Ukraine, and Yugoslavia. <br>
In addition to participants from those countries, three teens from Haiti--where
George Soros established the Fondation Connaisance et Liberte last year--also
attended. But no matter what the country, the program's goals are the same: to
foster strong communication skills, promote critical thinking, encourage
tolerance and respect for different ideas, and promote an active interest in
current issues. The summer camp and tournament are the culmination of the
program's ongoing activities. Before attending the camp, students spend the
year debating in their native languages in their home countries and studying
debate through clubs funded by the program. Like many of the Open Society
Institute's other programs, the Regional High School Debate Program is carried
out in close cooperation with program coordinators at local institutions in the
Soros foundations network.<br>
"Until about six years ago, formal debate was virtually unknown in these
countries.  Even translating the term `debate' was problematic--there was no
equivalent in these languages," said Liz Lorant, director of regional programs
at the Open Society Institute. "However, once the teachers and students
understood the idea of debate, all barriers fell."  <br>
And if to American ears "summer camp" conjures up images of lakeside cabins and
mornings spent horseback riding or learning how to canoe, the debate camp at
Celakovice was a different story altogether. The Czech Management Center itself
is a gray, lackluster building that until the Velvet Revolution served as a
training center for Czechoslovakia's communist elite. And yet, despite external
reminders of the Soviet era, inside the Center the past was firmly in the past.
Students and teachers from all over the world lived together, ate together,
played together, and worked together in harmony. For the week in August that it
hosted the camp, the small village where the Center is located took on a new
face, recognizable as the face of the future: the face of debate.<br>
The camp's varied activities culminated in a final tournament that set the team
from Hungary in competition with debaters from Moldova. The issue under
discussion was whether government censorship of the media for the protection of
citizens can be justified. The Hungarian debate team ended up taking the final
prize (scholarships for each team member), but students and coaches from all
teams emphasized that while the tournament was an exciting event, victory was
not at the heart of what was important about their efforts. "The new
friendships I have formed here are what's vital about the camp experience,"
confirmed Alina Belukha, a student from the Dniepropetrovsk region of
Ukraine.<br>
Ken Broda-Bahm, director of debate at Towson State University in Maryland,
agreed: "While the camp is foremost a debate program, debate was not the only
focus. Other activities, such as acting, painting, dancing, sports, and social
events shared the schedule with debate. The resulting atmosphere was different
from the tense, ultra-competitive environment of debate workshops in the United
States." <br>
In the week leading up to the tournament, students attended workshops to hone
specialized skills, for debate is a far more complex affair than the random
expressing of opinions. Indeed, it is an exceptionally structured exercise,
with a special vocabulary to describe its discrete components--the resolution,
affirmative side, negative side, arguments, proofs, cross-examination, and the
decision. Teachers and students, divided into groups of beginners,
intermediates, and the advanced, undertook a daily regimen of workshops dealing
with these components and related issues, such as evidence research, team
strategy and roles, techniques of delivery, and the different styles of formal
debate. "We were fortunate to have top international coaches and students as
hands-on instructors and mentors," said Tricia Mullen Keane, program officer at
the Open Society Institute. "They provided innovative teaching methodologies
that the other teachers and coordinators can integrate into their clubs and
classrooms in their own countries."<br>
The workshops helped students become more articulate and increased their
analytical skills, knowledge of current issues, and self-awareness. Jan
Ruzicka, a self-effacing high schooler, returned to the Czech Republic from
Australia last Christmas when his <br>
parents reclaimed land and an inn that had been taken from his grandfather by
the communists. Jan, who plans to study hotel and restaurant management so that
he can take over the family business, said mastering the discipline and skill
that debate demands gave him the self-confidence to speak in front of hundreds
of people, a skill he was sure would be essential in his planned career.<br>
"When I was growing up, my mother constantly urged me to look for my own
voice," said Anca Pusca, a philosophical eleventh grader from Timisoara,
Romania. "The debate program helped me to find that voice." Anca's teammates
Dan Dimitriu and Carmen Draghici added that debate had helped them to resolve
conflicts, not only within themselves but with their families, their friends,
and even complete strangers. "The special thing about debate is that we not
only shake hands with each one of the opposing team members before the round,
but also after the round, no matter if we win or lose," said Carmen. "You can
not be involved in debate and be intolerant."<br>
Many students indicated that much of what they learn in school does not relate
to their everyday lives. The debate program, many said, made them more
attentive listeners and made it easier to separate fact from fiction when
listening to politicians and teachers. "One of the most difficult things for
people to comprehend is how to, let's say, prove that white is white but also
that white is black," said Ilija Gospodinov, a sophisticated teenager from
Skopje, Macedonia. "In other words, it is very difficult to argue with
conviction if you do not agree with what you are saying. This is when sharp
listening skills and the power of logic come into play. These are skills
students can use in every facet of life, whether business, academics, or
personal."<br>
In a region where minority voices have long been suppressed, the debate program
has had a tremendous impact on the female participants. Kate Golovko, a recent
high school graduate with a slight British accent, is from Chisinau, Moldova.
She and her two teammates formed the only all-female team at the camp. They
competed in the final round of the tournament, and Kate was selected as one of
the camp's top 15 speakers. "I don't want to be confined to an office," she
said. "Many women in my country are more or less pressured to hold traditional
office jobs, but that's not for me. Debate has changed my life because it has
given me a powerful tool, the power of effective communication and
self-confidence. I encourage women to participate in debate because they can
learn how to use logic as a power source."<br>
The debate camp was a mind-opening experience for many of the teens. Peter
Piasecki, an articulate and creative teen from Lodz, Poland, said, "The concept
of an open society was abstract until I came to the camp. People have a
tendency to stay in their own world, with their own people. Your thoughts are
only about the small world you create for yourself. But when you come to a camp
like this, you see that there are so many different kinds of people with so
many different kinds of experiences. You become friends with these people, and
it changes your perspective."<br>
On the last day of the camp, Alina Belukha, a student from Ukraine, could be
seen clutching a purple folder inscribed with large day-glo letters spelling
out "Late Night with Ukraine." Alina recounted how an American student had
written the phrase in commemoration of his many late night tutorial sessions
with the Ukrainians. To Alina, the folder was evidence of the friendships
formed at the camp. With a warm smile, she opened up the folder ever so
delicately and displayed the autographs and addresses of all the friends she
had made and with whom she planned to correspond. "Because we lived in a closed
society for so long, it has been difficult for us to be open and honest about
who we really are. But now it is important for us to learn how to reveal our
soul and character. Through debate we learn to question, and this brings us
closer to an understanding of ourselves and the world around us." <br>
<br>
<br>
Books Across Borders<br>
Reprinted from the Washington Post<br>
by Frances Pinter<br>
<br>
One day in 1994, not long after I had been appointed director of the Central
European University Press, my telephone rang and I heard the voice of George
Soros, the university's founder, posing a rhetorical question. "Wouldn't it be
great," Soros asked, "if we could somehow support the translation of classic
works of Western intellectual thought into the languages of Central and Eastern
Europe?"<br>
It would be great, I knew. And it would also be, I realized, a tall order to
implement such a complex, ambitious idea. For, while most political walls fell
all over Central and Eastern Europe in late 1989 and 1990, some remained
standing. Although a state-subsidized publishing industry was in place in many
countries of the region, the book publishing outside of the underground
samizdat culture was characterized by a monopoly of approved texts by
politically correct authors or writers imaginative and creative enough to
disguise their message in a politically acceptable vernacular.<br>
Among the utterly unavailable texts were the classic works of Western
political, social, legal, and economic philosophy, a gap that even six years of
democracy in Central and Eastern Europe has been slow to fill. Even at this
moment, if you are a first-year political science major studying in, say,
Latvia, texts whose availability is taken for granted by your American
counterparts--John Stewart Mill's On Liberty, de Tocqueville's Democracy in
America, even Aristotle's Poetics, to name just a few, are unavailable in your
native language. If you are studying law, economics, or sociology, or are
involved in gender studies or international relations, your predicament is even
worse: there may be nothing at all available to read in your field.<br>
Imagine, then, the shock felt by Melissa Hagemann, director of the Open Society
Institute-Budapest's Library Support Program, just a few years ago when, on a
visit to the national library in Tirana, Albania, she inquired about the
library's reference resources. Why yes, she was told by the librarian, the
library did have a copy of the complete Encyclopedia Britannica. When Hagemann
went to check, she found that, indeed, they did, but only of the 1913 edition!
All of this, inevitably, led to a central question: How could one help to
introduce Western liberal ideas into the newly democratized nations of Central
and Eastern Europe without, in widely available quantities, the books on which
those ideas and values are based?<br>
In an attempt to answer that question and to respond to some of the problems
illustrated above, the Central University Press Translation Project was founded
in 1995. Based on similar but smaller projects initiated by a few of the
foundations in the Soros foundations network, we sought to demonstrate that
translation efforts could be a highly effective and, if well-designed and
implemented, relatively inexpensive way of helping Eastern European publishers
redefine themselves in a changing world.<br>
From the outset, I saw that there were fundamental questions to be answered.
For example, how could OSI best obtain, and balance, the opinions of
intellectuals and scholars from both the East and West as to what kinds of
books should be published? How could we avoid supporting and promoting a list
which was, perhaps, too exclusively Anglo-Saxon in its orientation? Whose input
should be solicited in compiling a list of recommended titles? Central European
University faculty members? Outside experts? Publishers themselves? And, of
crucial importance to me as a publisher, how could we design such a project so
as to promote the growth of an innovative and efficient local publishing
industry?<br>
But one must start somewhere, and in the case of the Central European
University Press Translation Project, it was with a pilot program in Romania in
late 1994, at which time a list of about 250 recommended titles compiled by
Central European University faculty was circulated to Romanian publishers.
Through an open competition organized by publishing program coordinator Marina
Ghitoc at the Soros Foundation for an Open Society-Bucharest, in which
publishers themselves selected titles from the project list, 15 publishers were
awarded grants to support the publication of over 30 titles. Among the titles
were classic works by Immanuel Kant, Max Weber, and Ludwig Wittgenstein, as
well as essential textbooks in economics, history, and sociology, and
contemporary classics by writers such as Hannah Arendt, Karl Popper, Isaiah
Berlin, and Michel Foucault.<br>
As I was convinced that only if publishers had something to lose would they put
their hearts and souls behind the project, we decided that the Budapest office
of the Central European University Press would only assist with procuring
translation rights and various other publishing functions, and at the same time
insisted that publishers further invest their own resources.<br>
During 1995, in addition to Romania, the program was introduced in Albania,
Bulgaria, Poland, and Ukraine, where initial competitions for support funds
have received an enthusiastic response. In Bulgaria alone, over 70 applications
were received from a group including virtually every qualified publisher in the
country. In Romania, response to the program was so positive that a number of
publishers volunteered to translate additional books, with OSI funding only
copyright fees. The program has broadened to include over a dozen other
countries in 1996, and over the next several years we hope to support the
publication of some 500 titles per year. <br>
But translating classic works also often raises questions which are particular
to each individual country and language. In the case of Karl Popper's works,
for example, a recent translation of one of his books into Mongolian by a
political philosopher trained in Moscow turned out to be riddled with Marxist
terminology. It took a professor of Asian studies at Budapest's Eotvos Lorand
University familiar with the Mongolian tradition of translating ancient
philosophical and spiritual texts to rework the translation, reviving an old
philosophical vocabulary which was once part of the local translation
culture.<br>
The project of translation, I was also aware from the beginning, is very much a
two-way street, and we in the West, too, have been deprived, during the 50-year
reign of communism, of greater access to any of the classic works of
nineteenth- and twentieth-century Eastern and Central European fiction. Missing
from many shelves are works by writers of such world-class caliber as the Czech
Jan Neruda, the Hungarians Kezso Kosztolanyi, Zsigmond Moricz, and Gyula Krudy,
and Polish writers Boleslaw Prus and Witold Gombrowicz, writers whose work
deserves to be on the syllabus of every Western course in the literature of
this region. In acknowledgment of that glaring literary omission, the Central
European University Press English-Language Division recently relaunched the
Central European Classics series, begun (and remaining) under the editorship of
Timothy Garton Ash, with newly commissioned translations of Kosztolanyi's
Skylark, Neruda's Prague Tales, Moricz's Be Faithful Unto Death, and Brus's The
Doll. These are available worldwide through Oxford University Press'
distribution of Central European University Press titles in English.<br>
Over the long term, I hope we will be able to support the emergence and renewal
of a strong, diverse, and independent publishing industry in Central and
Eastern Europe, not merely a key element of any civil society, but of any
civilized person's claim to an open, inclusive, and stimulating intellectual
and cultural life. With all due respect to Robert Frost, who came of age in a
very different world, that while poetry may sometimes be what is lost in
translation, much of the world's rich scholarly, academic, and literary
heritage is also be found there.<br>
<br>
Frances Pinter is director of the Central European University Press and the
Open Society Institute Publishing Center. <br>
<br>
<br>
The Center on Crime, Communities, &amp; Culture<br>
<br>
Fear of crime, particularly violent crime, is a hallmark of life in the United
States. While almost everyone is afraid of crime, research shows that some
communities, particularly low-income and urban minority communities, represent
a disproportionate number of both victims and perpetrators of crime.<br>
<br>
The goals of the Center on Crime, Communities, &amp; Culture are to foster a
more informed and balanced national debate on crime, victims' concerns,
punishment, and the rehabilitation of individuals and communities; to support
and spotlight service programs which effectively address the needs of at-risk
youth, juvenile offenders, victims, prisoners, as well as the families of these
populations; and, to encourage knowledge transfer on successful criminal
justice programs and policies across the United States and between the United
States and other nations.<br>
<br>
The first nine months of the Center's history has been an extraordinarily
productive time. Established by OSI in the spring of 1996, the Center has
already provided more than $1.4 million in grants to over two dozen groups,
developed a fellowships program, and issued several publications in conjunction
with the Center's research department.  <br>
<br>
A nation that incarcerates as many of its citizens as does the U.S. cannot hope
to remain an open society. To truly address the injurious impact crime is
having on our entire society, the problem must be approached and the solutions
discovered community by <br>
community. We must find new answers. <br>
<br>
<br>
Rhythms to Ratios<br>
Open Society Institute<br>
The Algebra Project Brings Robert Moses' Activist Legacy<br>
 into the Classroom<br>
by Beth Breger<br>
<br>
Math teacher and civil rights activist Robert Moses spent the 1960s leading
voter-registration drives in the Mississippi Delta and, later, teaching
mathematics in Africa. When he and his family returned to the United States,
they enrolled their children in the Martin Luther King, Jr. Elementary School
in Cambridge, Massachusetts. Moses found he wasn't happy with the mathematics
instruction his daughter Maisha received, so he began tutoring her at home,
himself. When Maisha reached eighth grade, her skills were so advanced that her
teacher invited Moses to transplant his home tutoring into the classroom. The
Algebra Project--now a program that operates in schools in 17 states across the
nation--was born.<br>
<br>
The Algebra Project's pedagogy is based on Moses' belief that abstract concepts
can be made more intelligible to children by relating mathematics to the
concrete experiences of daily life. A subway ride can teach the concept of
negative numbers, gumdrop-toothpick cubes can elucidate exponential theory, and
African drum rhythms can explain ratios. <br>
<br>
Moses' method for teaching the language of algebra is contained in a five-step
process: experiencing an event; drawing or modeling the event; describing the
event in idiomatic English; describing the event in more regimented English;
and representing the event with symbols. Thus, the student moves step-by-step
from a tangible event into the symbolic language used to represent it in
algebra.<br>
<br>
On a recent visit to a classroom at the King School, fourteen years after the
program was initiated, I saw the Algebra Project in action. What at first
sounded like a lecture on the Boston mass transit system turned out to be an
introduction to the mental processes and language of algebra. The students sat
in five different clusters around the room, each group hovering over diagrams
of the subway system that they had developed as a team. <br>
<br>
One delegate from each group presented the team's diagrammatic voyages, based
on actual field trips along different routes of Boston's subway system. Each
group proudly displayed work, accepted questions from their classmates about
why they chose their particular designs, what each symbol represented, where
trips started and finished, and how the diagrams could help a new subway rider
navigate the route between Boston and Cambridge.<br>
<br>
To those schooled in more traditional methods, this may seem more like playtime
than math class. But in fact, the thinking and reasoning skills taught by
Moses' math games help introduce students to the kind of abstract thinking and
symbolic language that is necessary for them to begin to grasp the concepts of
higher math. "At first, I didn't believe we were doing math,"  Laurance
Kimbrough, one of Moses' students, told Smithsonian magazine. "Now I look back
at what we did and I realize it really helped me."<br>
<br>
Moses focuses on algebra because he believes that without it the door to
college and most skilled professions is locked. "Computers can crunch more
numbers than anyone's going to dream of crunching," he told the New York Times.
"There are no jobs out there for people who [just] know how to divide." In an
interview with Smithsonian, he said, "New technology demands a new
literacy--higher math skills for everyone. Up in the [Mississippi] Delta, the
largest employer is now a shipping service. All the dollies have computers on
them. They need warehouse workers who are trained in computers."<br>
<br>
The Algebra Project is more than a novel teaching method; it has changed the
dynamic in classrooms. "We are now hearing more voices . . . children who sat
silently are contributing to conversations," said Pamela Paternoster, manager
of the Algebra Project in Cambridge. "Classrooms are set up differently. Desks
are no longer in rows but are clustered together to facilitate cooperative
learning." And, according to Paternoster, children aren't the only ones
transformed by the Project. "For the first time, teachers across the city are
talking to each other about math. They are taking more risks and are not afraid
to try new teaching approaches."<br>
<br>
And the Project's approach seems to be paying off in more ways than higher math
scores on achievement tests. Reading and writing skills are also improving, as
well as school discipline. "I see almost no one from the Algebra Project for
disciplinary reasons. They're too busy with the activities," said school
principal Ken Acton. An evaluation funded by the National Science Foundation of
the Algebra Project's efforts in Mississippi concluded that the project "has
had an extremely beneficial effect on students--particularly on their
attitudes, motivation, problem-solving, and ability to articulate and share
mathematical ideas."<br>
<br>
Moses compares his work with the Algebra Project to his days registering voters
in the South: "In the 1960s everyone said sharecroppers were apathetic, that
they didn't want to vote. It wasn't until we got them demanding to vote that we
got attention. Here, where kids are falling wholesale through the cracks--or
chasms--dropping out of sight, becoming fodder for jails, people say they don't
want to learn. The only ones who can dispel that notion are the kids
themselves. We have to get them to demand what everyone says they don't want."
The Algebra Project helps children who would otherwise be left behind reach an
intellectual level that could open up opportunities their parents might never
have dreamed possible. <br>
<br>
Beth Breger is a program officer for education at the Open Society
Institute-New York.The Institute recently awarded the Algebra Project a $12
million grant to be used over the next three years. For more information about
the Algebra Project, call (212) 887-0152.<br>
<br>
IMMIGRANTS' BURDEN<br>
by George Soros<br>
<br>
In the last seven years, I have devoted considerable energy to support the
creation of open societies in the former Soviet bloc. In those countries, the
meaning of open society was easy to explain: it was the opposite of Communism.
Open society was the United States, a country characterized by a reliance on
the rule of law, a democratically elected government, a diverse culture, and
respect for people who are different. The truth, of course, was always more
complicated. Yet the image and the ideal were inspiring, and they remain so to
this day. Refugees fleeing persecution, family members reuniting with loved
ones, and young entrepreneurs with talent and drive have long come to America
seeking a fair chance to contribute and, in the process, have enriched our
culture and strengthened the nation. But much of that fair chance was taken
away when the recent welfare law went into effect. That legislation bars most
legal immigrants from receiving a range of public assistance.<br>
According to the Congressional Budget Office, more than 500,000 immigrants are
likely to lose Supplemental Security benefits, and about 900,000 are likely to
lose food stamps. Legal immigrants represent only about 5 percent of those on
public aid, yet they are absorbing over 40 percent of the cuts in welfare. <br>
Immigrants have always pulled their weight. Except for the right to vote, legal
immigrants have enjoyed the same rights and shared the same responsibilities as
citizens. They serve in the military. They contribute more in taxes than they
receive in benefits. Denying them the safety net they help pay for is neither
necessary nor fair, and it breaks with a long and proud tradition of treating
legal immigrants as future citizens who are assets, rather than as non-citizen
aliens who are a burden. <br>
More than half of the legal immigrants who will lose their benefits have lived
in the U.S. for more than five years and are likely to be eligible for
naturalization. More than one million are expected to apply for citizenship
this year. Yet in taking benefits away from struggling immigrants, we are
adding yet another obstacle to those they already face in applying for
citizenship, including learning English, studying for the test, and paying
processing fees.<br>
There is no question that the welfare system needs to be reformed so that it
moves people from dependency to work. But to do so we must spend more money,
not less, in the short term, because creating work requires more public
investment and job training--for citizens and legal immigrants. Depriving
immigrants creates false savings at the cost of perpetrating an injustice. <br>
As an immigrant and naturalized U.S. citizen, I have a deep sympathy for those
who come to America in search of a better life. I have prospered, but I know
that we all need a helping hand at some time in our lives. After World War II,
I left Hungary and stayed in England for several years, working as a railroad
porter. I broke my leg and was taken care of, free of charge, by the National
Health Service. I depended on government assistance. <br>
If immigrants to America suffer similar misfortunes, if they cannot work or
find a decent-paying job and their families are starving, where will they turn
for help? In the answer lies our identity as a people and as a nation. <br>
<br>
<br>
Aiding Postcommunist Societies: A Better Way?<br>
<br>
Since 1989, the U.S. government has sponsored a wide array of economic,
political, and humanitarian assistance programs aimed at helping the countries
of Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union carry out the transition to
capitalism and democracy. Although far short of the Marshall Plan in magnitude,
the U.S. effort to <br>
aid the former communist countries has nonetheless entailed <br>
considerable resources--more than $2 billion for Central and Eastern Europe and
close to $10 billion for the former Soviet Union. Driven by a sense of historic
urgency, this assistance effort was put together in a tremendous hurry, with
maximum attention to getting aid flowing as rapidly as possible and minimal
attention to organizational design and innovation. Although the aid initially
unfolded in a honeymoon phase of sorts, in the past few years it has
increasingly attracted criticism, above and beyond the frequent laments from
some quarters over what some people believe to be its insufficient quantity.<br>
<br>
Both foreign external analysts and local participants report a fairly
consistent litany of operational problems with U.S. assistance: too much of the
aid goes to American organizations rather than to people in the target
countries; the aid is often too concentrated in large, top-down projects rather
than smaller, grass-roots efforts; and it is too often based on predetermined,
U.S.-oriented models rather than on local realities. The lack of much real
response to the criticisms of U.S. assistance is not primarily a result of
indifference or cynicism on the part of assistance officials. It is due instead
to the deeply entrenched psychological and bureaucratic structures that encase
U.S. assistance programs.<br>
<br>
Fortunately, there exists a positive example of a different way of giving aid
to Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union, and it is not merely one small,
experimental program, which, although interesting, is obviously limited to
particular circumstances. Rather, it is a very large donor carrying out
wide-ranging assistance programs in most of the countries of the region. That
donor is George Soros and his philanthropic creation, the Soros foundations
network. A comprehensive study of the work of the network is well beyond the
scope of this article. What is presented here is only an analysis of the basic
assistance-giving methods of the  foundations, through a portrait of the Soros
operation in one country, Romania, with a focus on how the Soros methods differ
from those of official U.S. foreign aid. The work of the Soros national
foundation in Romania is not typical of all the activities of the Soros
foundations. It differs, for example, from the more high-profile, politicized
involvement of Soros in Poland and Hungary and the big-ticket
institution-building initiatives, such as the controversial Central European
University. But it is at least somewhat typical of the work of many of the less
high-profile national foundations which constitute a significant share of the
overall effort of the Soros foundations network. As such it is useful as a
window into an interesting and potentially instructive <br>
universe of foreign aid.<br>
<br>
Paying Heed to Localism<br>
<br>
As a guiding principle of foreign aid, localism has the same special status as
many other received truths in governmental affairs, such as the need for
bureaucratic innovation and efficiency--it is much cited but rarely practiced.
Western assistance officials are quick to talk of the need for, among other
things, sensitivity to the local environment, local "ownership" of assistance
programs, and local capacity-building. Yet, in Eastern Europe and the former
Soviet Union, much of the Western aid of the past six years has been unloaded
in rapid fashion without much attempt to involve locals in the process, to
ensure that aid gets to locals, to design assistance programs on the basis of
conceptions of societal change that reflect a deep understanding of local
conditions, or to keep locals well-informed about the assistance. What
fundamentally characterizes the approach of the Soros foundations network, and
distinguishes it from the approaches of other major Western donors, is its
genuine localism on all these counts.<br>
The United States Agency for International Development (USAID), like most
Western official donors, operates in Romania through a small bubble colony. The
USAID field office in Romania is a tiny piece of the American government
transplanted in Romania. In contrast, the Soros operation in Romania, the Soros
Foundation for an Open Society-Bucharest, has very little of the character of
an outpost of a foreign organization. At each of the four branches of
SFOS-Bucharest (unlike almost all Western donors in Romania, Soros has offices
outside Bucharest, in Cluj, Iasi, and Timisoara), the board of directors, the
management, and the staff are all Romanians. The selection committees that
SFOS-Bucharest uses for its many open grants competitions are similarly all
local. Unlike the USAID office in Romania, SFOS-Bucharest has the primary
responsibility for decisions about allocating assistance funds in the country.
The Open Society Institute in New York exercises some oversight over the
activities of all foundations in the network, but that relationship is
generally much less close and less control-based than the relationship between
USAID headquarters in Washington and its field offices in the region.<br>
<br>
A second key point of difference is the targeting of the assistance. Most USAID
funds for Romanian programs go to American organizations: U.S. consulting
groups, accounting firms, nonprofit non-governmental organizations (NGOs),
universities, and other organizations. The U.S. contractors and grantees
deliver training and technical assistance to Romanians in the form of
workshops, conferences, seminars, organizational advice, counseling, expert
analysis, and studies.<br>
<br>
The assistance of the foundation in Romania follows the inverse pattern--most
of it goes directly to Romanian individuals and groups; only a small share goes
to people and organizations outside the country. The assistance to groups in
Romania generally consists of small grants (usually $5,000 to $25,000) to
organizations within a sector, such as media, human rights, or public health. A
sizable proportion of SFOS-Bucharest's  funds go to individual Romanians,
usually as educational scholarships for short- to medium-term study abroad or
professional development activities requiring travel abroad. The grants to
individuals are usually micro-grants in U.S. assistance terms, ranging from as
low as $40 up to a few thousand dollars.<br>
<br>
A third facet of the foundation's localism concerns the design of projects.
USAID programs are generally designed by Americans, either USAID staff in
Washington, consultants hired in Washington and sent out on project design
missions to Romania, or U.S. contractors and grantees already involved in
related assistance programs. In contrast, the programs of the Soros Foundation
for an Open Society-Romania are designed primarily by Romanians, usually the
program staff of the foundation, although OSI-NY and OSI-Budapest sometimes
contribute technical assistance to the design of programs in Romania and other
countries, or create regional programs which include Romania.<br>
<br>
At the risk of oversimplification, the variance between the two approaches to
assistance is the same as that between a focus on the process rather than on
the result. USAID emphasizes the results it wants to help postcommunist
societies achieve (namely, a market economy and a democratic political system)
and characterizes its specific programs as building blocks relating to these
goals. An underlying assumption of this approach is that process is the servant
of result. <br>
<br>
In the case of Romania, for example, if external donors and Romanians focus
sufficiently on defining and endorsing the desired results of political and
economic transformation, a process to achieve those results will follow.
SFOS-Bucharest focuses instead on trying to foster or strengthen a process of
change, by supporting individuals who are seeking to change, rather than on
results per se. Process is assumed to be the master of result--if the right
process of change gains strength, Soros believes, the result will be good.
Soros is not indifferent to endpoints; in fact his underlying goals are
essentially similar to USAID's. An open society, he says, "is something akin to
what we have in Western Europe and North America." <br>
<br>
Benefits of Localism<br>
<br>
The establishment of a genuinely local organization to run the assistance means
that programs can be designed and overseen by people with a real understanding
of the sectors they are trying to shape, rather than by outsiders who usually
have only a superficial, generic understanding of the particular sectors in
question. Outsiders do sometimes bring a fresh perspective to a troubled
sector, as well as valuable experience in assistance efforts with similar
sectors in other countries. Yet, compared to foreign consultants, local program
officers, if carefully selected, usually have a much greater knowledge of where
the talent lies within a sector, how the sector has or has not been changing in
the past years and why, and how the sector interacts with other institutions or
forces within the society. This sort of knowledge permits the development of
assistance programs that build productively on local realities rather than
programs that try to produce changes that donors have decided should occur.<br>
<br>
An additional benefit of the Soros foundations network's use of local persons
to run its national foundations is that the experience of working in the
foundations provides sustained, real-world training to locals in all aspects of
the work, from policy formulation to financial management. This sort of
training is in great demand in Romania and other former communist countries.
The network's extensive use of locals as directors and as members of award
committees is also a multiple plus. It injects considerable local expertise and
knowledge into decision-making processes.<br>
<br>
Giving a large proportion of the assistance directly to people and groups
generally results in greater impact per dollar than indirect assistance through
U.S. or other external intermediary organizations. In part this is simply
because of the elimination of middlemen and the much higher costs of U.S.
personnel and overhead. It is not merely the difference in costs, however, that
leads to the greater impact of direct assistance, it is also the method itself.
So much of the Western-funded technical assistance seems to pass through a
country like Romania and leave distressingly little trace. On the other hand,
direct grants, if carefully targeted, either in conjunction with technical
assistance or on their own, often produce visible and definite, albeit modest,
results, as seen in the direct grants by the Soros Foundation for an Open
Society-Romania, and other donors, to independent newspapers, radio stations,
environmental groups, human rights groups, and other small organizations in
Romania.<br>
<br>
In such contexts of partial or serious stagnation, the Soros foundations
network approach of planting seeds for change rather than trying to engineer
results seems preferable. What one sees in looking at Soros foundations
projects in Romania is many small beachheads of interesting, often dynamic
activity--social science institutes regenerating themselves, cultural
organizations reaching new audiences, new professional journals under way,
civic groups expanding their operations, and thousands of individuals who have
been able to pursue advanced educational and professional opportunities abroad.
One cannot know with certainty precisely what these many activities and changes
will lead to, but they have clearly reached many areas of talent in the country
and, at a minimum, are positive developments in and of themselves.<br>
<br>
Thomas Carothers, a senior associate at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace in Washington, D.C., has worked on democracy assistance
programs in many regions of the world during the past ten years for a variety
of U.S. government organizations and NGOs. His latest book is Assessing
Democracy Assistance: The Case of Romania (Carnegie Endowment, 1996).<br>
<br>
A Forgotten War<br>
A Commentary on Tajikistan and the Western Media <br>
by David Rieff<br>
<br>
Except for a few aid workers and diplomats, almost no one outside the former
Soviet Union has ever heard of Tajikistan. While by no means its greatest
misfortune, this fact has certainly not helped the country in these post-Cold
War times. For when the Soviet Union dissolved in 1991, so did the
idea--current in Western Europe and North America since 1945--that any place of
interest to Russia was also of interest to the West. By the early 1990s,
Washington was no longer even very interested in Afghanistan, where it had been
intensely involved for more than a decade. And if there was no interest in the
travails of Tajikistan's richer and more strategic southern neighbor, what hope
was there for the little Central Asian republic when its own troubles began in
May 1992?<br>
<br>
As with politicians, so with the press. Not only did Tajikistan never receive
even a fraction of the space regularly devoted to the agonies of Bosnia,
Somalia, or Rwanda in the front sections of the New York Times and
theWashington Post; it was all but ignored. Without sustained political
interest, editors of news programs in the United States and Western Europe felt
no pressure to send crews to Tajikistan. With no television coverage, probably
the only way people in the rich world can be goaded into indignation over a
catastrophe in a faraway place, the politicians never had to deal with a crisis
in which involvement would always have necessarily been based on moral rather
than geostrategic criteria.<br>
<br>
This may seem like an argument that public sentiment carries the day in foreign
policy matters. I do not mean to suggest anything of the sort. The most public
pressure can do is put an issue on policymakers' agenda and, as we saw in
Bosnia, even a great deal of activism may not succeed in provoking timely
action. In any case, the attention places like Bosnia, Somalia, or Rwanda
receive in the Western media is rarely as lavish as is often made out. Compare
the coverage the Rwandan genocide received with that lavished on Charles and
Di's slow-motion divorce or the murder trial of O.J. Simpson, America's
low-rent Othello. Most people don't have a lot of psychological room for
disasters in distant places. But to the extent they can care about such
matters, they cared about Rwanda and did not care about Tajikistan. <br>
<br>
And yet, from a moral point of view, it is not clear why this should have been
so. Ordinary Tajiks suffered as much as the citizens of Sarajevo or Mogadishu.
While undeniably complex and resistant to easy or cheap solutions, the conflict
in Tajikistan was no harder to understand or resolve than the Bosnian war or
the Somali emergency. Those of us from the West who travel regularly to places
like Tajikistan have grown accustomed to returning home to find indifference
among our friends, most of whom cannot even locate on a map the zones of war
and misery where we risk our lives and our sanity by staring so intently at so
much suffering and cruelty. And with a few exceptions, people at home are not
particularly interested in knowing more. <br>
<br>
The reality is that they do not really approve of our having made such
journeys. Ignorant of the causes of wars in places like Tajikistan, most people
seem to believe that there is no cause beyond the presumed savagery of the
inhabitants, a quality Westerners who have never met an Uzbek, a Hutu, or a
Bosnian Serb seem perfectly comfortable ascribing to them. And so ignorance
breeds not more ignorance but complacency--we do not have wars at home;
therefore there must be something wrong with them.<br>
<br>
It is often assumed that if people could see what places such as Tajikistan are
like, they would feel differently. Somehow, we still believe that knowledge is
power. If Tajikistan was ignored, it must be because there was no sustained
international press coverage. In other words, no "CNN effect" for officials in
Washington or Brussels to deal with. United Nations Secretary General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali once bitterly referred to CNN as the sixteenth member of the
Security Council. But CNN only provides a spotlight, not knowledge. At best, it
serves up information that might provide the basis for knowledge--a very
different matter.<br>
<br>
What is undeniable is that we are growing tired of other people's misfortunes.
If we don't have to look at them, so much the better. And if these misfortunes
are broadcast only occasionally, that is, if people are not repeatedly
subjected to images of dead children and refugees on the march, they will
ignore them. One recalls the few instances--Biafra, Somalia, Rwanda,
Bosnia--that actually mobilized the public, which is another way of saying we
remember a few moral successes. In reality, these instances have been
exceptional. It is Tajikistan, that paradigmatic "orphan conflict," that is the
norm, not Bosnia, just as it is indifference, not compassion or outrage, that
is the customary reaction to the hell that is the lot of four-fifths of the
world's population. Humanitarian relief workers have a name for this:
compassion fatigue.<br>
<br>
To be sure, individual stories still have the capacity to engage public
sentiment in the West. When a dying baby in a Sarajevo hospital was pictured on
British television, reaction in Europe was so strong that the British prime
minister had to send a special plane to bring the infant to England for
treatment. But unless suffering can be personalized, not to say sentimentalized
in this way (the baby in question was a hopeless case; it was already too late
for her, as it was not for Sarajevo itself), it often seems as if it does not
really move anyone who is not there to witness it.<br>
<br>
I do not believe that we in West have yet sunk so far into our own
self-regarding reveries to say openly that Tajik lives are not as precious our
own, or that their fates are less worth caring about. But it is growing harder
to resist the intuition that the global village is really a charnel house. And
the more that realization sinks in, the harder it becomes, paradoxically, to
assimilate what is taking place in all the conflicts raging in the world
today.<br>
<br>
Even in more orderly times, what has happened in Tajikistan in the past four
years would have been hard enough to take in. Some 50,000 people died during
the Civil War in 1992. More than a million became refugees or were "internally
displaced," the euphemism used to describe people who are forced to flee
because of political<br>
 or natural disasters, but who do not actually cross any international
frontier. But while this disaster was taking place, so were many others.
Tajikistan? There are 50 wars taking place in the world as I write. How can
anyone care about all of them? Perhaps the better question is, at the rate
things are going, how long will we who live in the more fortunate parts of the
world care about any of them.<br>
<br>
And while those whose attention matters were not paying attention, thousands of
Tajik refugees chose to cross the Amu Darya River into Afghanistan--then, as
now, itself at war--a choice that tells one all one needs to know about how
desperate the situation was at the time. Their movement had the irresistibility
of a swelling tide. No appeal from international relief agencies, no guarantee
that their rights would be protected, could stem the flow. They were scared.
They had seen their friends and relatives killed. Their world had been
shattered.<br>
<br>
And yet, to an outsider, almost the most terrible thing about this story is how
commonplace it has become at the end of the twentieth century. So generic, in
fact, that it becomes all but impossible to find the emotional and moral
strength to remain indignant or feel, however inchoately, that such things
should not be permitted to happen and that something should be done to stop
them.<br>
<br>
For all the glib talk of life in a wired global village, ours is a time of
forgotten wars in countries that seem as remote to the average American or
Western European as the dark side of the moon. People in New York or
Tokyo--citizens of the rich world--can find out more easily than ever before
about what happens in the Tajikistans of the world. But the fact that all this
information is available does not make people want to think about it any more
than they did when obtaining such information was more of a struggle.<br>
<br>
For "they," read "we." This is a story about all of us. Which is probably bad
luck for Tajikistan. Because Tajikistan is not only unknown because it is far
away. It's unknown because thinking about it, and all the other places like it,
where the lives of tens of thousands are snuffed out in the space of a few
months and where hundreds of thousands of other people are forced to flee their
homes for a life of uncertainty, misery, and exile, is far too disturbing.
Really imagining the world as it is might mean behaving differently. It would
certainly mean not sleeping so soundly, or thinking so much about money, or
vacations, or the dangers of secondhand smoke. Instead, we designate a few
people to deal with the question; these we call "humanitarians," and they are
both our heroes and our excuse.<br>
<br>
David Rieff, a writer, is a member of the advisory board of the Open Society
Institute's Project on Open Society in Central Eurasia. <br>
</body></html>
