<html>
<head>
<title> About the Project on Open Society in Central Eurasia
</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>
<tr>
<td><h1>
About the Project on Open Society in Central Eurasia
</h1></td>
</table>
At the close of 1995, the 
<a href="/tajkstan.html"><b>Tajikistan Project</b></a> 
expanded its 
mandate to cover four additional countries: 
<a href="/armenia.html"><b>Armenia</b></a>, 
<a href="/azerbjan.html"><b>Azerbaijan</b></a>, 
<a href="/mongolia.html"><b>Mongolia</b></a>, and 
<a href="/uzbkstan.html"><b>Uzbekistan</b></a>. The new Project on 
Open Society in Central Eurasia will make available 
information and funds to support programs that deal with 
social, cultural, and legal issues, as well as other 
activities that support the development of civil societies.
<p>
For a brief moment in 1995, war-weary, impoverished 
Tajikistan seemed to be lurching toward peace and semi-
stability, but the signs were deceptive, the efforts proved 
in vain.
<p>
The political situation appeared to normalize after widely 
criticized elections confirmed Emomali Rakhmonovs de facto 
presidency. Rakhmonov moved to replace the worst human 
rights abusers in the Ministry of the Interior. Oinikhol 
Bobonazarova, a law professor and outspoken advocate of 
human rights, held under house arrest for 
nearly two years, was allowed to travel abroad. Despite such 
efforts, serious human rights violationsincluding at least 
50 extrajudicial killingspersisted. A report by the 
Committee to Protect Journalists called Tajikistan a land 
without news where independent voices in the press have 
been silencedexiled or killedby the government and its 
supporters.
<p>
In an effort to breach the military and political 
confrontation, President Rakhmonov met the opposition 
leader, Mullah Said Abdullo Nuri, in Kabul, laying the 
groundwork for a breakthrough in August on the principles 
for achieving national reconciliation in Tajikistans civil 
war. In December, UN-sponsored talks got under way in 
<a href="/turkstan.html"><b>Turkmenistan</b></a>, 
only to founder in acrimonious stalemate. 
<p>
In late 1995, hostilities resumed between government and 
opposition  troops, reaching as intense a level as had been 
seen at any time since the victory of the Kulyabi, Russian, 
and Uzbek forces in 1993. 
An attempted coup from within the ruling coalition in 
February 1996 revealed how acutely regional cleavages 
continue to divide Tajiks. The events shook the government 
to its foundations, prompting the resignation of the Prime 
Minister and several other leading politicians.
<p>
Providing Support for Stabilization<br>
During the first part of the year, the Tajikistan Project 
supported activities in line with signs of stabilization, 
funding the continued presence of Human Rights 
Watch/Helsinki, a fact-finding mission by the Committee to 
Protect Journalists, and Internews efforts to develop 
independent television. Law professor Oinikhol Bobonazarova 
organized a first-ever human rights law course at Tajikistan 
State University with the Constitutional and Legislative 
Policy Institute. An OSI grant to Save the Children 
Federation (U.S.) supported an innovative Group Guaranteed 
Loan Scheme aimed at providing small loans to households 
headed by women.
<p>
The Tajikistan Open Forum sponsored debates about regional 
security issues, the peace process, political Islam, and 
human rights at the Council on Foreign Relations, the 
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, and the 
Brookings Institute. Speakers included the UN Special Envoy 
to Tajikistan and representatives from the Russian Embassy 
and Human Rights Watch, among others. 
<p>
A special Congressional briefing by opposition leader Hajji 
Akbar Turajonzoda, organized by Congressman Rob Andrews, led 
President Clinton to write and comment publicly on the U.S. 
commitment to supporting a peaceful political settlement in 
Tajikistan. The project commissioned a series of position 
papers, aimed at sharpening debate on these matters, for 
publication in 1996.
<hr>
