<blockquote>                                      
<a name="background"></a>
<h2>Background</h2>
The communist regimes in Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union had a profound influence on the arts and culture of the region. Under communism, artists had to find favor with the state in order to ensure support for their work, resulting in a culture in which freedom of expression was severely restricted. Artists who attempted to express ideas incompatible with the regime were forced underground, forming an important dissident voice. Today, arts and culture, while free of state and party control, continue to suffer from a dearth of funding as governments and private funders concentrate on more urgent priorities in the transformation process. The Soros Foundations, however, believe that nurturing the diverse voices of a country's culture, from the artists to the audiences, is as important to the creation of a strong and vibrant open society as, for example, the building of market economies and independent media.
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="scca"></a>
<h2>Soros Centers for the Contemporary Arts</h2>

The largest arts and culture initiative funded by the Soros Foundations is a network of <b><a href="osiart.html">Soros Centers for the Contemporary Arts (SCCA)</a></b>, which are devoted to the development of the visual arts in Central and Eastern Europe and to the integration of the region's arts communities into the international arts world. The SCCA network, which includes 15 countries in Central and Eastern Europe, increases the international art world's access to the arts of the region by promoting its artists, arts professionals, and organizations through local and international cooperation.<p> The centers select modern and contemporary visual artists for comprehensive documentation and organize exhibitions of local contemporary art. 
The SCCA act as resource centers for information on foreign grants, scholarships, arts programs, competitions, and exhibitions, and organize press conferences to publicize international opportunities in the arts. A number of international foundations and institutions use the SCCA to channel information, projects, and finances to local arts groups, thereby facilitating collaboration with other reputable worldwide arts organizations. The centers also select Soros grantees in each country.
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>
<a name="artslink"></a>
<h2>ArtsLink</h2>

Another program, <b><a href="osiart.html">ArtsLink</a></b>, enables artists and arts managers from Central and Eastern Europe, the former Soviet Union, and the Baltics to work with U.S. artists and arts organizations by funding exchanges, residencies, and collaborative projects. The program in the U.S. offers a five-week residency in an established, nonprofit arts organization, incorporating the visiting professional into the host organization's activities and providing interaction with local artists and arts groups. ArtsLink allows artists and arts managers to exchange ideas, expertise, and technical innovations about their work while training in a variety of U.S. museums, galleries, and studio spaces. 
A public-private initiative, ArtsLink is a partnership of the SCCA network, the National Endowment for the Arts, the Trust for Mutual Understanding, and the Citizen Exchange Council.<p>In addition to their participation in these regional programs, national Soros foundations provide major funding for arts projects such as cultural journals, art books, drama and music productions, and visual arts exhibits. In Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Macedonia, Slovenia, and Yugoslavia, efforts to maintain and revive arts and culture also serve as a way of rebuilding a sense of community while bringing the area's plight to world attention.
<p><a href="#top"><img align=middle src="/images/go_up_bt.gif" alt="Top"></a>

<h3><a href="gopher://gopher.soros.org/11/Prog_Cat_Info"><img align=middle 
src="/images/gopher.gif"><b> Program Category File</b></a></h3>
</blockquote>                                      
